<HEADLINE>
CITY BACKS EASED VERSION OF STREE VENDING BAN 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seven months ater the Giuliani administration backed
away from a plan to ban street vending in large parts of Manhattan,
a city panel approved a compromise measure on Thursday that still
bans food carts and other vendors, but from far fewer blocks than
its original plan did.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, as part of his quality of life campaign, Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani called for limits on street vendors, saying
they congested the city's sidewalks. On May 24, the Street Vendor
Review Panel, made up of three administration officials appointed
by the mayor, voted to ban food vendors from 300 blocks in
Manhattan and other street vendors from 261 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   But in June, after howls of protest and threats of lawsuits,
Giuliani retreated from his original proposal. Administration
officials said at the time the mayor would not give up his efforts
to limit street vending but made clear they were looking for a
compromise solution.
</P>
<P>
   Current law does not allow the review panel to restrict the
number of vendors on each block, but that issue is one that the
city council is expected to debate in hearings next month.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations passed Thursday would prohibit food vending
on 100 blocks, mostly in midtown and downtown Manhattan. It would
restrict other vendors, who sell everything from books to incense,
on 49 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions vary from block to block, but, generally, in
the financial district, vendors must stay off restricted blocks
from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m., Monday through Friday. In midtown, vendors
must generally avoid the restricted blocks every day from 7 a.m. to
7 p.m. Food vendors have also been barred from two blocks in Queens
and five blocks in downtown Brooklyn along Fulton Street.
</P>
<P>
   Vendors said that the restrictions would only increase
congestion by crowding vendors onto other streets.
</P>
<P>
   The new ban will go into effect 30 days after the list of blocks
is published in The City Record, the city's daily journal of public
transactions. Curt Ritter, a spokesman for Giuliani, said he
expected the list to be published by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rossi, vice president of the Big Apple Food Vendors
Association, said the new plan allows more vending downtown, but
maintains most of the original plan's restrictions in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't cut us much slack,'' he said. ``You are pushing
vendors into a smaller area. You are just concentrating the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The business districts want one push cart per intersection, the
vendors want to allow four and oppose block by block bans, Rossi
said. Pablo Ruiz, 38, has sold $2 tacos and $1.75 burritos at the
corner of Eighth Avenue and 38th Street for four years, but the new
restrictions would ban food vendors there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh man,'' Ruiz said when told of the new restrictions. Ruiz
said he caters to Mexican and other Hispanic immigrants who work in
nearby factories, and would lose all his customers if he was forced
to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This spot is for Mexican people,'' he said. ``This is where my
people are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
