<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROBINSON-UNLV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLV WAGERS THAT ROBINSON CAN BUILD WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG SPOON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barely a month into his new job as head football coach at
Nevada-Las Vegas, John Robinson learned first-hand how the folks in
Las Vegas define the term ``rebuilding.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials, who previously allocated $18 million for the
renovation of Sam Boyd Stadium, gathered with Robinson and local
media last week to say goodbye to the old press box. But instead of
simply dismantling it, they blew it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we do things in Vegas,'' said UNLV publicist
Mark Wallington, referring to the city's practice of imploding
outdated hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who admitted to watching ``a few small charges'' go
off, said the story probably was exaggerated. UNLV administrators
are gambling that their hopes for Robinson are not.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 63, was hired Dec. 3 to take over a team that has lost
16 consecutive games. Fired a year earlier after an unimpressive
second stint at USC, Robinson was dabbling in broadcasting and
enjoying time with his wife Linda when the Rebels came calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some other agendas and I wasn't sure what I was going to
do,'' Robinson said in a phone interview. ``They came asking me
about it and they were pretty aggressive. The school president
(Carol C. Harter) pretty much convinced me they wanted to make some
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what kind of changes, Robinson isn't exactly sure. Win some
games, no doubt. The specifics? That's what they're paying him for
_ $350,000 a year for the next three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been genuinely impressed by coach Robinson's enthusiasm
about the task at hand,'' said UNLV athletic director Charles
Cavagnaro. It is now up to Robinson to convert that enthusiasm into
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what changes they want to make,'' Robinson
said. ``Basically, they said, `You give us the vision and we'll
follow it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous for us to make lofty predictions, but UNLV
football will be on the move. We are going to be second to none and
we're going to recruit the best players possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Robinson and USC fans learned the past few years, it is
not enough simply to bring in a name coach who has won before.
Robinson, 104-35-4 lifetime as a college coach, led the Trojans to
a 9-2-1 record and a Rose Bowl victory in his third year back in
1995. But 6-6 and 6-5 seasons and two years without a bowl
appearance led to his dismissal following the 1997 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   UNLV has little in the way of returning impact players. Running
back James Wofford, who rushed for 816 yards and five touchdowns,
is back. So is leading receiver Len Ware and standout defensive
back Randy Black. But the only quarterback returning is sophomore
Chris Hayward, who attempted only 37 passes as a third-stringer
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson must take this group and blend it with newcomers well
enough to make improvements in a new conference. UNLV will play
next season in the Mountain West Conference, which includes Air
Force, Utah and BYU.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the weak link in the conference, but we're not going to
stay there,'' Robinson promised.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in school history, UNLV has funded the
maximum 85 football scholarships allowed by the NCAA. Robinson had
19 scholarships available and has received 10 oral commitments so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Among those are two quarterbacks who might see playing time
quickly. They are Jason Vaughn (6-foot-4, 205 pounds), a transfer
from Middle Georgia Junior College who will participate in spring
drills, and Ryan Hanson (6-2, 210), who passed for 3,082 yards and
31 touchdowns at Los Alamitos High.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has also received a commitment from one of Nevada's top
prep prospects, quarterback and defensive back Lawrence Turner of
Cheyenne High. All-state JC offensive lineman Greg Hulett (6-3,
290) of Los Angeles Valley College recently committed, as did wide
receiver Nate Turner (6-2, 205) of Compton College.
</P>
<P>
   He is setting his sights high with a few more holes to fill
before the Feb. 3 signing date.
</P>
<P>
   ``They recruited here, but they recruited at a low level,''
Robinson said about previous recruiting efforts. ``I don't want to
talk negative about the old group (of coaches), but they kind of
recruited the leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can compare us to Arizona State when they recruit against
USC and UCLA. They end up with guys you thought had no reason to go
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson won't discuss details of the bitter end at USC, but he
admits a fresh beginning was better for all in the long run. At
UNLV, as he did when he first returned to USC, he has the dream and
he believes he has the backing from administrators. The proof,
however, will be in the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think coach Robinson would have come to join us if he
didn't believe the commitment was there at the top,'' Harter said.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, will the commitment on the football field be
enough to make a difference?
</P>
</TEXT>
