<SLUG> BC-CALDOR-CLOSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALDOR, A DISCOUNTER MIRED IN BANKRUPTCY, TO CLOSE ITS STORES 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Conn., Mich.)   By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWALK, Conn. _ Caldor Corp., the discount retail chain that
filed for bankruptcy more than three years ago and has since
struggled to stay afloat, announced Friday that it would liquidate
its holdings and close all of its 145 stores in nine East Coast
states.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, company officials said in a statement, stems from
its inability to negotiate a reorganization plan with a group of
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Caldor's chairman, Warren D. Feldberg, said that the company had
explored a number of options, including court-ordered mediation
with its creditors, since filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in
September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company was left with no alternative but an orderly
wind-down and liquidation,'' Feldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement added that Caldor would begin
going-out-of-business and that the closing of the stores should be
complete by mid-May. Besides selling its inventory, company
officials said they intended to sell off Caldor's real estate
holdings. The company leases all but three of its stores.
</P>
<P>
   Feldberg also said that many of the company's 20,000 employees
would be retained during the liquidation process, but it did not
say how many, or what sort of severance program would be offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is working on a package for severance and extended
medical care but it is too early to discuss any specifics,'' said
Wendi Kopsick, a Caldor spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kopsick said that the staff at the corporate headquarters
here was being reduced immediately to a core group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were layoffs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded in Port Chester, N.Y., in 1951 and has
$2.5 billion in sales. At the corporate headquarters here, workers
carrying cardboard boxes filed out of the building after learning
of the liquidation at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph C. Carbone, 62, of Southampton, N.Y., said he and other
employees were notified of the closing at a meeting in the
Bridgehampton, N.Y., store. ``It's a little sad, but we're hoping
someone else takes it over,'' said Carbone, who has worked for nine
years in the auto and hardware sections. He added, ``There's a
certain amount of sadness but no tears.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which was delisted last year by the New York Stock
Exchange, announced two weeks ago that it was no longer placing
orders or accepting deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been recent reports that Caldor was trying to
sell 64 of its stores to other retailers, including Kohl's, a chain
of department stores mainly located in the Middle West; Dayton
Hudson Corp., which owns the Target discount chain, or Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Kohl's and Dayton Hudson were not returned; no one
answered the telephone at Kmart headquarters in Troy, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of interest in the sites, but it is too
early to discuss specifics,'' Ms. Kopsick said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
