<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUSKIEMEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT BIG MAC ON STANFORD MENU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Suddenly, nine days after being desperate for
their first victory of 1999, the Washington Huskies are playing
with house money. Nobody is going into Stanford realistically
figured to win this year, but the Huskies visit Saturday with a
surprise conquest of Cal in their hip pocket.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, just maybe, they have a shot at the third-ranked
Cardinal if they get a semblance of what Todd MacCulloch gave them
Thursday night in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was awesome,'' guard Donald Watts said. ``He made a few
moves that kind of surprised me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd wasn't going to let us lose. If we get everybody on the
court playing with that kind of focus, we can beat anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch had a line for the ages against Cal, a team good
enough to have beaten North Carolina: 13 of 14 from the field and 5
of 5 from the foul line for 31 points; 17 rebounds, three blocks,
three steals, two assists, two fouls and no turnovers in 37
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be a stretch to say that MacCulloch made himself
some money against Cal. He was playing against an athletic, if
unpolished, center in 7-foot Francisco Elson.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight stays trained on him Saturday. For the fifth time
in his UW career, MacCulloch faces Stanford's 7-2 Tim Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd like to be known as the best center in the
Pac-10,'' MacCulloch conceded. ``With the centers in this league,
if people consider that of me, that's a great honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, it will not be as easy as it seemed against Cal for
MacCulloch, who said afterwards he felt he could do anything.
Playing against Stanford's brawlers is a little like getting into a
car accident; it can take a major toll on the body.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the anticipated pounding from Stanford's front line,
MacCulloch said, ``I don't see why they wouldn't try to. And I've
got to try to push them out of their comfort area.''
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't necessarily what UW coach Bob Bender wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it becomes a wrestling match inside, he can step away from
the basket,'' Bender said. ``Taking him away from the basket is
going to give us some opportunities to take it to the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   What benefited Washington in the second half at Cal was the move
of MacCulloch out of the low post, opening up some lanes for Husky
perimeter players.
</P>
<P>
   If MacCulloch gets trapped into a shoving match down low and the
Husky ball movement is stagnant on the perimeter, Stanford (16-2,
6-0) might win by about its average margin in Pac-10 games: 20
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're tremendous,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   There is an element of curiosity to the MacCulloch-Young
rivalry. Both are fifth-year seniors, MacCulloch having redshirted
as a freshman for development and Young having sat out the 1995-96
season with back problems.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four games head-to-head, there has never been one in
which each performed well. Both players have had two good games,
one at home and one on the road, and two sub-par ones.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch, however, has emerged as the dominant player this
year, third in the Pac-10 in scoring (18.7) and first in rebounding
(11.1) and blocks (1.69). Young, a lesser light on a better team,
averages 9.3 points and 6.4 rebounds while playing seven minutes a
game less.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in Seattle when the Huskies faced Stanford for the
first time in conference play, the Cardinal was 18-0 and won on
Kris Weems' 3-pointer at the buzzer. Now, Stanford is on a streak
of 12 straight wins.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal is a third of the way to becoming the first team in
the 21-year history of the Pac-10 to go unbeaten in league play.
And performances like the 94-45 annihilation of Washington State
Thursday night are fanning speculation that it might happen.
</P>
<P>
   If the Huskies can't foil Stanford's dreamy scenario, at least
they know it won't have been a lost weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
