<SLUG> BC-BKW-HUSKIEWOMEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON NEEDS NO STOKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Excuse the Washington Huskies if they wake up Saturday
morning with their energy level already percolating.
</P>
<P>
   Here comes Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal have recently dominated the Pac-10 rivalry that
resumes Saturday at 5 p.m. at Edmundson Pavilion, where the Huskies
have been unbeatable in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   They are 4-0 at home this season and none of the games has been
decided by fewer than 10 points. The Huskies beat Washington State
and Arizona State by 32 points, defeated Arizona 73-63 and whomped
California by 22 points Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   So much for appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford coach Tara VanDerveer might have been reading the
Huskies' minds earlier this week when she said, ``Opponents are
licking their chops.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10's premier program during VanDerveer's 13-year career
on The Farm _ the Cardinal is a remarkable 174-30 in conference
play during that span _ Stanford already has lost more conference
games this season (two) than in any season since 1993-94, when it
was 15-3. Stanford is 8-9 overall this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a different kind of team,'' VanDerveer said. ``We just
had five great players leave at the same time, and that created a
huge void in experience. But at the same time, it is real exciting
to see such great production from the freshmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bethany Donaphin, a 6-foot-2 first-year forward from New York,
barely missed her third Pac-10 double-double Thursday night against
Washington State when she scored 16 points and had nine rebounds.
Freshman guard Lindsey Yamasaki leads the team with a 14.4 scoring
average, including 32 in a loss to Santa Clara in December.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite having just one senior, forward/guard Regan Fruen,
the Cardinal is tied for third in the Pac-10 with a 4-2 record. The
more experienced Huskies are alone in second at 5-1, one game
behind No. 10-ranked UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   To stay close to the Bruins and ahead of the Cardinal, the
Huskies must end a streak of nine consecutive losses to Stanford,
which leads the overall series 19-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominance in the past doesn't matter,'' VanDerveer said. ``It
just gives other teams more motivation to play against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington's last win against Stanford was Jan. 6, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   That was before current Husky seniors Jamie Redd, Amber Hall,
Malinda Lynch and Molly Hills entered college. Saturday is their
final chance to beat the Cardinal at home.
</P>
<P>
   Redd needs 12 points to pass Rhonda Smith and move into first
place on the Huskies' all-time scoring list. Hall, who scored 18
points and had 11 rebounds in the win over Cal, has eight
double-doubles this season and leads the Pac-10 in rebounding,
averaging 10.2 a game. She led the league the past two seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
