<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-OWEN-SPI &LR;      01-23 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS HOPE OWENS CAN SHED `LAID-BACK' LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This is what they are saying about Billy Owens now _
he will be an adequate backup for Detlef Schrempf, providing points
and rebounds off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   This is what it has come to for Billy Owens _ a 29-year-old in
the prime of his career whose destination was stardom, not Seattle,
a former All-America and No. 3 overall draft pick reduced to role
player.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with that in Owens' mind. He figures to
help the Sonics with his rebounding and versatility. It's just that
everyone expected a quantum vertical leap from Owens and,
comparatively speaking, the 6-foot-9 forward has barely gotten his
feet off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   After signing a three-year contract worth more than $6 million,
Owens participated in his first practice as a Sonic Friday night
and looked sharp. He went up and under Dale Ellis for a layin. He
grabbed a defensive rebound, led the fast break and passed to Gary
Payton for a three. He pulled down an offensive rebound and laid it
in. There will be nights when he dazzles, others when he struggles.
</P>
<P>
   How did Owens go from headlines on the front page to small type
in the boxscore? It might have been caused by his effort and
intensity, or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   That's the rap on Owens, however unfair. From all accounts he is
a good guy and good player. It's just that with a little more
gumption, he could have been more on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Owens is delighted to be here, relishing his next
opportunity, conceding that his relaxed approach to the game might
have been detrimental early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have got high expectations and put the label on you as
an All-Star,'' he said. ``I admit, my first three years, I was
laid-back and I took (time) off in the summertime.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not look like it, but he cares about what's happening on
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody runs around like Reggie Miller,'' Owens said. ``You've
got different types of basketball players. I might be quiet, but
I'm not trying to be quiet this year. A lot of people say I take it
easy. I want to shut a lot of people up.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he will flourish here with a winner, surrounded by a
team that might better use his talents. Maybe he will recapture the
collegiate brilliance he enjoyed at Syracuse that at one time
prompted comparisons to Magic Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Owens joined the Orangemen as one of Jim Boeheim's most heralded
recruits. The young man had just led Carlisle High School to its
fourth straight Pennsylvania state championship with Owens scoring
53 points in the title game. He was named the U.S. High School
Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   At Syracuse, the rise continued with more All-America honors and
selection as 1991 Big East Conference player of the year his junior
season after averaging 23.3 points, 11.6 rebounds, 3.5 assists and
2.4 steals.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his ball-handling and all-around ability, Villanova
coach Rollie Massimino called him ``a Magic Johnson who can
shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, Owens shined. Even his coach noticed a great player
who was not assertive enough in spite of statistics that said
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't take over,'' Boeheim said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   During Owens' first visit to Seattle, he played for the U.S.
national team at the Goodwill Games in 1990. He was the leading
scorer (21.4) for the silver-medalists and yet, coaches who watched
the team play and work out wondered about Owens' effort.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson, who was then coaching the Golden State Warriors,
said: ``He has terrific skills and he's an intelligent player. If
there is a negative, he can move his intensity level up. I don't
think he plays as hard as he can all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Del Harris, then coaching the Milwaukee Bucks: ``He's a
highly talented player, but he's the kind of player I have trouble
with personally. The game comes so easily for him, he doesn't look
like he's trying. As good as he is, I feel there's another level he
could play at if he pushes himself.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly not sea level, but not the summit either. Owens
is somewhere inbetween, and it's hard to determine whether he's
ascending, descending or perched on some rock outcropping in the
middle of his climb. Everyone, it seems, keeps waiting for
elevation in his game.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were hopeful, not once but twice. They selected Owens
with the third pick in the '91 draft but sent him to Golden State
on the eve of the '91-92 season for three players, one of whom was
Mitch Richmond, a many-time All-Star. No one would take Owens for
Richmond straight up now.
</P>
<P>
   In his rookie season, Owens was on the Warriors team that the
Sonics stunned in the first round during George Karl's first season
in Seattle. He averaged 14.3 points and became the first
undergraduate to unanimously be named to the first-team NBA
All-Rookie squad since Michael Jordan and Hakeem Olajuwon made it
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   After being traded to Miami in 1994, Owens was maligned by coach
Pat Riley, who wants workaholics to put in 25-hour days. Tim
Hardaway, his former teammate at Golden State, also was not a fan
of Owens. Hardaway believed that Owens was squandering his ability
by not working hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento got him back in a four-player deal in '96, and Owens'
reputation clung to him like his jersey. No. 30 was perceived to
not be totally dedicated.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the positive spin on the downward developments.
Although inconsistent last year, Owens received fluctuating minutes
from coach Eddie Jordan. Owens played out of position for much of
the season at power forward, also affecting his production.
</P>
<P>
   Owens' scoring average has dropped the past five seasons and
shooting percentage the past four. But he has worked on his
perimeter shot and has improved his 3-point accuracy the past three
seasons. He has bulked up in the offseason, hitting the weights in
preparation for hitting the boards.
</P>
<P>
   You will come to know him as Billy O, another transplanted
Sacramento King who brings vital attributes to Seattle along with
Olden Polynice. He won't have O.P.'s exuberance but then, neither
did Derrick McKey or Sam Perkins, both of whom factored highly in
Sonics' playoff runs in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
