</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOFFMAN-SUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES MAGAZINE MUST PAY DUSTIN HOFFMAN FOR ALTERED PHOTO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California and ``e'' entertainment
news files.) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a ruling that could change how celebrity images
are used, a judge has ordered Los Angeles magazine to pay Dustin
Hoffman $1.5 million because he was ``violated by technology'' when
the magazine digitally altered a photo from his movie ``Tootsie.''
</P>
<P>
   A computer was used to gussy the actor up in a dress and heels.
U.S. District Judge Dickran Tevrizian also said in Friday's ruling
that in its presentation of Hoffman and other stars in the
pictorial, the magazine acted maliciously, a remark that sets up
the possibility for an even bigger punitive damages award.
</P>
<P>
   ``The photos were manipulated and cannibalized to such an extent
that the celebrities were commercially exploited and were robbed of
their dignity, professionalism and talent,'' Tevrizian wrote in a
20-page ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The judge set a hearing for Thursday to determine how much the
magazine owes in punitive damages. A spokesman for Capital Cities
ABC, the magazine's Washington, D.C.-based parent company, said the
verdict will be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Rex Heinke, who has defended the media in many other
First Amendment cases, pointed out that the technology used in the
Hoffman case ``wasn't even feasible a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinke said the ruling wouldn't make it easier for celebrities
to sue over editorial articles based on parody. But he doubted that
the $1.5 million verdict would go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a substantial number that is going to get the
attention of people in the media and advertising world,'' Heinke
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman sued in April 1997, just a few weeks after the ``Grand
Illusions'' fashion layout appeared.
</P>
<P>
   On the witness stand for two days during trial last week,
Hoffman claimed that the magazine trivialized his character from
the hit movie by making readers believe he had re-created the role
for an advertising supplement.
</P>
<P>
   In several hours of emotional testimony, Hoffman suggested that
other actors who saw the layout might assume his career was
spiraling downward after 30 years of A-list movie roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a fish in the ocean. The sharks don't bother you
unless they think you are wounded,'' Hoffman said Tuesday. ``That
to me signified a wounded career.''
</P>
<P>
   Tevrizian agreed, explaining in his ruling that $1.5 million is
``fair market value'' for an endorsement from an actor of Hoffman's
stature. The judge, who called Hoffman ``truly one of our country's
living treasures,'' scolded the magazine for its conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles (magazine) fabricated an image of Dustin Hoffman
using computer digitalization techniques, and then published that
image knowing it was false,'' Tevrizian wrote. ``To be blunt, the
celebrities were violated by technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney-owned Capital Cities ABC released a short statement,
reiterating its lawyers' trial argument that the layout was meant
to be a humorous article, not an advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed with the result and plan to appeal,'' the
statement said. ``Editorial use of the material in question is
protected by the First Amendment, and we strongly believe our use
was appropriate and protected.''
</P>
<P>
   The layout was filled with altered photographs of living and
dead stars, including Cary Grant, Humphrey Bogart and Ingrid
Bergman, all in modern fashions with the designers' names listed.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's picture included his head and the background shot of
an American flag from a 1982 ``Tootsie'' poster, seamlessly merged
with the body of another man dressed in 1997 fashions.
</P>
<P>
   The caption read: ``Dustin Hoffman isn't a drag in a
butter-colored silk gown by Richard Tyler and Ralph Lauren heels.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman claimed he hadn't been paid for a domestic commercial
since he made $3,000 for a Volkswagen ad in 1966 _ a year before
his starring turn in ``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's lawyer, Charles Shephard, said the First Amendment
didn't protect the magazine because editors knew the information
was false, and didn't use it to promote any news angle.
</P>
<P>
   Shephard pointed out that at least one of the items that the
actor was ``wearing'' belonged to a major advertiser for the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look at this and not think that these designers were
being promoted,'' Shephard said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0010 </DOCNO>
