<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5349 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  LAWPARTNERSSAYTRIALVERYU     01-23 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 LAW PARTNERS SAY TRIAL VERY UNLIKE JUDICIAL PROCEEDING  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
The media have billed it as the trial of the century.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the six high-powered trial attorneys at Lewis and Roca call
President Clinton's trial as they see it: ``A big joke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a real trial, not under the American legal system,''
explains Patricia K. Norris, a partner in Lewis and Roca's
commercial litigation department.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Douglas L. Irish, the firm's senior trial lawyer: ``No use
in kidding ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Explains Susan Freeman, a partner in the firm's finance and
bankruptcy group: ``In a real case, the charges wouldn't have
survived a grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   I gathered some of the brightest trial litigation minds at Lewis
and Roca to scrutinize the impeachment trial. The law &UR; firm's
conference room is abuzz as they answer such questions as ``Is good
law being practiced?'' ``How is the case being presented?'' ``Is
America witnessing stellar legal arguments?'' and ``Will the
president win the case?''
</P>
<P>
   My findings? The trial is a sham. Legal proceedings such as this
one simply don't exist in the American justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Let these attorneys explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Problem No. 1:
</P>
<P>
   No one has determined whether President Clinton committed an
offense worthy of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have a lot more respect for the senators if they had
answered that question,'' says Robert H. McKirgan, practice manager
in charge of the firm's commercial litigation group. ``Basically,
they're holding a trial without determining whether an offense has
been committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem No. 2:
</P>
<P>
   There are no ``real'' jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a real case, the jurors are neutral,'' quips Dawn M.
Bergin, a member of the firm's civil/business litigation group.
``Not a bunch of senators who have stake in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem No. 3:
</P>
<P>
   There were no opening statements to lay out the facts that will
be presented during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, what we're hearing is closing arguments,'' says
Shelia Carmody, a partner in the firm's tort group.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, there are more basic problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, they say, cases like the one against
President Clinton are uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see many perjury cases. They are very, very rare,''
McKirgan says.
</P>
<P>
   There are other legal questions.
</P>
<P>
   Would a federal prosecutor press criminal perjury charges
against a person from a private civil case?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're way too busy for that,'' Norris says.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, would the charges have survived a grand jury?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not with the attorney who grilled the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a very poor job cross-examining the president,'' says
Irish, who teaches such techniques at the National Institute for
Trial Advocacy. ``He would have gotten a D in my class.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been proud moments. The attorneys cite the
performance of White House counsel Cheryl Mills and the inspiring
performance by retired Sen. Dale Bumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a lot of it, however,'' Norris says. ``For
the most part, it has been very painful to watch the kind of
lawyering that has been practiced in this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys then begin a conversation about the damage the
presidential trial could have on the court system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole system is grounded in the truth. If you don't have
the truth, the whole system is jeopardized,'' says Carmody. She
observes that no one, not even Clinton, should get away with lying
under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Norris asks, ``Will this feed into the growing cynicism of the
justice system and how justice is administered?''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman presents a presidential concern: ``Are we creating a
system, like a parliament, in which the president serves at the
pleasure of the senators?''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, President Clinton's trial will have one
benefit:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kenneth Starr examination? We should show it to our
associates and tell them, `This is how not to conduct a
cross-examination,' '' McKirgan says.
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, seems to be able to tell me whether President
Clinton will win the case. It's not a real court of law, after &UR; all,
they explain again. Just politics. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
