<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5351 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-dalecolumn-HNS &LR;      01-23 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-dale </SLUG>
 column -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Condensed diet product unlikely to be too tasty
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Considering the proliferation of bad teams and, hence, the
preponderance of awful games over the past several NBA seasons,
it's arguable this barnstorming schedule the strife-torn league is
shoving down the customers' throats will provide a level of play
that's no less satisfying than the expansion-era status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, even under the best of circumstances, Nuggets vs.
Mavericks traditionally has been a poor investment of time as well
as money.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps, knock on wood, the lack of practice hours might
rein in the coaches' convoluting instincts a bit. They deserve a
significant share of the blame for robbing their sport of its
natural grace, what with the overdone isolation tactics and
stifling defensive schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Pro hoops is supposed to be about running and jumping, not
standing around or participating in a scrum.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 50 games in 90 days the Rockets will play _ compared
to 82 over 171 this past season _ seems like an awful lot of
running and jumping in a compacted period. Factor in the normal
transit grind and jet lag plus the likely weather crisis or two and
we are going to witness some excruciatingly blah, brain-dead,
leg-weary performances before the playoffs mercifully roll around.
</P>
<P>
   Then at least, the second-season adrenalin rush will carry the
lads the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who flies regularly on business knows the toll it
extracts. Imagine the beating these guys are going to endure
dragging their oversized torsos on and off airplanes day after day
after day. When Charles Barkley terms the scheduling of three games
in three nights ``stupid,'' he's not just being the Chuckster and
mouthing off. It is stupid.
</P>
<P>
   But unavoidable, because David Stern's magic number was 50
games. If ever there figures to be a survival-of-the-fittest,
last-team-standing season, this will be the one. Other than Hakeem
Olajuwon and Scottie Pippen, trainer Keith Jones might be the most
crucial member of the Rockets' family.
</P>
<P>
   Boy is he going to be busy when the Rockets hit their
five-games, six-nights, five-cities ordeal in mid-February. Buy
stock in muscle balm, people.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rudy Tomjanovich looks ready, though. He appears to have
lost about 25 pounds since last season. Maybe he assumes he'll have
to suit up at some point when the bodies start dropping around him.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, of course, lost three full practices during the
interminable wait for the ink to dry on Pippen's complicated
sign-and-trade contract, but that ultimately insignificant delay in
getting under way might prove fortuitous for the long haul. The
Rockets, you see, will be more ``rested'' when the
marathon-turned-sprint of a season starts Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Before the aforementioned long march from Houston to Minnesota
to Florida via New Jersey, the Rockets receive a four-day respite
after playing five times in seven days at the outset. Thereafter,
they have mere back-to-back days off on only five occasions, and
not until April 27-28 are they fully travel-free for both.
</P>
<P>
   Once the abbreviated training camp ends, Tomjanovich could wind
up with no more than a dozen regular workouts over the duration of
the entire season. If practice does indeed make perfect, you won't
be seeing much perfect _ and I doubt Leslie Alexander will be
offering any money-back guarantees for what's likely to be, on more
occasions than not, a horribly ragged product.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Rockets surely will be one of the top teams. Imagine
how dreadful the dregs will be. We could end up seeing even more of
a gross imbalance between the contenders and the fodder than we've
come to expect. Ironically, Chicago could be the worst of the
worst, too. One dire prediction has the disassem-Bulls winning 10
fewer games than the next most godawful team.
</P>
<P>
   With Chicago in a free-fall mode, the East will be a horrific
bore. Imagine how unattractive the overcrowded schedules of those
teams will be. A lucky fan might see Milwaukee, Toronto and Boston
on consecutive nights, and spend $1,500 or more for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Through Stern, the NBA speaks high-mindedly of the need for at
least 50 dates to preserve the season's ``legitimacy,'' but what
the cramming is really all about is salvaging revenues. To preserve
the same games-to-days ratio as last year's schedule would have
limited the season to a maximum of 43, a further financial
sacrifice the owners weren't about to endure.
</P>
<P>
   You kidding? Enough season-ticket cash has been painfully
rebated. So, Houston, you'll get to pay to see the Clippers twice,
business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   If quality were the real priority, the season would have been
shortened to no more than 40 games. The colleges somehow manage to
identify a legitimate national champion with fewer, don't they?
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as skewed as this NBA season is, a worthy _ albeit
bushed _ successor to the Bulls will emerge in late June. The
debate is whether a noble end will justify the sloppy,
helter-skelter means. Your answer probably depends on how many
dollars you have tied up in your seats, and which city you call
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
