<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX'S REGIONAL ATTITUDE KEEPS TCU WELL-EXPOSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere across the great state of Texas, or perhaps Oklahoma,
Louisiana, Arkansas or New Mexico, some young hoop phenom might
tune in to Fox Sports Southwest tonight to watch the TCU Horned
Frogs play the Nevada-Las Vegas at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   He would be the kind of athlete who might carry a Top 25 program
to the Sweet 16 or, someday, maybe even a Final Four. And, having
seen the merits of TCU, Fort Worth and Frogs basketball on the
small screen, he might decide to visit the campus, even sign a
letter of intent to attend the school.
</P>
<P>
   Or so TCU basketball coach Billy Tubbs no doubt hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game against UNLV and Monday's at Tulsa are two more
opportunities for Tubbs and TCU to sell the program to potential
recruits via television, in this case Fox Sports Southwest. The
games are also a great way to reach out and touch far-flung alumni
and other supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Sports Southwest regional package features five TCU
games this season, a nice local complement to the Frogs' occasional
national exposure on ESPN and ESPN2. Previously, TCU appeared on
Fox in games against Texas Tech and Gonzaga. The SMU-TCU game Feb.
6 is also scheduled for air time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about exposure more than anything else,'' said Brian
Estridge, director of broadcasting at TCU. ``With TV, it's a `show
it and they will come' philosophy. It's good for our recruiting. It
makes us seem big time.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU is sharing Fox Sports Southwest's regional basketball
package with SMU, Tulsa and Rice. The Frogs get the most games
televised this season _ five _ thanks to their record last season,
which was the best among the group.
</P>
<P>
   The four schools fit nicely into Fox's regional sports
broadcasting effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all within our viewing area,'' explained Jon Heidtke,
vice president and general manager of Fox Sports Southwest.
``People tend to think of us as a Dallas-Fort Worth-area network,
but we're sensitive to all the regional product in our territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV package is in its second season, and indications are that
it's a business and marketing success that's likely to be
continued. Heidtke said Fox likes the fact that the schools are
aggressive marketing partners, promoting the games on campus and to
their fans everywhere, making for grateful advertisers and
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   TCU, which covers the production costs of its games and receives
advertising revenue from the broadcasts, said the package is
basically a break-even one, financially.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty good deal for us,'' Estridge said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not economics that make games like tonight's and
Monday's valuable to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get on TV, it kind of lights everybody up,'' Estridge
said. ``The players like it and Billy likes it. He loves to use the
term `exposures.' He wants us to get as many exposures as possible.
That way, they can tell recruits that they'll be on TV this many
times.''
HBO SHOW SCORES AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   HBO is first and foremost a movie channel, but its forays into
sports are first-rate, especially its ongoing series ``Real Sports
With Bryant Gumbel.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest installment, which airs at 9 p.m. Monday locally and
repeats throughout the week, is one of the most provocative. The
lead segment focuses on the growing problem of offshore sports
wagering via the Internet. Although the subject has been covered
elsewhere, Real Sports goes the extra mile _ literally _ traveling
to the Caribbean where bookmakers operate. Especially noteworthy is
the discovery of a company that claims to be licensed to operate in
Aruba but is actually run out of Bethlehem, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a segment on assistant coaches in the NFL that
looks at the grueling hours and constant job insecurity faced by
this group of men chasing the dream of becoming a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   It's a show that lives up to its Emmy Award status. \Ntagtop:
(817) 390-7375 \Ntagbottom:dmark\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
