<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-23 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Alexander is what an owner should be
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronice
</P>
<P>
   Team owners are like a box of chocolates, or so we thought.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is sugar-coated. Everything is labeled with snappy
words. But once we sink our teeth into what they're really all
about, we realize they are just nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Adams. John McMullen. Tweedle Dee and Tweedle Dum.
</P>
<P>
   We laughed at their antics and doubted their motives. We spent
years buying the stuff they tried to sell us, but then we knew
better. We heard all their billowy rebuttals to criticism, but we
finally had enough and showed them the highway.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen went on to own a hockey team called the Yankee Devils,
or something appropriate like that. Adams went on to show the fine
people of Petticoat Junction just what he is all about _ .500 or
below.
</P>
<P>
   When Leslie Alexander flew into town in this atmosphere of doubt
and deceit _ shortly after McMullen's departure and in the middle
of Adams' holding us hostage for a new stadium _ we had to figure
his carry-on luggage was a carpetbag.
</P>
<P>
   We had to doubt. We had to figure he would deceive, just like
the nutty box of chocolates we knew before. And we weren't the only
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander strode into town in 1993 without a smidgen of NBA
experience, telling everyone within earshot that he would be a
``very, very, very hands-on'' owner. And there was a collective
``uh-oh'' bouncing off the walls of the Rockets' offices.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes rolled. Then a few heads did. A series of strange
front-office hires followed, and we figured here we go again.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander acted different and talked different, with a New York
accent _ ``ya know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Nuts, we said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Tomjanovich, probably the best thing the Rockets franchise
ever knew, quietly thought the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   We considered Rudy T one of us and trusted his instincts. He was
a sleeves-rolled man who put in long days and unwound with a cold
beer. Like the bumper sticker says: Rudy T wasn't born a Texan, but
he got here as fast as he could.
</P>
<P>
   When Tomjanovich privately doubted Alexander, we did, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think Rudy wondered,'' Alexander said. ``He didn't
know what to expect from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, there was a prevailing opinion that Alexander would:
</P>
<P>
   A) Move the Rockets to another city, presumably in Florida,
which he called home.
</P>
<P>
   B) Run the franchise into the ground by hacking the budget,
trimming the payroll and clipping more corners than a bad barber.
</P>
<P>
   C) Play general manager and make bad move after bad move.
</P>
<P>
   But now we know. Les is more.
</P>
<P>
   This week's trade for Scottie Pippen is one of the five biggest
deals the Rockets have ever made, along with those that brought
Moses Malone, Ralph Sampson, Clyde Drexler and Charles Barkley.
Three of the five came under Alexander's watch, and all of them
were considered stunners.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we know. With Pippen arriving, possibly carrying the next
Rockets championship in his hands, we know Alexander should take a
bow for becoming what this town has wanted all along.
</P>
<P>
   He is an owner who works like we work, dreams like we dream, and
expects what we expect. He got here as fast as he could.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich and Alexander have built a unique but profound
relationship, even as their personalities and styles contrast.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of it all is a trust that Tomjanovich will coach
his backside off. Alexander will cover Rudy T's back with smart
moves and first-class surroundings, such as the upgraded team
plane, the improved practice facility and a checkbook that opens
wide at all the opportune times.
</P>
<P>
   Like this one. Pippen chose Houston because this is where he
wanted to be, as much because of Alexander as Tomjanovich. Barkley
turned down more money from Seattle for the same reasons. Hakeem
Olajuwon considers Alexander the best thing that ever happened to
this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   From the days of picking up the phone and calling agents as he
once did bond traders, trying to control everything, Alexander has
handed the line to executive VP Carroll Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   He has allowed the mistake-prone righthand man, John Thomas, to
move on and replaced him with the impressive George Postolos. He
has surrounded and rewarded handsomely a close circle of confidants
like Robert Barr, once the strength coach but now a vice president
and a huge asset in the Pippen deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you win championships,'' Alexander said. ``If you
save a few bucks here and there, it could cost you in the long
run.''
</P>
<P>
   He has transcended the box of chocolates we once knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for John McMullen, maybe people would have liked
me a little more at the start of this,'' Alexander says. ``Ya know
what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   After Drexler, Barkley and now Pippen, yes, we know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 0111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
