r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-RACING-RECOVERY-T     01-23 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING-RECOVERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE-RACING INDUSTRY SHOWS SIGNS OF RECOVERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, the health of horse racing was like that
of a patient with a terminal illness. Last year, however, the sport
began showing signs of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   A national advertising campaign started. Fan interest perked up.
Sales prices of thoroughbreds skyrocketed. Many tracks whose
grandstands had been emptying recorded gains in attendance and
betting.
</P>
<P>
   The patient remains in critical condition. But at least phony
optimism has been replaced by a legitimate reason for hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, it was a good year for an industry that needed
one,'' National Thoroughbred Racing Association chief executive
officer Tim Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing-oriented NTRA, which last year spent $22 million
of mostly industry-generated money in an attempt to increase
racing's public awareness, deserves much of the credit for halting
the sport's free fall. Its hard-edged ``Go Baby Go'' ad campaign
struck a chord with the MTV-ish audience for whom it was targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors also went into racing's comeback, explained Smith,
who tries to remain politically correct by downplaying the
first-year impact of the NTRA.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: Real Quiet's highly publicized near miss of a Triple
Crown sweep, one year after stablemate Silver Charm barely missed.
Also, the national economy was strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real events are always as important or more important than
marketing,'' Smith said. ``But we didn't hurt. We played some
role.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTRA intends to spend about $30 million this year, and its
co-op advertising program with racetracks is slated for a 50
percent increase, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest focuses of this racing year will be the
launch of the Television Games Network, tentatively scheduled for
July.
</P>
<P>
   The network plans to offer live national and international
racing 24 hours a day on local cable systems. TVG's parent company,
United Video, is controlled by Telecommunications Inc. (TCI), a
cable giant that has more than 25 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   At-home wagering on horse races is not legal in Texas _ tracks
may seek that soon _ but Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie general
manager Corey Johnsen said he is likely to encourage area cable
systems to carry the channel because of the increased exposure it
will provide for racing.
</P>
<P>
   Even in markets where existing horseplayers will have the option
to stay home and bet on televised races, Smith said he believes the
network will create enough new fans to boost on-track attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The NTRA also has teamed with Fox Sports to create an 11-race
series for older handicap horses.
</P>
<P>
   The NTRA Champions on Fox series begins Jan. 30 with the Donn
Handicap at Miami-area Gulfstream Park. Each race will be
televised, either nationally on Fox Sports or on a Fox regional
sports channel. The series concludes with the Aug. 29 Pacific
Classic at Del Mar near San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Having a superstar horse to compete in these races doesn't hurt,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away and Awesome Again, the leading candidates for 1998
horse of the year, have been retired. But barring injury, Silver
Charm could fill that role this year. Other big-name horses still
competing include Real Quiet, Victory Gallop and Free House.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bob Baffert will be shooting for his third consecutive
Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes victories. His leading early
prospect is Exploit, unbeaten in four starts. The 3-year-old colt
belongs to Bob and Beverly Lewis of California, who also own Silver
Charm.
</P>
<P>
   The Triple Crown begins May 1 with the Kentucky Derby, followed
by the May 15 Preakness and June 5 Belmont Stakes. The eight
Breeders' Cup races will be Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie's thoroughbred season
is April 15-July 25. Tentative dates for the track's fall quarter
horse meet are Oct. 1-Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Houston Race Park in Houston is conducting live racing for
thoroughbreds until April 11, and has a July 2-Sept. 12 quarter
horse meet. Retama Park near San Antonio, the state's other Class 1
track, will run a mixed thoroughbred and quarter horse meet from
April 23-June 27 plus a July 30-Oct. 24 thoroughbred-only season.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Texas Racing Commission is expected to rule on an
application by Squaw Creek Downs in Willow Park _ formerly Trinity
Meadows _ to resume Class 2 live racing and simulcasting at the
site.
1999 horse racing New on the scene
</P>
<P>
   NTRA Champions on Fox series
</P>
<P>
   Television Games Network Major races
</P>
