<SLUG> BC-BKC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU PAYS WELL TO MAINTAIN ATHLETIC SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're a Billy Tubbs fan, you are, de facto, a member of the
Billy Tubbs congregation.
</P>
<P>
   You take the good with the bad. You cheer and cackle when Tubbs'
TCU basketball team piles up 153 points. You wince and look the
other way when the other coach charges that Tubbs was running it
up.
</P>
<P>
   You laugh at his funny lines. You shrug away his wise-guy ones.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Tubbs fan, you look only at the winning and the
filled seats at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum. You think Tubbs is Will
Rogers, even when you hear a fifth-place, John Calipari Starter Kit
like tonight's Bill Bayno whine that Tubbs is something else.
</P>
<P>
   TCU is filled with Billy Tubbs fans these days. And as of this
week, the price just got a lot higher.
</P>
<P>
   Since Tubbs arrived on campus one stunning night five seasons
ago, the Frogs have won 96 games and lost 50. They are 62-9 when
playing at home. Under Tubbs, TCU basketball has spent 14 weeks
ranked in The Associated Press Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it was the football coach who, after going 6-5 in the
regular season, was called in this week and given a new seven-year
contract that could be worth up to $900,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even getting into that situation,'' said Tubbs, for
once without much to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good contract at TCU, which I think carries over into
the next millennium. And I just need to take care of my own
business right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said he would rather keep his mind occupied with tonight's
visit by Bayno and conference rival Nevada-Las Vegas. The Frogs are
15-3 and ranked 21st, but Tubbs says he knows his team could and
should be playing better.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a high priority thing on my list,'' Tubbs said,
when asked about football coach Dennis Franchione's new contract.
``Since I've been here, TCU has been very fair to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, it wasn't a financial thing. It wasn't that
I got an immense raise. The reason I came was that I wanted to be
here, and that TCU showed me that it was ready to make a commitment
to basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``commitment,'' as it turns out, was worth about $450,000,
Tubbs' reported annual financial package, once you add up his
salary, camps and shoe deal.
</P>
<P>
   To put that ``commitment'' to Tubbs into perspective, consider
this: His predecessor, Moe Iba, started at TCU in 1987 for a salary
of about $60,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   When Tubbs, who appeared to have worn out his welcome at
Oklahoma after 14 seasons, was first approached by TCU
representatives, he half-dismissed them, saying, ``I don't think
you can afford me.''
</P>
<P>
   Try us, the TCU people said.
</P>
<P>
   And here the Frogs are, five years later, ranked 21st in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic assumption is that you get what you pay for. Tubbs'
hiring raised eyebrows around the country. His reputation _ both as
a rascal and a Final Four coach _ has thrust the TCU program into
the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Without Tubbs, there is likely no Lee Nailon, TCU's All-American
and leading scorer. Without Tubbs, there is likely no huge crowd at
Daniel-Meyer tonight and No. 21 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stuff will take care of itself, as long as we stay
committed to basketball,'' Tubbs said. ``More than, `What can you
do for me?,' my concern is, `What can you do to help me get where I
want to go in basketball?'
</P>
<P>
   ``If they paid me nothing and I knew I could win a national
championship, I'd take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there he goes, running it up again.
</P>
<P>
   But as usual, Tubbs knows the score. He knows that even though
there is a new athletic director in town, the same people who made
that ``commitment'' to him five years ago are still in place. Tubbs
knows that they know that his presence is important, as TCU
positions itself for whatever the new millennium in college
athletics will bring.
</P>
<P>
   Between the soon-to-get-a-raise Tubbs and Franchione, the $7
million coach, TCU is sending platinum smoke signals to any NCAA
wheelers and dealers who may be scanning the horizon. Those brief
but dark days of wondering whether TCU would have a healthy
Division I home appear over.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs is a rascal, but a winning one. And if you buy into what
TCU is trying to do, you know that it comes with a price tag _ the
rascals and the Sun Bowl victories alike.
</P>
<P>
   Try us, the TCU people said. Commitment has never come cheap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
