<HEADLINE>
FORMER NORTH TEXAS COACH HIRED BY RAVENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former North Texas football coach Matt Simon was hired as the
Baltimore Ravens' new running backs coach yesterday, one of four
assistants brought in by new head coach Brian Billick.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, who spent four seasons as the Eagles' head coach, was
replaced last February by Darrell Dickey after compiling an 18-26-1
record. This past season, he served as an intern for the Denver
Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   During the past few weeks, Simon said he had talked with
Billick, formerly the Minnesota Vikings' offensive coordinator,
about some of Billick's options. Billick's name was brought up in
rumors about several vacant head coaching positions before he
accepted the Baltimore job. Once he signed with the Ravens, he
brought in Simon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some other opportunities _ some in the NFL and a couple
in colleges,'' Simon said. ``But my focus was toward the NFL. I
felt like the opportunity to work for Brian Billick would be
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Milt Jackson (wide receivers), Steve Shafer (defensive backs)
and Mike Smith (defensive assistant) were also hired by Billick
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Simon's relationship with Billick began in the Pac-10, when
Simon was an assistant at the University of Washington and Billick
was on the staff at Stanford University. After leaving Washington,
Simon was offensive coordinator at the University of New Mexico
before coming to UNT in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, 45, was still under contract at UNT after being
reassigned within the athletic department last year. He said his
new job would dissolve his relationship with UNT.
</P>
<P>
   Simon reports to Baltimore in February, right after the Super
Bowl, to begin off-season planning and development of the Ravens'
offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
