<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TRENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS OPTIMISTIC WITH TRENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ After the events of yesterday, the Mavericks might feel
comfortable calling themselves a legitimate playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   But Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson laughed and said
he wasn't ready to make such a bold prediction.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has reason to laugh after what transpired over the past
24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the Mavericks beefed up their inside game with the
signing of free-agent center John ``Hot Rod'' Williams to a
three-year, $5.775 million contract, they added some more muscle to
their plate yesterday when they agreed to a one-year, $1 million
deal yesterday with free-agent power forward Gary Trent.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks will have a news conference today at the Tom
Landry Center to introduce Trent to the Fort Worth-Dallas media.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Trent averaged 11.7 points and 6.3 rebounds and shot
47.7 percent from the field while playing for the Portland Trail
Blazers and Toronto Raptors. Portland traded the 6-foot-8,
250-pounder to Toronto on Feb. 13, and Nelson was overjoyed that he
was still available at such a bargain basement price.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a gift from the gods,'' Nelson said. ``Must have been
my good living that did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The signing of Trent, Nelson said, officially ends the team's
pursuit of free-agent forward Cedric Ceballos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to sign Ced, but Trent came along, and we just jumped
all over it,'' Nelson said. ``Basically we said goodbye to Ced and
good luck, and I hope he gets what he's looking for, and we're
going on, just like we did with Kurt \RThomas\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent comes to the Mavericks with a checkered past and a lot of
baggage.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 7, 1997, Trent's pregnant girlfriend, Roxanne Holt, told
Portland, Ore., police that Trent hit her in the face and kicked
her in the ribs during a domestic dispute at his home where she was
living at the time. Police charged Trent with misdemeanor assault,
and he pleaded guilty to harassment _ a lesser misdemeanor charge _
and was put on one-year probation and ordered to attend anger
management sessions.
</P>
<P>
   While Trent was on probation, he showed up at Theron Hall's job
at a Portland youth mentoring program and community center and
punched him in the face, knocked him to the ground and choked him.
That led to a five-day stay in jail for violating his parole.
</P>
<P>
   Trent and Mavericks forward Samaki Walker are longtime
acquaintances. They're both from Columbus, Ohio. They played
against each other in high school and worked out together this past
off-season for a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked out head-to-head, got some good workouts in and went
out to eat and talk afterwards,'' Walker said. ``His power game and
his explosiveness is incredible. There's not too many people who
are going to move him around.
</P>
<P>
   Walker believes he can help keep Trent out of trouble, adding
that the 24-year-old four-year veteran has been misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gary has to be around some people who has some good
influences on him,'' Walker said. ``I've known Gary for years, and
he's truly a good guy and I think he'll fit in pretty good here.''
THE NBA IS BACK
</P>
<P>
   Who says the NBA in dead? It's alive and well in Dallas, if last
night's scrimmage is any indication.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks drew a surprising crowd of 9,200 at Reunion Arena
for their free scrimmage. That figure surpasses the 8,833 fans who
attended the Jan. 6, 1998 ``regular-season'' game at Reunion Arena
between the Mavericks and Denver Nuggets.
</P>
</TEXT>
