<HEADER>
A5366 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-2NDL     01-23 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-2NDLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR MOVES TO COMPEL LEWINSKY TO MEET WITH HOUSE PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS graf 2, to move up fact that Lewinsky's lawyers contend
immunity agreement does not extend to congressional testimony;
grafs 11,12, which begin `But in a letter...' to move up info on
letter from Lewinsky's lawyers; graf 13, which begins `Two lawyers
not...' to add info on Op-Ed article in Saturday's NYT claiming
Starr's agreement does not grant Lewinsky congressional immunity;
graf 14, 15, which begin `Neither Starr nor...' to add info on
Lewinsky lawyers; graf 19, which begins `In his motion...' to add
info that Lewinsky will travel to Washington on Saturday; editorial
refinements and restructuring grafs 3,4; graf 10 to move up info on
content of immunity agreement; grafs 16, 17 to move up info from
Starr on role of IOC; other minor wording changes throughout.) (This story replaces NY-ORGAN-SHORTAGE on NYT Page 1) 
(Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CASE, IMPEACH-SCHOLARS) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, sought an
emergency court order Friday to compel Monica Lewinsky to submit to
interviews over the weekend by House prosecutors in President
Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Starr sought the order at the request of Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., the lead prosecutor, after Ms. Lewinsky rejected a request
to meet with the House prosecutors, or managers, last week. Her
lawyers are contending that her immunity agreement with Starr does
not extend to congressional testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, who held a closed hearing in
U.S. District Court Friday afternoon, was still considering the
request late Friday evening, said Paul McNulty, a spokesman for the
House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge grants the order, Ms. Lewinsky would face intense
questioning over the weekend. The House prosecutors believe that
her answers could be pivotal as the Senate decides early next week
whether to question witnesses or decide Clinton's fate without
witnesses, McNulty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting down to the point where we need to know who
we're going to call and why we're going to call them,'' McNulty
said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   As the week drew to a close and the White House defense team
finished its presentation, the House managers faced increasing odds
against calling witnesses. The situation grew more questionable
Friday as prominent senators, like Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., called for
a quick end to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces two articles of impeachment, voted by the House of
Representatives a month ago, that accuse him of perjury and
obstruction of justice. The articles say he lied about his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and engaged in illegal maneuvers to
have friends and aides cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky and Starr reached an agreement last July giving her
immunity from prosecution, provided that she answer questions
truthfully. She was interviewed extensively by grand jurors and
Starr's prosecutors, and her testimony about her relationship with
the president was the foundation for much of Starr's case against
him. The House managers also leaned heavily on Ms. Lewinsky's
testimony to try to show that Clinton lied to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Although it might seem that she has already been asked every
conceivable question by Starr's prosecutors, and that nothing new
could be gleaned from her recollections, the House prosecutors want
to question her nonetheless. Hyde, the chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, went to Starr because, as the official who
reached the immunity agreement with Ms. Lewinsky, he is its chief
enforcer, McNulty said.
</P>
<P>
   The immunity agreement calls upon Ms. Lewinsky to testify
truthfully before grand juries, trial juries ``and in any other
executive, military, judicial or congressional proceedings.'' As
for debriefings, the agreement specifies that they will be
conducted by Starr's office and before ``attorneys, law enforcement
agents and representatives of any other institutions'' as his
office requires.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter to Starr's office on Thursday, Plato Cacheris
and Jacob A. Stein, Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers, said it would be
inappropriate for their client to be ``placed in the position of a
partisan,'' meeting with Republicans but not Democrats in the
impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   They said their client would appear before the Senate if
subpoenaed. But despite the sweeping language of the immunity
agreement, they said they were not convinced by Starr's assurances
that he could guarantee her immunity before the Senate if she
testified there. ``It is our understanding that only the Senate by
majority vote can do that,'' they wrote. ``We would appreciate your
supplying your legal authority for your position.''
</P>
<P>
   Two lawyers not connected with the case contended in an article
Saturday on the Op-Ed page of The New York Times that Starr's
agreement with Ms. Lewinsky does not grant her congressional
immunity, despite its wording. The lawyers, Charles Norman Shaffer
and Gerald Solomon, said the Senate would have to seek a federal
court order granting such immunity. Shaffer represented John W.
Dean during the Watergate hearings.)
</P>
<P>
   Neither Starr nor Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers could be reached Friday
night. Her lawyers also contended that her obligation to submit to
questioning would be void if the independent counsel were acting as
an agent for another entity.
</P>
<P>
   In his motion, Starr said Ms. Lewinsky could insist that his
office supervise debriefings by the House managers. But he rejected
any suggestion that his office would be acting as an agent for
them.
</P>
<P>
   His office, he said, ``has its own, continuing duty to provide
the House with information relating to impeachment.'' In any event,
he said, the immunity agreement allows the independent counsel's
office to subject her to questioning not only on its own behalf but
on behalf of ``representatives of any other institutions as the
O.I.C. may require.''
</P>
<P>
   McNulty, the managers' spokesmen, also insisted that Ms.
Lewinsky ought to fear nothing from House questioners _ assuming
she tells the truth _ because her immunity agreement covers
anything she might say. In his motion before Judge Johnson, Starr
explained his need for an emergency order: ``The Senate's schedule
requires the House to submit its motion to call witnesses as early
as Monday, and the House has stressed its need to debrief Ms.
Lewinsky this weekend.'' Ms. Lewinsky was planning to travel from
Los Angeles to Washington on Saturday in case she must face
questioning, an associate said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican prosecutors' sense of urgency becomes clear when
the impeachment timetable is analyzed. If, as expected, there is a
motion in the Senate early next week to dismiss the case against
the president, the House prosecutors want to be able to argue
against it based on whatever new nuggets they can wrest from Ms.
Lewinsky's memory.
</P>
<P>
   And if the motion to dismiss the case is defeated _ as
head-counters think it would be, given the Republicans' 55-45
advantage in the Senate _ Republicans would want to use those
nuggets to support their arguments that witnesses should be called.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Starr's motion, at Hyde's request, before Johnson was
almost literally an 11th-hour attempt. Should the judge not grant
the motion, Republicans would lose their last big opportunity to
gauge what Ms. Lewinsky might say on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   One official close to the proceedings insisted there was still
information that Ms. Lewinsky could provide, contradictions she
might resolve. As an example, he noted her recollection that the
president's personal secretary came to her apartment at 2 p.m. on
Dec. 28, 1997, to retrieve gifts the president had given her.
</P>
<P>
   Yet cellular-phone logs show the secretary, Betty Currie, called
Ms. Lewinsky at 3:30. Perhaps, the official suggested, Ms. Lewinsky
would recall, after her memory was jogged, that Ms. Currie came by
closer to 4 p.m., a two-hour difference that could be crucial in
showing motive and intent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
