<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-GUGLIOTTA-AZ     01-23 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-GUGLIOTTA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING AN ALL-TOO-FAMILIAR WAITING GAME  
 SUNS EAGER TO GET GUGLIOTTA DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After meeting with Tom Gugliotta and his agent, Richard Howell,
late Thursday night and into the early hours of Friday morning, the
Suns were left once again to wait for a top free-agent prospect to
make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta and Howell left town on Friday with an offer from the
Suns and might meet today with officials of the Minnesota
Timberwolves, for whom he was a Western Conference All-Star last
season. Suns General Manager Bryan Colangelo said he hopes to get a
decision from Gugliotta today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're on their way home and will speak to family members,
discuss alternatives and hopefully in the near-term future, we'll
have some idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those alternatives are few, but they still could cost the Suns
Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota can give the 6-foot-10 power forward a seven-year
contract valued at about $86.5 million. The Suns are allowed to
offer a six-year deal with a maximum value of about $67 million,
but their salary-cap situation probably will prevent them from
reaching the maximum number.
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility is that Gugliotta would sign with
Minnesota for the $86.5 million deal and then be traded to another
club _ the leading candidate being the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're hearing back from them is Tommy wants to go play
for the Lakers,'' Minnesota Coach Flip Saunders said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Minnesota owner Glen Taylor confirmed for reporters that
the Timberwolves will meet with Gugliotta and Howell today, and he
anticipates the sign-and-trade scenario being proposed.
</P>
<P>
   If the Timberwolves turn it down, Gugliotta likely will sign
with the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's something else they want,'' Taylor said when he
was asked about the offer the club already has on the table. He
said the sign-and-trade has been requested before.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things they've talked about _ every day,''
he said. ``It has to be a deal that helps the Timberwolves. If they
had to run him through here (in a deal), we're not going to stand
in their way. But it has to be a great deal for the Timberwolves.''
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, the Lakers have offered packages that include
forwards Elden Campbell and Sam Jacobson and guard Eddie Jones, but
there are base-year-compensation issues that could complicate any
deals for Gugliotta, whose cap number will change from about $5.5
million to $9 million if he re-signs with Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Timberwolves have rejected sign-and-trade proposals,
but if the club believes it ultimately will lose Gugliotta without
compensation, that position could change _ and the Suns still would
be without the big man they hope to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor sounded skeptical about the chances of the Timberwolves
keeping Gugliotta, but he said the bridge has not been burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting close,'' Taylor said. ``He hasn't (burned the
bridge) with me, but what's important is his teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota attempted to sign Philadelphia free-agent forward Joe
Smith to a $1.75 million salary-cap exception, and the club
announced that Smith has come to terms _ but he did not sign the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is waiting to see if Gugliotta is signed to stay in
Minnesota. If so, he probably won't sign the deal. He could even
wind up in Phoenix. However, reportedly there has been friction
between Gugliotta and Timberwolves point guard Stephon Marbury
which could influence Gugliotta's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thought is, Joe will be here and Tommy won't be here,''
Taylor said. ``But if you asked a couple of days ago, I was 99
percent sure Tommy would be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta arrived at America West Arena just before 11 p.m.
Thursday night _ about the time Antonio McDyess was agreeing to
terms with the Denver Nuggets. Ainge told reporters after the
club's limited morning workout that he didn't leave for home until
about 3:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting on his decision,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Suns lose Gugliotta, they could turn to Smith or re-sign
their own free agent, Clifford Robinson, and still have salary-cap
room to sign another high-profile free agent such as Miami guard
Brent Barry, who was unsigned as of Friday night. The Suns lost two
of their options on Friday when Vlade Divac signed with Sacramento
and Golden State power forward Jason Caffey re-signed with the
Warriors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 0128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
