<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5369 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITHSONIAN-HEYMAN-SF     01-23 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHSONIAN-HEYMAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITHSONIAN INSTITUTION CHIEF TO RESIGN AT END OF YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 
WASHINGTON _ I. Michael Heyman, the former chancellor of the
University of California at Berkeley who led the Smithsonian
Institution through a five-year period of both controversy and
success, has decided to retire at the end of the year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I look forward to returning home to California ... and
re-establishing my ties with the University of California and the
San Francisco Bay Area, '' Heyman wrote in a statement obtained by
The Chronicle. Heyman will announce his intention to resign to the
Smithsonian's board of regents Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I leave the Smithsonian in a formal sense,'' he wrote. ``It
will always be a part of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyman was named secretary of the Smithsonian in 1994, becoming
the first nonscientist to hold the post. He frequently noted that
overseeing the Smithsonian, a massive complex of 16 museums,
research facilities and the National Zoo, was much like governing
the UC Berkeley campus.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the 69-year-old former law professor said he is
leaving Washington for California for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being pulled, I don't feel pushed out of here,'' Heyman
said from his office in the Smithsonian's red castlelike
headquarters on the Capitol Mall. ``I'm getting pulled by age, by
desire to ratchet it down and by my desire to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stop being responsible to the success of a big,
complex organization,'' added Heyman, who was chancellor at UC
Berkeley from 1980 to 1990. ``I don't want to bow out of the world.
I'd like to spend three-day weekends at Stinson Beach, rather than
a day and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyman is credited with reorganizing the Smithsonian's
bureaucracy, dealing with its shortcomings in diversity, boosting
fund raising and overseeing a 150th anniversary exhibition that
toured the country and was seen by more than 3 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But his tenure may be best remembered for a controversy that
erupted during his first weeks in the job over an exhibit at the
National Air and Space Museum about the Enola Gay, the plane that
dropped an atomic bomb on Hiroshima, Japan, on Aug. 6, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, which had been prepared before Heyman was
secretary, raised ethical questions about the decision to drop the
bomb and showed the devastating effects of the attack on the
Japanese. Even before it opened, the exhibit touched off protests
from veterans groups, who complained bitterly that the 50th
anniversary of the end of the war in Japan should not be
commemorated by presenting something so sympathetic to the former
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman found himself embroiled in controversy and ultimately
decided to scrap the exhibit and replace it with a modest display
of the plane, which in turn drew fire from critics who said he had
given in to the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of Enola Gay, we spent a lot of time ... trying to
figure out how you deal with controversy and controversial
exhibitions,'' Heyman said. ``We fashioned a process where there's
got to be some real discussion at the museum level ... as to what
exhibitions are going to be shown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a public institution, we ought to try to present subjects
broadly, rather than platforms for individual political
viewpoints,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York, the former law clerk to Supreme Court Justice
Earl Warren also took steps to increase private donations to the
Smithsonian, which relies on federal dollars for about 70 percent
of its $450 million annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he took over, eyebrows were raised when corporations
began sponsoring exhibits. A minor furor erupted when Orkin, a
company known for making insecticides, financed an insect zoo at
the Natural History Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that everybody around here has gotten used to the fact
that we have to seek a lot of funding,'' Heyman said. ``And some of
that is going to come from the corporate community.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyman said later this year the Smithsonian will embark on an
ambitious quest for private donations _ the first ``capital
campaign since an aborted attempt in 1920'' _ in an effort to raise
$600 million to $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   The money is needed primarily to provide more space, as well as
for repairs and restorations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning to the Bay Area, Heyman said he hopes to teach a
class at the Boalt Hall School of Law in Berkeley and get involved
in pro bono work such as resuming his involvement in regional
planning.
</P>
<P>
   After six years in Washington, Heyman frowned on the pervasive
``quest for prominence ... for advancement'' that marks Washington
but said his distaste for such behavior did not factor into his
decision to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really miss California,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
