<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5372 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-MCDYESS-AZR &LR;      01-23 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-MCDYESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDYESS DRAMA FULL OF INTRIGUE  
 EX-TEAMMATES KEPT `FAR AWAY' DURING DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antonio McDyess finally appeared before the microphones Friday
in Denver, but somehow it seemed more like the resolution of a
hostage situation than a basketball player's contract signing.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours before, a phone call from a distraught
McDyess had sent three former Phoenix Suns teammates in a mad dash
to Denver to help him sort through his situation.
</P>
<P>
   But despite chartering an aircraft and jawing with security
guards at McNichols Sports Arena, Rex Chapman, Jason Kidd and
George McCloud were prevented from speaking to their former
teammate, who was kept sequestered for most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, McDyess agreed to a six-year, $67 million contract
to play for the Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old power forward, apparently having second thoughts
about his decision to spurn the Suns and play for the Nuggets,
started the process in motion by calling Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't get into the details of the conversation,'' Chapman
said, ``but he was very upset. Antonio had some serious doubts
about his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   According to sources familiar with the ordeal, Chapman asked
McDyess if he wanted some of his former Phoenix teammates to come
to Denver to discuss the situation before he made his decision.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess, who already had put off a news conference and delayed
his contract signing, asked them to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman, Kidd and McCloud _ the three remaining Suns teammates
who were closest to McDyess _ boarded a chartered flight for
Denver. Sources said the flight was chartered by the Suns, but
General Manager Bryan Colangelo would not confirm that.
</P>
<P>
   When the Suns arrived, a Colorado Avalanche hockey game was
under way, and it was sold out. The players were not allowed in the
building, and security threatened to have their limousine towed
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't go there to whisk him away from Denver,'' Chapman
said. ``We wouldn't have stopped him if he wanted to get on the
plane with us and come back. But we were really concerned about his
well-being. He was very, very upset about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got word (Thursday), Jason and myself, that he wanted to
talk, and from there we ended up in Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuggets General Manager Dan Issel called in his own troops,
summoning point guard Nick Van Exel, Coach Mike D'Antoni and
assistant coach John Lucas from training camp in Colorado Springs
about 60 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   He also enlisted the help of Colorado Avalanche goalie Patrick
Roy and the hockey club's general manager, Pierre Lacroix.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to fight fire with fire,'' Issel said at the McDyess
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   However, Issel didn't take exception to the Suns' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what this kid means,'' he said. ``If the shoe was on
the other foot, I probably would have done the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The three Phoenix players tried to reach McDyess by a cellular
telephone. One of McDyess' agents, Tony Dutt, agreed to set up a
meeting. Dutt, according to sources, told the three to meet McDyess
at an Embassy Suites Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But he never brought McDyess to them. With the three Suns
players on the way to the hotel, McDyess was ushered out of the
arena. Chapman said the three players never were able to make
contact with McDyess himself while in the Mile High City. Van Exel
admitted the hotel meeting was a ruse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to keep them as far away as possible,'' said Van
Exel, who described McDyess as upbeat, not upset, during the
evening. ``That's what we had to do. It worked.''
</P>
<P>
   A snowstorm kept the Suns in Denver overnight, and they returned
Friday not even knowing for sure what McDyess had decided to do.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said he at first discounted a report that McDyess was
reconsidering, then heard from a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rex was already talking to a rather emotional Antonio McDyess
on the phone,'' Colangelo said. ``I placed a call to one of his
agents, James Bryant, and about 45 minutes later I received a call
from Tony Dutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He opened the conversation by asking whether we were still
interested if Antonio was still interested. I told him that the
bridge to Phoenix had not been burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, Colangelo received three calls, two from
friends of McDyess and a third from Bryant, informing him that
McDyess would sign with the Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   There have been questions throughout the recruiting process of
McDyess, one of the most attractive free agent players available
this season. Dutt also represents Van Exel, who is seeking a new
contract with Denver. And he is associated with Lucas, who was
hired as an assistant coach by the Nuggets. The Denver club also
traded for another Dutt client, Keon Clark, and signed a former
high school teammate of McDyess as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said the three players didn't go to Denver to try to
change McDyess' decision, they just wanted to make sure it was he
that was making the decision and that he was happy with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a special person away from basketball,'' Chapman said.
``Whether or not he wears a Nuggets uniform or a Suns uniform makes
no difference to me at all. The most important thing to me was to
find out if he was happy. He really struggled with this decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who have never played pro sports will say,
`Wow, what a problem to have. Do you take $86 million versus $67
million,' or whatever it is. That's not what this is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was about his friends, his contacts, his relationships
with people he's closest to. He had some real doubts about his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a sensitive guy, and I don't think he should be condemned
for making the decision he made.''
</P>
<P>
   McDyess insisted Friday he made up his own mind when he was
asked how he would respond to those who question why he would
choose the Nuggets, who won 11 games last season, over the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my decision,'' he said. ``I had to do what was best for
Antonio, not for whoever is out there asking that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing was not being pressured, just go out and make my own
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns gave up two players, two first-round draft picks and
two second-round draft picks to Denver to get McDyess in a 1997
trade. Coincidentally, the Suns' first home game, Feb. 7, is
against the Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely sad to see him leave,'' Suns forward Danny
Manning said. ``When we do step on the court against Dice, we want
to let him know he left a pretty good team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
