<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLALL-STAR-SCHOE     01-23 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING A NARROW FOCUS  
 FOR SCHOENFELD, ROAD TO TITLE IS FREE OF CLUTTER 
</HEADLINE>
 ALL-STAR-SCHOENFELD-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB McMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ ``Carpe diem.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Schoenfeld doesn't appear to have any visible tattoos
permanently etched into his skin, but if he ever decided to get
one, that's what the inscription should read. And it should be in
big, bold letters _ right across his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carpe diem.''
</P>
<P>
   Seize the day. Seize the moment.
</P>
<P>
   That's Schoenfeld, the well-spoken, highly motivated and
incredibly focused head coach of the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the veteran NHL bench boss what's on his mind as he prepares
to make his first visit to the All-Star Game as an assistant coach
for the North American squad in Sunday's 49th annual game here at
the Ice Palace, and you won't find what you're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I'm going to spend the next couple days
thinking about our next opponent on Tuesday, the Buffalo Sabres,''
Schoenfeld said. ``Don't get me wrong, I'll try to have a little
fun while I'm at the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I pretty much have always been a game-to-game coach and a
day-to-day person. I expect to win the next hockey game. That's
all. That's where I focus my energy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how the fiery head coach lives his life away from the
ice, too. Private when it comes to his personal life and his
family, guarded to a point when asked about hockey-unrelated
issues, Schoenfeld won't allow himself to become distracted when
he's off the clock and on ``his'' time.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, even when hockey is the focal point of the
conversation, Schoenfeld won't clutter his mind _ or his daily
agenda _ with matters that are of no interest to him.
</P>
<P>
   So, Coach, have you spoken yet with Ken Hitchcock, the Dallas
Stars' head coach, whom you'll be working with behind the bench on
Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I'm sure we will talk and attend a function or two
together before the game,'' Schoenfeld said Wednesday. ``But I've
got to tell you, that seems so far away right now, I'm not even
thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   OK then. What did you think of the Pavel Bure trade?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any thoughts about Pavel Bure,'' he said wearily.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Schoenfeld about this three-day break away from his team,
and he almost starts to gnash his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   One gets the feeling that as much as he'll try to enjoy the
All-Star experience this weekend, he'd much rather be back at the
Coyotes' practice facility in Scottsdale. If the league and the
players' association would allow it, he'd be driving his team, a
franchise-best 24-11-7 at the break, through three straight days of
practice, fine-tuning its neutral-zone trap, putting overtime work
into the struggling power play and reviewing game tapes over and
over, looking for something he or one of his assistants might have
missed.
</P>
<P>
   Here he is in Tampa, cut off from his team. However, four of his
players are here with him: forwards Keith Tkachuk and Jeremy
Roenick, who will skate for the North Americans, and defenseman
Teppo Numminen and goalie Nikolai Khabibulin, who will be
representing the World team made up of European-born players.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schoenfeld's probably not going to have too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try not to,'' said Schoenfeld, who with even moderate
success in the playoffs likely will receive a three-year contract
extension before his current deal runs out next year. ``We go back
to work against Buffalo and then I'll be thinking about
Philadelphia, the Islanders and Nashville. I've got it all there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wish the break was a little bit longer so we could
get some more of our injured guys back. But three days might help
us. It might save us in one game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Schoenfeld. Always thinking. Always looking to seize some
sort of upper hand over the competition, but always taking it one
team at a time, one day at a time. That's why he never got too
confident when the Coyotes stormed out of the gates and took the
NHL by storm, tearing out to a 14-2-2 start, which included an
undefeated November (10-0-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``From this point on, the points are much harder to come by,''
he said. ``People are scratching and clawing to get into the
playoffs or to move up in the standings or vying for first in the
division. . . . I don't want to say these two points are more
important than two points in October, but it seems that way. Teams
are becoming more desperate, and you'll find come February, it gets
worse, and it gets worse again in March and worse in April and
worse in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything escalates. No one can afford to look at an opponent
lightly. People are going to be prepared to play us. We have to be
prepared to play them. And if you're not, you're not going to win
the hockey game. We weren't prepared, emotionally, for Nashville (a
week ago), and we lost that game. There isn't that big a difference
between our team and any other team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the Dallas Stars. We're not. We don't have the
depth. We don't have the level of skill at all the positions. . . .
We're as good as our workload, and when are workload isn't there,
we don't beat anybody. Our players have to realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``carpe diem.'' Seize the day. And seize the
moment. Knowing Schoenfeld, he won't let them forget. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
