r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BEARS-MCGINNIS-AZ     01-23 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BEARS-MCGINNIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARS LEFT AT ALTAR 
 MCGINNIS UNHAPPY WITH CONTRACT TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bears have been McDissed.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials scheduled a news conference Friday afternoon to
announce Cardinals defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis as their new
head coach, but it never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Negotations between McGinnis and the Bears broke off and
McGinnis walked out of the team's offices in Lake Forest, Ill.,
without the job.
</P>
<P>
   Bears officials were hopeful that McGinnis would speak again
with team President Mike McCaskey, but the two sides hadn't
resolved their differences as of late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to McGinnis said the team was willing to
guarantee only two years of his contract, which was believed to be
a four-year deal. The Bears wouldn't say why there was a breakdown
in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The source said McGinnis also was upset with the amount of money
he would be able to use for assistant coaches' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskey was concerned about guaranteeing McGinnis' entire
contract because the team already owed former coach Dave Wanndstedt
$2.5 million. Wannstedt was fired last month and hired as defensive
coordinator of the Dolphins, but that didn't eliminate the Bears'
financial obligation to him.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem between the two sides, according to sources
close to the Bears, was that the team announced the hiring before
McGinnis was able to inform members of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Another source said McGinnis heard about the news conference to
announce his hiring on the radio while he was driving to the Bears'
Halas Hall for what he thought was a negotiating session.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the recorded greeting on what was Wannstedt's
office phone said, ``You have reached the voice mail of Chicago
Bears head coach Dave McGinnis'' before McGinnis had come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Bears officials were so certain they had reached an agreement
with McGinnis to become their 12th head coach that they announced
on Friday morning they had hired him and that he would be
introduced at a noon (Arizona time) news conference. But then _ in
a manner reminiscent of the Nuggets' handling of Antonio McDyess'
contract situation the day before _ media members were told the
news conference would be delayed until 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At 1 p.m., no news conference was held. Ted Phillips, vice
president of operations for the Bears, then told the Chicago media
that there had been a delay.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears' big announcement was becoming a public-relations
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   `There are a number of issues that still have to be resolved,
and we don't really have a timetable right now for when it will be
resolved,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips refused to give specifics. ``I'm not at liberty to
discuss those,'' he said. ``There's just several issues that have
to be discussed. That's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the rest of the afternoon, the Bears kept insisting
that things ``were being worked out.'' But at 2:30 p.m., Bears
spokesman Bryan Harlan confirmed that McGinnis had left the
building.
</P>
<P>
   If McGinnis doesn't take the Bears job, he is expected to return
to his duties with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   If McGinnis does leave, Tobin is expected to consider
replacements inside and outside the staff. Secondary coach Larry
Marmie and defensive line coach Joe Greene likely would be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   Another coach who would have been interviewed was former
Cardinals assistant Jim Johnson, who replaced Tobin as defensive
coordinator at Indianapolis. But Johnson, who spent last year as
linebacker coach of Seattle, took the defensive coordinator's job
at Philadelphia on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis, 47, was the fifth and final candidate to interview for
the Bears' job when he met with McCaskey on Thursday. Instead of
leaving Chicago and returning to the Valley, he stayed there and
agreed to a deal with McCaskey late Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   He informed Cardinals officials Friday morning that he was going
to take the Bears' job.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin, a longtime friend and associate of
McGinnis, even released a statement about McGinnis' apparent hiring
by the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely happy for Dave,'' Tobin said. ``This is what you
work for throughout your professional coaching career . . . I think
he'll do a good job and lead the Bears to success for many years to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players already had prepared for McGinnis' departure.
</P>
<P>
   Outside linebacker Jamir Miller said that McGinnis always was
``positive'' and ``always kept us motivated, no matter how bleak
the situation appeared . . . I'm very, very happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Ronald McKinnon said ``Dave has been like a
father figure to all of us on defense. He took care of us, kept our
spirits high, and he made sure we were ready to play. He joked
around with us and had fun, but when it was time to play, he got
down to business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
