r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-OREGON-NEWMAN-AZR     01-23 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-OREGON-NEWMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR HIS CHANCE  
 NEWMAN FITTING IN AS OREGON ASSISTANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Don Newman doesn't need any of those books
telling men how if they just learn to open up and share their
feelings, all the social ills of the world will disappear and women
won't even mind the toilet seat being left up. Occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Although he would probably choke on the description, Newman is
the prototype of what some portray as the ideal,
end-of-the-millennium male _ tough and tender, strong yet caring,
giving and willing to unzip his heart and unleash a torrent of
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Women from Venus? Men from Mars? Newman's address is right here
on planet Earth at the University of Oregon, specifically, where he
works as an assistant basketball coach to Ernie Kent and where
today he will try to help the Ducks beat Arizona State and many of
the same players that he helped to 18 wins last season as their
interim coach.
</P>
<P>
   Others _ coaches, especially _ might hide what churns inside
behind a wall of false indifference, but not Newman. Never has,
never will. He freely admits he has been awaiting this day with
great anticipation and not a small amount of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably couldn't help but be that way,'' he said. ``I still
follow these guys all the time, and I've seen them a lot. I saw
them in Maui, and I've followed them through the Pac-10. One part
of you is extremely proud for those guys, seeing how they're
playing and progressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman didn't see the Sun Devils lose by 30 at Oregon State on
Thursday; he was occupied with the Ducks' two-point loss to
Arizona. But he has charted the growth of seniors Bobby Lazor and
Mike Batiste and junior Eddie House, plus freshmen Kenny Crandall
and Chad Prewitt, whom he recruited, like a doting father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a warm and satisfying feeling,'' he said. ``I felt like
last year, we really acquired a big-time belief in ourselves and
the program, and that's carrying them through. I'm sure (new coach)
Rob Evans is excited about having three veterans on the floor, and
young guys who can take the program forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans wasn't particularly excited after the Sun Devils' worst
loss of the season, but he has the job he always wanted and knows
better days are ahead. It's the job Newman wanted, too, even
though, as an emergency replacement for Bill Frieder, he was told
by Athletic Director Kevin White it would be for one year and one
year only.
</P>
<P>
   White made two runs at Utah Coach Rick Majerus and talked to
other coaches before getting Evans, who built the program at
Mississippi while coaching White's son.
</P>
<P>
   Newman and assistant Lanny Van Eman took ASU to the doorstep of
the NCAA Tournament despite finishing with seven recruited
scholarship players, and Newman was convinced he deserved a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Newman still harbors some of the disappointment at not being
hired, but not the bitterness, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts every time I think about it,'' he said. ``No question
I could get the job done, and I proved that. But I did get it
behind me. But I'll never forget the experience and the feeling
when I had to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman, who checked into some head-coaching positions at other
schools, seems to have settled comfortably into his new job even
though ``I've gone from a leadership role to more of a support
role.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent, meanwhile, sounded ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been great,'' Kent said. ``I needed someone who could not
only recruit, I needed the right role model, a father figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great working relationship and a great friendship.
How could you not like and get along with Don Newman? He has such a
great heart. He can go into any environment and make anyone feel
totally welcome and at ease.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman admitted there was a brief period of adjustment, but Kent
delegates authority to all of his assistants and encourages their
input. But Newman, 41, has a one-year contract and makes no secret
about wanting to be a head coach again. Then again, he doesn't make
a secret about much of anything. Kent understands and will let
Newman look around after the season. If nothing materializes, Kent
said Newman is welcome back.
</P>
<P>
   As for today's reunion, Newman anticipates a big yank at his
heartstrings. He will talk to Batiste and Lazor, House and Prewitt
and Crandall before the game, and it might not be the easiest thing
he has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the relationship ever really stops with
players,'' he said. ``The closeness we had, the things players grow
from, I like to think my time with them was extremely positive and
hopefully, they learned some things as men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all about relationships. All about getting on the same
page, about letting everyone know we're in this together. It was a
heavy dose of brotherhood, or parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   The players, too, have been looking forward to this, although
their thoughts are more occupied with reversing the Oregon State
blowout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be cool to see him,'' said House, who against
the Beavers went without a three-point basket (0 for 7) for just
the second time all season. ``He not only was our coach, he's a
close friend.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
