A5379 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONA_PENNST-AZ     01-23 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA_PENN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA TO FACE PENN STATE IN PIGSKIN CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona started near the bottom last year. The Wildcats will
start near the top next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats will test their national-championship credentials
at Penn State on Aug. 28 in the Pigskin Classic, which will kick
off the 1999 college football season.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from last season's opener at winless Hawaii,
where the untested and unknown Wildcats launched a 12-1 season that
ended with Holiday Bowl victory over traditional power Nebraska and
a No. 4 ranking in the final 1999 polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-lose situation,'' said Arizona Coach Dick Tomey, who
was rewarded with a new five-year contract after last season, the
best in school history. ``It's an opportunity for us to find out
who we are right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also will give us a lot of motivation during the spring and
summer. We've got a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The game figures to match two teams with national championship
aspirations. Both are a good bet to be ranked among the top 10, if
not the top five, in preseason ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions, 9-3 and No. 17 in 1998's final poll, are
expected to have to have 36 of its top 44 players back from last
season. The Wildcats will lose six key starters to either
graduation or the pros. Junior offensive lineman Yusuf Scott
recently decided to make himself eligible for the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona accepted the ABC-televised game, its 12th on the 1999
schedule, after Colorado backed out Thursday afternoon. The
Buffaloes apparently withdrew in part because the athletic
department remains unsettled in the wake of a coaching shuffle.
Gary Barnett was hired from Northwestern to succeed Rick Neuheisel,
who left for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great for Arizona football,'' said Wildcats Athletic
Director Jim Livengood, who described the game as preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Preseason or regular season, the game will count in the
strength-of-schedule factor for the Bowl Championship Series
formula. Tomey said strength of schedule was not a consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win all your games, you're going to get there (the
national title) anyway,'' said Tomey, whose 1998 Wildcats were one
loss to UCLA from making a claim on the national crown.
</P>
<P>
   However, Livengood said it could prove to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking ahead or suggesting anything about next year,
but, sure, it's a possibility,'' he said. ``But even without that,
there are all kinds of positives. The national exposure helps
big-time. And I think it's been proven that _ win, lose or draw _
that first game doesn't necessarily hurt you later in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will mark the first meeting between the schools. It
also will be the opener in a 34th season for Penn State Coach Joe
Paterno. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
