<HEADLINE>
HARPER LEAPS INTO LEADER ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Lakers hired themselves
a newcomer to play the part of team leader, designated wise man and
occasional enforcer. But Derek Harper didn't need to waste time
introducing himself.
</P>
<P>
   He took the floor Thursday night at UC Santa Barbara's Robertson
Gym and immediately began barking encouragement and instruction to
his young teammates, who dutifully listened with all the respect
due a 15-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me that's just automatic respect,'' 20-year-old Kobe
Bryant said of Harper. ``I have automatic respect for him because
of all the hard work he's put in with the Knicks and Mavericks....
I'm gonna listen, I'm gonna pick his brain, whatever he has to say.
I think it's good to have a guy like Derek here.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely why executive Jerry West hired the 37-year-old guard.
Harper's been to the finals with the Knicks and everywhere else in
turns with Dallas and Orlando. He came to the Lakers, whose oldest
returning player was enigmatic Elden Campbell (30), knowing his
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's to be the oldest player on the team,'' Harper
quipped. ``But that comes with stability, leadership, to defend
some of the bigger point guards in the Western Conference and
hopefully to help this team win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has doubted the Lakers' talent the past two seasons, but
as they've watched their postseasons end with disastrous series
defeats to the veteran Utah Jazz, the weaknesses have been clear.
Sure, the Lakers could use more reliable perimeter shooting and a
hard-nosed, rebounding power forward, but just as much, they've
needed an experienced leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' Harper said. ``Because the talent's in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   And he didn't wait to let anyone get comfortable with him before
taking control.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys know me, everybody here knows me. They know what
I'm about and where I'm from, so I'm not going to wait until the
season's over to be a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher remains the starting point guard, but Harper will
provide defense off the bench and constant tutoring. Any doubts
about his durability faded with his physical exam _ team doctors
said he's one of the three best-conditioned players in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Harper was in demand this offseason, listening to offers from
Miami, New York and Indiana, among others. All offered the same $1
million salary, but the Lakers had something the other contenders
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the big fella (Shaquille O'Neal). I looked at Shaq
being the dominant piece,'' he said. ``I just liked the opportunity
this team has to win it all. I think this team is ready to make a
move past everybody in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my mind made up (to play for the Lakers). I was sort of
waiting for a call from Jerry (West) to be perfectly honest with
you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In demand: It appears fan bitterness over the lockout has been
overestimated. The Lakers had 16,000 free tickets for their open
scrimmage Wednesday at the Forum, and they were snatched up in
about 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After season tickets, the Lakers had only 3,500 seats left for
next Friday's exhibition vs. the Clippers but, expecting a mad rush
at the box office, chose to donate the seats to youth groups in
Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   A huge turnout is also expected for Monday's 5 p.m. open
scrimmage at UCSB's Thunderdome. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to all Lakers home games go on sale Sunday at the Forum
box office and all TicketMaster outlets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
