<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BYU BACK DOESN'T PICK NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge coach Ron Ponciano got a
phone call late Wednesday that left him flabbergasted.
</P>
<P>
   It was Duke Hall, the uncle of former BYU running back Ronney
Jenkins, saying the junior enrolled at Big Sky rival Northern
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm miffed,'' Ponciano said. ``The communication with that, to
say the least, was extremely poor because you could never talk to
the kid. They never, ever said once they were going to go visit
NAU.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins visited with several CSUN coaches Monday, though
Ponciano was out of town. ``When he comes up and says, `So this is
where you play, huh?,' you kind of figure he may not be our type of
guy,'' Ponciano said. ``When he came back from the visit to NAU,
which they never said he was going on, and it's always so vague,
then what's the real thing going on here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's really worked out nicely. He's going to be proud to
play in (NAU's) facility, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins couldn't be reached at NAU. Hall said he never heard
Jenkins bash CSUN's football facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said it wasn't a certainty Jenkins would have been
academically eligible at CSUN. However, NAU coach Jerome Souers
said Jenkins will participate in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, who ran for 1,307 yards and 12 touchdowns for the
Cougars last season, withdrew from BYU after violating the school's
honor code for what were termed ``sexual transgressions.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jenkins enrolled at CSUN it could have created a logjam in
the backfield. Jaumal Bradley returns for his senior season and
Washington State transfer DeJuan Gilmore is also enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Gahr WR commits: Jamaal Perry, a 5-foot-10, 159-pound receiver
out of Gahr High in Cerritos, gave an oral commitment to attend
CSUN in the fall. He did so during an unofficial visit to CSUN on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay in California, I liked the campus and I liked
the coaches,'' said Perry, who also played defensive back at Gahr.
``The coaches said I have a choice, but I think I'll go line up in
the slot and play receiver. I like catching the ball and running
with it better....''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who also returned kicks, had nine touchdown catches for a
Gahr team that finished 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Another new face on CSUN's campus this spring will be Kennedy
High product Karalus Doyle, who also played at Valley College. He
went to Florida A&AMP;M after Valley College but left school after a
few days and didn't play football. He'll be a walk-on for the
Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He possesses a great deal of speed and he's got size,'' said
Valley coach Gary Barlow. ``He was offered a scholarship to a I-AA
program in Florida A&AMP;M and they made the playoff, so that tell you
the level he can play. I think going away to Florida and seeing
what it takes to succeed at that level will really help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, former Arizona State offensive lineman Craig Sweasy is
expected to enroll at CSUN, but lax academics will keep the
Atascadero High graduate on the sideline for a year. If he meets
academic requirements for the 2000 season, he would have one year
of eligibility remaining. Blue Chip Illustrated selected him as an
All-Region performer at Atascadero.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches cannot comment on recruits until they receive a national
letter of intent.
</P>
<P>
   Colunga to transfer: Ponciano said defensive lineman Mike
Colunga will transfer out of the program because of academic
problems since enrolling at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   Colunga, who spent two seasons at San Bernardino Valley College,
had an injury-riddled season and played in only three games,
registering seven tackles and 1{ sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I'd help him with anything I could,'' Ponciano
said. ``He's looking at some Division II schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said three freshmen, all of whom were red-shirting,
would transfer after poor academic showings. They are linebacker
Alvin Steen and safeties Chris Karibee and Alex Blanco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
