<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIA-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENQVIST SENDS NO. 3-SEEDED RAFTER PACKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to delete last 4 grafs of original and add MATCHPOINTS
section with Saturday game results.) (js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ It is too late for Patrick Rafter to
whisper in the tournament director Paul McNamee's ear about
changing the Australian Open this year. Too late to suggest nicely
_ this is Rafter, after all _ that the hardcourt surface be made
quicker and the balls lighter so that Rafter's serve-and-volley
style can play as well at home as it does in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, it was Thomas Enqvist's turn to remind the third-seeded
Rafter, and the nation that admires him, of his limitations. Along
the way, the straight-talking and flat-hitting Swede reminded the
tennis world that he is playing as well as anyone this January.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter has won the U.S. Open the past two years, but in eight
appearances in Melbourne he has never advanced past the fourth
round. His legs are still powerful, his reflexes still quick and
his hair still a little too long and unkempt for the taste of some
older Australians, yet his game is not quite the same at Melbourne
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the conditions suited him really well, and I think he
played too big and strong for me,'' Rafter said after Enqvist
dismantled him, 6-4, 4-6, 6-4, 6-4. His loss means that Pete
Sampras, who chose to skip this tournament to rest, will remain
No.1 when this Grand Slam event ends.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it was hardly a reaffirming day for the pecking
order. Marc Rosset, a mountain of a man from Switzerland, put an
end to Britain's hopes by defeating sixth-seeded Tim Henman in
straight sets, 7-6 (7-5), 6-3, 7-5. In the night session, in a
match played indoors after the retractable roof on Center Court was
closed because of rain, Wayne Ferreira of South Africa upset
ninth-seeded Richard Krajicek, 6-7 (1-7), 6-7 (5-7), 6-4, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the 16 men's seeded players remain and, for the
first time in Australian Open history, all four top-seeded players
are out at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of top 10 players out there that aren't in the
top 10,'' Rafter said. ``The men's game is very close.
Unfortunately, it's not like women's tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   In years past that observation might have rung true, but Friday
provided plenty of evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   First came Maria Antonio Sanchez Lorenzo's perplexingly lopsided
6-3, 6-0 upset of third-seeded Jana Novotna, the reigning Wimbledon
champion. Then came Chanda Rubin's 7-6 (7-3), 4-6, 6-4 victory over
15th-seeded Natasha Zvereva. Last came Emilie Loit's 7-5, 6-1
defeat of ninth-seeded Conchita Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the attitudes are changing,'' said the 20-year-old
Loit, who admitted she had to stop trembling at 5-0 before closing
out the match. ``I think there is a psychological difference now,
and the more examples there are of players in the top 100 beating
players in the top 10, the more it will keep happening.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a disastrous tournament for the Spanish. Of the 22
Spaniards who came here, including Alex Corretja and the reigning
French Open champions Carlos Moya and Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, only
Sanchez Lorenzo remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy for myself, but I'm a little sad for my
friends,'' said Sanchez Lorenzo, a baseliner ranked 65th who lost
in the first round of every Grand Slam event last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just still in a state of shock,'' said Novotna, who could
not remember when she had last lost a set at love, ``really not
knowing what went wrong, and it was just a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's once-promising career has been derailed since mid-1996
by a broken bone in her right hand, subsequent surgery to remove
part of the bone and six months of rehabilitation. Defeating
Zvereva should help her regain the form that made her a
semifinalist here in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just out here working hard for as long as I can,'' the
30th-ranked Rubin said. ``I feel like I can do as well as I did and
better.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rubin was trading ground strokes with Zvereva, Rosset was
firing huge forehands and first serves at Henman. Rosset's next
opponent, Bohdan Ulihrach of the Czech Republic, is well within the
long reach of the 6-foot-7-inch Swiss. Enqvist's next opponent is
Australia's other main attraction, Mark Philippoussis, who rumbled
past Jan Kroslak of Slovakia, 3-6, 6-3, 6-4, 6-1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   France's SANDRINE TESTUD, the 14th-seeded player, beat SERENA
WILLIAMS, 6-2, 2-6, 9-7, on Saturday. . . . ANNA KOURNIKOVA won
again despite double-digit double faults, securing a 4-6, 6-2, 6-3
victory over Germany's ANDREA GLASS. Kournikova tapped in her first
serve at an average speed of 77 miles an hour and her second serve
at 69 mph, yet could not avoid 14 double faults. Kournikova, the
12th-seeded player, next plays No. 7 MARY PIERCE, a 6-2, 6-2 winner
over Italy's RITA GRANDE. . . . ANDRE AGASSI swept aside JIRI NOVAK
of the Czech Republic, 6-3, 6-2, 6-1, and will play a fellow
American, &UR;  &LR; VINCE SPADEA, in the fourth round. JIM COURIER, a
two-time champion here, injured a groin muscle and had to quit
while trailing by 5-7, 6-4, 6-2, 3-0 against No. 10 YEVGENY
KAFELNIKOV of Russia. Kafelnikov next plays in the Round of 16
against ANDREI PAVEL of Romania, who struggled to knock off the
American newcomer PAUL GOLDSTEIN, 3-6, 6-3, 2-6, 7-5, 6-3. ...
Spadea scored a 6-3, 6-4, 6-4 triumph over MARTIN DAMM of the Czech
Republic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
