<HEADLINE>
SUNS TRY TO STAY POSITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Day 2 of the post-NBA lockout era, the Suns were looking for
a reason _ any reason _ for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   A roster with enough players for a starting lineup _ any lineup
_ was a start.
</P>
<P>
   A great beginning it wasn't. Nevertheless, the Suns signed five
players Friday to bring their roster to seven. It's not exactly the
Magnificent Seven, but it is one step from Thursday, when the Suns
didn't have enough manpower to open training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Between two workouts Friday at America West Arena, their roster
more than doubled. Before the second session, the Suns signed
veteran center Joe Kleine, rookie Toby Bailey, third-year center
Horacio Llamas, second-year swingman Marko Milic and second-year
guard James Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Kleine had been expected. He signed for one
year at $1 million, which is the minimum for a veteran of at least
10 years. Kleine, a Suns center from 1993 through 1997, returns to
Phoenix after spending last season with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe is a great guy in the locker room,'' Suns Coach Danny
Ainge said. ``He's a real vocal guy, and I think we need that. We
have a lot real quiet leaders on our team. They're not vocal. But
Joe is. He's got great experience and played with a lot of very
great teams. His clubhouse leadership will be one of his greatest
assets this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, a second-round draft pick from UCLA, Llamas, Milic and
Collins signed a variety of minimum contracts allowed under the new
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, a 6-foot-4 shooting guard from Florida State, appeared
in 23 games last season for the Los Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' roster figures to grow by at least one more player
today. Veteran swingman George McCloud, a sometime Suns starter
last season, is expected to sign and be in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, he played just about every role,'' Ainge said of
McCloud, who was with Jason Kidd and Rex Chapman Thursday night in
Denver as Antonio McDyess agonized over whether to sign with the
Nuggets or return to Phoenix. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Briefly. . .  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Danny Manning, on his progress from last season's serious knee
injury: ``I'll be ready to play. I've been going out every day.
This is no different. I just go out everyday and see how I feel.
I'm not putting any limitations on myself. I'll play it by ear, day
by day.''
</P>
<P>
   Still waiting: Center Luc Longley was still waiting for the
NBA's official stamp of approval on his deal. The Suns acquired him
from Chicago for Mark Bryant, Martin Muursepp, Bubba Wells and a
conditional first-round draft pick. Longley said the league still
was waiting for a signature from Bulls General Manager Jerry
Krause.
</P>
<P>
   Moving on: John ``Hot Rod'' Williams, a Suns backup center and
McDyess' biggest friend last season, signed a three-year, $5.775
million contract Thursday with the Dallas Mavericks. Six teams were
reported to have interest in the 36-year-old Williams, a 12-year
veteran. He supplants A.C. Green, another former Sun, as the
Mavericks' elder statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Expected additions: Former Puerto Rico Olympian Jose Ortiz and
Milwaukee veteran Jamie Feick are expected in camp today. Feick
appeared in 45 games and averaged 2.3 points for the Bucks last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge was trying very hard to be a happy camper: ``This whole
scenario is one of the strangest experiences I've ever been
involved with. Hopefully, it's something we'll look back and laugh
at. It's getting weirder and weirder all the time. I hope I still
have a sense of humor.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
