<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' FOX STAYS HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ First the lockout, then quibbling NBA
lawyers, then the traffic on the Pacific Coast Highway. Somehow,
Rick Fox's road back to the Los Angeles Lakers seemed filled with
more obstacles than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Fox never wanted to part company with the Lakers after last
season, but everything, it seemed, conspired to keep him from
returning. Right up until Thursday night, when the congested PCH
kept him from attending the team's first training-camp workout at
UC Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox was on the court Friday morning, rejoining the team he
insists he never planned to leave.
</P>
<P>
   There were, again, the other suitors _ including Atlanta, New
York and Seattle _ some dangling more than the $1.75 million the
Lakers could give. Fox listened and that's about all he did.
</P>
<P>
   Once league lawyers set down the final details of a new labor
deal and the lockout was officially over late Wednesday night, Fox
sat down with Lakers executive Jerry West and made arrangements to
resume his Lakers career. A one-year contract for now, hopefully a
multiyear to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really appreciate the appreciation other teams have for me
as a player, but this is home now for me and I'll stay here,'' Fox
said. ``I have unfinished business, not just here but in this
league in general. I have so many goals to accomplish and this is
the best place to get them done.''
</P>
<P>
   He's talking about championships, a goal the Lakers fell short
of last season, leaving Fox tearful and frustrated, even uncertain
whether he'd return. Those doubts faded quickly with the time off.
</P>
<P>
   The long offseason let Fox spend quality and quantity time with
his son, Kyle, in Boston, further his acting career in two movies,
``Resurrection'' and ``The Collectors,'' and meet a new girlfriend,
singer Vanessa Williams.
</P>
<P>
   A Thanksgiving and Christmas with family, for the first time in
15 years, was ``a great experience,'' he said. But Fox is glad the
long vacation is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed the rest,'' Fox admitted, ``but it ate at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as being swept in the conference finals tore at him. Fox
could have made another title run somewhere else but asked if he
ever seriously considered leaving said, ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some (teams) really push hard, and they're teams I would
have played for, if I didn't have this affection for this team and
the goals of going forward with this team. I couldn't turn my back
on that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So for the second straight offseason, Fox singlehandedly gave
meaning to the trite and usually untrue phrase ``it's not about the
money.'' For Fox, who turned down a $20 million deal to sign here
in 1997, it isn't. He's proven that again.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I went through last year made it easier to go through
this year,'' Fox said. ``You turn down offers again, much more
lucrative. But it's staying true to what you believe in.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I know the experience I got out of last year after turning
(the $20 million) down, I was a much more fulfilled basketball
player, much happier about the team I was on and the opportunity to
play for a championship. And it's my honest belief you're rewarded
when you go out and give a good day's effort.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the usual expectation from Fox, the Lakers' starting
small forward last season. He was the only one to play all 82
regular-season games and started all 13 playoff games despite
having to duct-tape himself together for the final six weeks after
suffering a variety of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Del Harris has a variety of options at small forward,
where Robert Horry and Kobe Bryant also figure to spend time. But
he's grateful to have Fox for another run at the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick brings a good all-around game with a lot of toughness.
He's one of the best combinations of nice people who are tough of
any of the athletes I've known,'' Harris said. ``And we like that
about him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
