<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-COHN-NOTEBOOK-AZR     01-23 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COHN-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL JUNKIE MAKES GOOD ON HIS CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona schools are visiting the Oregon schools in the
Pac-10 this week, which makes it a good time to check in with
Valley native Joel Sobotka, the first-year head coach at Portland
State and, at 28, the youngest coach in Division I.
</P>
<P>
   And even if it isn't a good time, we're going to do it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So how's it going, Joel?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. The Vikings are 12-4 overall, 5-1 and tied for
second in the Big Sky Conference behind Northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased,'' Sobotka said. ``The guys are doing a great
job.''
</P>
<P>
   More interesting than Portland State's season, however, is how
Sobotka got here. A basketball junkie predating his Horizon High
School days, Sobotka was an Arizona State basketball manager for
Bill Frieder as recently as 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A '93 ASU grad, Sobotka's official title was video coordinator,
``but I ended up doing all the stuff nobody wanted to do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty incredible when you think about it,'' he said.
``It's all happened pretty fast, but I had a chance to work under
some good people, and I've had a real passion for it. Circumstances
all led to me getting the job, but if I wasn't prepared and ready,
I wouldn't have gotten the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Using contacts such as former ASU assistants George McQuarn, Jim
Phillips and the late Lynn Archibald, Sobotka got to coach at camps
and clinics. He knew former Tempe Corona del Sol High School coach
Sammy Duane and Ritchie McKay, who attended Mesa Westwood High
School and Mesa Community College and who would end up as head
coach at Portland State when the school restored its Division I
program in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sobotka impressed everyone with his knowledge and enthusiasm. He
got a job as an assistant at Eastern Oregon State (junior) College
before returning to ASU for a year to work for Frieder. Then he
joined McKay at Portland State.
</P>
<P>
   After McKay took the head coaching job at Wyoming in August, it
appeared Portland State would hire Rick Adelman, a big name who
used to coach the NBA Portland TrailBlazers. But at the last
minute, the Sacramento Kings hired Adelman and Sobotka got the
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't been able to sit back and enjoy it,'' said
Sobotka, who inherited four starters and has made the most of it.
``I haven't had the chance to think, `Wow, this is overwhelming.'
Every day is a great opportunity. It's so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobotka still is an avid Sun Devils fan, and he still stays in
touch with former players Ike Austin, James Bacon and Wun Versher.
But Stevin ``Hedake'' Smith he can do without. Sobotka was pained
by the point-shaving scandal that led to Frieder's dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard seeing it become a national story,'' he said. ``It
was really discouraging to see the program get tainted like
that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Scary Stanford &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scary, and impressive, thing about Stanford is it can do so
many things to beat you. Take Thursday night, when the supposedly
quickness-challenged Cardinal used its running game to negate a
surprising zone thrown at them by a pretty quick Washington State
team. Stanford outscored the Cougars, 64-29, in the second half and
won, 94-45, for its 12th straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were stagnant in the first half,'' said guard Arthur Lee,
who had 12 points, one of five players to score in double figures
for the Cardinal. ``A zone will make you do that. . . . When we
pushed them out of their zone with the transition game, that was
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve point guard Mike McDonald returned after being sidelined
for a foot injury, and that helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boggles my mind to read some of the stories saying Stanford
is better without him,'' Cougars Coach Kevin Eastman said. ``They
are better with him, no question.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tarnished Bears &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's with California? After beating North Carolina on Dec. 29,
and appearing to emerge as a threat to Stanford, the Golden Bears
are 2-4, including home losses to Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a hint: Guards Geno Carlisle and Thomas Kilgore did not
start against Washington on Thursday because car trouble caused
them to be late for the pre-game shootaround. Kilgore earlier in
the year was suspended for two games for missing a team bus, and
Carlisle did not start, for the first time, last week against
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Coach Ben Braun addressed his team for 30 minutes after the
Washington loss, emphasizing the importance of today's game against
Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to establish an indentity for ourselves,'' Braun
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gag order &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Athletic Director Bob Goin has the solution to deal
with some of the negative publicity surrounding his successful but
morally ambiguous basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   Increase the graduation rate? Ensure there are no more rules
violations, the likes of which got an assistant coach fired? Keep
players out of trouble off the court?
</P>
<P>
   Nah. Goin is urging Coach Bob Huggins to restrict the number of
interviews he gives.
</P>
<P>
   Goin said, ``We've got to do a better job of screening because
of situations like this, the ESPN thing,'' a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ESPN thing'' was a feature on Huggins and the players
title ``Bad News Bearcats.'' An associate sports information
director called it a ``hack job.''
</P>
<P>
   In a printed release, Goin said, ``Bob Huggins . . . has the
right to be interviewed by whatever media outlet he wants to.
However, I have requested that Bob reduce the number of interviews
he does because I want our basketball team to be able to focus on
the remainder of the basketball season.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Big improvement &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Newman was 20-114 as head coach at Sacramento State before
becoming an assistant to Bill Frieder and later the interim head
coach at Arizona State. But that record looks pretty good compared
with that of his successor. Under Tom Abatemarco, the Hornets are
0-15 this year, 1-40 since the start of last season and have lost
32 straight dating to December 1997. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
