<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-STADIUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN SITE COMMITTEE LOST SIGHT OF GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even before the first of nine meetings, many area
residents called Cal State Northridge's site committee a sham,
stacked with proponents for an on-campus stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They were right. The committee was a sham.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was for another reason. The committee didn't do what
it set out to do, which was to recommend a site for a new football
stadium to university president Blenda Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 12-member panel, of which nine were present
Thursday, kept the issue clouded.
</P>
<P>
   They voted to recommend three proposals in a final report to
Wilson: an 8,000-seat stadium on the North Campus, about 75 yards
south of the existing football field; a renovation of Pierce
College as an off-campus site; and to include a residents'
recommendation, which would put a stadium anywhere but on campus.
</P>
<P>
   When CSUN cut four sports (baseball, men's volleyball, men's
soccer and men's swimming) in 1997, Wilson was accused of not
getting enough input before making her final decision. This time,
Wilson set up a committee so all sides would be represented.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was supposed to come up with one site, but under
pressure from the residents decided it would be better not to make
any definitive statement.
</P>
<P>
   That's a disservice and a disgrace. They failed.
</P>
<P>
   If the committee recommended the proposed North Campus site,
lawsuits would have followed, the surrounding community would have
been enraged, but at least a decision would have been reached.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation project at Pierce College? If this was the sole
recommendation it would have caused a revolt among the athletic
department, especially in the football quadrant. But, again, it
would have been a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we get a half-a-year's-worth of wasted time, no
decision, and we arrive at the same spot we were a year ago when it
was announced football needed another location to play for the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   Some decisions were made.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the committee decided some people favor an
on-campus facility and some favor an off-campus site. Of course,
that much was known six months ago. There was also opposition from
the neighboring residents in regards to an on-campus site, which,
again, was known.
</P>
<P>
   The committee meetings should have been used to listen to all
sides, come up with one plan, then try to solve all of the problems
with one site.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't an indictment of committee chairman David Honda
because he was left with no alternative. He didn't vote. He gives
direction, maintains order, but once a motion is made, and then
someone seconds it, there's little else he can do.
</P>
<P>
   This is an indictment of the other committee members _ three of
whom were absent Thursday, though CSUN men's basketball coach Bobby
Braswell had a legitimate reason since his Matadors had a game.
</P>
<P>
   What's bothersome is this committee didn't have the backbone to
be definitive on the most crucial issue regarding the university
and the community.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't want to be the scapegoat for everyone who disagreed
with it, and made it clear that Wilson will be exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   All along Wilson was going to have the final say. All along one
side was going to be enraged with her decision.
</P>
<P>
   The site committee members were supposed to recommend a site,
but ran away from doing their job because they didn't want to be
held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   So when Wilson makes the final decision, either the residents
will be upset, or the proponents of an on-campus stadium will be
upset.
</P>
<P>
   However, the thing people should be angered over is the failure
of the committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
