<SLUG> BC-CAR-SUPERCROSS-LUSK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEROTYPE FAILS TO CAPTURE BIKER  
 CLEAN-CUT LUSK DOES IT HIS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He doesn't have bleached hair, wouldn't know a tattoo parlor
from a paint shop and doesn't have a single pair of baggy pants
hanging in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Ezra Lusk, your non-typical American Motorcyclist
Association Supercross Series riding stick-in-the-mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, I have a certain image that I try to live up
to, and I think it's to be a clean-cut, hard-working and determined
rider,'' Lusk said. ``I think it's a good image, one that
represents myself and represents Team Honda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how other people dress. There's nothing wrong it.
It's just not me.''
</P>
<P>
   So if you're expecting Lusk to arrive at Bank One Ballpark
tonight fitted with a shiny nose ring, the chances are greater that
Dennis Rodman will divorce Carmen Electra and marry Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ezra is a blue-collar guy,'' supercross spokesman Pat Schutte
said. ``He's not really outspoken and kind of likes to be low key.
But . . .''
</P>
<P>
   But on the racetrack, wow.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lusk doesn't ride with the flash and pizazz of a Jeremy
McGrath (who does?), he is one of the sport's most technically
efficient riders.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Lusk knows how to win.
</P>
<P>
   Despite riding for much of last season with a fractured left
hand and a separated right shoulder, Lusk still had a career-high
four wins and a runner-up finish to McGrath, a five-time champion,
in the final standings.
</P>
<P>
   Lusk is off to an even better start this season, winning the
season opener at Anaheim two weeks ago and following it up with
another win last week at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Lusk won last year's Valley race, when it was held at Sun Devil
Stadium in front of a crowd in excess of 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   A similar turnout is expected at BOB, which has impressed riders
seeing the facility for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome,'' said Yamaha rider Jimmy Button, who attended
Greenway High School and now lives in Tuscany Hills, Calif. ``My
parents still live here and have (Diamondbacks) season tickets.
They told me it was something special. Now I believe them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Campbell, a rider from Apache Junction, also was getting his
first inside look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've passed it before, but I didn't know what it was like
inside,'' Campbell said. ``It's great. I think the course is going
to be a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Button believes the layout has the potential to entice better
racing than Sun Devil.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Arizona State University) was a tight course,'' Button said.
``I could be wrong, but I think (BOB's course) is more open and
makes for better passing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Lusk has to worry about making a lot of passes.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had to rally past two riders in the closing stages
at San Diego, one of the keys to Lusk's early success has been
quick starts, meaning he hasn't had to fight through congested
traffic to get up front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honda's given me a good bike, but other than that, I haven't
done anything different with my starts,'' said Lusk, who leads
Honda teammates Mike LaRocco and Mickael Pichon in the standings.
``If anything, I'm taking it a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I felt like I pushed the edge a whole bunch, and
that probably had a little bit to do with the reason I didn't stay
healthy. I told myself I wasn't going to do that this year, and
I've pretty much had two great races.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, I'll have to start pushing the edge, but not as
much as the other riders because they're having to chase me instead
of my having to chase them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, everyone expects to be chasing Lusk and McGrath for
the title. Even Lusk admits McGrath, the defending champion and
winner of five of the past six titles, is the rider he most has to
fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jeremy will be the toughest guy,'' Lusk said. ``I know
there's a couple of other guys that will be pushing us, too, but I
don't expect them to all be up there every weekend like Jeremy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy is still the guy you have to beat.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 0216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
