<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5393 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRL-BOAT-AZR &LR;      01-23 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-BOAT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOAT HAS CATCHING UP TO DO  
 SEEKS TO REDEEM SUBPAR '98 SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly hoarse from repeatedly thanking A.J. Foyt for unlocking
the Indy Racing League door three years ago, Billy Boat wants to
thank the legendary car owner one more time.
</P>
<P>
   With a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Teammate) Kenny (Brack) won it last season,'' said Boat, who
won at Texas Motor Speedway last season. ``I think I can do the
same. But for us to be championship contenders, we need to be
finishing more races.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest downfall of our program last year. We
just flat didn't finish enough races. That's the part I was most
disappointed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a broken left femur and a fractured pelvis, injuries Boat
suffered in a June crash at New Hampshire International Speedway,
didn't bother Boat as much as the failed finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that happened last year was after I came
back from being (injured), I felt like I was way behind and I was
always trying to play catch-up,'' said Boat, who lives in Glendale.
``So, at times, I probably pushed the car too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely crashed too much. A lot of it was because
(someone else was at fault). Some of it wasn't. But the way I look
at, this is a new year and everybody is starting from a clean sheet
of paper. We're back at ground zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Liftoff is Sunday in the IRL season opener at Walt Disney World
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Today marks the start of qualifying, something Boat was terrific
at in 1998, when he captured a series-high six poles.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as Boat already has defined, was finishing what he
had started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had any trouble going fast,'' Boat said. ``Our
trouble was finishing races. (Foyt) and I had a conversation during
the off-season, but it's not like there's any pressure on me. A.J.
let's you drive at your own pace. It's not like I have to prove
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the bottom line in racing is you want to take the
checkered flag. If you're not doing that, you have a lot of room
for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you want to be in contention for the championship, the
way to do that is through consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat could name several racetracks he'd rather begin that quest
at than the tricky 1-mile tri-oval in Lake Buena Vista, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the setting, some drivers have referred to the
course as ``Mickey Mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat won't go that far, but he does admit to not yet quite
figuring out the quickest route from Point A to Point B.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the easiest racetrack to race on or set your car
up,'' Boat said. ``It's almost impossible to run side by side in
the corners, unlike Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick to making your car go fast at Disney is making your
car turn in Turn 1, where it has a tendency to push the front end
(toward the outer wall), but also make it comfortable in Turn 2. If
your car is too loose in Turn 2, you feel like you're always trying
to save your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your car is too good in Turn 1, that means you're probably
going to be too loose in Turn 2. So you have to compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat isn't the only driver familiar to Walt Disney's
difficulties. Brack also has been victimized, finishing 13th in
last year's race.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last season's dismal start, Brack rebounded, winning
three straight races at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not have known too much about me last year, but I
think they know I can drive,'' said Brack, a native of Sweden.
``And I know it will be hard to win another title, but I don't
think it will be harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good team. We all get along great. I like where I'm
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Brack means it. After last season's championship
run, he said he received several driving offers from non-IRL teams,
turning thumbs down to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably had three real good offers, but I can't tell you
which (series),'' Brack said. ``I'll leave that private. But they
were with race-winning teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Team Foyt returning intact can only mean trouble to everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, there's a lot of good teams out there,'' Boat
said. ``You can never count out (Team Menard). They lost Tony
Stewart (to NASCAR Winston Cup racing), and there may be a little
bit of a learning curve (with new driver Greg Ray) to get back to
where they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``But (Ray) is a good driver, and that team has good
equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt also has provided Boat and Brack with good equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Brack proved it last season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Boat says, it's his turn. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 0217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
