<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA_WADE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY PAIR CHOOSE WILDCATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Avondale Westview High School's Andrae Thurman started with
Arizona in mind. Desert Vista's Bobby Wade began with Arizona State
in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the best of friends and competitors since fifth
grade kept an open mind about both programs when deliberating their
football futures. Wade,`` The Arizona Republic'' player of the
year, ended up seeing what Thurman felt from the get-go.
</P>
<P>
   Verifying what Wade told ``The Republic'' earlier this week, he
and Thurman made oral commitments to Arizona official by calling a
news conference Friday at Desert Vista.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Tomey?'' Thurman asked after Wade dialed Arizona Coach
Dick Tomey on a cellular phone. ``How's it going? Me and Bobby
would like to tell you that we're coming to U of A.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantastic,'' Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt. Tomey is getting two of the most coveted state
recruits. Both said ASU was a runner-up, ahead of Colorado and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Wade, 5 feet 10, 180 pounds, set a Class 5A single-season record
with 41 touchdowns off 1,614 rushing yards and 720 receiving yards.
He scored the go-ahead touchdown in the fourth quarter of three
state playoff games on the Thunder's march to the 5A title.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman, 6 feet 1, 170 pounds, came off a 13-interception junior
season to star on offense as a senior, where he turned 52 catches
into 913 yards and 11 touchdowns. Thurman was UA's only prep
receiver recruit and Wade said he was promised a shot at tailback
even though several suitors liked him at defensive back, where he
had 12 interceptions and led his team in solo tackles as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, I always wanted to go to school with (Thurman),''
said Wade, who was hosted by Ortege Jenkins on his campus visit
last weekend. ``It just so happened everything was perfect at U of
A.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really had a belief in me to at least give me a chance to
play tailback. (Other schools) weren't giving me a chance to play
where my heart is. If I work hard enough and get my size up, I can
be a great collegiate back.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade and Thurman played freshman football together at Westview
before Wade transferred to the Ahwatukee Foothills area school.
They became such good friends that they got Wade's father, Robert,
and Thurman's mother, Trisha, dating.
</P>
<P>
   Wade and Thurman can sign national letters of intent on Feb. 3. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
