<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     01-23 1702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-CHRISTIANS (Jarsol, India) _ India has a long history of
deadly clashes between its dominant Hindu majority and its sizable
Muslim minority, but in the past year there have been more attacks
on Christians, who make up only 2.3 percent of the nation's
population. By Celia W. Dugger. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TERROR (Washington) _ Seeking to muster public support
for a large increase in federal spending to defend against
unconventional terrorist attack, Clinton on Friday appeared with
top government health and law enforcement officials to announce
steps to strengthen domestic defenses against biological, chemical
and computer warfare. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-LOBBYING (Washington) _ Richard Holbrooke, Clinton's
choice to be the top U.S. diplomat at the United Nations, denied on
Friday that he had violated federal lobbying laws, the issue that
has held up his nomination since the summer. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SALINAS (Mexico City) _ MEXICO CITY _ The verdict that
sentenced Raul Salinas de Gortari, brother of the former president
of Mexico, to prison for 50 years for masterminding an
assassination sent the strongest signal yet that the political
elite is no longer beyond the reach of justice. But the ruling did
not resolve troubling doubts about the weak and tainted case on
which it was based. A news analysis. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POPE (Mexico City) _ Thousands of glinting lights,
reflections of mirrors held up by Mexican followers, welcomed Pope
John Paul II's plane as he arrived in Mexico Friday to address
Latin and North America as a whole. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-UNREST (Jakarta) _ In the worst violence in Indonesia
since May, 45 people have died in four days of rioting between
Muslims and Christians on the island of Ambon, local officials said
Friday. With map.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The Security Council, divided by
radically differing Russian and U.S. proposals for dealing with
Iraq, began discussion Friday of a ``third way'' proposed by
Canada. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina) _ Western powers warned the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, that simply allowing the head of the
international monitoring mission to remain in Kosovo is not enough
to avoid the threat of NATO air strikes. By Steven Erlanger. With
map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARK-TORNADOES (Little Rock, Ark.) _ The storm system rose out of
Texas and Oklahoma and crossed into Arkansas on Thursday. By the
time it exhausted itself, the tornadoes it spawned had killed seven
people. An additional person was killed in Tennessee. By Steve
Barnes. With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ORGAN-SHORTAGE (New York) _ The number of donations of vital
organs used for transplants in critically ill patients has reached
dangerously low levels, transplant experts said on Friday,
resulting in the deaths of at least three patients in recent weeks
who would likely have survived if they received liver transplants.
By Jennifer Steinhauer. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCE-OF-WHALES (Boston) _ Richard Max Strahan, self-titled
``Prince of Whales,'' is a longtime radical campaigner whose
solicitation table covered with graphic photographs of bloody
whales injured by ships or fishing gear is a fixture in Boston
gathering spots, and who has himself become a self-representing
fixture in the Boston courts. But Strahan is better known as Mad
Max, in part for his tendency to lash out at anyone who disagrees
with him. By Carey Goldberg. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ With a small, but increasingly important
number of Republicans expressing doubts about the wisdom of calling
witnesses, the Senate's senior Democrat, Robert C. Byrd, the
leading institutional voice of the Senate, said President Clinton's
impeachment trial should come to an end and said witnesses would
add nothing to the process. By Lizette Alvarez and Frank Bruni.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ Assuming a more active role,
senators posed questions to defense and prosecution teams for the
first time on Friday, producing the semblance of debate in the
impeachment trial of President Clinton. By R.W. Apple Jr. With
photos.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEWINSKY (Washington) _ Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, sought an emergency court order Friday to compel Monica
Lewinsky to submit to interviews over the weekend by House
prosecutors in President Clinton's impeachment trial. By David
Stout.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCHOLARS (Undated) _ After the White House completed
arguments this week, experts on impeachment said the president's
lawyers have offered constitutional and factual arguments powerful
enough to counter the momentum of the House's case and blunt the
effort to call witnesses. By William H. Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ What had been designed to be a
question-and-answer time for senators who swore an oath to be
impartial jurors in President Clinton's impeachment trial turned on
Friday into rebuttal time for the opposing legal teams. A news
analysis. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-GAYS (Washington) _ Five years after the Clinton
administration adopted its ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy for
homosexuals in the military, the armed services discharged more
homosexuals last year than in any year since 1987. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS (Washington) _ Jim Nicholson overcame an energetic
challenge and was overwhelming re-elected as chairman of the
Republican National Committee on Friday after pleas from his
supporters that he should not be blamed for the party's
discouraging performance in last November's election. By Richard L.
Berke. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-ROE (Washington) _ As an estimated 100,000 abortion
opponents paraded past the White House Friday calling President and
Mrs. Clinton murderers, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton denounced
violence against abortion practitioners as ``domestic terrorism''
and said the Clinton administration would propose spending $4.5
million in next year's federal budget to improve safety at abortion
clinics. By Katharine Q. Seelye. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-INVEST (Undated) _ A look at the delirium surrounding
investing in Internet stocks. By Edward Wyatt and David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-GREETINGCARDS (Boulder, Colo.) _ Blue Mountain Arts has
vaulted to the top of the fierce world of e-commerce by offering
online greeting cards. Its site is now the Web's most popular
shopping stop. By Leslie Kaufman. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Paul Maritz, the third-highest
executive at Microsoft and a principal architect of the company's
Windows and Internet software strategy, which the government says
is illegal, denied its illegality in his 160-page testimony. By
Steve Lohr. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTV-PRIMESTAR (Undated) _ In a deal that represents further
consolidation in the direct-to-home cable industry, Hughes' DirecTV
has agreed to buy troubled Primestar, the medium-power
direct-to-home satellite company, for $1.8 billion in cash and
General Motors stock. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ As our marathon culture war reaches its
catharsis in Washington, it may be Hollywood's turn to provide the
farcical coup de grace. The talk here is that ``Saving Private
Ryan'' might lose the Best Picture Oscar to a movie drenched in sex
(and lies about sex) whose lovable hero shamelessly cheats on the
wife and kids he's left at home. The dark horse, of course, is
``Shakespeare in Love.'' By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEILBRONER-ECONOMISTS (Undated) _ Ask economists in the baby
boom generation why they became economists, and any number will
give some credit to Robert L. Heilbroner. So it is somewhat
surprising to find Heilbroner increasingly critical of the
economists he helped inspire. They have missed the point, he says.
By Louis Uchitelle. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-J (Undated) _ In unscrambling the puzzle of the books
attributed to Moses, scholars have identified four narratives by
letters _ J, E, P, D. Now, after a dozen years of research, Richard
Elliott Friedman, a professor of Hebrew and comparative literature
at the University of California at San Diego, has tantalizingly
argued that the J narrative comprises a ``hidden book'' that is
nearly 3,000 years old and that runs from Genesis to the First Book
of Kings. By Gustav Niebuhr. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ON-THE-ROAD (Undated) _ Consider them latter-day nomads. Or
maybe, come to think of it, more like venerable turtles, who carry
their homes on their backs. They are the hundreds of thousands of
elderly and retired people who take to life on the road, spending
all or much of the year wandering around North America in assorted
trailers, converted buses, campers and motor homes. By Tom Chaffin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SCANDAL (Undated) _ Another member of the International
Olympic Committee, Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi of Libya, resigned,
and the trail of Olympic corruption extended to Sydney's securing
of the 2000 Summer Games. A top Australian Olympic official has
acknowledged offering $35,000 apiece to two IOC members from Africa
the night before Sydney defeated Beijing by two votes to secure the
Games, according to a report on Saturday in The Sydney Morning
Herald. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS (Purchase, N.Y.) _ The Knicks held their second
official workout, and their first with Sprewell. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
