u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNBIZ-FINAL-BUDGET-N     01-23 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBIZ-FINAL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 24 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELIMINATE: BIZ-DIARY. ADD: BIZ-UNIVERSAL-SAVINGS.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will send the following Money
and Business articles for release Sunday, Jan. 24, 1999:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE SECTION FRONT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KELLOGG-CEREAL (Battle Creek, Mich.) _ Lately, the Kellogg
company's attempts to revive its stagnant breakfast business have
been about as successful as trying to freshen soggy cereal with
more milk. Now, key investors are out of patience, senior-level
executives have left in frustration and some shareholders wonder if
the best bet may well be to sell the storied but beleaguered
business. The board, meanwhile, is mired in conflicts, and the
company still operates in the shadow of the quirks of its
idiosyncratic founder. By Dana Canedy and Reed Abelson. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic and Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CARMAKERS-SALES (Tulsa, Okla.) _ The carmakers are out to
overhaul how they sell cars, and how Americans buy them. Ford is
going farthest, buying up dealerships in mid-size cities, entering
into joint ventures with leading dealers and thereby gaining
control over the car-buying experience. Here is the view from Tulsa
and Oklahoma City, which of all places is the cutting edge. By
Keith Bradsher. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic and Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (New York) _ A weekly feature looking at
developments of the market worldwide. By Gretchen Morgenson.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-PROFILE-NEUPERT (Undated) _ Profile of Peter Neupert, CEO of
Drugstore.com. By Matt Richtel. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BRIEFS (Undated) _ A weekly column of short items on people
and personalities that make business more than a dollars and cents
proposition. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-GRASSROOTS (Irvine, Calif.) _ Grassroots business column:
Irvine, Calif., and other Nerdistans. Joel Kotkin. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-UNIVERSAL-SAVINGS (Undated) _ In his State of the Union
address and, again, before a roaring crowd in Buffalo, N.Y.,
President Clinton last week floated the idea of Universal Savings
Accounts, a new type of subsidized savings for low- and
moderate-income workers akin to a 401(k) plan. The government would
use 11 percent of the projected budget surplus to match money the
workers would save on their own in the USAs. By Leslie Wayne.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Unndated) _ Economic view column: Two economists
who are during battle in the Microsoft trial. By Michael M.
Weinstein. (Moved).
