<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5423 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLYWOOD-BLACKLIST-R     01-23 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-BLACKLIST-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FREES THE HOLLYWOOD ONE
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ On an evening this March, the ailing, 89-year-old
Elia Kazan, one of America's greatest film and theatrical
directors, is scheduled to receive an honorary Oscar at the 71st
annual Academy Awards. It will not only crown Kazan's career but,
in many ways, spell the end of the tormented legacy of the
Hollywood blacklist.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan was unanimously selected Jan. 7 by the 39-member board of
the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, which has given
honorary Oscars in the past to such icons as Buster Keaton,
Satyajit Ray, Greta Garbo, Orson Welles and Akira Kurosawa. What
was surprising about this latest decision, which came after an
impassioned speech by Karl Malden, a long-time Kazan colleague, was
that there was no dissent.
</P>
<P>
   For decades Kazan has symbolized the darkest moment of the
blacklist, when friend informed on friend before the House
Un-American Activities Committee, which was zealously looking for
communist influence in Hollywood. On April 10, 1952, Kazan, a top
Broadway director with an important film career, informed on eight
old friends from the Group Theater who, along with him, had once
belonged to the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lee J. Cobb, Burl Ives, Jerome Robbins and other
prominent entertainment figures also named names, none had quite
the success or fame of Kazan. Nor were they as criticized as he
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was about time to honor him,'' said Malden,
who met Kazan in 1937 when both worked at the Group Theater, and
later starred in ``On the Waterfront'' and other films by Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there'd be a slugfest,'' he added. ``They all voted
to give him the award.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, angry dissent among some blacklisted
screenwriters over giving an Oscar to Kazan at the March 21
ceremony. But what seems most surprising about the overall response
to the Academy's announcement is how muted it has been. The
emotions and fury that stamped the blacklist days and lingered for
decades finally seem to have faded.
</P>
<P>
   In Kazan's case, his advanced years may be a reason for the
change _ many of his adversaries are dead _ and his extraordinary
record is impossible to ignore. He was the nation's most
significant postwar theatrical director, and his film classics also
include ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' ``Viva Zapata!'' and ``East
of Eden.''
</P>
<P>
   New debate about the Cold War and a recent spate of books have
also muted opinions about Kazan. New scholarship has persuaded many
people that icons of the left like Alger Hiss and Julius Rosenberg
were probably Soviet spies.
</P>
<P>
   Although adamant that injustice was done in convicting Hiss and
Rosenberg, the writer and editor Victor Navasky acknowledged some
ambivalence about the Kazan award.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it's a human thing,'' said Navasky, publisher of
The Nation and author of ``Naming Names'' (Viking, 1980), a book
about the Hollywood blacklist. ``He's not physically well and he
made this great cinematic contribution. Second is, with the passage
of time, some of the passions have cooled and things are being put
in a different perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason was the collapse of the Soviet Union, he said,
and the release of archives that tempered many historians' harsh
view of American anti-communism, a new trend. ``There's something
in the air that's a reaction against the historical revisionism of
the 1960s, 1970s and 1980s, which said that America was a
contributor to the Cold War, too,'' Navasky said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Navasky and historian Allen Weinstein, who interpret
anti-communism very differently, separately mentioned Dalton
Trumbo, a prominent blacklisted writer, and said that Trumbo summed
up their feelings about the Kazan case. ( Weinstein's current book,
``The Haunted Wood,'' with Alexander Vassiliev, details Soviet
espionage in this country until the early days of the Cold War.)
</P>
<P>
   Trumbo told the Screenwriters Guild's Laurel Awards dinner in
1970 that the blacklist was marked by ``bad faith and good, honesty
and dishonesty, wisdom and stupidity, good and bad on both sides.''
He cautioned the audience not to ``search for villains and heroes
or saints or devils because there were none: there were only
victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Schrecker, a history professor at Yeshiva University and
author of ``Many Are the Crimes: McCarthyism in America'' (Little,
Brown, 1998), which is hostile to anti-communism, said she could
see why Hollywood could honor Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I certainly don't approve of what Kazan did during
the McCarthy period,'' Professor Schrecker said, ``one can maybe
learn a lesson from Bill Clinton and compartmentalize, and separate
Kazan, the informer, and Kazan, the artist.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Kazan's case complicated, though, seems to be his
personality. After testifying, Kazan took out an ad in The New York
Times justifying his action _ several blacklisted writers still
talk about the ad _ and he remains steadfast in his convictions. In
his ad, the director denounced communism as a ``dangerous and alien
conspiracy,'' and said that ``liberals must speak out.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1988 memoirs, Kazan said he acted honorably in naming
names and would do so again. He said American communists and their
supporters did not speak out against Stalin's atrocities. ``I
remember those things and I'm glad I was on the other side,'' he
said. Kazan was one of many, including the scholars Edmund Wilson
and Irving Howe, who believed that the Communist Party had a
ruinous effect on film, theater and the wider culture.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan's defenders say it's absurd to say that he personally
destroyed careers because he named names that the committee already
knew.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the hard feelings have not completely disappeared. Walter
Bernstein, author of the memoir, ``Inside Out'' (Knopf 1996), about
his years as a blacklisted screenwriter, said of Kazan: ``The
committee had all the names. They didn't need the names. They
needed  &UR; your &LR;  name. They needed Kazan's name. They needed him. He
made a choice. He did a bad thing. He hurt other people in the
profession. He went over to the side of people who were bigots and
racists and gave them his name and his eminence, which was
considerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Polonsky, another prominent blacklisted writer, spoke
with outrage:``Has he ever said, `Gee, I'm sorry. I shouldn't have
done that. I was wrong.' Others have said it. He didn't. If he
said, `I did a bad thing and I'm sorry I did it,' no one would care
anymore!''
</P>
<P>
   But these men are in the minority these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time passes and wounds heal, things lose their passion,'' said
Jeanine Basinger, chairwoman of the Film Studies department at
Wesleyan University, which is curator of Kazan's papers. ``People
look at the mess we have now _ the imperfection in sports heroes,
the imperfection in politicians. Who is anyone to judge how they
would have behaved back then?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
