<HEADER>
A5424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      01-23 1838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Jan. 24:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FEMALE-SUICIDE (Lutou, China) _ Female suicide is the
puzzling plague of rural China, making the country's rate the
highest in the world; the overall suicide rate is also one of the
highest. In the last few years, a small group of government
officials, researchers, health workers and women's advocates in
China have gingerly started to research and confront what is still
so often regarded as a sensitive and embarrassing problem. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal. With photo, map and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POPE (Mexico City) _ John Paul II urged the Bishops of
North and South America gathered here to take better care of the
poor. But sounding a new and somewhat uncharacteristic note, the
Pope also instructed them to minister to the rich. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-SCANDAL (LAUSANNE, Switzerland) - Behind police
barricades, accused members of the International Olympic Committee
on Saturday pleaded their cases in attempt to avoid expulsion for
misconduct in the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ASSASSINATION (Johannesburg) _ A high-level official of
a South African multiracial political party, the United Democratic
Movement, was assassinated Saturday, riddled with bullets as he
left a grocery store near his home. With the campaign for South
Africa's second national elections just gearing up, the killing of
the official, Sifiso Nkabinde, once again raises questions about
whether political violence will return as the vote approaches. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-PENSIONERS (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ Millions of retired
government workers across Brazil are watching the financial crisis
that is enveloping Latin America's largest economy tear the first
breaches in the social contract that has shaped their lives. What
else, they wonder, will be open to question in the new scheme of
things? ``You work really hard, and what is it for? Just to worry
at the end of your life?'' said Djalma da Silva Rodrigues, who
worked for the Federal Revenue department for 38 years. By Diana
Jean Schemo. With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV (Moscow) _ His boss is back in the hospital, his
budget for 1999 is dismissed as unrealistic, the economy is sure to
get worse and the International Monetary Fund is still playing hard
to get. For Prime Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov of Russia, now four
months in office, the new year has yet to bring good news. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-RECOVERY (Seoul, South Korea) _ A bit more than a year
after South Korea had to accept a humiliating bailout from the
International Monetary Fund, it is showing signs of crawling back
from the abyss. Unemployment rates are still rising, and the
economic misery is widespread, but there is a growing conviction
that South Korea has already bottomed out and may now help lead the
way for Asia out of the economic crisis. By Cheryl WuDunn. With
photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-INTERROGATIONS (Jerusalem) _ For the first time, Israel's
Supreme Court is weighing the legality of methods of interrogations
used by the Shin Bet security service against hundreds of
Palestinian suspects every year. The spectacle of nine judges
considering these methods, which have been called torture by the
United Nations, Amnesty International and other human rights
groups, was extraordinary, and is unparalleled in other countries.
By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-KURD-LEADER (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Many Turks recently have
been playing a variation of a popular parlor game: Where's Apo? The
Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan, widely known as Apo, is
Turkey's most wanted fugitive. He left Italy eight days ago after a
stay of more than six weeks, but nobody seems to know where he
went. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN (Cairo) _ King Hussein of Jordan is preparing to
name one of his sons as his heir, Jordanian officials said today,
culminating a dizzying week in which the King returned from six
months of cancer treatment abroad and then dismissed his brother as
Crown Prince. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-MEDICINE (Salt Lake City) _ As a nurse turned computer
systems manager, Laureen West is one of a crowd of consultants able
to describe how year-2000 computer malfunctions could interrupt the
distribution of medicines. But as a brain tumor patient who needs
daily doses of synthetic-thyroid and other drugs to stay alive, the
43-year-old Mrs. West has no rivals when it comes to convincing
listeners that it matters. By Barnaby J. Feder. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICS-CURRICULUM (Undated) _ For generations of high school
students, the sequence of science has been a given: 9th-grade
biology, 10th-grade chemistry and, for the minority who make it
that far, 11th-grade physics. But that sequence, established a
century ago when science was a simpler matter, is now being
questioned, with a growing number of scientists and educators
arguing that physics ought to come first. By Tamar Lewin. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   NATURALIST-EAGLES (Rockport, Wash.) For the 229 bald eagles that
Libby Mills counted last Wednesday, the eight-mile stretch of the
Skagit River between here and Marblemount is the four-star,
all-you-can-eat sushi bar of Washington's waterways. By Tina
Kelley. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ A federal judge Saturday ordered
Monica S. Lewinsky to submit to an interview with the independent
counsel on behalf of House prosecutors, drawing a bitter White
House attack on their effort to force Ms. Lewinsky's cooperation.
The decision by Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, issued moments before
senators resumed a second day of questioning in President Clinton's
impeachment trial, ignited a furious question-and-answer session on
the Senate floor. By Eric Scmitt.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-JONES-LAWYERS (Washington) _ Some of the most serious
damage to Bill Clinton's presidency came not from his high-profile
political enemies but from a small secret clique of lawyers in
their 30s who share a deep antipathy toward the president,
according to nearly two dozen interviews and recently filed court
documents. By Don Van Natta Jr. and Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Washington) _ With the trial of President
Clinton moving into an unscripted period of critical votes, an
increasingly restless Senate is searching anxiously for a way to
bring the impeachment proceedings to a swift conclusion. But the
parties Saturday appeared sharply divided over how to do this. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-FITZGERALD (Washington) _ Sen. Peter G. Fitzgerald,
R-Ill., had expected to spend his first weeks in Congress finding
an apartment, hiring a staff and drafting the bills he had promised
to voters during the campaign. Instead, he celebrated his arrival
here by digging up his Dartmouth College American history textbook
to brush up on those 18th and 19th century presidents whose names
are echoing around the marble halls of his new workplace. By Adam
Nagourney. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BIBLE-BELT (Pendleton, S.C.) _ In this stretch of the
Bible Belt where highways are punctuated with billboards about
``Heaven. Hell. The Choice Is Yours,'' it has been one hellish bad
week. What hurts most is the impeachment trial in Washington. But
almost as hurtful are Clinton's soaring approval ratings. ``Either
the pollsters are asking the wrong questions or this country is so
wrong morally that we are going down the tubes,'' complained Johnny
Landreth Jr., as he ate a fried-chicken lunch beneath the ``No
Swearing'' sign at Bill's Cafe on Highway 76. By Blaine Harden.
With map.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LINCOLN (Washington) _ Sen. Blanche Lincoln seems
anxious to show she is not in the tank for her fellow Democrat and
Arkansan, President Clinton; over and over, in an interview in her
office last week, she volunteered that she was trying to make good
on her oath of impartiality. By Melinda Henneberger. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CALIFORNIA (Washington) _ California has always been
critical in the presidential equation. But by moving up its primary
to join New York and eight other states on March 7 in 2000,
California's primary holds life-threatening powers over
underfinanced campaigns that are still forming. While that might
suggest an urgent need to organize and tap financial sources, Vice
President Al Gore appears to be the only aspirant from either party
who has amassed a powerful array of support at this early juncture
of the 2000 campaign. And the advantage appears compelling. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-RUSSIA (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright embarks Sunday on a trip to a weakened but obstinate
Russia, with little expectation on either side that much
improvement will be made in a relationship plagued by disagreement
on everything from Russia's economic collapse to air strikes
against Iraq. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY-STOCKS (Washington) _ A proposal by President
Clinton to invest some portion of Social Security reserves in
stocks ignited a brushfire of criticism last week. But lawyers,
administrators and scholars point out that stock investments by
governments and their agencies are neither new nor rare. And those
investments have not, they say, created the widespread problems
critics predict. By Diana B. Henriques. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd on what the scene in the
White House might be like if the Senate drops the impeachment
charges against the president: ``Now we know what the definition of
`is' is,'' Clinton roared with a grin. ``I is off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
