<HEADER>
A5447 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENIOR-ROMANCE-2ndTak     01-23 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-ROMANCE-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES:   a great couple.'' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Older people _ women especially _ often have a hard time finding
an opposite-sex companion.
</P>
<P>
   At age 65, there are about 150 women for every 100 men,
according to Butler of the International Longevity Center. And
because women live longer, and men seek younger women, ``it's a
double-whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They do have to be aggressive when they want to find
someone,'' he said, and mentioned ``the casserole brigade'' _ the
onslaught of women who bring food to comfort and socialize with
recently widowed older men they know.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Loren G. Lispon, chief of the University of Southern
California's division of geriatric medicine, said he's ``seen
situations in retirement housing where some of the older men are
hounded to death, almost, by women.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the main obstacles to relationships among seniors is the
memory of a dead spouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard psychologically _ are you being disloyal to your
mate? You have to overcome that,'' Lispon said. And sometimes the
guilt or suspicion about a relationship comes from children who ask
``Is she after his money, is he after her money, what is this all
about? _ When it's probably much more innocent, about companionship
and affection.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothman and Alexander were not looking for a companion when they
came to the Jewish Home's Eisenberg Village campus.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman had cared for his wife, Sally, for years after
Alzheimer's disease made him a stranger to her. When she died March
16, 1997, he moved from their house in Sherman Oaks to the seniors
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``God sent me here. Otherwise I'd have been all alone in the
world, in a seven-room house with a bunch of fruit trees,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But when he arrived, ``I was very lonely, depressed. I never met
anybody here that interested me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go to my room and sit in my rocker all day long,''
gazing at a picture of Sally he kept above the television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to look at it and I'd start crying,'' he said. ``I
stayed in my room crying practically every day. I couldn't eat, I
lost weight.''
</P>
<P>
   After three months of that, he spotted Florence Alexander in the
dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Of course he remembers the date: June 23, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Already widowed once at age 37, Alexander lost her second
husband, Norman, about 10 years ago. It was her first day at
Eisenberg Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat down,'' she said. ``Our eyes met and he moved over,
and we've been friends and lovers ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first met, it was just a friendly situation,'' Rothman
said. ``Then we got closer and closer.''
</P>
<P>
   And when did they fall in love?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't realize it,'' Rothman said. ``It just grows and
grows. It's just something that happens over time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very, very fortunate to have found each other,'' she
said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Once seniors do hook up, they face other challenges to
courtship and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Arthritis and other infirmities common to old age can can cause
difficulties, not to mention erectile impotency or lubrication
problems. But the Aging Council survey showed that 63 percent of
sexually active seniors were able to perform consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when they do occur, such obstacles to intercourse don't
necessarily deter intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Birren, director of the Anna and Harry Borun Center for
Gerontological Studies at the University of California, Los
Angeles, said some married couples get closer as they age, even if
they're less sexually active. They may spend more time together,
talk more and engage in other activities more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are much closer as a couple, but the physical aspect of
sex has dropped off,'' he said. ``Some of these people are more
content with their later life, but it no longer has to involve sex.
Young people may have physical sex, but it may not be intimate
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In your youth, it's sex that draws you,'' Rothman said. ``At
this stage of the game, it's a different kind of love entirely.
It's not just looking for sex. You look more for companionship. It
brings you closer together and you become like one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lispon, of USC, said an older person starting a relationship
after 10 years alone ``acts no differently than a teenybopper in
her first relationship. Our bodies may be decaying, but our spirit
remains the same.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about what attracted them to each other, Rothman and
Alexander mention reasons ranging from their loneliness after
losing their spouses to the undefinable ``chemical attraction''
they said they felt when they first laid eyes on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's nice looking. He dresses beautifully. He's very
affectionate. I love when he hugs me and when he kisses me,''
Alexander said. ``I'm 86 years old, and I love being cuddled and
held and kissed. Who doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam is so ... Sam,'' she said, turning to stroke his hand and
gaze at him like a schoolgirl. ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, thanks! That goes double for me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
