<HEADLINE>
COUPLE SHOWS THERE'S NO AGE LIMIT ON ROMANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whenever they're together, their hands
instinctively, unconsciously reach for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Their eyes flash when they talk about the spark at their first
meeting, 19 months ago. And they've been inseparable ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what this giddy couple will be like in another year or
so _ say, when he's 90 and she's 87.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sleep together. I love the idea of him holding me in his
arms, and loving me,'' Florence Alexander said of her gentleman
friend, Sam Rothman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed each other,'' he added. ``I thank God for sending me
a companion.''
</P>
<P>
   The two met after they lost their spouses and each moved into
the Jewish Home for the Aging in the L.A. suburb of Reseda. The
center is the largest residential care facility for the elderly in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman and Alexander are proof that puppy love isn't just for
pups, contrary to the assumptions of people half their age. Or a
quarter their age. And older Americans are showing that passionate
glances aren't dimmed by fading eyesight, and minor aches and pains
are no obstacle to romantic embraces.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by the National Council on the Aging revealed
that nearly half of all Americans 60 or older have sex at least
once a month, and the figure is 80percent among those with partners
_ whether married or involved in another relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as though we don't think our parents ever had sex,''
said Dr. Robert Butler of the International Longevity Center in New
York. ``In the minds of so many people, old age and sickness go
together, which is unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, published in September, showed that 30percent of
seniors with partners said sex is as physically satisfying as it
was in their 40s, while 31percent said it's even more satisfying
now.
</P>
<P>
   And 39percent of all seniors said they want sex more often than
they're getting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how old you are, or where you are in your life, you
need companionship,'' said Valica Boudry, a spokeswoman at the home
for seniors. ``The sort of stance we take on it is if people have
interest in it, as long as they're cognitively alert and aren't
being taken advantage of, it isn't any of our business. They're
adults. They're adults and this is their home.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they maintain their own rooms and respect each other's
space, Rothman and Alexander share every meal, spend evenings
watching movies and often take trips together.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go to Las Vegas, I tell them I need a room for me and
my girlfriend,'' Rothman said. So they get a standard room, with
two double beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't use (both) beds,'' Alexander cut in.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple also stressed they have no interest in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would marriage do for us that we don't have now,'' except
cut into Social Security benefits? Rothman asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed emotionally,'' Alexander said. ``Can a piece
of paper make it any different how you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, at this stage of the game ... Wait, can you get
pregnant?'' Rothman asked, shooting a glance at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try,'' she said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman, a former newspaper typesetter, now must wear a hearing
aid after 60 years of working around deafening printing presses
from Miami to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors must shout to make themselves understood. But when
Alexander speaks to him in a normal tone, every word gets through.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he sees me somewhere, he always comes over _ no matter
who is around _ and kisses me right on the mouth. I love it,''
Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful I have a fine woman like that,'' Rothman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, baby,'' she said, gazing at her octogenarian beau,
impeccably dressed in his French blue shirt, pale gray suit, and
complementary tie and suspenders. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Born in Warsaw, Poland, Rothman came to the United States at
age 13 and moved to Detroit. The only family he has left are
Alexander's children and in-laws, who have adopted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so lucky to have found a companion, a lover, a family,''
said Rothman, who gives a prayer of thanks for Alexander every
night before bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest disease in this world is loneliness,'' he said.
``If you're lucky enough to meet someone _ to talk to, to watch
television with _ God bless you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not lonely, because we have one another,'' added
Alexander, a lifelong kindergarten teacher who moved to Los Angeles
from Detroit in 1935. She and Rothman never met there.
</P>
<P>
   But she calls their meeting in Reseda ``ba-sheret,'' a Hebrew
term for ``God meant it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very blessed and happy that I have someone who cares
about me a lot,'' she said. ``We make a great couple.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
