   In any case, where would New York City ever find parking space
for 6,000 more cars?
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An Update on Fiber  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turning conventional dietary wisdom on its head, a team of
Boston researchers announced that eating fiber does not prevent
colon cancer. Their 16-year study of more than 88,000 female nurses
found that women who ate a diet rich in fruits, vegetables and
whole grains were no less likely than others to develop the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   But don't bite into that burger and fries just yet. Some experts
found flaws in the research. And fiber still wards off heart
disease, the nation's leading killer.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   Special Funds for Iraq  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even with oil prices at record lows, Iraq has begun to sell
enough oil under a special U.N. relief program that Baghdad can
make improvements in its broken-down electrical supply system.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the ``oil for food'' program, which has provided
every Iraqi with a monthly ration of food, medicine and basic goods
like soap and cooking oil, said that more than $81 million had been
released for the purchase of power-generating equipment, most of it
from China. Iraq, under trade sanctions since 1990, has also
recently bought telephone equipment and computers.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   Hacker Destroys USIA Web Site
</P>
<P>
   The intruder was mean as well as clever. Not content just to
invade the Web site of the U.S. Information Agency and leave a
cryptic message, he (or she) knocked the site off the Internet. By
week's end, computer experts at the agency, which oversees a
variety of cultural and educational-exchange programs, were still
trying to restore the site and promising better security. The
intruder called himself ``Zyklon,'' perhaps after Zyklon-B, the gas
used in Nazi death camps.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID STOUT
</P>
<P>
   No Choking, We're Knicks  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some fans claimed they would cancel their season tickets,
wondering aloud if the franchise had sold its soul for a shot at a
championship. Others were ecstatic to learn that one of the
National Basketball Association's most talented players was coming
to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, when the Knicks sent the popular John Starks to
Golden State for the petulant Latrell Sprewell, a cacophony of
reaction and opinion followed.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, who 14 months ago choked and punched his former coach
in two separate altercations, joined the team over the weekend
after being cleared to play by the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts, who once boasted
of bringing only solid citizens to the Knicks, explained, ``It's
not fair for me to judge what people have gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MIKE WISE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
