<HEADER>
A5457 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-STOCKS-ART-2TA     01-23 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-STOCKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY INVESTMENT PLAN RAISES A DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ind., S.C., W.Va., N.J., Mich.)  (Duplication notice: Also being filed ``a'' category) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A proposal by President Clinton to invest some portion of Social
Security reserves in stocks ignited a brushfire of criticism last
week, although the attacks may have focused on easily solved
problems and ignored some thornier issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan, said he strongly
doubted that the plan could be insulated from political
interference. Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways
and Means Committee, argued that the concept would give the
government undue influence over corporate affairs. Other critics
asked how the government could pursue an antitrust case against
Microsoft if it were also a Microsoft shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers, administrators and scholars point out that stock
investments by governments and their agencies are neither new nor
rare. States, cities and several independent federal agencies,
including the Federal Reserve System, have pension plans that have
invested heavily in stocks for years. And those investments have
not, they say, created the widespread problems critics predict.
</P>
<P>
   What has proved difficult is determining who bears the burdens
of any losses and who reaps the benefits of any surpluses _ a
question made compelling by the difficulty of predicting market
performance. Even more daunting is the challenge of providing small
retirement accounts, like those envisioned by both the president
and his Republican critics, without being overwhelmed by
administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Cavanaugh has a snappy answer to the question of whether
the government can invest in stocks without becoming bogged down in
political shenanigans or corporate meddling. ``Can it be done? It's
been done,'' he said. ``We did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavanaugh was the first executive director of the Federal
Retirement Thrift Investment Board, created by Congress in 1986 to
cover federal employees, including members of Congress like Archer.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about potential conflicts between shareholding and
governing _ as in the Microsoft case _ Cavanaugh shrugged. Since
the plan invests in a stock index fund, he said, the accounts of
the federal lawyers and the federal judge in the Microsoft case
almost certainly hold a few Microsoft shares. But because Congress
designed the agency to be insulated from both the political process
and the corporate battlefield, he said, no ``horror stories'' have
emerged. The White House has also cited the protections of a stock
index fund in defending its plan.
</P>
<P>
   Strong legislation protects the agency from political pressure,
Cavanaugh said. Corporate meddling is precluded because the
commercial bank selected to manage agency investments also votes
its shares on matters like takeovers and executive compensation.
The only factor the bank can consider in casting its votes,
Cavanaugh added, is what is best for retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not can it be done. The question that should
be asked,'' he said, ``is whether the Congress, having protected 3
million federal employees from political manipulation of their
retirement funds, will be willing to extend that same protection to
the 150 million beneficiaries of Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that the federal retirement system's
approach would work for a fund as large as a Social Security stock
fund would be _ the president's proposal calls for investing about
$700 billion in stocks over the next 15 years, an amount that would
have made it the largest single investor in today's market.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Schotland, a Georgetown law professor who helped drive the
campaign to modernize TIAA-CREF, the pension plan for the nation's
university and college faculty, said it might be wiser to delegate
the voting of shares to an independent fiduciary institution.
Others said the problem could be resolved by requiring that the
government cast its shares with the majority of other shareholders
in any important dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Most statewide pension funds have invested in stocks for years,
as have most large municipal pension programs. According to
Nicholas Greifer, senior policy analyst with the government Finance
Officers Association in Chicago, only three states _ Indiana, South
Carolina and West Virginia _ did not permit stock market
investments by statewide pension funds as of 1997. Since then, all
three have obtained legislative or voter approval to permit such
investments, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state funds have a somewhat uneven record when it comes to
insulating investment decisions from improper influences, several
pension industry executives said. Roland Machold, who retired in
July as director of the New Jersey Division of Investments, said
that over the years ``there is hardly a state that hasn't had some
brush with scandal with its pension fund.''
</P>
<P>
   But most frequently, Machold said, those problems have involved
the selection of outside consultants or investments in exotic
assets, like venture capital investments in local businesses,
substandard mortgages and poorly understood investments like
derivatives. ``The states have almost never screwed up buying
nationally listed securities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   State legislatures have occasionally ordered pension funds to
abstain from certain investments _ for instance, in companies doing
business in South Africa during apartheid and, more recently, in
tobacco companies. But most state pension funds with strong
professional leadership have avoided interference by special
interests, said Ian Lanoff, who ran the Labor Department's
compliance program under ERISA, the federal law governing private
pensions, in the Carter administration and who now specializes in
pension law in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the refusal by New York City's pension funds to help
bail the city out during its fiscal crisis in the mid-1970s, and
the later refusal of Michigan public pension funds to help rescue
Chrysler Corp. More recently, he said, the largest public pension
funds have been largely successful in resisting efforts to ban
investments in Northern Ireland and in companies involved in
Holocaust reparations disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ERISA requires pension funds to base investment decisions solely
on the best interests of retirees, Lanoff said. ``Most states have
taken ERISA principles and applied them to their own plans.''
Similar standards would help insulate a Social Security fund even
further from political interference, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But public pension funds have been less successful in insulating
themselves from politics in the tug-of-war over fund surpluses and
shortfalls, said Gene Kalwarski, a public-pension specialist at
Milliman &AMP; Robertson in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There have been ``vicious and bitter debates'' over whether
surpluses in public pension funds should be used to improve
retirement benefits or to reduce the amount taxpayers must
contribute the next year, he said. Similarly, if a fund falls short
_ perhaps because of stock market losses _ the battle rages over
whether to cut benefits or raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   It is unrealistic to expect that such battles _ already a
feature of the Social Security debate _ will not continue,
especially if future stock returns do not mirror recent strong
gains, several legal scholars said.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the plan assume that any shortfalls would remain
the responsibility of federal taxpayers, as they are now.
</P>
<P>
   Such uncertainties persuade some that stock investments by the
Social Security fund raise more problems than they solve. ``My own
instinct is to be very chary,'' said Richard Nathan, director of
the Rockefeller Institute of government, the public policy research
arm of the State University of New York in Albany. ``The past in
the stock market is not necessarily prologue.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Boyd, who specializes in state government studies at the
institute, shared that concern. ``State funds are large, very, very
large,'' he said, ``but the Social Security fund would be huge.
That makes it more visible, but more cumbersome.''
</P>
<P>
   But trying to give beneficiaries a stock market tonic in the
form of small individual accounts _ a feature of both the
president's plan and several Republican alternatives _ raises
administrative problems that Cavanaugh says would be virtually
insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of providing individual plans, similar to corporate
401(k)s, to workers at businesses with 10 or fewer employees would
consume most of what the typical Social Security beneficiary could
afford to invest, Cavanaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of America's 6.5 million businesses are very
small, he said. And it is that factor, not the number of Social
Security participants, that will determine the ``economies of
scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, financial services companies charge about $300
for each participant in such small-scale plans. Since the average
Social Security wage is approximately $20,000 a year, a worker
trying to save 2 percent of that would invest just $400 a year but
pay $300 a year in expenses.
</P>
<P>
   While the White House and Republicans have disputed that
administrative costs would be that high, Cavanaugh is not
persuaded. ``You would be better off putting your money in the
mattress,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5459 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-STOCKS-ART-2TA     01-23 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-STOCKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY INVESTMENT PLAN RAISES A DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ind., S.C., W.Va., N.J., Mich.)  (Duplication notice: Also being filed ``f'' category) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
