further from political interference, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But public pension funds have been less successful in insulating
themselves from politics in the tug-of-war over fund surpluses and
shortfalls, said Gene Kalwarski, a public-pension specialist at
Milliman &AMP; Robertson in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There have been ``vicious and bitter debates'' over whether
surpluses in public pension funds should be used to improve
retirement benefits or to reduce the amount taxpayers must
contribute the next year, he said. Similarly, if a fund falls short
_ perhaps because of stock market losses _ the battle rages over
whether to cut benefits or raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   It is unrealistic to expect that such battles _ already a
feature of the Social Security debate _ will not continue,
especially if future stock returns do not mirror recent strong
gains, several legal scholars said.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the plan assume that any shortfalls would remain
the responsibility of federal taxpayers, as they are now.
</P>
<P>
   Such uncertainties persuade some that stock investments by the
Social Security fund raise more problems than they solve. ``My own
instinct is to be very chary,'' said Richard Nathan, director of
the Rockefeller Institute of government, the public policy research
arm of the State University of New York in Albany. ``The past in
the stock market is not necessarily prologue.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Boyd, who specializes in state government studies at the
institute, shared that concern. ``State funds are large, very, very
large,'' he said, ``but the Social Security fund would be huge.
That makes it more visible, but more cumbersome.''
</P>
<P>
   But trying to give beneficiaries a stock market tonic in the
form of small individual accounts _ a feature of both the
president's plan and several Republican alternatives _ raises
administrative problems that Cavanaugh says would be virtually
insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of providing individual plans, similar to corporate
401(k)s, to workers at businesses with 10 or fewer employees would
consume most of what the typical Social Security beneficiary could
afford to invest, Cavanaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of America's 6.5 million businesses are very
small, he said. And it is that factor, not the number of Social
Security participants, that will determine the ``economies of
scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, financial services companies charge about $300
for each participant in such small-scale plans. Since the average
Social Security wage is approximately $20,000 a year, a worker
trying to save 2 percent of that would invest just $400 a year but
pay $300 a year in expenses.
</P>
<P>
   While the White House and Republicans have disputed that
administrative costs would be that high, Cavanaugh is not
persuaded. ``You would be better off putting your money in the
mattress,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
