<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POPE-700&AMP;ADD-N     01-23 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE SAYS NEGLECT OF THE PRIVILEGED PROMOTES SECULARIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ John Paul II urged the bishops of North and South
America gathered here to take better care of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But sounding a new and somewhat uncharacteristic note, the pope
also instructed them to minister to the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love for the poor must be preferential, but not exclusive,''
the pope said in an Apostolic Exhortation, his definitive answer to
the questions raised in a 1997 synod of bishops of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leading sectors of society have been neglected and many
people have thus been estranged from the church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that secularization is sweeping unions, the military,
politicians and other better-off social groups, the pope warned
that, ``If this evangelization of society's leaders is neglected,
it should come as no surprise that many who are a part of it will
be guided by criteria alien to the Gospel and at times openly
hostile to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since communism collapsed, John Paul II has devoted much of his
attention to the moral failings of capitalism. This document, like
previous ones, lashed out at the inequities of an unbridled
free-market system.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more in countries of America, a system known as
`neo-liberalism' prevails; based on a purely economic conception of
man, this system considers profit and the law of the market as its
only parameters,'' he said. But now, the pope is also raising the
spiritual needs of a wealthier flock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I'm surprised,'' said George Weigel, a theologian who
is writing a biography of John Paul II. ``But it sounds like good
news. It is a new recognition of a new social reality in Latin
America, that it is moving beyond an oligarchy and impoverished
masses, and developing a middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see it as the pope's concern that the church in Latin
America, having rejected the Marxism embedded in liberation
theology, but not the message, has overemphasized the poor and
alienated the rich. And many church leaders who had gathered in
Mexico to receive the document expressed complete agreement with
the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``People whose gains are ill-gotten are sinners, of course,''
said Cardinal Dario Castrillon Hoyos, a Vatican official from
Medellin, Colombia. ``But there are also people who have worked
hard to earn a decent living.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``The pope is saying that a mother may prefer her
child who is sick, but she does not abandon the ones who are
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope summoned the bishops of what he prefers to call
``America'' to Mexico to urge greater solidarity and cooperation
between the north and south of the continent. He is asking them for
a new evangelization of the Americas, where the church sees its
main hope of expansion in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the most urgent problems raised by the bishops and
addressed in the pope's reply had to do with the Catholic Church's
difficulty in ministering to even one sector of society, let alone
all.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of priests _ a preoccupation in the United States,
where one priest ministers to 1,000 parishioners _ is an emergency
in Latin America, where there is one priest for 13,000
parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, as he looks ahead to the next millennium, expressed
dismay about a rival evangelization taking place with the spread of
evangelical Protestant movements.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1990 visit, the pope scolded Mexican bishops for having
left their flock ``deplorably vulnerable'' to proselytizing
Protestant denominations. Since that visit, though, the number of
converts has steadily grown.
</P>
<P>
   Bernardo Barranco, director of Mexico City's Center of Religious
Studies, estimates that the number of Protestants has grown by 30
percent to 40 percent since the 1990 census and that they now
number between 4.6 and 4.9 million. Not all are evangelical or
Pentecostal; at least some have joined traditional Protestant
denominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of proselytizing by sects and new religious groups
in America cannot be ignored,'' the pope said. ``Pastoral policies
will have to be revised, so that each particular church can offer
the faithful more personalized religious care.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Believers in Latin America have often blended ancient indigenous
rites with Catholic ritual. The pope urged bishops to indulge local
traditions, as long as they do not clash with church orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   He asked them to discover ``the true spiritual values present in
popular religiosity, so that enriched by genuine Catholic doctrine,
it might lead to a sincere conversion and a practical exercise of
charity.''
</P>
<P>
   The document, which is made up of 74 densely packed chapters, is
long and unwieldy in tone, the product of many committees.
</P>
<P>
   But one theme was particularly personal to the pope, namely, his
desire to unify North and South America into one church, which is
why he calls it a Synod of America.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has always expressed deep reverence for Our Lady of
Guadalupe, a dark-skinned virgin said to have appeared to an Indian
peasant named Juan Diego 476 years ago, and who helped convert
Mexico's Indian population to Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   She is Mexico's national saint, and her shrine receives about 3
million pilgrims a year. The pope, who offered a Mass at her
basilica on Saturday, his third visit to her shrine, declared in
the document that her saint's day, Dec. 12, should be equally
commemorated in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Some view that exhortation as a symbol of the pope's real
intentions for the Americas in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pope thought at one point that a spiritually
chastened Eastern Europe would take the lead in ushering in a new
evangelization,'' said the Rev. Lorenzo Albacete, a theology
professor at St. Joseph's Seminary in Yonkers, N.Y. ``But now he
sees that that is just not happening. He realizes that the U.S.,
with its unrivaled power _ economic, technological, social and
cultural _ is the future. So what does the church do? Its biggest
resource is Latin America _ there alone the church presence is
really strong. They are here within the empire, they have a better
chance of influencing the U.S. than any church in any other
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
