<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5466 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-680&AMP;ADD-N     01-23 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS LEWINSKY TO SUBMIT TO STARR INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Tenn., Fla., Ark., W.Va., Maine, Miss.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-FITZGERALD,
IMPEACH-BIBLE-BELT, IMPEACH-LINCOLN, IMPEACH-WITNESSES-REVIEW)  
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge ordered Monica Lewinsky on Saturday
to submit to an interview with the independent counsel on behalf of
House prosecutors, drawing a bitter White House attack on their
effort to force Ms. Lewinsky's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, issued moments
before senators resumed a second day of questioning in President
Clinton's impeachment trial, ignited a furious question-and-answer
session on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats assailed the fairness of the House prosecutors' using
the authority of the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, to compel
Ms. Lewinsky's cooperation, while Republicans demanded to know how
the Senate could untangle important conflicting testimony without
hearing from witnesses like Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling came in response to a request from Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., the lead prosecutor, after Ms. Lewinsky rejected a
request to meet with the House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling, Johnson said that House prosecutors had no right
under Ms. Lewinsky's immunity deal with Starr to force her to
submit to their questioning. But she ruled that the independent
counsel could compel Ms. Lewinsky to answer questions from his
staff and allow the House prosecutors to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., one of the 13 House prosecutors, all of
whom are Republicans, opened Saturday's session in the Senate by
explaining that the prosecutors, or managers, merely wanted a
routine meeting with Ms. Lewinsky before deciding whether to ask
the Senate to depose her.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House counsel, Charles Ruff, with sarcasm in his
voice, ridiculed a claim by the House prosecutors that they were
merely seeking a routine interview with a potential witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine what that little conversation is going to look
like, held in the independent counsel's office, with the people
there who have the capacity to put Ms. Lewinsky in jail?'' Ruff
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we really say that it's just normal, just OK, to have one
side using the might and majesty of the independent counsel's
office threatening a witness with violation of an immunity
agreement if she doesn't fly across the country for this little
chat?'' Ruff said. ``I think not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers have balked at allowing her to meet with
the House managers, arguing that it would cast her in ``a partisan
light.``
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to trail along with the House managers struck us as
wrong,'' Jacob Stein, a lawyer for Ms. Lewinsky, said in a
telephone interview Saturday. Stein said it was unlikely that Ms.
Lewinsky would appeal Johnson's order, and he did not know when the
interview might take place.
</P>
<P>
   But congressional officials say the interview could happen this
weekend. Ms. Lewinsky would face intense questioning from Starr's
lawyers. The House prosecutors believe that her answers could be
pivotal as the Senate decides early next week whether to question
witnesses or to decide Clinton's fate without witnesses, the
managers say.
</P>
<P>
   Under the impeachment procedures adopted by the Senate, senators
would have to vote separately on whether to depose witnesses and
then whether to call any to testify in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats, using the awkward procedure of submitting
written questions to the trial's presiding officer, Chief Justice
William Rehnquist, who reads them aloud, challenged the House
prosecutors about why they did not consult the Senate before
seeking Starr's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a normal practice to do this,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum,
R-Fla. ``We would have been incompetent and derelict if we hadn't
tried to talk to her.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question posed by Republican senators about
examples of conflicting testimony where witnesses might help, Rep.
Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., cited the president's testimony about gifts
he gave to Ms. Lewinsky, the differing accounts between Ms.
Lewinsky and Vernon Jordan Jr. over what details of her
relationship she shared with Jordan, and the conflicting accounts
involving Betty Currie's role in dealing with Ms. Lewinsky's gifts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The House managers entered the Senate chamber Saturday morning
well aware of the swirling talk among senators about ending the
trial, and that the pressure was on the prosecutors to reverse that
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is not on what individual senators may be saying,''
Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., said on CNN on Friday night. ``Our
focus is on trying to do our job and present this case. We believe
that there's a compelling case that the president did commit
perjury before the grand jury, and engaged in a series of acts
involving obstruction of justice. We are going to proceed, to the
extent that the Senate will allow us to do so, to make our case.''
</P>
<P>
   Canady acknowledged that the White House had challenged parts of
the House managers' arguments, but he insisted that overall the
prosecution was strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll pick at little parts of the case, but there are some
of these things that just can't be explained away, and the
president's defense has consisted throughout in denying the obvious
and asserting the implausible.''
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of the trial begins on Monday, when senators are
to begin debating whether to dismiss the case and whether to depose
witnesses. Votes on one or both motions could happen later in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., a guardian of Senate tradition,
shocked the Capitol on Friday when he announced that he would
introduce the motion to dismiss. Byrd, an 81-year-old Senate dean,
said he did not believe that witnesses would add any meaningful
testimony and that the two-thirds vote required to convict Clinton
was not within reach.
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate on dismissal and witnesses takes place, in
open and closed sessions on the Senate floor, Democrats and
Republicans said Saturday they expected the flurry of private
meetings and mini-negotiations over how best to end the trial to
intensify.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, on Saturday endorsed a suggestion
of Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, to convene all
100 senators in the ceremonial Old Senate Chamber to discuss how to
bring the trial to a close.
</P>
<P>
   It was in that rarely used chamber two weeks ago that senators
struck an unusual bipartisan accord on the rules for the first
phases of the Senate trial. ``We have to figure out how to serve
our constitutional duties,'' Snowe said on CNN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
