<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-485&AMP;A     01-23 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S PREMIER TRIES TO FILL VACUUM AT TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ His boss is back in the hospital, leaving him with most
of the work. His budget for 1999 is dismissed as unrealistic, and
it doesn't even take into account $8 billion that Russia has
already promised not to pay its creditors. The economy is sure to
get worse before it gets better, and the International Monetary
Fund is still playing hard to get.
</P>
<P>
   For Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov of Russia, now four months
in office, the new year has yet to bring good news. President Boris
Yeltsin's latest ailment, diagnosed as a bleeding ulcer, only
confirms a trend that was already evident: Primakov, a former
foreign minister, has had to assume more and more of the
president's duties, being careful not to show any unseemly
enthusiasm for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's presidential elections are technically still 18 months
away, and most _ though not all _ of the top contenders would
prefer to hold off the start of a real campaign. But the vacuum at
the top has become so obvious, and so persistent, that some are
beginning to wonder how much longer the country can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest noise has come from Yuri Luzhkov, mayor of Moscow,
who is widely seen as the leading contender for Yeltsin's job. A
former Yeltsin ally who has now made a point of keeping his
distance from the increasingly unpopular president, Luzhkov came
right out and told journalists recently that the time had come for
Yeltsin to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov's tone became slightly more tactful after Yeltsin's most
recent hospitalization, but like the little boy who has finally
blurted out that the emperor has no clothes, he wants to be the one
to spread the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no secret to anyone that he has not been in good health
for a long time,'' Luzhkov said last Monday, referring to the newly
hospitalized Yeltsin. ``Society and the state must get an answer
from the president on how he wants to resolve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Primakov has been filling the gap well enough
to make himself Russia's most trusted politician, several public
opinion polls indicate. Arriving in the political and economic
firestorm that erupted after Aug. 17, the day the ruble collapsed
and Russia went into virtual default, Primakov has earned points
simply for restoring an impression of political stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Primakov came on the wave of expectations of a civil
war,'' said Igor Bunin, director of the Political Technologies
Center, a local research group, ``he is considered a stabilizer of
the political situation. With the lack of trust in the president
and the Parliament, the government's rating is very high,
unprecedentedly high.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov may or may not end up being a contender for Yeltsin's
job, but on one thing all observers agree: Given the president's
well-known sensitivity to real or apparent rivals, Primakov will
certainly not tip his hand until he has to.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For now he is simply strengthening his position inside a
government that is fast filling up with Primakov appointees. Many
are old allies from his five-year stint as head of Russia's foreign
intelligence agency. The most notable of these in recent days was
Yuri Kobaladze, the former press officer at the spy agency, who has
reportedly been named deputy head of Russia's state-owned radio and
television company.
</P>
<P>
   These appointments have been closely watched for clues to the
direction of Primakov's economic and other policies, which are
still unclear. Most analysts assume that Primakov is aiming above
all to secure the loyalty of a large and unruly bureaucracy during
a time of political transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody in Primakov's position would try to insert his own
people in key positions,'' said Thomas Graham, a Russian expert and
senior associate at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Primakov's principal achievement has been his ability to
buy peace with the Communists who dominate Russia's usually
truculent Parliament, in part by making one of their deputies, Yuri
Maslyukov, his chief deputy minister for economics.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists have repaid him by withholding criticism of a $25
billion budget that on paper commits Russia to the strictest
austerity. But that same budget _ which must be voted on by the
Parliament twice more before it is adopted _ has been roundly
criticized by the IMF as not tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts have criticized the document for making a series of
rosy assumptions _ including a stable ruble, moderate inflation and
the expectation that international lenders will stump up $4 billion
in credits to fill an anticipated budget deficit of the same
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has also assumed that its foreign creditors, who are owed
$17.5 billion this year, will be willing to roll over half that
amount with a new restructuring agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, representatives of the so-called London Club _
creditors who hold Russia's old Soviet-era commercial debt _ agreed
to a restructuring arrangement that allows Russia to avoid a
technical default.
</P>
<P>
   Maslyukov, who was in Washington the week before last to lobby
the monetary fund, has said that Russia will not bend to the fund's
main demands, in particular the rollback of a recent cut in the
Russian value-added tax. He has also insisted that Russia is asking
only as much money _ about $5 billion _ as it needs to keep paying
back its overall fund debt, which is about $16.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest in the fund only amounts to refinancing debts to
the fund itself, the debt that our predecessors contracted in the
name of Russia and that we recognize,'' Maslyukov told the Russian
newspaper Kommersant.
</P>
<P>
   As a fund team assembles here for another look at Russia, many
observers, Russian and foreign, expect that more credits will
eventually be forthcoming, for political if not economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West and Primakov are tied together whether they like it
or not,'' Graham said. ``The West cannot afford a catastrophe in
Russia any more than Primakov can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
