<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-880&AMP;A     01-23 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BUILDING NETWORK IN CALIFORNIA 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Attn: N.J., N.H., Iowa, Mass., Texas)  By MICHAEL JANOFSKY  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As vice president, Al Gore has traveled to
California so many times that aides have lost count. They think his
latest trip this weekend, his second of the year, is the 52nd. But
they are not eager to bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   He has built a prodigious network of constituent groups and
contributors to help him win California's 54 electoral votes, the
most of any state, and help him become the fifth incumbent vice
president to capture the White House by election. (The others were
John Adams, Thomas Jefferson, Martin Van Buren and George Bush.)
</P>
<P>
   California always has been critical in the presidential
equation. But by moving up its primary to join New York and eight
other states on March 7 in 2000, just weeks after the first two
election tests, the Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary,
California's primary holds life-threatening powers over
underfinanced campaigns that are still forming.
</P>
<P>
   While that might suggest an urgent need to organize and tap
financial sources, Gore appears to be the only aspirant from either
party who has amassed a powerful array of support at this early
juncture of the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget, we're just at the very beginning,'' said Gina
Glantz, campaign manager for Bill Bradley, the former New Jersey
senator who recently entered the presidential race. ``Sooner more
than later, we'll have a more formal organization in California.
But we're just getting started.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Torres, chairman of the California Democratic Party, said
any others who might be contemplating a run, like Sen. John Kerry
of Massachusetts, had not significantly raised their profiles in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the primary is so early, they should have
started organizing six months ago,'' Torres said. ``If they would
ask me for advice now, I'd tell them not to waste their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who lectured at Stanford University after his three
terms in the Senate, is not without ties to California. He has
campaigned for Democrats from swing districts, like Reps. Ellen O.
Tauscher and Gary A. Condit, and his friendship with Michael D.
Eisner, chairman of the Walt Disney Co., could lead to big
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the reality is, Gore is leaps and bounds in front,'' said
Rep. Loretta Sanchez, from California's Orange County. She also is
a director of Gore's political action committee, Leadership '98,
and an incoming chairwoman of the Democratic National Committee, a
position that requires neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's strength in California flows directly from the power of
incumbency and instant access to Air Force Two, a combination that
allows him to deliver federal largess and to campaign for Democrats
whenever he wants _ and often on the same trip.
</P>
<P>
   On a dozen visits last year, he announced grants and programs
worth more than $550 million, and almost every Democrat running for
statewide office won in November, including Gray Davis, the state's
first Democratic governor in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he did in planning for this weekend, Gore has made
special efforts to court the same groups that twice turned out
money and votes for Clinton, including Hispanic and black voters
and people in the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Through science and technology issues, long a passion of his,
Gore has tried expanding that base by impressing environmentalists
and Silicon Valley executives with his knowledge of topics like
``salmon as an indicator species'' and ``massive parallel
computing.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he has taken unusual steps to familiarize himself
with high-tech issues, meeting periodically with small groups of
industry representatives at all levels _ ``Gore Techs,'' his aides
call them _ to discuss new and future technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave an address on forestry, water issues and clean air
about a year ago at Lake Tahoe,'' said Ruth Hunter, a board member
of the California League of Conservation Voters. ``He was more
informed than some of the enviros.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Yang, a co-founder of Yahoo, the Internet portal, said he
and other high-tech executives had grown to respect Gore for
interest in issues vital to Internet growth, like privacy and
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one meeting I was in with him, he talked very eloquently
about network economics, how decision making can be distributed in
the network world,'' Yang said. ``It's good to see that he can
think about these things and not reduce himself to sound bites.''
</P>
<P>
   With people of Hispanic descent now California's fastest growing
ethnic group, making up 30.8 percent of the state's population,
Gore has pursued them as aggressively as any group. Last year, he
often appeared at campaign and issue-related events with Cruz M.
Bustamante, who became the state's first elected lieutenant
governor of Hispanic descent, and with Antonio R. Villaraigosa, the
new state assembly speaker. In one East Los Angeles event with
Hispanic union workers days before the election, Gore delivered his
entire get-out-the-vote message in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know George Bush Jr. is doing all he can to show support for
the Latino community in Texas, speaking Spanish and all that,''
said Bustamante, who refers to Gore as Alberto. ``But I can't think
of any candidate, Democrat or Republican, who could break the bond
that exists for the vice president.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yvonne Burke, a Los Angeles County Supervisor, said Gore had
developed a similar bond with many black Californians for promoting
issues important to low-income people, like economic development in
inner-city neighborhoods and employment discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   She said the vice president also won points when he attended
events like the funeral last fall of Tom Bradley, who was a hero to
many blacks as the first black mayor of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, people coming to California, come to raise money and
only see the more affluent communities,'' Ms. Burke said. ``The
president has always been visible in all of Los Angeles'
communities, and the vice president's approach has been very
similar.''
</P>
<P>
   As for fund-raising, a sensitive subject for Gore since his 1996
appearance at a Buddhist temple almost led to a Justice Department
investigation, the vice president is relying heavily upon people in
the entertainment industry who raised money for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   They include David Geffen, the record industry executive, and
Rob Reiner, the actor and director. Both said Gore had attributes
that made him more attractive than Clinton was before becoming
President.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, Bill Clinton had to start from scratch,'' Geffen
said. ``Al Gore is extremely well-known and well-liked. I can't
imagine why he would not enjoy great support.'' He called Bradley a
``very decent and honorable guy,'' but a primary candidate who has
``zero chance'' to defeat Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner had Gore's help last year, leading a successful ballot
initiative that raises taxes on cigarettes and uses the money for
children's services.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll say that he's not as glamorous as President Clinton,''
Reiner said of the vice president. ``But in a strange way, that
makes people even more dedicated to him. He's a policy wonk, but at
least with him you get none of the extras and distractions you get
with the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
