<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-ASSASSINATION     01-23 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ASSASSINATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION PARTY POLITICIAN GUNNED DOWN IN SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ A high-level official of South
Africa's new multiracial political party, the United Democratic
Movement, was assassinated Saturday, riddled with bullets as he
left a grocery store near his home in a rural area about an hour's
drive north of Durban.
</P>
<P>
   With the campaign for South Africa's second national elections
just gearing up, the killing of the official, Sifiso Nkabinde, once
again raises questions about whether political violence will return
as the vote approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Nkabinde was a controversial figure who was expelled by
President Nelson Mandela's African National Congress party for
allegedly spying on the party for the former apartheid government.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he was accused of inciting political violence in his
hometown of Richmond and stood trial on 16 murder charges. He was,
however, acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Nkabinde had been elected secretary-general of the
UDM, a party launched by two prominent politicians, one black and
one white, in the hopes of developing support across racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   While the party was initially dismissed as a curiosity, polls
have shown that it has growing support and that this backing _
between 5 and 7 percent _ is indeed coming from both blacks and
whites.
</P>
<P>
   But a cloud of violence had always surrounded Nkabinde. After he
was expelled from the ANC, a violent turf battle developed around
him in Richmond. Dozens of people died in what appeared to be a
tit-for-tat exchange between ANC supporters and those that stayed
loyal to Nkabinde.
</P>
<P>
   With national elections expected sometime this spring, political
analysts had been concerned about the role Nkabinde might play at a
time when violence in the KwaZulu-Natal province has, on the whole,
been declining.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, most of the province's political violence was
related to the rivalry between the African National Congress and
the Zulu-based Inkhata Freedom Party. In the last decade, more than
10,000 people died in political clashes between the two.
</P>
<P>
   But they have been negotiating to end their differences. Lately,
there has been talk of partnership, and many believe that in
exchange for cooperation, the Inkhata Party's leader, Chief
Mangosutho Buthelezi, has been offered the deputy presidency if, as
expected, the ANC once again wins the elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Nkabinde and his party remained a wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nkabinde was not popular with the ANC, Mandela issued a
statement Saturday saying that ``the government would leave no
stone unturned'' in search of his killers.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said Nkabinde was gunned down by several
assailants shortly before 8 a.m. as he left the Bridgeway
Supermarket, accompanied by his bodyguard and his bodyguard's
mother, both of whom were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said they recovered more than 60 shell casings
from the scene. Nkabinde's car, a silver BMW, had 33 bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   By afternoon, the head of his party, Bantu Holomisa, had arrived
in Richmond and condemned the shooting as ``barbaric.'' He said
there could be no doubt that the killing was politically motivated,
but did not speculate who was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   A car apparently used by the assailants was found about 20
minutes after the shooting, parked in Richmond's cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Around Richmond, the mood was tense as many residents waited to
see whether there would be further killings. In 1997, shortly after
Nkabinde was expelled from the ANC, murders were so frequent that
the government sent in the army to patrol the area.
</P>
<P>
   When Nkabinde was arrested, things quieted down. But after his
release, more violence followed. Finally, the government
transferred all local police officers from Richmond, in an effort
to stop what officials believed was police complicity with
Nkabinde.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, there has been little violence in the area.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, police set up roadblocks on the roads approaching
Richmond and were stopping and searching all cars, while army
helicopters hovered over the area.
</P>
<P>
   The United Democratic Movement was founded by Holomisa, who was
himself expelled from the ANC for insubordination, and Roelf Meyer,
once a powerful figure in the largely white-supported National
Party. The party's platform includes holding a referendum on
reinstituting capital punishment and abolishing affirmative action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
