<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-PENSIONERS-830     01-23 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-PENSIONERS-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL INSECURITY IN BRAZIL FOR GOVERNMENT RETIREES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ They have been called ``privilegiados'' and
``maharajahs'' who collect lavish pensions and benefits, and
portrayed as budgetary vampires who drain the pension system and
contribute nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, millions of retired government workers across Brazil are
watching the financial crisis that is enveloping Latin America's
largest economy tear the first breaches in the social contract that
has shaped their lives. What else, they wonder, will be open to
question in the new scheme of things?
</P>
<P>
   ``You work really hard, and what is it for? Just to worry at the
end of your life?'' said Djalma da Silva Rodrigues, who worked for
the Federal Revenue Department for 38 years, many of them at the
country's borders for the customs service. ``God in heaven, what is
this? We gave everything for our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is truly perverse,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is financially on the ropes, with its currency plunging
in value since the government allowed it to float freely against
the dollar a week ago. Hard currency reserves are dwindling. The
Group of Seven major industrialized nations, the United States and
the International Monetary Fund have contributed to a $41.5 billion
bailout package to pull Brazil through the current turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   In return, foreigners expect Brazil to show that it can carry
out structural changes that strike at vested interests. The vote in
Congress on Wednesday night to trim welfare benefits proved it can
_ even though the markets appeared unimpressed in their reaction,
and the plunge in the currency and the flight of dollars continued
on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will raise the pension contributions of most
government workers to just under 25 percent for the highest
earners. The measures will save Brazil only $2.5 billion this year,
but the plan shatters a longstanding cultural taboo against retired
government workers' having to continue to pay into the pension
system.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, retired government workers _ 905,000 _ now outnumber
the 902,000 active civil servants. Government projections indicate
that pensions will produce a $29 billion deficit this year.
</P>
<P>
   If outsiders viewed Wednesday night's vote as a test of
commitment to sound fiscal management, retired workers watched
through a different lens.
</P>
<P>
   Some saw it as the just end to a sweet ride. Others, like
Rodrigues, were bitter and felt the government was changing the
rules not so much in the middle of the game but after it had ended
for most of them. Retirees from the private sector, who have had to
buy supplemental retirement policies to collect their pensions of
more than 1,200 reals a month, now some $750, said it was about
time.
</P>
<P>
   But for all government workers, Wednesday's vote, which is
expected to be approved by the Senate, shatters a sense of security
that had shaped the lives of public servants. The congressional
bill increases the pension contributions of civil servants and, for
the first time, requires most government retirees to pay at least
part of their pensions back into the social security system.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, this vote has been one of the biggest blows on the
heads of workers,'' said Claudette Alves da Silva Souza, president
of the municipal workers union of Sao Paulo, which represents
147,000 civil servants. While the congressional vote itself affects
only federal workers, Sao Paulo officials said last week they would
apply it to state and municipal workers as soon as the federal law
took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Souza said she agreed with the need for reform to balance
public accounts, but noted that the government had not struck at
more powerful vested interests, like Brazil's wealthy landowners,
the banking sector or multinationals operating in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even within the Civil Service, some classes have remained
protected. The military, both retired and active workers, have so
far been exempt from the reforms affecting the rest of Brazil's
public workers, and they will not have to contribute to the pension
system. Judges and teachers are also protected from some of the
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's being hit?'' Ms. Souza said. ``It's the middle class and
below that's being called upon to pay for the mistakes of a
government that implemented a disastrous policy.'' She said that
many civil servants went to work for the government at the start of
their careers because of the retirement benefits offered.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's pension system for government workers remains generous
by any standards. Retired civil servants receive their highest
salary for as long as they live, and after retirement they continue
to collect any salary increases their union negotiates, as if they
were still working.
</P>
<P>
   Pensioners today say that is a legacy of Brazil's decades of
hyperinflation _ the dizzying price rises that were halted by
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso's 1994 Real Plan, which for
almost the first time in workers' memory gave them a currency and
stability they could count on.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. Henrique Carlos Goncalves, 50, retired two years ago after
working for 37 years, 22 of them for the city of Sao Paulo. Now he
works in private practice, but still pockets a monthly pension of
1,500 reals. He expects to lose about 150 reals of that because of
Wednesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   But he argues that governments at all levels in Brazil have used
pension funds as political purses, and he says that is what has
bankrupted the system. ``That still persists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To many private-sector workers, like Levy Kauffman, a former
vice president of the telephone company, it was high time for
Brazil's governing class to abandon its privileges. Watching the
congressmen who supported the government reform speak above the din
of opposition critics, he said, ``We're at a stage in Brazil where
a minority that's organized controls a majority that's
disorganized.''
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman, 75, nodded as he watched Roberto Jefferson, a
congressman from Rio de Janeiro, defend the social security reforms
as necessary for Brazil's solvency. ``For each real the public
servant puts into the pension system, the government puts in 10,''
Jefferson intoned. ``And there's no actuarial table in the world
that can make sense of that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' Kauffman said, as if at last hearing somebody who
spoke his language.
</P>
<P>
   Even some civil servants, like Jose Cruz, a retiree from the
Federal Revenue Service, did not dispute that pensioners should
finally make some contribution. Cruz is a regular at the ``Retired
Persons' Room,'' a lounge the ministry sets aside for former
workers on the top floor of the Federal Revenue Service tower here.
</P>
<P>
   As he heard Rodrigues criticize the congressional reforms, Cruz,
80, shook his head. Because he collects more than 3,000 reals a
month, he will contribute under the new system, cutting his income
to the tune of some 750 reals a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bleeding is more or less reasonable,'' Cruz said, ``but
when you mess with people's pockets, nobody likes it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than the prospect of the money, it was perhaps the sense
that other Brazilians were looking at him as a kind of freeloader
that wounded Cruz the most. ``They say we didn't contribute
anything,'' he said, ``but nobody in the world retires without
having given something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
