<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MLK-THE-THIRD24-COX     01-23 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-THE-THIRD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin Luther King III climbs own mountaintop
 &HT;    By Rebecca Thatcher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He was only 5 when his father, Martin Luther
King Jr., gave the ``I Have a Dream'' speech in Washington, D.C. He
was 10 when his father was shot to death in Memphis, Tenn., in
1968.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King III, who will speak in Austin this evening,
has carried the weight of his father's legacy on his broad
shoulders ever since. Like other children of martyred icons of the
1960s, King, 41, has struggled with his role as the oldest son of
Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But King's prominent role in this year's Martin Luther King Jr.
Day celebrations and his new post as president of the organization
his father co-founded, the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, show that he may be coming into his own.
</P>
<P>
   King, who lives in Atlanta, also is national chairman for the
Kindness and Justice Challenge, which encourages children to
perform acts of kindness and justice to honor Martin Luther King
Jr.'s birthday. He has traveled extensively to promote the
challenge, doing an ``excellent'' job relating to schoolchildren
and their parents, said Matt Heyd, project director.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a terrific spokesperson for that effort,'' Heyd said.
``They really admire what Mr. King stands for, (that) . . .
everybody can be great because anybody can serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Carroll, one of the organizers of the gala where King will
speak tonight at the Omni Southpark Hotel, said King has a
back-to-the-basics message that she thinks will be well-received.
</P>
<P>
   King says ``we need to reshape our priorities in regards to
children and family,'' Carroll said. ``Let's get involved with our
children. Let's look at them as our future.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who has two sisters and one brother, grew up in Atlanta
and graduated from Morehouse College. For many years, public
speaking has been his main profession.
</P>
<P>
   He was a commissioner of Fulton County, which includes Atlanta,
from 1987 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the board of directors of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference appointed him president. The organization
promotes voter registration and civil rights and campaigns against
racism and prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has had a low profile recently, and observers
are hoping that King can reinvigorate the group.
</P>
<P>
   King publicly committed the leadership conference to a broad
agenda of uniting African-Americans around common goals at the
group's annual convention in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision is to expand our efforts toward the education and
empowerment of our youth, the economic empowerment of our community
and the advancement of nonviolent conflict resolution for our
society,'' King said in a July article in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. ``We need the experience and wisdom of the
old coupled with the energy and talent of the young. We are all in
this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
