<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5493 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THERMOMETERS24-COX     01-23 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THERMOMETERS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thermometers test food for doneness, safety
 &HT;    WITH ART, RECIPES at end of file
 &HT;    By Kevin Tankersley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If one were to visit a restaurant kitchen, one
likely would see a thermometer dial peeking out of the top of the
chest pocket on the chef's white jacket. No, the chef isn't sick
and keeping track of his or her own temperature, but using that
thermometer to check the doneness of food being served to the
restaurant patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three key reasons to using a thermometer,'' said
Jill Gully, a cooking coach at H-E-B's Cooking Connection, pointing
to a sign displayed in the store's meat department: It eliminates
the guesswork on whether food has cooked long enough; it prevents
overcooking; and helps ensure food safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are all important'' reasons, Gully said. Plus, besides
assuring food is cooked properly, thermometer use also can save the
consumer money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a minimal investment,'' Gully said of the simple dial
thermometer, which sells for about $6. ``If you've got a couple of
pounds of ribeyes and burn them, that's more than the cost of the
thermometer.''
</P>
<P>
   A digital thermometer sells for about $10.
</P>
<P>
   Using a food thermometer is simple, Gully said. Take the
temperature of the meat near the end of the cooking time. When
cooking large items such as roasts, chickens or turkeys, simply
insert the thermometer into the thickest part of the meat, making
sure the tip of the thermometer does not come in contact with bone
or large pockets of fat. Wait 10 to 15 seconds and the internal
temperature of the meat will be displayed on the dial or digital
readout.
</P>
<P>
   The thermometer must be inserted into the meat at least 1 1/2 to
two inches to work properly, Gully said. For thinner cuts of meat,
such as steaks or hamburger patties, the thermometer can be
inserted from the side. A patty or steak can be lifted with a
spatula or tongs to avoid hands being burned from the frying pan or
grill.
</P>
<P>
   Gully said determining the exact time meat is cooked through
contributes to how good it will taste when served.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beef is 72 percent water,'' she said. ``The longer you cook
it, the more the water evaporates. The (proper) temperature will
tell you when it's safe but still maintaining the maximum moisture
and juiciness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gully said a thermometer comes in handy in other areas of
cooking as well. It can tell a bread baker when water is at the
proper temperature to add yeast, or let a cook know when leftovers
are reheated to a safe degree, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistics show that only 5 percent of all households possess
a meat thermometer,'' Gully said, ``and only 2 percent use them on
a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are few recipes where a thermometer can come in handy:
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN GARLIC PORK ROAST
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 pound boneless pork loin roast
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon seasoned salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon oregano leaves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Blend all seasonings well and rub
mixture over all surfaces of pork loin. Place pork in shallow
roasting pan and roast until meat thermometer inserted in roast
registers 155 to 160 degrees, about 60 to 90 minutes. Remove pork
from oven; let rest 10 minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings, each with 163 calories, 24 grams protein, 7
grams fat, 195 milligrams sodium, 66 milligrams cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWESTERN GRILLED PORK TENDERLOIN
</P>
<P>
   2 whole pork tenderloins (about 1 1/2 pounds total)
</P>
<P>
   5 teaspoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons oregano
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix well all seasonings and vegetable oil. Rub
mixture over all surfaces of tenderloins. Cover and refrigerate
from 2 to 24 hours. Grill over medium-hot coals, turning
occasionally, for 15 to 20 minutes, until thermometer inserted
reads 155 to 160 degrees. Pork is done when there is still a hint
of pink in the center. Slice to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings, each with 154 calories, 26 grams protein, 6
grams fat, 141 milligrams sodium, 66 milligrams cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipes from National Pork Producers Council (www.nppc.- org)
</P>
<P>
   HONEY MUSTARD STEAKS WITH GRILLED ONIONS
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless beef top loin steaks, cut 1 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup coarse-grain Dijon-style mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon each cider vinegar and water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper sauce (such as Tabasco), if desired
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon coarse grind black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 large red onion, cut into 1/2-inch thick slices
</P>
<P>
   Combine mustard, parsley, honey, vinegar, water, pepper sauce
and pepper. Place beef steaks and onion on grid over medium coals;
brush both with glaze. Grill 9 to 12 minutes for rare (140 degrees)
to medium (160 degrees), turning once and brushing with glaze.
Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Recipe may also be prepared using beef ribeye steaks cut 1
inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED SIRLOIN WITH RED PEPPER SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   1 boneless beef top sirloin steak 3 pounds), cut 2 inches thick
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried or fresh rosemary leaves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   For the Red Pepper Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   2 medium red bell peppers (a 7-ounce jar of roasted red peppers
may be substituted)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Prepare peppers by broiling 3 to 4 inches from heat on a baking
sheet, turning frequently, until evenly charred. Transfer to a
sealable plastic bag; close and set aside until peppers cool. Peel
charred skin from peppers and remove seeds. Preheat oven to 350
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   To make sauce, blend peppers, vinegar and salt in blender using
pulse switch until coarsely chopped. Press rosemary into both sides
of sirloin steak. Roast on rack in a shallow roasting pan in oven
for 50 to 60 minutes or 16 to 20 minutes per pound. Remove roast
when a meat thermometer inserted in center reaches 135 degrees for
medium-rare or 150 degrees for medium doneness. Let roast stand 10
minutes before carving into thin slices. Serve sliced beef with red
pepper sauce. Sauce may be served at room temperature or heated.
Sauce yields 1 cup. Makes 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipes from Texas Beef Council (www.txbeef.org) TESTING THE
TEMP
</P>
<P>
   A thermometer should be inserted into food just prior to the end
of the recommended cooking time. Insert the thermometer into the
thickest part of the meat, being careful not to touch bone or fat.
For a whole chicken or turkey, the thermometer should be placed in
the thickest part of the thigh or breast.
</P>
<P>
   The thermometer should be inserted 1 1/2 to two inches; if
testing temperature on a thinner steak or patty, insert from the
side. Wait 10 to 15 seconds for the temperature to register on the
thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   For roast, steaks or chops, the temperature should read about
130 degrees for a rare piece of meat; 140 degrees for medium-rare;
150 for medium; or 160 for well done.
</P>
<P>
   For ground been patties, meat balls or meat loaf, the
temperature needs to be 160 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   A fully-cooked ham should be reheated to 140 degrees, while a
fresh ham needs to be cooked to 155 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   A whole turkey or chicken needs to reach 180 degrees in the
thigh or 170 degrees in the breast. If the bird is stuffed, the
stuffing must reach a temperature of 165 degrees. Poultry parts and
ground poultry should also be cooked to 165 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Tankersley writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
