<HEADER>
A5494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINTERIZE-BEDROOM24-C     01-23 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTERIZE-BEDROOM24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few simple additions can turn bedroom into inviting cold-weather
haven
 &HT;    By Amy Kincheloe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If recent chilly nights had you shivering under
your covers, perhaps it's time to winterize your bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   One solution way to winterize your bedroom for enjoyable warmth
is to sleep under a down comforter.
</P>
<P>
   Down is the fluffy, delicate undercoating of a goose. It is one
of nature's best insulators because it retains the body's natural
warmth while allowing air to flow through and moisture to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Sears Home Fashions sales manager Jane Hagy said down can
actually be used any time of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down is a year-round covering because it breathes,'' Hagy
said. ``I grew up in Minnesota, where we kept our down comforters
on the bed throughout the year. I still leave mine on all
year-round.''
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for down comforters, Hagy said to look at the
ounce weight. The more ounce weight a comforter has, the more
``fluff'' it will have.
</P>
<P>
   She also said to look for a box stitch because this will help
ensure the longevity of the comforter. Box stitching holds the down
in place for an even distribution of warmth and ease of
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Box stitch comforters also better serve a wider range of
climates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should last a long, long time because all you have to do
is fluff them up,'' Hagy said.
</P>
<P>
   Hagy said most down comforters only come in white because they
are usually covered with a duvet to provide color and to help keep
them clean.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to winterize your bedroom is with flannel sheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sold a lot (of flannel sheets). In fact, we don't have
many left,'' said Margaret Barrientos at Kmart department lead.
</P>
<P>
   Barrientos said the biggest sellers this season have been from
the Martha Stewart Collection in colors such as burgundy, hunter
green and navy. She recommended going with a brand name you trust
when buying flannel sheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look for the name brand because some of the other ones aren't
worth it,'' Barrientos said.
</P>
<P>
   Flannel sheets get softer with time. The more you wash and dry
them, the cozier they get.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping on a featherbed also can winterize your bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Featherbeds have been popular in Europe for years, and now they
are appearing in more American bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are buying them for the comfort, softness and
the feel,'' said Kathy Schmedthorst, Dillard's manager of home
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Schmedthorst said the featherbeds are placed on top of a
person's mattress and can be slept on directly. Also, both the
mattress and the featherbed can be covered with a flat sheet
because most fitted sheets will not go over both.
</P>
<P>
   Schmedthorst suggested the latter because the quills of the
feathers tend to stick out on an exposed featherbed.
</P>
<P>
   The featherbed might not be for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allergies can prevent you from sleeping on a featherbed,''
Schmedthorst said. ``But they are very comfortable. They're like
being all snuggled up and are really neat to sleep on.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmedthorst also said sleeping on a large feather or down
pillow can add to the comfort level of your bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Down pillows are praised for their ability to permit the head
and neck to locate their natural resting position, and feathers are
valued for their ability to supply sleepers with comfort and
support for a lesser cost.
</P>
<P>
   Feather pillows are usually made with at least 50 percent
feathers, with the rest consisting of down.
</P>
<P>
   When choosing a feather or down pillow, keep this in mind: Soft
pillows are for those who sleep on their stomach, medium pillows
are for those who sleep on their back and firm pillows are for
those who sleep on their side.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswomen from Dillard's, Kmart and Sears said other
popular winter bedroom fashions included electric blankets,
electric mattress pads, heated throws and woven throws.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, being comfortable is the key. If your bedroom is too
hot or too cold, your sleep time can be fragmented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The room itself has to be kept comfortable for you, but
everyone's level of comfort is different,'' said Dr. Robert
Springer, director of the Southwest Sleep Center.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, these bedroom fashions could make the
difference in you and your mate fighting over the thermostat all
night.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Kincheloe writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
