<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATHROW-HABEAS24-COX     01-23 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHROW-HABEAS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Details of habeas corpus rule
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Clarence Gideon was charged with breaking into a
poolroom, a felony. He didn't have the money for an attorney, so he
asked the court to appoint one.
</P>
<P>
   The court refused, so he represented himself and was convicted.
From his Florida prison cell, Gideon filed a handwritten petition
for habeas corpus. The Latin phrase, meaning ``you have the body,''
is the name of a legal principle that demands that the government
bring to court a person (i.e., ``the body'') it has in custody so a
judge can decide whether the prisoner is being legally held.
</P>
<P>
   Habeas corpus predates the Magna Carta and is embedded in both
the U.S. and Georgia Constitutions. Its right can be suspended only
when the nation is threatened, such as in cases of invasion or
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   In Gideon's case, he said his constitutional rights had been
abridged because he had not had proper representation at trial. His
appeal resulted in the landmark 1963 U.S. Supreme Court ruling,
Gideon vs. Wainwright, requiring states to appoint counsel to
represent indigent defendants charged with serious state offenses.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent rulings, the U.S. Supreme Court has required
states to appoint counsel for indigent defendants in misdemeanor
cases that could result in jail time and for defendants pursuing
direct appeals of their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1985, the U.S. Supreme Court rejected an appeal that
claimed the U.S. Constitution required appointed lawyers for
indigents in their state habeas petitions. Exzavious Gibson's case
before the Georgia Supreme Court claims that right is in the
Georgia Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Indigent death row inmates get appointed lawyers when they
pursue their habeas claims through the federal courts because
Congress, in 1986, passed legislation ordering it.
</P>
<P>
   Death-row habeas corpus petitions typically make one or more of
these types of challenges:
</P>
<P>
   _ The performance of the lawyer who represented the defendant at
trial was so deficient that an adequate performance could have
resulted in a different outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   _ An investigation of the prosecutor's case reveals that
important evidence favorable to the defendant _ such as bias on the
part of a witness, or a plea deal that may have influenced the
witness' testimony _ had been suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   _ There is information that shows possible misconduct by jurors.
</P>
<P>
   _ The trial was tainted by an unconstitutional bias, such as the
composition of the jury that imposed the sentence or the grand jury
that brought the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATHROW24-COX     01-23 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHROW24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Habeas corpus in death row cases a `minefield'
 &HT;    WITH sidebar DEATHROW-HABEAS
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There is no doubt that Exzavious Lee Gibson killed
Douglas Coley in the winter of 1990. He stabbed the Eastman grocer
39 times and left him to die face down in a pool of blood behind
the counter of the family store.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after the slaying, police found Gibson in his
grandmother's home, hiding in a closet. Coley's wallet and
blood-stained money were found stuffed under Gibson's bed. An hour
later, the 17-year-old gave police a videotaped confession.
</P>
<P>
   Dodge County prosecutors sought the death penalty against Gibson
and, after a four-day trial, a jury sentenced him to die in
Georgia's electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   While Gibson's case appears fairly straightforward, it has
become anything but. After Gibson's direct appeals were denied, he
filed a petition for habeas corpus, a civil lawsuit routinely filed
by death row inmates that challenges the legality of a conviction
and sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1996, Gibson, who has an IQ of 76, became the first
condemned inmate in the modern history of the death penalty who was
forced to proceed with his habeas hearing without a lawyer. A
transcript of the proceeding showed Gibson clearly had little idea
of what was going on before him, at one point even telling the
judge he did not know how to plead in a proceeding that did not
require it.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson offered no evidence, asked no questions and raised no
claims. His petition was dismissed out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   After having no lawyer at all, Gibson is now represented by
Atlanta's most prestigious law firm, which is asking the Georgia
Supreme Court to make it a constitutional right for death row
inmates to have state-funded counsel in their post-conviction
proceedings. Georgia is one of only two states in the country with
the death penalty that does not provide lawyers at this stage.
Wyoming is the other and it has no prisoners on death row.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Supreme Court does not appear eager to hear Gibson's
case. King &AMP; Spalding lawyers filed Gibson's petition before the
court in May 1997; the 20-month wait is an extraordinary lag time
in a court known for its efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The case raises issues that affect the rights of all death row
inmates and could pose thorny policy questions for state lawmakers:
</P>
<P>
   _ If the Georgia Supreme Court ultimately decides to hear
Gibson's appeal and agrees that condemned prisoners have a right to
counsel during habeas proceedings, who will pay for the appointed
lawyers and how much will it cost?
</P>
<P>
   _ If death row inmates have a right to counsel, why not a
prisoner facing a sentence of life without parole?
</P>
<P>
   _ Why not an inmate sentenced to five years for burglary?
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 40 percent of all death sentences nationwide are
overturned on appeal, many through habeas corpus petitions.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's court appearance may have cost him his best chance of
obtaining relief in court. Because all death penalty appeals
involve horrible killings and rarely involve a question of whether
the defendant committed the crime, appellate courts scrutinize
whether the death sentence was properly and constitutionally
imposed. Gibson, only 17 at the time of the killing, was a drug
addict with diminished mental abilities. His trial lawyer's closing
arguments in which he pleaded for Gibson's life lasted only a few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976, when the U.S. Supreme Court reinstated the death
penalty, almost 500 people have been executed. More than 3,500
people now sit on death rows in 38 states _ including 121 in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 75 people have been freed from death row after
evidence showed they were wrongly convicted, according to the
Washington-based Death Penalty Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   These freed prisoners surely benefited from having competent
counsel, said Stephen Bright, director of the Southern Center for
Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely unconscionable that in a country that has
over a million lawyers, a person would stand alone at the bar of
justice facing the death penalty,'' Bright said of Gibson's case.
``There's no excuse for it, and there are so many people on death
row now in Georgia that if something is not done, this is going to
happen again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, most habeas petitions for death row inmates
have been handled by a state and federally funded resource center.
But the center has just two lawyers and one investigator, and its
caseload is so overwhelmed that Georgia Supreme Court Chief Justice
Robert Benham has asked Georgia law firms to take on death row
habeas cases for free. Benham's plea attracted many volunteers, but
not enough to represent Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Anderson, president of the American Bar Association, said
the Georgia Supreme Court should hear Gibson's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``A society that takes life as a punishment must take all
necessary steps to ensure that the person whose life was taken
received due process of law,'' Anderson, an Arkansas attorney, said
in a recent interview. ``That means representation of counsel
through every step of the proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing details of Gibson's crime, Anderson said the case
presents grisly facts that make it ``extremely difficult'' for any
court to have to decide such an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it points up the importance of everyone in our society
receiving due process, especially people on the fringes of society,
especially the most despised members of society,'' he said. ``If
constitutional rights can be taken from these people, they can be
taken from anyone, even you and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Oconee circuit District Attorney Timothy Vaughn, who prosecuted
Gibson's case, said Gibson has had enough access to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a difficult issue,'' he said. ``But with more
lawyers, the state and counties will have to pay for them, and the
cases will go on and on and on. The cases will become so
financially burdensome that nobody seeks the death penalty
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Thurbert Baker said the Georgia
Constitution includes no right for state-funded lawyers in habeas
proceedings, noting that the U.S. Supreme Court has ruled there is
no federal right for it as well. ``This is going to be a matter for
the Legislature to take up, if it chooses to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the Mississippi Supreme Court heard a challenge
similar to Gibson's by a death row inmate convicted of killing four
nieces and nephews. It ruled that the due process clause of its
state constitution requires death row inmates to have state-paid
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indigent death row inmates are simply not able, on their own,
to competently engage in this type of litigation,'' the court ruled
in the 7-2 decision.
</P>
<P>
   In motions before the Georgia Supreme Court, Gibson's lead
attorney, Joseph Bankoff, a King &AMP; Spalding partner who specializes
in commercial litigation, called Gibson's habeas hearing ``one of
the most unfair and one-sided evidentiary hearings conducted in
this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankoff said King &AMP; Spalding took on Gibson's case for free
after being presented with the record by two of the firm's younger
associates, Christian Genetski and Courtland Reichman.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reading the record of the trial court, I was offended in
the same way they were by what we read and what we saw had
happened,'' Bankoff said.
</P>
<P>
   In his motion, Bankoff noted that five months after Gibson's
hearing, Paige Whitaker, a state attorney who specializes in death
penalty cases, prepared a 49-page order denying Gibson's petition
and mailed it to the judge who presided over Gibson's hearing. The
judge, Carlisle Overstreet of the Augusta circuit, signed
Whitaker's proposed order without change.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, habeas corpus litigation in death penalty cases
has become one of the most complex of legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   John Godbold, former chief judge of the federal appeals court in
Atlanta, has said that ``the average trial lawyer, no matter what
his or her expertise, doesn't know any more about habeas than he
does about atomic energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Strict rules require death row inmates to raise all their habeas
claims initially in the state courts. If the claims are not raised
at this time, they are considered to be defaulted when the inmate
takes his case to federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Indigent death row inmates have neither the freedom, legal
resources nor the legal skills to master this process, a group of
prominent Atlanta lawyers have told the state Supreme Court. In a
friend-of-the-court brief, the lawyers _ Emmet Bondurant, C.B.
Rogers, Conley Ingram and Miles Alexander _ said denying inmates
counsel in these proceedings has the same effect as abolishing
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Habeas corpus is a minefield,'' said Atlanta lawyer Jack
Martin, an expert in death penalty litigation. ``The slightest
little misstep causes even the most valid constitutional claims to
be lost for good. The law shouldn't be a game, but that's what it
is. It only shows how essential it is for them to have a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
