<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-535(2T     01-23 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-535(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS SEEK END TO TRIAL, BUT DIVIDE ON BEST COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: La., Okla., W.Va., Utah, N.D., Vt., N.J., Texas, Ky., Iowa,
Minn.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-BIBLE-BELT, IMPEACH-WITNESSES-REVIEW) 
(bl) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the trial of President Clinton moving into an
unscripted period of critical votes, an increasingly restless
Senate is searching anxiously for a way to bring the impeachment
proceedings to a swift conclusion. But on Saturday the parties
appeared sharply divided over how to do this.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, after two weeks of passionate opening arguments by
House prosecutors and the White House, that the Senate still lacks
the 67 votes needed to convict Clinton and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats would like to end the trial now, either by
supporting a motion by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., to dismiss the
case or by voting against calling witnesses, which would pave the
way for a final vote on the articles of impeachment. Such motions
are to be considered this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could argue this until hell freezes over and the end result
would be the same,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday morning, senior Republicans said they would oppose
the Democratic effort to dismiss the case and they signaled that
would be a party position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it sets a constitutional precedent that doesn't make
any sense,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the majority whip.
``Every single impeachment trial in the history of the United
States Senate has had a resolution by voting up or down on the
articles.''
</P>
<P>
   The sharp words against Byrd's motion reflected the fact that
the Republicans, their caucus divided, face a far more difficult
and risky political calculation than the Democrats, even though
they, too, would like the trial to end relatively swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's public-approval ratings soared after his State of the
Union address and the public remains overwhelmingly opposed to his
removal from office. Conservatives, however, who make up the
Republicans' base, are already rebelling against an early end to
the trial. And many Senate Republicans are loath to sharply
repudiate the House Republicans who pushed through the two articles
of impeachment on a near party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting this tug and pull, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a
conservative, said, ``I don't feel the need to have witnesses,''
but quickly added, ``The House, as of now, has given us every
reason to believe they're going to ask for witnesses, so this is
not about me.'' He said ``impartial justice'' required that if the
House prosecutors wanted to depose witnesses, then ``within
limits'' they should be allowed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans, by contrast, have become less certain about
the merits of deposing Monica Lewinsky or Clinton's secretary,
Betty Currie, or his confidant, Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I think the House is going to have to make its case,''
said Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, who just a week ago was openly
leaning toward calling witnesses. ``If they can make a case for
witnesses, I'll vote for them, but it has to be a strong case.''
</P>
<P>
   Balancing those conflicting sentiments, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott is looking for a way to have only a handful of witnesses
deposed in private and to stringently control the length and scope
of the questioning so that the trial could end in February.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The leader's intention is to have this not go beyond
mid-February,'' said John Czwartacki, his spokesman. Such a plan
would give a bow to the House managers' insistence on witnesses but
leave the end of the trial in sight.
</P>
<P>
   But it is far from clear whether senators would really be able
to control the process if they voted to allow depositions of
witnesses behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are envisioning perhaps a week of taking
depositions. But David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, told the
Senate on Friday that if witnesses are summoned for deposition, the
White House would want to call witnesses itself, cross-examine
witnesses and subpoena documents for discovery. ``I think you are
looking realistically at a process of many months to have a fair
discovery process,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats looked far less likely Saturday to help negotiate time
limits because they were infuriated by the House managers' surprise
request to Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr _ even before the
Senate vote on whether to call witnesses _ to force Ms. Lewinsky to
testify before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outrageous thing,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
``To take that desperate act, all I can think of is, they are
losing it. It is mindboggling, absolutely mindboggling, this
arrogant disregard of the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way to end the trial is for six or more Republicans to
bolt and vote with the Democrats this week to block witnesses. (In
the case of a 50-50 tie, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist can
cast the decisive vote if he chooses.)
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's decision to sponsor the motion to dismiss the case
signaled that the 45 Democrats will have a nearly united front to
end the trial, since Byrd, the Senate's constitutionalist, had once
said he might consider voting for Clinton's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Republicans say, Lott is not trying to hold anyone to a
party position on witnesses, giving Republicans maneuvering room on
this issue. ``Nobody's going around saying, `You ought to do this,
you ought to do that,''' said one influential Republican senator.
``There's a general feeling we don't want to give the back of our
hand to the House. Other than that, there's broad latitude to do
what you damn well please.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other ideas are also floating about as informal discussions go
on inside the parties and across party lines. But an agreement on
how to end the trial could still prove elusive. ``There's a
majority to end the case but not a majority for any individual
motion to achieve that objective,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli,
D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, for instance, opposes a vote on articles of
impeachment and wants to dismiss the case outright because that
would discredit the House's vote to impeach . ``We're now arguing
about history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans insist that they have an actual vote on the
articles so they can say they followed the trial through to the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, has suggested that after witnesses are
deposed, if it is ``absolutely guaranteed'' there are not 67 votes
to convict the president, the Senate could recognize the House
impeachment as ``the highest vote of condemnation and of censure''
and vote to adjourn.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch's proposal has drawn fire from Republicans, who want a
vote on conviction, and Democrats, who fear that adjournment would
leave the charges pending against Clinton and leave him never fully
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   With the questioning of House prosecutors and White House
defense lawyers set to wrap up Saturday, the next few days will
give senators long hours to negotiate. ``This procedure forces us
to interact a lot,'' Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said wryly,
``because we are all around in one place.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the trial rules, beginning Monday, the Senate will be in
session but veering between public forums and closed discussions,
unless Sens. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, and Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., win a
bid to make all trial deliberations public. Such a rules change
would take 67 votes to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule calls for the White House and House prosecutors
each to get one hour for public debate on the effort to dismiss the
case. At that point, when Harkin and Wellstone make their motion to
open the proceedings, that must be debated in secret _ for up to 16
hours. The vote would be held in public and if their move fails,
the Senate would go back into closed session so that the lawmakers
can deliberate in private _ for up to 16 hours _ on whether to end
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Senate would move on to the motion to depose
witnesses. For this the House managers and White House would have
three hours each to debate for and against the proposal in public
session. But the debate by the senators would once again take place
in a closed session and could last up to 16 hours. At that point
the back-to-back votes on whether to dismiss the case and whether
to call witnesses would take place in public.
</P>
<P>
   Facing such a prospect this week, Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.,
said the mood in the Senate was ``like a two-week root canal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
