<P>
   CHINA-VICTIMS _ BEIJING _ When Chen Linna was a 14-year-old
schoolgirl, she had a recurrent dream: should she kill her father
after a wall poster declared him to be a ``criminal''? It was 1957,
and Chen's father had just been denounced by Mao's communists as a
``bourgeois rightist.'' A respected Chinese journalist with proven
communist revolutionary credentials, he was shipped off to one of
China's first forced labor camps. Now, after four decades, the
Communist Party is finally debating behind closed doors whether to
expunge Mao's verdict against the ``rightists'' as a historic
error. (Albright-Kunstel, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
