<P>
   CUBA-ECONOMY _ HAVANA _ At a crowded farmer's market in Old
Havana, Jose Marquez laments the high fees he must pay to the
government in order to sell tomatoes and melons at a small stand
for a few pesos a piece. He says that the Cuban government seems to
be doing everything it can to stop the spread of private
entrepreneurship on this socialist island. On Jan. 1, Cubans
celebrated the 40th anniversary of Fidel Castro's revolution. But
there's little to celebrate. The economy is a mess. In recent
months, the government appears to have back-peddled on economic
reforms that were so highly touted only a year ago. Spurring the
government on is economic turmoil in Asia, Brazil, and other parts
of the world, ``proof'' that capitalism doesn't work, at least
according to Castro. (Emling, Cox News Service)
