<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORES _ WASHINGTON _ Bill and Al, Hillary and Tipper.
Bill and Hillary, Tipper and Al. Either way, it's a family of
political soul mates with contrasting styles, and it has held
together with remarkable consistency through a painful year of
scandal. The First Foursome will be on display more than ever in
the months to come, as Gore steps increasingly from the shadows for
his own presidential bid and the administration uses Mrs. Clinton
and Mrs. Gore to help articulate the goals and policies of a
popular president with a serious credibility problem. (Deans, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUSINESS _ WASHINGTON _ When business talks, Congress
listens. The first two hearings held by Chairman Bill Archer,
R-Texas of the House Ways and Means Committee after President
Clinton's State of the Union address were on the economy's health
(Wed. Jan. 20) and Social Security reforms (Thurs. Jan. 21). Those
topics are top priorities on the legislative wish lists compiled by
the capitol's biggest business lobbies, which range from the
upstart National Federation of Independent Business to the old
familiar U.S. Chamber of Commerce. In Wednesday's Billion-Byte
March, the chamber and NFIB also helped fund the first big email
lobbying blitz of the year on any topic other than impeachment.
What else they want, and why. The odds they face. (Mollison, Cox
News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With sidebar list of the NFIB and chamber lobbying
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has proposed
that, for the first time, the government invest part of the money
in the Social Security trust fund in the private market. Economists
are split on the idea with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
giving thumbs down, while former Social Security Commissioner
Robert Ball gives it thumbs up. A look at the pros and cons of the
issue at the heart of the Social Security reform. (Lipman, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MLK-THE-THIRD _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He was only 5 when his father,
Martin Luther King Jr., gave the ``I Have a Dream'' speech in
Washington, D.C. He was 10 when his father was shot to death in
Memphis, Tenn., in 1968. But Martin Luther King III's prominent
role in this year's Martin Luther King Jr. Day celebrations and his
new post as president of the organization his father co-founded,
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, show that he may be
coming into his own. (Thatcher, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BEETHOVEN-BABIES _ LOS ANGELES _ Former Georgia Gov. Zell Miller
was right; playing Beethoven for an unborn child may have positive
consequences on the child's well-being. A group of researchers
report on new findings about the consequences of early child care
at the annual meeting of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
15.
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW _ ATLANTA _ As the Georgia Supreme Court opens its
January term on Monday (Jan. 25), there's one important case
pending that it apparently does not want to consider: whether to
allow death-row inmates the right to have appointed lawyers during
their post-conviction appeals. The issue is a thorny one for the
court because it doesn't want to require the Legislature to pay for
death-row lawyers, but it is also aware that about two-thirds of
all death-row convictions are ultimately reversed. And there are
dozens of former death-row inmates who have been found to be
innocent, including a couple in Georgia, and they obtained their
relief in the courts through habeas corpus petitions. Their claims
would never have gone anywhere without competent counsel to
represent them. The case before the Georgia Supreme Court involves
Exzavious Gibson, who is without a doubt guilty of stabbing
repeatedly a grocer during an armed robbery. But Gibson, who has an
IQ of 76, had to represent himself during his post-conviction
hearing, the procedure of which has been described as complicated
as any in the legal system. Georgia is one of only two states in
the country (Wyoming being the other) that does not appoint counsel
for death-row inmates filing habeas corpus petitions. (Rankin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/DEATHROW-HABEAS _ ATLANTA _ What is habeas corpus, anyway?
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
