<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKOREA-RECOVERY-ART-2     01-23 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-RECOVERY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SEOUL, South Korea: a year.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The transition, however, has produced some sorry victims, like
Cho Il-young, who have fallen through the holes in the safety net
because they lost their jobs before the program was expanded or
because their companies were never registered. Cho, a 30-year-old
factory worker, was let go more than a year ago from a small
affiliate of Kia Motors, a car manufacturer that was one of the
first chaebol to collapse. He has not collected any benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work one day only to find that the company was
folding, but he could not bring himself to tell his wife. Instead,
he prepared for work every day, and went to the employment office
in the morning and the library in the afternoon. At the time, his
company was too small for him to receive unemployment benefits, so
he had to draw on his personal savings to pay for food and other
daily expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, he finally broke down and confessed to his
wife, who had suspected something was amiss all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, my savings have almost bottomed out, but I don't
have any opportunities for new employment,'' said Cho, who cannot
receive benefits, because he is not newly unemployed. Now he is
angry because the price of ramen noodles, his staple food these
days, rose to 400 won, or 34 cents, from 330 won when the won
weakened. But prices never fell again when the won recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done all different types of work,'' he said. ``But I
couldn't even break even. I couldn't even make enough money to
cover transportation costs. There's a lot of talk about the economy
rebounding, but this is true only in the statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Another cloud over South Korea is political uncertainty. Not
only does it share a border with North Korea, a heavily armed
communist state that could explode or implode at any time, but Kim
is locked in a bitter confrontation with the opposition political
party, and he is supposed to give up power late this year to a
coalition partner under a deal that most analysts expect to fall
apart at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kim so far has surprised some of his critics by the
vigor with which he has moved to restructure Korea's economy and
lift it out of its worst contraction since the end of World War II.
Along with Thailand, South Korea seems eager to rip apart the seams
of the old economy and tailor itself for future growth.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of investor confidence is that the South Korean
currency, the won, has soared from its lows a year ago. Now a
dollar fetches about 1,180 won, compared with 1,600 in December
1997 and about 800 before the crisis erupted. The government
stabilized the won partly by increasing interest rates early last
year, but now interest rates have come down again.
</P>
<P>
   The falling interest rates have eased the debt burdens of many
companies. With lower rates, investors have poured their money into
the Korean stock market, which last year more than doubled, in
dollar terms, over the previous year and was the world's best
performing market in dollar terms in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Like Thailand, the government has also moved far more quickly
than Japan and other Asian countries to fix its broken banking
system, pouring in more than 64 trillion won, or $54 billion, to
retool it. One of the reasons South Korean banks are in such bad
shape is that they lent on the basis of government instruction,
becoming ``the ATMs of the Finance Ministry,'' as William Overholt,
Asia strategist at Nomura International in Hong Kong, put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korea's military culture is mainly to blame'' for many of the
banking system's troubles, said Choi Gye-sung, a 54-year-old Korean
banker who took early retirement last year. ``The military culture
means giving orders, and it doesn't matter if things work out or
not,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes will take longer to change, but the fear of a collapse
of the financial system is gone. With the number of bankruptcies
declining, a measure of calm is returning to the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody believed that something worse might come before the
end of the year, like an American crisis or a credit crunch, but
that didn't happen,'' said Cho Dal Ho, chief economist at Samsung
Economic Research Institute, referring to the end of 1998. ``We
expected the bank loans would blow up, but our expectation turned
out to be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Another striking initiative of Kim has been his campaign to lure
foreign investors with new tax incentives and subsidies and quicker
approvals. Attitudes in Korea Inc. have shifted from antipathy to
admiration of foreigners, and Western investors have swooped into
Korea on bargain hunts, bumping into one another as they swish in
and out of Korean company offices and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   From corporate tire-kickers to property investors to big-time
acquirers, foreign investors poured in $8.9 billion in investment
last year, more than one-third of the entire amount invested in the
previous 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   As the new year opened, the government sold off a
multibillion-dollar controlling stake in Korea First Bank to an
American consortium; this deal and all the others will bring in
Western-style management and a focus on profitability. But perhaps
the biggest spur toward profits at the top chaebol will come from
the smaller, nimbler competition.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at Daesang Corp., the top seller of monosodium
glutamate in Korea, strategic planners are thinking a bit more
about profits. Last year, Daesang sold a money-making venture in
animal feed to BASF Co., based in Germany, so that it could pay off
its debts. And it is moving out of marginal businesses as well, to
boost overall profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the days of high growth, all that mattered were
increased sales and increased market share,'' said Lee Geon-duck, a
manager in strategic planning. Immediately he began scribbling on a
sheet of paper a set of equations on profitability that have become
the mantra of the company. ``But now what really matters is the
amount of profit generated from each investment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
