A5512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COLUMN-SUPERBOWL-     01-23 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-SUPERBOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS-FALCONS HAS THE MAKINGS OF A DOOZY
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is true. No denying it. Most football fans yearned for a
Minnesota-Denver tango in Super Bowl XXXIII. That matchup would
have delivered the teams with the best records from each
conference, two clubs with explosive offenses and, combined, more
marquee stars. The rookie receiver Randy Moss would spice the
entire affair. Purple Pride would overflow. Minnesota purple vs.
Denver orange? How much more colorful could it get?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Denver Broncos versus the Atlanta Falcons in Super
Bowl XXXIII is cooking, simmering, boiling to a point that come
next Sunday, we will see a super show. This game is going to
provide tingling theater. Among the reasons are:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Dan Reeves-vs.-Mike Shanahan/John Elway factor. It began
with niceties from both camps when the teams earned their Super
Bowl berths. Bad blood was behind them, the parties initially said.
New day. New time. Uh, not quite. Emotions have begun to spill for
Reeves, the Falcons' head coach, and Shanahan, Denver's head coach,
and Elway, Denver's quarterback, three guys who used to work
together in Denver before a nasty split. The bad blood between them
has begun to spill. Sharp criticisms. Old wounds have been reopened
between men who used to work closely together who grew to not trust
or enjoy each other. They fought it. They could not help it. And
now, on the inside, for sure, there is little cooling it. Take bad
karma between leadership, wrap it into a football game, a game with
the highest stakes possible, and the trickle-down effect is
enormous. You have drama. The result is one party left flying and
the other left crying. Tremendous desire. Tremendous personal
stakes. Worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Terrell Davis of Denver and Jamal Anderson of Atlanta are
running backs who will excite every time they touch the football.
The challenge will be special for both teams' defenses to squeeze
these exciting runners and their gifted offensive lines. Both backs
are adept pass catchers, too. Both also know the importance of
outplaying and outrushing each other. Tremendous desire. Tremendous
personal stakes. Worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   _ No slap against the Vikings, but the Atlanta defense is more
fun to watch. Bigger and harder hitters. And led by bruising
tacklers Bill Romanowski at linebacker and Steve Atwater at safety,
the Broncos can offer crunching blows all day long. The best
football is, in part, hitting. Pure smack-you-in-the-mouth hitting.
Get ready for a physical game. Tremendous desire. Tremendous
personal stakes. Worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   People around the Falcons now think of them as a team of
destiny. Even Reeves talks about this, because before they became
Dirty Birds the Falcons were simply foul.
</P>
<P>
   This is a franchise that had made the playoffs only once in the
last six seasons. They began the 1997 season, Reeves' first in
Atlanta, with a 1-7 record. The season before Reeves came, Atlanta
was a 3-13 team.
</P>
<P>
   But this season the Falcons righted themselves, began to
implement Reeves' plan of smart, sound and simple football (run the
ball, stop the run, don't make turnovers and create turnovers) and
then smelled success.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual and special way, the Falcons late in the season
turned Reeves' life-threatening quadruple heart surgery into
positive motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said: ``As a coach, you preach and preach things, and you
can only hope it gets through to the players. This is a different
group because they are close and they have responded. They
listened. They have done all of the things we as coaches have asked
and that makes me proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcon players say that when their coach faced his
life-or-death situation, it turned up their focus. They listened
even more. Responded more. Details, details. Thus Reeves, when he
returned as the playoffs unfolded, had them squarely in the palm of
his hands. For Reeves, a coach's nightmare had become a coach's
dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that when it looked like we might lose
Coach Reeves for good that everybody stopped dead in their tracks
and got serious _ real serious,'' said Tony Martin, a Falcons
receiver. ``We turned a negative into a positive. We became even
more of a team and everybody around here gave everything a little
more attention and effort.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it all served the Falcons well. It helped push them
over the top in the playoffs, to a tough victory at home over their
personal Big Brother, the San Francisco 49ers, and then the
improbable victory at heavily favored Minnesota. Is destiny
calling? Is Super Bowl XXXIII simply meant for Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone around the Falcons sure thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   In Super Bowl XXXIII, someone is going to scoop the ball up and
score on a game-swinging play, or knock it loose and recover it to
save the day, or catch it for 90 yards in a flashy moment, or,
simply, be in the perfect place at the perfect time for one key
moment or for several throughout the game. The hero.
</P>
<P>
   We are talking the Super Bowl XXXIII MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the likely candidates?
</P>
<P>
   _ Terrell Davis _ Won it last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jamal Anderson _ Durable. Dependable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Terance Mathis _ Falcons receiver with a flair for the
dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shannon Sharpe _ Denver tight end with a lot of mouth, a lot
of production.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jessie Tuggle _ Falcons linebacker is league's career-leading
scorer on fumble returns and among all current players is leading
tackler.
</P>
<P>
   _ Darrien Gordon _ Denver double trouble as punt returner and
cornerback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
