<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     01-23 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS' SPECTACLE: BRING THEM ALL ON
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This season is going to be nutty enough, so the
Knicks might as well load up on characters rather than character.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, fans are going to be treated to the spectacle of
strangers being thrown together in the name of a National
Basketball Association season, 50 games in three months, with
dubious prospects of artistry.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams are going to be in better shape than others. (Not so
fast, you heavy-breathing Knicks.) Other teams are going to be more
cohesive. (Mr. Houston, meet Mr. Sprewell. Mr. Camby, meet Mr.
Ewing.)
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Dave Checketts, the chief executive officer of
Madison Square Garden, is renouncing his ``self-righteous''
attitude, in which he maintained he would not hire players on the
divisive side, the Knicks might as well go for broke.
</P>
<P>
   There is no claim here of any insider basketball scoops about
the availability of Rod Strickland and Dennis Rodman, but one does
hear their names bandied about. The unpredictable point guard and
the eccentric forward would fit right in.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks took a huge risk in hiring Latrell Sprewell because
he could blow at any time. I'm a firm believer in giving people
second chances, but I like to hear them throw around a little
remorse and a little insight, however phony it may be. Just fake
it.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, Sprewell sounds like a guy who thinks he had a bad
day at the gym when he tried to choke his coach last season, so why
is everybody always picking on him? I would have admired the Knicks
more if they had passed on him, but I can understand why they went
for his talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing he can do is stay out of the newspapers,'' said
Herb Williams, the 40-year-old solid citizen just retained for his
18th season in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, if they think you're not playing hard, they will
needle you, but if you hustle, you can make a mistake here and
there,'' said Williams, referring to on-the-court blunders.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell has talent on his side, along with the fact that the
Knicks were in dire need of a makeover. I cannot work myself into
any maudlin state over the departure of Charles Oakley and John
Starks because, in the past year, I found myself terminally bored
with the same limited and dysfunctional act.
</P>
<P>
   However, I suspect this new lot has even greater potential for
dysfunction. Few of the Knicks spent time working out together
during the lockout, partly because their nominal leader, Patrick
Ewing, was busy as the head of the players association.
</P>
<P>
   Their coach, the disciplined and knowledgeable Jeff Van Gundy,
is a trifle testy about hearing that 10 or 11 Indiana Pacers were
working out together but that his squad is symbolically arriving in
separate sport-utility vehicles from different corners of the
basketball globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys are in good shape and some guys' conditioning level
is less than NBA-level right now,'' Van Gundy said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The coach said he can see extra weight on some players, while
others might ``look all right, but their cardiovascular condition
is not great.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing looks heavy, and he has bad knees, and Van Gundy admitted
Ewing could be challenged by three games in three nights, which
happens three times during the retooled schedule. ``I wouldn't want
to use him for just 24 minutes rather than his usual 35,'' Van
Gundy said, ``but I'd ask him if he wanted to take a game off now
and then.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks sound like candidates to get whacked by the short,
grueling season, but Williams said: ``This game is 90 percent
mental and 10 percent physical. You start looking for hidden
agendas, that's where you get in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the worst thing a player could do was pace
himself, ``because that's where you get hurt.'' He did not think
the Knicks would be at a disadvantage because of their reliance on
the 36-year-old Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the teams that have won championships,'' Williams
said. ``Sure, the Bulls had Michael, but Houston won with Hakeem,
and Detroit won with Isiah, and before that the Lakers won with
Magic. The older guys know how to get your rest and stay mentally
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of mentally ready, Williams said it might help Sprewell
to join the franchise with perhaps the heaviest news media coverage
and most demanding fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes care of it right here, then he knows he can handle
anything,'' Williams said. ``I think it's tougher here, but also
better.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sprewell can avoid the coach-choking, teammate-battering
image he had with Golden State, he will have a chance. The nice
thing about this short and frantic season is that between the 50
games and the travel, there won't be much time for practices. That
will be good for Van Gundy's throat, if nothing else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
