<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-MEDICINE-ART-NYT &LR;      01-23 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-MEDICINE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUSADER DECLARES THAT Y2K POSES THREAT TO NATION'S MEDICINE
SUPPLY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Minn., Tenn.)   ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ As a nurse turned computer systems manager,
Laureen West is one of a crowd of consultants able to describe how
year-2000 computer malfunctions could interrupt the distribution of
medicines. But as a brain tumor patient who needs daily doses of
synthetic-thyroid and other drugs to stay alive, the 43-year-old
Mrs. West has no rivals when it comes to convincing listeners that
it matters.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. West's obvious lack of ease in talking publicly about a
condition she long kept private only adds to the wallop when she
speaks, whether to church groups here in her hometown, to seminars
for health care officials or, as in October, to a Senate
subcommittee as an expert witness on Y2K, as the year-2000 problem
is known.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are confronted with her, it is hard to view Y2K as
just a computer issue,'' said Joel Ackerman, founder of the Rx2000
Solutions Institute, a Minneapolis clearinghouse for year-2000
medical issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. West, who works with the clearinghouse as a consultant,
embodies much of what is most troubling about Y2K: uncertainty
about the extent of the problem, questions about who the reliable
experts are and doubts about where reasonable precautions slip over
the line into dangerous overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K threat stems from computer designers' onetime practice
of using just two digits for recording of the year in dates, like
99 for 1999. Accordingly many computers and electronically
controlled machines mistake 00 for 1900 rather than 2000, or cannot
interpret it at all.
</P>
<P>
   To date, almost all the publicity about Y2K in health care has
focused on concerns that because medical devices like pacemakers,
X-ray machines and intravenous pumps have embedded microprocessors,
they could malfunction. While evidence is mounting that most
medical devices will be fine, Mrs. West and others are drawing
attention to their demand that the health care industry give the
public much more information about how it plans to handle the
distribution of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just ask yourself how many people you know who are
drug-dependent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, it has been an uphill battle for consumers.
National groups that could apply pressure for information and
coordinated planning, like the American Association of Retired
Persons, are only beginning to look at the possibility of Y2K
breakdowns in the medical pipeline. The nation's largest overseer
of health care delivery, the Department of Health and Human
Services, says the entire issue of drug distribution in the year
2000 is not its concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a state issue, because they regulate the pharmacies,''
said Campbell Garbett, a spokesman for the department.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of specific reassurances that the risks are
minimal, there is a ready audience for the worst-case scenario that
Mrs. West describes. It starts with interruptions in the shipments
of raw materials to drug companies, breakdowns in the factories
that make crucial medicines and snarls in the transportation and
warehousing networks that distribute them. It continues with chaos
at the nation's 118,000 pharmacies, where computers keep patient
records, and at the HMOs and insurance companies that must
authorize payments before most prescriptions are filled.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. West also fears that power and phone systems vital to all
these links in the chain could collapse for days, even weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In response to all this, she has argued that the federal
government should enact a one-time waiver allowing patients to buy
90-day supplies of drugs whose prescriptions are currently
restricted by law to 30 days, and should encourage insurers to
reimburse promptly for such stockpiling. Patients, she says, should
be warned immediately to begin setting aside money to cover their
share of the costs of the added supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in the health care industry call Mrs. West's
prescription counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could create a lot of problems that wouldn't exist
otherwise,'' said Keith Mallonee, vice president in charge of
systems development at the McKesson Corporation, one of the
nation's largest drug distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
   Mallonee and others say patient stockpiling could create
shortages of some medicines, a development that would be especially
threatening to the poor, many of whom would not be able to afford
stockpiling's cost.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, since studies show that patients often fail to consume
their entire supply of medicine from prescriptions running 30 days
or longer before switching to new drugs or simply quitting,
distributing large drug supplies to consumers could be very
wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can advocate not stockpiling,'' said Daniel Nutkis,
president of the Odin Group, a health care research and consulting
firm in Nashville, Tenn., that created Vitalsigns 2000, the first
Y2K planning group representing every part of the medical pipeline.
But the issue, Nutkis said, is how large the stockpiles should be _
perhaps only a few days' supply _ and how much, if any, should be
maintained by consumers rather than health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Nutkis also said new kinds of cooperation within the industry
might well be part of any solution. For instance, while competition
would normally drive a pharmaceutical company to make sure that it
could meet the full demand for its particular drug, it would now
make sense, he said, to build up supplies of unique drugs in
preparation for Y2K and have everyone agree to stock less of those
drugs for which there are alternatives. ``There are only a few
therapies where you only have one option,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. West says she is taking criticism of her proposals
seriously and is open to discussing alternatives to home
stockpiling, for instance creating regional supplies in secure
locations like armories.
</P>
<P>
   What might seem like minor glitches to those running the health
care system, she argues, could mean anxiety, pain or even death for
many of the tens of millions of Americans taking drug cocktails to
control AIDS, insulin for diabetes, drugs to prevent rejection of
transplanted organs, and numerous other medications.
</P>
<P>
   `` ``And it's not just the chronically ill we need to
consider,'' Mrs. West said. ``If you have a terminally ill patient,
you have to have enough narcotics to allow them to go humanely.''
</P>
<P>
   Planning for disaster is nothing new for Mrs. West, a Mormon who
keeps supplies of food and water in her basement in response to
religious teachings as well as Y2K fears. But it took Y2K to
transform her into a campaigner with very public health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm walking a gangplank when I speak in public,''
said the intensely private Mrs. West. But, she added, neither she
nor the fears she voices will disappear any time soon: ``I live,
breathe, think about year 2000 all day long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
