u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-KURD-LEADER-NY     01-23 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-KURD-LEADER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURDISH REBEL FLEES ITALY, BUT TO WHERE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Germany)  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ During their weeklong religious holiday that
is now drawing to an end, many Turks have been playing a variation
of a popular parlor game: Where's Apo?
</P>
<P>
   The Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan, widely known as
Apo, is Turkey's most wanted fugitive. He left Italy eight days ago
after a stay of more than six weeks, but nobody seems to know where
he went.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after Ocalan disappeared from Rome, Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit of Turkey said he had learned from ``extremely reliable
sources'' that Ocalan had flown to Russia. But on Friday Russia
denied that he was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can officially say that Ocalan is not on Russian
territory,'' Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers in Greece reported that Ocalan had applied for a
six-month residence permit from the Greek government, but the
application was denied.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish foreign ministry has summoned the ambassadors of
Estonia, Ukraine and South Africa, all countries to which Ocalan
was reported heading, and warned that they must not shelter him.
</P>
<P>
   Each day brings a new round of speculation on Ocalan's
whereabouts. He was said to be in Belarus, then Lebanon, then Iran.
On Friday, one Istanbul newspaper reported that Ocalan was in the
enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh, which the world recognizes as part of
Azerbaijan but which is under the military control of ethnic
Armenians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Nagorno-Karabakh is not part of Armenia from a legal
point of view, Turkey could not apply any pressure on Armenia,''
the newspaper said. ``If Turkey were to exert any pressure, that
would imply a de facto recognition of Armenia's control of the
enclave.''
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish defense minister, Hikmet Sami Turk, said he had no
idea where to look for Ocalan, but pledged that Turkey would not
let him rest. ``Wherever Apo goes,'' he said, ``we will keep
chasing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey holds Ocalan responsible for an estimated 30,000 deaths _
that being the total number of soldiers and civilians said to have
died in the 14-year war waged by his Kurdistan Workers Party. He
portrays himself as the leader of a struggle against oppression.
</P>
<P>
   After Ocalan arrived in Rome in November, Turkey demanded that
Italy extradite him for trial here. That proved impossible because
Italy's constitution does not permit the extradition of suspects
who might face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Italian efforts to send Ocalan to Germany, where he is sought in
connection with several crimes, also failed. Many Kurds live in
Germany, and the government there feared violence if it brought
Ocalan to trial.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin said: ``We
regret that the path chosen by Italy does not appear to have
advanced the goal of bringing Ocalan to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch, a group based in New York, said Ocalan's
guerrillas were responsible for hundreds of executions. It said
Italy and the international community have ``in this case missed an
important opportunity to signal that those who commit atrocities
will be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have repeatedly demanded that the Turkish government
investigate and hold accountable those members of its security
forces responsible for serious violations of international human
rights,'' the group's executive director, Holly Cartner, said in a
statement. ``Had Turkey done so, it might have found greater
international sympathy for its case against Ocalan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
