<HEADER>
A5531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN24-C     01-23 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fate finally unites Bowl, Anderson
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has been a great week of practice for Jamal
Anderson. He is so prepared for this Super Bowl that it's almost
scary.
</P>
<P>
   Before the serious media riot breaks out in Miami, the Falcons
audacious running back has refined his sound bites at humble
Suwanee. A little clearing of the throat in advance of the most
grueling few days of public relations imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, Anderson's ready. Every adjective is honed, every
overstatement is at the point of peaking. Seeing a German
television crew Wednesday, he immediately went into his rap about
capturing whole new continents. ``I'm trying to make sure I cross
over. I want to be on all the European stations, that's my goal. If
I see a camera from Europe, I'm coming to find it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm (going after) Spain, Germany, Sweden, Denmark, Russia. The
folks freezing in Siberia, y'all will get to watch me. Y'all will
get to say, 'He's very, very handsome, and a pretty good player.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Another line Anderson auditioned several times last week
concerned his ambitions about a future career on celluloid,
something beyond NFL Films. ``I'm trying to be like Will Smith.
Will Smith saved the world twice. Why can't I save the world, too?
Somebody out there must have a script for a football player who can
save the world. Why not?'' he wondered. It has played very well,
and we expect to hear much more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is unconcerned about the infamous Super Bowl
distractions. In fact, he has every intention of becoming one.
</P>
<P>
   You gain 1,800 yards, perfect a dance craze and cure a blighted
franchise, then the horizon is truly endless.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the one Falcons personality best suited for the epic
compost-slinging to come and still have plenty left for game day.
To borrow an old image, Anderson is quite comfortable making like
an AM radio on scan. Now is no time to clam up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have fun,'' he says, serving a valuable reminder.
``It's fun to be in the situation we're in. That's why I say
nothing's really a bother to me, because I'd rather you guys be
here `bothering' us than bothering the Packers or any other team.
All I wanted to do for so many years is win, and now we're winners.
This is it, it gets no better than the Super Bowl. Everything is
fun for me, it really is. That's what I'm trying to convey in my
interviews and my attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   It's inevitable that something Anderson says will be
misinterpreted this week. The volume alone is sure to create some
kind of trouble. That's how Super Bowl week works. He might mention
a fondness for deviled ham; it will come out: ``Anderson Cuts Deal
With Satan!''
</P>
<P>
   He says he will mind his words when it comes to the opponent,
promising nothing that will give the Broncos an edge. And Anderson
just might be bright enough to carry that off, for he is not some
cheap Hollywood Henderson knock-off. ``Trust me,'' he says. ``I've
got to run the ball 30 times; you think I want somebody to hit me
harder? No, no, no. I'm going to say, `The Broncos are tough, the
best team, defending champs. They're vicious, ferocious, tenacious.
They're good, man.'''
</P>
<P>
   If ever a man and moment were meant for each other, this is it.
Raised on the idea that to be average is to be invisible, growing
up at the knees of all those celebrities his father guarded,
Anderson accepts what is happening to him as completely natural. He
is merely assuming a rightful place. ``Now (the celebs) are coming
to see me at the Super Bowl, the ultimate stage,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my element. This is my destiny,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one concern. Is the Super Bowl big enough to hold
Jamal Anderson?
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
