<HEADER>
A5532 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-AMERICUS-C     01-23 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-AMERICUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome to Reeves' town: Americus, Ga.
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMERICUS, Ga. _ They're painting the town red. And black and
white. With images of Falcons and such sentiments as ``Dan's Our
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Atlanta lines up against the Denver Broncos next
Sunday in Miami, all the storefronts on West Lamar Street will have
a fresh coat. Maybe even up North Lee Street.
</P>
<P>
   One look at the frenzy that has gripped this city of 17,000 and
you'd think it was the Americus Falcons in Super Bowl XXXIII. A
native son, Dan ``Our Man'' Reeves has coached the Falcons to the
NFL promised land, and the folks here are acting like they're
cheering on a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   From the city limits, where the sign at Clinic Drug Store reads
``Way To Go Dan Reeves &AMP; Atlanta Falcons,'' to the heart of
downtown, Americus is busting its buttons about the hometown hero.
</P>
<P>
   Banners have been ordered. A window of The Kinnebrew Co.
clothing store _ ``the Neiman Marcus of Americus,'' founder Hulme
Kinnebrew Jr. said _ features an autographed picture of Reeves from
his days as a Dallas Cowboys running back. The local newspaper is
sponsoring the Dirty Bird Talent Search: The person who does the
best interpretation of the now-famous Falcons dance wins $250.
</P>
<P>
   What's next, a Dan Reeves statue? ``We'll see, if they win the
game,'' Mayor Russell Thomas Jr. said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The whole city is in one happy dither. ``It's the biggest thing
to hit Americus since the flood of '94,'' said Caren Allgood of the
Downtown Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Americus suddenly discovered that Reeves used to
play football here. He was the starting quarterback at Americus
High, Class of 1960. They've followed his career as a player at the
University of South Carolina and with the Cowboys. Some folks, like
his high school coach, Jimmy Hightower, bought a satellite dish to
follow Reeves' coaching career at Denver and New York. Reeves was
the first inductee into the local sports hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   They've had so many Dan Reeves Days here, they could add up to a
week. He was home last spring to dedicate a recreation complex and
receive another proclamation: The road off Highway 19 leading to
the ball fields was named Dan Reeves Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves hasn't forgotten his hometown, either. He carries around
a souvenir from his youth, a scar on his right hand. ``We used to
play football in the cow pasture on our farm,'' he said. ``One
time, I went a little too wide around end and got tackled by the
barbed-wire fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The media descended upon Americus this week to check the local
pulse and was greeted with a down-home hug. ``Welcome CNN'' croons
the marquee at Sumter Bank and Trust, followed by a prediction:
``Watch Dan Reeves &AMP; The Falcons Do The Dirty Bird All Over The
Broncos.''
</P>
<P>
   The Art Club at Americus High heard company was coming and
jumped into action Wednesday, frantically painting storefronts,
even unoccupied shops. ``We'll probably be painting right up until
the kickoff on Sunday,'' said Ginger Bass, the art teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wants to get in on the act. As Bass' students were
putting their brush strokes on the front of Elizabeth's Christian
Book Store the other afternoon, a woman drove up in a pickup.
``Please paint my truck,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we did,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of a new gift shop around the corner walked up and
asked to be involved. ``You'll have to get on the list,'' Bass told
him. She pulled out a wad of phone messages. ``These are just from
this morning. The Ford dealer just called, and that's going to be a
nightmare. That whole building is glass windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass isn't worried about running out of paint, but she's already
out of catchy slogans. ``Dan's Our Man,'' ``Catch That Falcon
Spirit,'' and ``The Birds Of Prey Are Here To Stay'' went quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asking the store owners to help me out with slogans; I'm
burned out,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   With the pressure on, the folks at Computer Business Services
came up with ``How 'Bout Dem Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Jones of the Nancy Jones School of Dance weighed in with
``Hats Off To Our Falcons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Jones said. ``It's kind of fitting for a dance
studio.'' She said she didn't teach Reeves how to dance, ``but I've
danced with him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been that kind of week. Not everyone you meet in Americus
claims to have danced with the Falcons coach, but they all seem to
know him and are eager to share their Dan Reeves stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know his nickname is `Tuck'?'' Kinnebrew asked. ``I
think he got it because of Friar Tuck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he got it from the nursery rhyme, `Old Dan Tuck,''' said
his daughter-in-law, Carolyn Turner. ``Whenever he comes home, we
still call him Tuck. Americus is really excited for Dan. Everywhere
you go, that's all people talk about. This is a big, big deal for
us, seeing the success a hometown boy is having. There's a lot of
local pride and hometown enthusiasm here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's a Christian, and his mother shops with us,'' said
Malinda McKinney, who owns Elizabeth's Christian Book Store.
``We're just so proud he's done extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came from the Wal-Mart,'' Mayor Thomas said, ``and
everybody I saw in that store wanted to talk about Dan and the
Falcons. One fellow said to me (that) after that game against the
Vikings the doctors don't need to put Dan on a treadmill to check
the strength of his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Former teammates have been dusting off their memories, too.
Loveard McMichael, athletics director at Southland Academy, dug out
his Americus High team pictures.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael, No. 11, was a junior backup quarterback behind
Reeves, No. 10, the senior starter for the Americus Panthers. ``We
would have won the state championship if Dan hadn't broken his
collarbone,'' McMichael said. ``He missed several games. He had a
pin put in his collarbone so he could play and _ this tells you how
tough the guy is _ when they pulled it out, the pin was bent up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I didn't see the pin personally, but that's the local
legend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember he fumbled the ball one time in a game,'' said Ken
Hart, a former tackle now in the construction business, ``and coach
Hightower kind of humiliated him in practice the next day. He threw
a ball down three or four times in a row and made Dan practice
recovering a fumble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember hanging out with him all that much,'' said
ex-fullback Randy Green, now disabled with two ailing hips. ``He
was mostly with Pam (now Reeves' wife) when he was free. But I'm
ecstatic for Dan. In fact, I was pulling for Denver last Sunday; I
want to see him in a grudge match in the Super Bowl. I believe
he'll win that game.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Reeves' old friends have stayed in touch. The Class of
'61 sent him a good luck card this week. And all of Americus, it
seems, wants to let Dan Our Man know that the hometown folks are
pulling for him in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan is such a personable fellow,'' the mayor said, ``it makes
it real easy to be supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So tell me,'' Nancy Jones said, ``are they as excited in
Atlanta as we are down here?''
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
