<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-THEGAME-COX     01-23 1952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THEGAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'On to Miami' slogan proved premature in Minnesota
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS, Minn
</P>
<P>
   The Minneapolis cab driver negotiated the rush-hour traffic
deftly and swiftly through the snow, the way the Vikings ran
through the NFL regular season. He was in a festive mood, as was
the entire city, and with good reason. The temperature rose from
subzero to slightly above freezing. Former wrestling oaf Jesse
Ventura was hours from being inaugurated as governor. And the next
day, the town's superb football team had a great opportunity to
advance to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the happy cabbie chatted it up with his passenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good time to be in Minnesota,'' he said, glancing into
the rear-view mirror. ``Everyone's excited, especially about our
Vikings. What do you think of them? It should be a good game, don't
you think?''
</P>
<P>
   The response: ``Yeah, because the Falcons are a very good team,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the driver's eyes got narrow. He stopped the car at
the light, turned his head completely around and then expressed the
perspective that permeated the Twin Cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about the Super Bowl,'' he said. ``I'm not worried
about Atlanta. We'll definitely beat them. No problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the arrogance of the metropolitan area. It was not just
the taxi driver. There was the owner, Red McCombs, calling in
unsolicited to a Minneapolis all-sports radio station last week to
say, ``We're going Bird hunting and then on to Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   There was tight end Andrew Glover, proclaiming: ``When we are at
home, we are impossible to beat. Only the Vikings can truly beat
the Vikings.''
</P>
<P>
   There were the local newspapers _ The Minneapolis Star Tribune
and the St. Paul Pioneer Press _ with special editions already
prepared to distrubute after the game, proclaiming, ``ON TO
MIAMI.''
</P>
<P>
   There were athletic stores in the malls with T-shirts on display
calling the Vikings ``NFC Champions.'' There were several scheduled
``victory parties,'' including one thrown by McCombs at a downtown
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, it was all so premature, all so arrogant. The Falcons
earned their first Super Bowl trip with a dramatic 30-27 victory on
Morten Andersen's 38-yard field goal in overtime _ a kick that
touched off a explosion of emotions in Atlanta and Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredible, when you think about it,'' said Falcons coach Dan
Reeves, who five weeks earlier had undergone quadruple bypass heart
surgery. ``I couldn't be prouder.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only for the outcome, but for the way the Falcons defeated
the Vikings, an 11-point favorite with a 16-1 record and way too
much confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons took a 7-0 lead on the first drive of the game, but
the Vikings went ahead 20-7 after key fumbles by Harold Green and
O.J. Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota could have held that lead at the end of the first
half. But coach Dennis Green _ whose offense had attacked all year
_ wanted more. So quarterback Randall Cunningham dropped back to
pass on third-and-10 from the Vikings 18. Falcons defensive tackle
Chuck Smith beat Pro Bowl tackle Todd Stuessie to the outside,
swooped in and knocked the ball from Cunningham. Travis Hall
recovered for the Falcons at the 14 with 59 seconds left in the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler hit Terance Mathis with a touchdown
pass on the next play, cutting the deficit to 20-14 and bolstering
the Falcons' confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play by Chuck was huge,''said linebacker Jesse Tuggle.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after the break, the Falcons continued to bore in.
Andersen cut the Vikings' lead to 20-17 on another field goal. It
seemed that momentum had shifted inside the noisy, purple-dominated
Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   It was like a big-top circus. The Vikings ran onto the field
before the game through a massive inflated ark. The sounds of a
sustained, screeching horn reverberated off the Dome's walls. Every
so often, the Vikings fight song blared through the speakers that
hung high above the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Into this noisy atmosphere came the Vikings fans, who seemed
intent on paying homage to their unbeatable team on the final step
to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it appeared in the final quarter when Cunningham
directed a long Minnesota scoring drive _ 15 plays, 82 yards _ to
put the Vikings ahead 27-17 with 13:41 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were in control then,'' Matthew Hatchette said.
</P>
<P>
   They were, but they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who wound up 27-for-43 for 340 yards and two
touchdowns, hit Tony Martin for a 70-yard gain that resulted in
Andersen's 24-yard field goal with 11:02 left.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota responded with running back Robert Smith, who led the
Vikings to the Atlanta 21 by gaining 41 yards on four carries. When
the Falcons defense held with 2:07 remaining, Minnesota trotted out
place-kicker Gary Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had not missed a kick since December 15, 1997, against
Denver. He had made all 39 of his field goal attempts this season,
and everyone considered the 38-yarder to put the Vikings ahead by
10 a chip shot.
</P>
<P>
   But he missed. The Falcons, still trailing by seven, celebrated
as if they had won the game, and the Vikings seemed to have the
life sucked from them. ``I couldn't believe it missed,'' Anderson
said. ``But that's field-goal kicking. You either make them or miss
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Battered and limping from hits in the backfield, Chandler
orchestrated an eight-play, 71-yard drive in 1:28. Without
timeouts. He hit Mathis for 9 yards and Ronnie Harris for 29 yards.
He rushed for 9 yards. At the end of the play, he hurt an ankle,
but stayed in the game. Jamal Anderson, who was held to 67 yards,
got a key first down on a 6-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   On first down from the Minnesota 16, Chandler's pass was
deflected and dropped by Vikings safety Robert Griffith with 57
seconds to go. Reeves gave Chandler two options on the next play,
and Chandler went with the same play. He was flushed out of the
pocket to his left and then fired a hard pass to Mathis, who
cradled the ball at the goal line for the touchdown with just :49
remaining. Andersen's extra point tied it at 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``That drive right there by Chris ranks right up there with the
great drives,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said, ``It was all or nothing. In a way, it makes it
easier because you know you have to score a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was still time left for the explosive Vikings offense.
But on third down from the 27, Green instructed Cunningham to take
a kneeto force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Green said he was following the team's pattern from all year.
Still, the Vikings fans booed.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, there was silence when the Falcons'
Andersen lined up from the Vikings 21 for the biggest kick of his
17-year career. Several Falcons on the bench were on their knees in
prayer. Reeves was not one of them. ``I wanted to see it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Andersen's kick ripped through the uprights, the players
raced to the field and fans in Atlanta fled to the streets _ both
in delirious celebration. Tears of joy flowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another day at the office,'' punter/holder Dan Stryzinski
said. ``I knew (Anderson) would get it done. He's the best clutch
kicker in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen said about the 26th game-winning kick of his career:
``The unit did its job. All I had to do was mine.''
</P>
<P>
   By doing his job with icy perfection, he sent the Vikings
players and fans home crying. When they departed the building, a
gray sky had begun to snow.
</P>
<P>
   And it seemed as if someone had pulled the plug on a city's
life-support system. Cunningham sparked images of Yul Brynner as
Pharaoh in ``The Ten Commandments,'' on his knees, head down,
pounding the turf with both hands _ just as Pharaoh did when he
realized that his troops, chasing Moses, were swallowed up in the
Red Sea. The Vikings did not get victory. What they got was the
silent treatment. No one considered that the most poignant noise
64,000 people could make would be silence. Regarded as the loudest
of NFL buildings, the Metrodome was like a library, except for the
Falcons falling all over each other in utter joy on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The people _ most clad in purple, many wearing painted faces,
horned caps and most definitely liquored breath _ exited the
building like school children in a fire drill: orderly and quietly.
Some looked back over their shoulders to reaffirm if what they'd
witnessed was true. And sure enough, they saw the Falcons basking
in their finest moment, and the Vikings who remained on the field
watching in stunned disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was our year,'' Vikings cornerback Jimmy
Hitchcock said. ``It was an unbelievable experience out there. I
just never saw it coming like this. Never. I just feel empty.''
</P>
<P>
   The crestfallen Vikings trudged toward their locker room in the
bowels of the building, heads bowed. Beaten. Crushed. Pro Bowl
receiver Cris Carter cried uncontrollably and had to be aided by
brother John off the field, up the ramp and toward the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Vikings said a word. There was a stony, eerie
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't quiet at all,'' Falcons defensive lineman Shane
Dronett insisted. ``I could hear the fans cheering all the way from
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had a sustained celebration on the field that
included Reeves doing a version of the crazed ``Dirty Bird'' on the
platform after receiving the trophy for the NFC Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can stand this, my heart's going to be in great shape,''
Reeves said. ``The only thing tougher than (the game) is going to
be dancing, in downtown Atlanta, the Dirty Bird. That ain't going
to be a pretty sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons fans would argue that; Vikings fans wouldn't. They
envisioned the Vikings as champs, nothing else. It seemed the
possibility of defeat never entered their minds. And so, a city
mourned.
</P>
<P>
   A Tribune editorial noted that, at a coffee bar in town the day
after, the music played was ``mournful music they used to play in
Eastern Europe when the dictator died.''
</P>
<P>
   Business died, too. Merchants anticipated on Monday a mad rush
for Vikings garb or big-screen televisions to watch the Super Bowl.
Instead, it was dead. The people were in mourning. Travel plans to
Miami were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL provided both the Vikings and Falcons locker rooms with
about 200 hats proclaiming each team NFC champs. The Falcons
proudly wore theirs. And the Vikings?
</P>
<P>
   ``They got shipped back to NFL Properties,'' said Dennis Ryan,
Vikings equipment manager. ``I saw the box, but I never opened it.
I don't know what the hats looked like, and I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Falcons said they did not come to Minneapolis to
lose. ``We came here to win,'' said Tuggle, defiantly, two days
before the game. ``I don't think the Vikings have been hit like
we're going to hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   The hit Minnesota took was emotional. ``I guess I have to accept
that Atlanta scored more points,'' McCombs said. ``But I just can't
grasp how. I knew we were going to Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Only, he didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't know that Gary Anderson would miss or that Moss would
drop a possible touchdown in the second quarter or that Smith would
be rendered ordinary or that their potent offense would be impotent
after halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, McComb and his fans didn't know that the Falcons would
not quit, that the offensive line would not make one false-start
penalty despite the noise, that the defense would surrender just
seven points in the last 40 minutes, that Chandler would be so
clutch, that grit and will can overcome talent, that the Falcons
have worn destiny all season.
</P>
<P>
   Worn it snug, like a championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
