<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside Baseball: Hole in roof another headache for Expos
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In yet another episode of Canadian baseball calamity, the roof
coming down on the Montreal Expos last week was greeted around the
majors with shaking heads. A brand new $24 million roof on Olympic
Stadium didn't last out the first big snowfall before a
3,200-square-foot panel _ the second largest of the 63 panels that
make up the roof _ ripped open under the weight of melting snow and
ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it has nothing to do with the Expos, really,''
Montreal manager Felipe Alou said. ``But if you're in Taiwan and
you read this, you're saying, `There go the Expos again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Upon reconsideration, it had been a pretty good winter for the
club. Club president Claud Brochu is ready to sell his 7.6 percent
of the club, which could lead to refinancing and some firmer
economic ground. Although attendance was down more than 500,000,
Alou likens the current young talent pool with his 1994 team, a
powerhouse that was poised to make a run into the postseason until
the strike killed the season and eventually stripped the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to spring training last year without a team,'' Alou
said, ``just a group of mostly young men who hadn't played in the
big leagues or hadn't played together. We feel like we have a team
now.''
</P>
<P>
   One that might be playing home games with one eye cocked at the
ceiling. The roof, a seriesof Teflon-coated fiberglass panels, was
promised to bear up under 3-foot snowfalls and wasn't ever supposed
to need clearing. The manufacturer, the American firm Birdair, also
installed roofs at the Georgia Dome, the Minneapolis Metrodome and
the Pontiac Silverdome, all of which have had problems with
collapsing segments.
</P>
<P>
   So much for a strong Expos start in 1999. Alou already has his
solution for dealing with a hazardous roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm going to be making too many trips to the
mound,'' the manager said. ``I'll send out the pitching coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Brave matters
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine was voted Brave of the Year by the Atlanta chapter
of the Baseball Writers' Association of America. The 1998 Cy Young
winner drew 13 votes, Andres Galarraga received three and Javy
Lopez one. . . . The club's decision to hold a two-day FanFest Feb.
6-7 while individual game tickets go on sale can be grouped with
the team's new family discount-ticket packages. The aim: to try to
reclaim some of the 103,000 fans it lost at the gate in Turner
Field's second year of operation. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the Braves coaching staff been revamped, the
scouting department will look new after the retirement of two
longtime employees. Major-league scout Bill Wight, who had been
with the organization since 1967, and Fred Shaffer, who has spent
50 years in baseball, both retired. Additionally, longtime
minor-league pitching coach Bill Slack, most recently assigned to
the Danville Braves of the Appalachian rookie league, announced his
retirement. . . . Pitching coach Leo Mazzone's book on the mound
craft goes on sale this spring. The book, co-written with
California sports author Jim Rosenthal, will be titled either
``Pitch Like a Pro'' or ``Pitch Healthy, Pitch Smart.'' Publisher
St. Martin's Press is still undecided. Mazzone dedicated the book
to manager Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Around the majors
</P>
<P>
   The Mets brought reliever Armando Benitez, acquired from
Baltimore, to meet the New York press, and most questions focused
on Benitez's drilling the Yankees' Tino Martinez last summer and
provoking one of the year's worst brawls. ``I'm not concerned that
this young man will be intimidated by New York,'' Mets pitching
coach Bob Apodaca said. ``He has come a long way. He pitched his
way out of the Dominican Republic. He has faced tougher situations
than this.'' . . . The Phillies are concerned that catcher Mike
Lieberthal's pelvis injury still hasn't healed fully, despite four
cortisone treatments and a steady diet of anti-inflammatories.
Philadelphia was 51-48 before Lieberthal went down with the injury
in late July and then went 24-39 without him. Back-up catcher Bobby
Estalella will be out until mid-May after shoulder surgery, and
newly acquired reserve Tom Prince has hit .198 in 12 major league
seasons. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's rotation is setting up like this: right-hander Pete
Harnisch, left-hander Denny Neagle, right-hander Brett Tomko,
left-hander Steve Avery and either right-hander Jason Bere or
left-hander Dennis Reyes at No. 5. The first four went a collective
53-37 in 1998. Last year, Reds manager Jack McKeon used 11
different starters, who went 53-60. . . . Great news for Braves
general manager John Schuerholz: Albert Belle's new contract with
Baltimore stipulates that he cannot be traded over its first three
years and can be dealt to one of only eight teams in the final two
years. The Braves are on the approved list. . . . Economics for
1999: Minnesota is hoping to pare payroll from $26 million to $11
million. That way, if the Twins can draw 1 million fans, they'll
turn a profit. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres' regret for acquiring reliever Randy Myers
mounts, as the club continues without success to dump his contract,
which has two years remaining at $12.25 million. The latest efforts
are concentrated with Seattle in a proposed trade for third baseman
Russ Davis and reliever Bobby Ayala. The Padres might pick up $2
million of the contract, but the Mariners' 1998 scouting reports on
Myers are poor, and the club already has given closing duties to
free-agent acquisition Jose Mesa. . . . The intoxication of
expansion: ``If they give me three months, I'll give them 10
years.'' That from free agent Billy Ashley after he signed with
Tampa Bay. In 618 career at-bats, Ashley is hitting .233 with 236
strikeouts, one every 2.6 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
