<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bure lifts Florida, division
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The Waffle House of the NHL's six divisions just
gained a little glitz.
</P>
<P>
   When the Florida Panthers swung a deal with Vancouver for
disgruntled superstar Pavel Bure, it created the first rumbling in
South Florida since the fledgling franchise made a stunning run to
the finals three years ago. It also might wake up the Panthers'
brethren in the Southeast Division, where the mediocre Carolina
Hurricanes, at only 20-18-7, are the lone team with a record that
tilts to the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it doesn't really change our thinking and how we'll
go about things next year,'' said Thrashers general manager Don
Waddell, whose team will play next season in the Southeast with
Florida, Carolina, Washington and Tampa Bay. ``But certainly it
could increase goal scoring in our division, which is fine by us.
Sometimes one guy can do that. One team signs a superstar, and then
the other teams feel they have to go out and get somebody. It's a
big move not just for Florida but the division as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Washington's ascension to the Stanley Cup finals last
year, the Southeast generally is considered the weakest of six
divisions. The Panthers made the deal knowing that the division is
up for grabs and hoping to use it as a marketing boost this year
and next, assuming they can extend Bure's contract. A five-year
deal paying Bure $9 million to $10 million annually could be
completed by next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``(We have)19,258 seats to fill (in a new building),'' Florida
president Bill Torrey said. ``We have a lot of competition here _
football is huge, the Marlins have new ownership, the Heat (is
getting) a new building. Pavel is somebody people want to see, and
they'll pay to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers have been a thrill ride since being born in 1993.
Fifth-place finishes in their first two seasons led to the firing
of coach Roger Neilson and the hiring of Doug MacLean. In MacLean's
first season, the Panthers finished 10 games over .500, got hot in
the playoffs and reached the Stanley Cup finals, losing to
Colorado. Then came the slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation after that year was that anything less than
the finals was a disaster,'' Torrey said. ``We signed a couple of
guys in free-agency who didn't play well and it hurt us. We were
looking for leaders who could help our younger guys, because we
knew in the next few years we had some guys coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers were bounced from the playoffs in the first round
in 1996-97. Last season, after a 7-12-4 start, MacLean was fired by
general manager Brian Murray, who named himself as interim
replacement. Murray went only 17-31-1 the rest of the season, then
set himself up for more criticism by hiring his brother, Terry, as
Florida's new coach this season.
</P>
<P>
   If Bure can cool this soap opera, it will be his greatest
achievement yet. Certainly, he possesses the talent. The Russian
had consecutive 60-goal seasons (1992-94), scored 51 for the
Canucks last season and led all scorers in the Winter Olympics with
nine goals in six games, including five in a semifinal win over
Finland. In his Florida debut Wednesday against the New York
Islanders, Bure scored twice in a 5-2 win _ and that was on
jet-lagged legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was laughing at myself, the way I was skating and handling
the puck,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Torrey said, ``Pavel has shown he's one of the
great goal scorers in the league and he's only 27 years old. On top
of that, he's one of the top personalities in the game. We have
guys in this league who score 50 goals who don't have Pavel's
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Torrey didn't have to mention Eric Lindros by name. Not that
Lindros wouldn't give another boost to the Southeast Division.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
