<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLYMPICS-SCANDAL-2TAK     01-23 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-SCANDAL-2TAKES(1,200)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT RESTRAINTS, OLYMPIC IDEAL IS TAINTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Behind police barricades, accused
members of the International Olympic Committee pleaded their cases
Saturday in an attempt to avoid expulsion for misconduct in the
Salt Lake City bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   About half a dozen IOC members arrived Saturday morning to face
questioning from a commission headed by Richard Pound, a Montreal
attorney. No members had resigned by noon.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were kept outside IOC headquarters by security guards
and police officers. As many as 11 members could face a
recommendation of expulsion on Sunday by the IOC's executive board
for accepting cash payments, tuition aid, medical treatment and
lavish gifts totaling three quarters of a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Kevan Gosper, the senior IOC member from Australia, tried to
contain another brush fire of scandal by saying he now believed
that offers of $35,000 apiece, made to two African IOC members the
night before the vote on Sydney's bid to win the 2000 Summer Games,
were appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   John Coates, president of Australia's Olympic Committee, said
Friday he had made the last-minute offers to Charles Mukora of
Kenya and Maj. Gen. Francis Nyangweso of Uganda on Sept. 22, 1993,
the night before Sydney defeated Beijing by two votes. Coates
defended the payments as attempts to help the Olympic committees in
the African countries, not attempts to line the pockets of IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper said he accepted the explanation. ``I have no reason to
believe that was bribery,'' Gosper said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gosper did not explain the difference between what was
appropriate for Sydney and what was inappropriate for Salt Lake
City. And he admitted he was in the awkward position of having to
seek a vote of confidence for the two cities from the IOC's
executive board on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   What now threatens to cripple the Olympics _ big money, big
temptations, big excesses _ is a corrupted evolution of the
financial revival that saved the Olympics 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Juan Antonio Samaranch, a Spanish marquis, became president
of the IOC in 1980, the five Olympics rings were fool's gold. The
1972 Summer Games in Munich, Germany, shed the blood of Israeli
athletes and shredded any notion that sport and politics are not
intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to pay for the 1976 Winter Games with public money,
Denver shuffled them to Innsbruck, Austria. The 1976 Summer Games
in Montreal left a debt of $1 billion. The 1980 Summer Games in
Moscow were boycotted by the United States after the Soviet Union
invaded Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic movement was in trouble,'' said Pound, an IOC vice
president. ``The IOC had little financing, unity was shaky at best
and the Games were becoming a Cold War battleground.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles won the 1984 Summer Games in 1978 essentially
because no one else wanted them. Tehran lost interest when the
shah's regime began to collapse. Islamic fundamentalism had no use
for sport. The Soviets led a retaliatory boycott in Los Angeles,
but what could have been a Cold War disaster became a hot property.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ueberroth brought to Los Angeles an Olympics that was
privately financed through television rights fees, corporate
sponsorships, ticket sales and licensing agreements. Shrewdly, he
gave exclusivity to various categories of corporate sponsorships.
Coca-Cola was the official soft drink, IBM the official technology
sponsor, Levi-Strauss the official outfitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Lake Placid, they had 50 official Band-Aid sponsors,''
joked Anita DeFrantz, an IOC vice president from Los Angeles,
referring to the 1980 Winter Games. ``Peter had one sponsor per
category, which created value for the sponsor and allowed him to
demand larger amounts of money.''
</P>
<P>
   When the 1984 Summer Games turned a profit of $220 million,
everyone decided they wanted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter added a couple of zeroes to everything,'' said John
Argue, who was president of the Los Angeles bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, at an IOC meeting in East Berlin, one of the most
infamous food fights in Olympic history took place among cities
vying for the 1992 Summer Games. Brisbane, Australia, sent in a
planeload of lamb and lobsters for a party whose tab has been
placed at nearly $2 million. Paris also airmailed a gastronomical
feast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the most food they had ever seen in East
Berlin,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no rules, so there were no rules to be broken. Ms.
DeFrantz heard stories of IOC members being put up in one of Paris'
most exclusive hotels ``for a long time, with their families. It
was out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 Summer Games were eventually awarded to Barcelona,
Spain, in 1986. That year, the IOC placed a limit of $150 on gifts
that IOC members could receive, but like traffic rules in Italy,
this limit appeared to be more of a suggestion than a law. There
are no real checks and balances on the IOC, which answers to no one
but itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say it's better to be an IOC member than a king,''
said Fred Ball, who was a member of Salt Lake City's bid committee
for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the IOC began holding the Winter and Summer Games in
separate years. The Winter Olympics now stood alone, instead of in
the shadow of the Summer Games. More corporate money could be
raised; budgets increased and so did the projected economic
benefit. Salt Lake City's expected budget of $1.45 billion is
nearly as large as the budget for the 1996 Summer Games in Atlanta.
The estimated economic impact in Salt Lake City for the 2002 Winter
Games is $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the winner was the city willing to lose the most
money,'' Pound said. ``Now the Games are seen has having a
beneficial economic impact. Sometimes that attracts the lowest
common denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   The bidding process has become a sort of neurotic mating ritual
in which bid cities, eager to please IOC members, tend to spend
money ``like drunken sailors on leave,'' Pound said. Salt Lake City
spent $14 million in private funds just trying to win the 1998 and
2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a corrupt process,'' said Robert Helmick, who resigned
amid allegations of conflict of interest in 1991 as an IOC member
and as president of the U.S. Olympic Committee. ``It starts with
first-class air tickets for IOC members and their wives. That's
$10,000 to $12,000. Then there is the excessive lifestyle bestowed
on IOC members by the bid cities. Fur coats, jewelry. They might
pay for college tuition for someone's kid. Or find him a job. It
goes beyond what is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Some IOC members have been as eager to receive as the bid cities
have been eager to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people from poorer countries travel to the United States,
they are very impressed,'' said Francois Carrard, the executive
director of the IOC ``The different level in standards can lead to
temptation. The other side is generous and says, `My dear friend,
what can I do for your family?' But those people should have read
the rules. Blame has to be shared.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because a vote is now held every two years to name a city to
host the Winter or Summer Games, there is steadier work for
so-called middlemen, or agents. Pound spoke sharply last week of
wanting to rid the Olympic movement of these agents, who reportedly
promise to deliver a bloc of votes for exorbitant sums of money.
</P>
<P>
   He said there were allegations that bidders hoping to have the
Winter Games in Sion, Switzerland, were approached by an agent who
claimed he could deliver 25 IOC votes for $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we are through with so-called Olympic agents, I
doubt that it will be a profitable business, if it ever was,''
Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City began setting off alarms at the USOC as early as
1989, when it was attempting to become the American candidate city
to bid on the Winter Games. At the time, officials were concerned
about the image that drinking was not allowed in the Mormon
capital. The Olympics, after all, are as much a 16-day party as a
16-day sporting competition.
</P>
<P>
   USOC officials who came to inspect Salt Lake City said they
found their hotel rooms stocked with bottles of wine and cases of
beer. Once, the inspection team was taken out in a horse-drawn
carriage while champagne was served.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them that was overkill,'' said Sandy Knapp, who headed
the selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a case of beer and a few bottles of wine were
penny-ante stuff. But the USOC's initial vigilance lagged as the
inducements in Salt Lake City grew to include cash payments and
benefits of more than $100,000 apiece to some IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Having the Olympics in Salt Lake City was considered paramount
by the USOC, whose officials feared that corporate support might
swoon after the Atlanta Olympics and that the USOC's quadrennial
budget of $400 million could shrink by as much as $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   With Salt Lake City as host, the USOC has made $54.5 million
from its cut of television rights fees and expects to earn
approximately $193 million more in cash and supplies in a joint
marketing agreement. Not until November 1997 _ two years after the
Salt Lake vote _ did the USOC institute a formal policy limiting
gifts to officials by bid cities to $50 in one phase of the bid
process and $150 in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did my predecessors fall down on the job?'' said Bill Hybl,
the current USOC president. ``In the future, we're going to do a
great deal more.''
</P>
<P>
   There is growing evidence that Samaranch was aware of
improprieties in the bidding process. Pound said he had once been
offered a $1 million bribe during television rights negotiations
for the Games and had informed Samaranch. But no disciplinary
action was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Henderson, who headed Toronto's unsuccessful bid for the
1996 Summer Games, said that Samaranch approved an arrangement in
which the Toronto bid committee paid the rent for the husband of
Pirjo Haggman, an IOC member from Finland. She resigned last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has both democratized the Olympic movement by
providing more opportunities for women and athletes from developing
nations, and made it more elitist with his autocratic, secretive
management style.
</P>
<P>
   He has said that the Olympic movement is more important than the
Catholic Church, and he threw a $16 million party in 1994 to
celebrate the IOC's centennial congress, two years after athletes
were left to swelter in an unair-conditioned village at the 1992
Summer Games in his native Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to catch too many people,'' Arnold Beckett, a
former member of the IOC's medical commission, said of the
committee's attitude toward doping. ``It won't look good.''
</P>
<P>
   The same criticism has been applied to corruption. His
detractors believe that Samaranch simply didn't want to know. Or
didn't want to act. He said he received only rumors, not facts.
Either way, everything he built has begun to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC needs to worry about losing the magic of the
Olympics,'' said Charlie Battle, who was in charge of international
relations for the Atlanta Olympic organizing committee. ``As they
have become such big business and have become so obsessed with
being big and having the best athletes, they have lost a little of
the magic of bringing the whole world together in the interest of
peace. They don't think people will pay big money for that. To me,
that's all they've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
