<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATURALIST-EAGLES-ART     01-23 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATURALIST-EAGLES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURALIST KEEPS AN EAGLE EYE ON EAGLES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKPORT, Wash. _ For the 229 bald eagles that Libby Mills
counted last Wednesday, the eight-mile stretch of the Skagit River
between here and Marblemount is the four-star, all-you-can-eat
sushi bar of Washington's waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills, 46, a naturalist with the Nature Conservancy, has
spent every winter Wednesday for the past 17 years counting the
eagles along this stretch. She notes _ on waterproof paper _
whether they are in trees, soaring in the air, flushed by human
intrusion or on gravel bars where they feast on the chum salmon,
dead for about a month and smelling accordingly, after their
upstream battle to spawn.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills pinpoints the eagles on contour maps, recording
whether they are adults, which are (at least 6 years old, or
juveniles, distinguished by their splotchy coloring.
</P>
<P>
   Here in this crossroads town on Highway 20, three hours
northeast of Seattle, the clouds have descended into a pervasive
mist, and the moss on the bark of the vine maples is thick enough
to grow its own ferns. Coming out of from the Cascade Mountains,
the Skagit River runs clear enough to show submerged fish carcasses
and skins in sharp detail, while across the water, eagles are
concealed behind layers of cottonwood, alder and fog. Their
melodic, trilling squeaks can be heard throughout the woods, the
male's voice higher and weaker than the female's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial thing is to remember, each eagle is good for two
big blotches of white,'' Ms. Mills said, referring to the confusing
density of the crowd of birds along the river. Those blotches were
so thick that a novice birder counted 10 eagles without moving the
binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills' data are used by the private Nature Conservancy for
measuring the health of the river, the salmon and the eagles, as
well as the eagles' breeding success along the stretch of river,
one of the largest winter concentrations of eagles in the country.
The bald eagle count peaked at 320 the week before last, with 310
the week before, and 285 before that, she said, with many flying in
from northern Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The number has increased significantly over the past decades,
primarily because of the reduction of logging in the eagles'
nesting areas, and the banning of the pesticide DDT, which kept the
shells of raptor eggs from hatching.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Ms. Mills said, there were 180 nesting pairs of bald
eagles in the state, and now there are more than 500 pairs. The
bird is still on the federal endangered species list, though
officials are debating whether to take it off.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills started counting at 9 a.m., when most of the eagles
had left their night roosts in cottonwoods or Douglas firs. An
early bird-watcher has the best chance of success, before the
crowds set in and scare off the birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right along the highway you're likely to have people coming
out and creating a hubbub,'' Ms. Mills said. ``Usually when people
come up, the birds just bolt.'' Some eagles will stay away from a
gravel bar for a full day if it has been disturbed by a human, she
said. The first weekend of the month, when 700 people visited one
section of the road where volunteer eagle watchers were stationed,
only 40 birds were seen.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills, who patrols the river banks in a station wagon
bearing the slogan ``Study Nature, Not Books,'' tries hard not to
count an eagle twice, though this can be difficult, when the
basically identical birds gather as thick as pigeons near fusty
fish carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, a really great day of birding is not spent counting,
but just watching behavior,'' Ms. Mills said, recalling how she has
seen an eagle carry an octopus back to its nest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very easy bird to watch, and I like that it gets other
people interested in birds,'' said Ms. Mills, who often speaks to
school groups about eagles. ``Often times, watching eagles gets
them interested in the whole environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you take just about any bird and pay any attention to
it, they're all equally interesting. Everything is.''
</P>
<P>
   At a designated counting spot where she used to be able to find
100 eagles, she pointed to a 20-foot conifer that now blocks her
view of the river. ``That's how long I've been here,'' she said,
hoping out loud that 30 eagles were not hidden behind what had been
a seedling when she started working here in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   As the temperature rose and the swan-white slopes of El Dorado
Mountain shone through the clouds, Ms. Mills started looking for
eagles riding the rising warm-air columns. or thermals. Soon after,
she saw 20 birds spiraling high, perhaps ones she had counted
earlier, perhaps not. The thermals lift them high enough to reach
the shelter of tall trees higher in the hills, where they spend the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see one slide on up Illabot Creek to a big night
roost, or slide on across the sky to another night roost,'' Ms.
Mills said. ``With all that lift, there's a lot of saved energy.
It's really easy to kind of get woozy watching them, instead of
watching a winter wren or a dipper. The eagles seem a lot less
real, almost.''
</P>
<P>
   One soared for more than 40 seconds before flapping its wings.
They wheeled counterclockwise, slipping in between each other
easily, at the same pace as the eddies in the fast green river.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
