<HEADER>
A5541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-INTERROGATIONS     01-23 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-INTERROGATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S TOP COURT WEIGHS INTERROGATION METHODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Shai Nitzan, a government lawyer, had some news for
the Israeli Supreme Court during deliberations earlier this month
on the methods used by the Shin Bet security service during
interrogations of Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A stifling, foul-smelling sack placed over the heads of suspects
would be replaced with ``something more airy,'' Nitzan told the
court. There were also plans to replace tight handcuffs used to
bind suspects' arms painfully behind their backs with looser chain
shackles, Nitzan said.
</P>
<P>
   The sack and handcuffs were ``not intended to burden'' the
detainees, Nitzan assured the court. The sack was used to isolate
suspects from each other, he said, and handcuffing was a security
measure.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of nine judges considering these and other methods
_ called torture by the United Nations, Amnesty International and
other human rights groups _ was extraordinary, and is unparalleled
in other countries. For the first time, Israel's Supreme Court is
weighing the legality of such techniques, used against hundreds of
Palestinian suspects interrogated every year by Shin Bet.
</P>
<P>
   The methods include shackling prisoners in painful positions
while depriving them of sleep for days, covering their heads with
sacks and subjecting them to loud music. Typically, suspects are
held for many hours between interrogation sessions on miniature
chairs that tilt forward. During questioning, some are grabbed by
the collar and violently shaken, causing their heads to whip back
and forth.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court hearings on the legality of these methods
began a year ago in response to petitions by Palestinian prisoners
and human rights groups, but only three sessions have been held so
far and the most recent, held this month, ended with an indefinite
delay. The court has been hesitant to rule on a matter that Chief
Justice Aharon Barak has said should properly be regulated by
parliamentary legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the court, Nitzan told the judges that a ministerial
committee on the Shin Bet had decided this month to submit a bill
on the conduct of interrogations. But with Parliament about to
break up ahead of early national elections in May, there is
virtually no chance that such a bill will pass in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   So the issue remains before the court. The question facing the
judges is whether in trying to foil terrorist attacks, the Shin Bet
may continue using techniques sanctioned in 1987 by a state
commission of inquiry into interrogation methods. That commission
ruled that under certain circumstances, the Shin Bet could use ``a
moderate measure of physical pressure'' detailed in a secret
section of its report.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, in response to suicide bombings in Israel, the
ministerial committee has approved ``increased physical pressure''
during interrogations, and in several cases the Supreme Court has
permitted the use of such methods against detainees. Amnesty
International asserts that this amounts to an effective
legalization of torture.
</P>
<P>
   But in court last week, Nitzan and another government lawyer,
Yehuda Schaffer, asserted that Israel was not violating the 1984
U.N. Convention Against Torture, which Israel ratified in 1991. The
methods used by the Shin Bet do not constitute torture, Nitzan
argued, and are ``legal and desirable'' when used to save lives.
</P>
<P>
   He cited ``the necessity defense'' under the Israeli Penal Code,
which absolves government agents of criminal liability if their
acts were required to prevent immediate, serious harm and there was
no other way to achieve their goal.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli human rights groups argue that the ``necessity defense''
applies only after the fact and in extreme cases, and cannot serve
as a prior authorization for routine abuse.
</P>
<P>
   They cite findings by the U.N. Committee Against Torture, which
has called Israeli interrogation methods torture or ill-treatment,
which are banned by the 1984 convention. While the committee
acknowledged that Israel faces a ``terrible dilemma'' in fighting
terrorism, it asserted that ``no public emergency of any kind
justifies the use of torture.''
</P>
<P>
   To support this position, the Public Committee Against Torture
in Israel, one of the groups petitioning the court, submitted an
affidavit by the lawyer for Timothy McVeigh, who was convicted in
the April 1995 Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No efforts were made to question or interrogate McVeigh
outside the presence of his attorneys,'' the lawyer, Robert Nigh,
said. ``Mr. McVeigh was never subjected to physical abuse by any
law enforcement officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Oyediran, an Amnesty International observer at the latest
Supreme Court hearing, said that in failing so far to issue a
ruling, the court had neglected its duty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
