<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CLASSIFIEDS-$ADV25-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER GROUPS BUY INTERNET CLASSIFIED BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release at 6:30 p.m. EST Sunday, Jan. 24)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The AdOne Classified Network, the premier Internet
classifieds business, announced Monday that the company and its
ClassifiedWarehouse.com consumer Web site have been acquired by a
consortium of leading U.S. media companies including The Hearst
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership projects that ClassifiedWarehouse.com's
classified advertising database, which averages more than three
million new ads per month, will grow to in excess of six million
new classifieds per month by the end of the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, known as AdOne, L.L.C., is the first purely
Internet start-up backed by a consortium composed of blue-chip
traditional media and new media companies. Lycos Inc., the second
most visited Internet portal, will play an important role in the
new partnership through its distribution agreement with AdOne and
ClassifiedWarehouse.com.
</P>
<P>
   George B. Irish, president of Hearst Newspapers and vice
president of The Hearst Corporation, said Hearst's investment in
AdOne was ``a good fit with our strategy of competing locally with
our newspapers' electronic classifieds and nationally with Lycos'
distribution and content.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hearst, the acquiring media consortium includes
MediaNews Group, the seventh largest newspaper company in the
United States, The E.W. Scripps Company, a diversified media
company and the nation's 10th largest newspaper publisher; Advance
Publications Inc., a diversified media company publishing
newspapers in 22 markets, and Donrey Media Group, a wholly-owned
affiliate of Stephens Group, Inc., of Little Rock, Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thrilled these blue-chip media companies have chosen to
back our vision of an open network composed of locally-based
classified advertising from premium media properties in large,
medium and small markets,'' said Brendan Burns, the president and
CEO of AdOne, L.L.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``AdOne brought together this unique group of high-caliber
traditional and new media companies because of their strong belief
in our inclusive corporate partnership philosophy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said AdOne has been successful because the company
bolsters its affiliates' positions as the most significant
information hubs in their local communities.
</P>
<P>
   The new AdOne, affiliated media partners, and the company's
ClassifiedWarehouse.com consumer site are solidly positioned to
play the leading role in the rapidly expanding $123 million online
classifieds marketplace _ a market which industry experts predict
will grow to nearly $2 billion by 2002, according to Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said that, with completion of the acquisition, AdOne and
its ClassifiedWarehouse.com consumer site will feature:
</P>
<P>
   _ Strong backing from four of the top 10 U.S. newspaper media
companies and a leading Internet portal;
</P>
<P>
   _ Significant market penetration in 38 of the top 50 U.S. media
markets;
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 350 affiliated media properties in the top 50 U.S.
media markets;
</P>
<P>
   _ The highest quality, most comprehensive collection of Internet
classifieds updated daily from leading newspapers and top-brand
online providers;
</P>
<P>
   _ A classifieds database predicted to grow to in excess of six
million new classifieds per month by mid-1999; and
</P>
<P>
   _ Established distribution deals with leading Internet brands
such as Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium was brought together as a result of a commitment
in the third quarter of 1998 from MediaNews Group, as the
consortium's lead investor, coupled with strategic initiatives
completed by AdOne's management team during the third and fourth
quarters of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
