<HEADER>
A5546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURUNDI-SANCTIONS-NYT     01-23 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURUNDI-SANCTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGIONAL LEADERS SUSPEND SANCTIONS ON BURUNDI
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: East Africa) 
(DW) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania _ East African leaders voted Saturday to
suspend the economic sanctions they had imposed more than two years
ago on Burundi, a tiny nation whose troubles have cast a large
shadow over the region.
</P>
<P>
   The move was one of several steps that heads of state took here
this week aimed at increasing cooperation among countries in East
Africa. The talks specifically sought a firmer place in the region
for Burundi and Rwanda, two countries still searching for stability
after the ethnic violence that claimed hundreds of thousands lives
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the heads of state from Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania
pledged to admit Rwanda into their plans for an East African
Community. Slated to begin this July, the community is an ambitious
effort to integrate the economic lives of more than 80 million
people through a trading block that would eventually share
passports, public works and currency.
</P>
<P>
   Though Burundi has not even applied, it was a measure of the
high hopes for the community, as well as for Burundi itself, that
the nation seemed all but admitted anyway. ``If Burundi applies,
its application will be treated favorably,'' said Francis Muthaura,
executive secretary of the Commission for East African Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed friendliness toward Burundi could not have
contrasted more to another meeting here in July 1996, when the same
countries gathered to protest a coup led by Maj. Pierre Buyoya.
Buyoya contended that he took power to end fighting that began in
1993 between Hutu rebels and the Tutsi-controlled Army. But the
other African leaders then imposed what they pledged would be a
strictly enforced embargo on trade with Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   The reality was that most goods seeped through anyway. But
supporters of the sanctions argued that they caused enough economic
trouble that Buyoya, who is Tutsi, complied with his neighbors'
demands that he share power with Hutu opposition groups and begin
peace talks with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth round of peace talks began here this week. Saturday,
Buyoya _ now addressed as ``Mr. President'' by his peers _ pledged
to remained committed to the peace talks even in the absence of
sanctions. ``The government of Burundi shall leave no stone
unturned to assure that we arrive at a peace agreement that is
all-inclusive by the end of this year,'' Buyoya told heads of state
and top ministers from states including Uganda, Rwanda, Kenya,
Tanzania, Ethiopia, Zambia and Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Nyerere, the former Tanzanian president, who is also the
negotiator for the Burundi talks, had opposed lifting the sanctions
out of fear that the peace talks would in fact collapse. The
leaders underscored that the sanctions were only being suspended
and could be reimposed any time until representative democracy is
restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should understand the meaning of suspension,'' Daniel
arap Moi, president of Kenya, said at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Though the sanctions initially won support among other African
nations, critics have argued with increasing force that they were
hurting average Burundians, for whom the cost of some basic goods
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also argued that the sanctions were beginning to
endanger the peace negotiations, in part because Buyoya's Tutsi
opponents complain that he has conceded much to the ethnic Hutu but
has received little in return. The Hutu make up 85 percent of
Burundi's population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lifting of sanctions is a very important signal from the
regional leadership to Burundians that they really do recognize
their sacrifices and the government's commitment to the peace
process,'' said one Western diplomat, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``It is also a way of taking away ammunition from those
within Burundi who are still resisting negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of Uganda, Yoweri Museveni, defended the sanctions
as having achieved results through a deliberate and coordinated
strategy rather than violence. ``We have got plenty of conflicts in
Africa'' he said. ``However the way they are handled is sort of
sometimes ad hoc. We don't give enough time to the dealing of these
problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
