<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Jan. 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The potent jet-stream disturbance that spawned severe
thunderstorms across the South in the past few days will weaken as
it splits over the middle Atlantic and southeast seaboards,
diminishing the threat of severe weather Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Some showers and thunderstorms will already be in progress
across southeast Florida early Sunday morning, but only isolated
incidents of strong gusts or hail are possible as energetic
jet-stream winds quickly lift northeast away from the state. In
their wake, a sluggish, weak upper-level low-pressure system will
touch off a few spotty showers over the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, the risk of moderate to locally heavy rains will
lessen after the first part of the day from the eastern Carolinas
to southeast New York as a cold front and a trailing, weakening
jet-stream disturbance push off the Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and mild, gusty winds from the south will also start to
diminish along the New England seaboard during the day as the cold
front forges east. However, gusts to 40 mph are possible Sunday
morning in some coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heavy snow will develop in the central and southern
Sierra Nevada of California as a potent upper-level low-pressure
system near San Francisco forces Pacific moisture to glide up the
sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and a few thunderstorms will also develop underneath the
lofty low across parts of central and southern California. Farther
east, moist Pacific winds will give rise to mountain snows across
parts of Nevada, Utah, western Wyoming and northwest Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Severe Storms
</P>
<P>
   Severe thunderstorms stampeded across the South on Friday night,
inflicting damage on Louisiana, Mississippi and Alabama. By
definition, a storm is ranked ``severe'' if it produces one or any
combination of the following three kinds of weather: tornadoes,
wind gusts of 50 knots or greater (57 mph), hail at least
three-quarters of an inch in diameter. A thunderstorm that produces
heavy rain and flooding does not constitute ``severe'' weather.
Instead of issuing severe thunderstorm warnings in these cases, the
National Weather Service posts flood warnings or flash flood
warnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
