<HEADER>
A5585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COACHES-NYT     01-23 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUBS CHANGE COACHES FOR QUICK TURNAROUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only an hour after Brian Billick was hired as the coach of the
Baltimore Ravens last Tuesday, he was on his way to Mobile, Ala.,
for a week of Senior Bowl practices. There were also interviews
with assistant coaching candidates because he has a staff to
assemble.
</P>
<P>
   Put hundreds of chatty coaches in one spot, in this case to
scout players participating in Saturday's Senior Bowl, and rumors
will fly, and Billick, the former offensive coordinator of the
Minnesota Vikings, was at the center of a lot of them. There was
talk that Billick was interested in hiring Johnnie Lynn, the
Giants' defensive backs coach, as his defensive coordinator,
although the former Ravens coordinator Marvin Lewis is a strong
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   There was also talk that Billick and his former boss, Coach
Dennis Green, had agreed on a trade involving the Vikings' backup
quarterback, Brad Johnson. The Ravens would get Johnson for a No. 1
pick in April's draft, and then the Vikings would select a
linebacker or a defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of year,'' Billick said, ``especially with all of
the coaching changes, the rumors are flying. You can't believe half
of them. Nothing has been settled about Brad.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe this: The landscape of the National Football League has
taken another dramatic shift. Billick was only one of the eight
head coaching changes this year. In the end, there were some
surprising, and not so surprising, aspects to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, Green Bay, Seattle, Chicago, Kansas City,
Baltimore, San Diego and Carolina changed coaches. And Miami almost
did.
</P>
<P>
   To keep his job in St. Louis, coach Dick Vermeil had to dismiss
several assistants. To keep his sanity, Dolphins coach Jimmy
Johnson hired as his assistant Dave Wannstedt, who had been fired
by the Bears. Chicago, recently one of the worst-run teams in
football, was supposed to announce the hiring of Arizona's
defensive coordinator, Dave McGinnis, as its head coach. A news
conference was scheduled, then canceled. The Bears would not say
why.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Marty Schottenheimer of the Chiefs resigned, and Kansas
City hired from within, picking its defensive coordinator, Gunther
Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Browns chose Chris Palmer, the offensive
coordinator of the Jacksonville Jaguars, as the first coach of
their new team.
</P>
<P>
   There were three black head coaches in the National Football
League before the latest openings. There are still three black head
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, ownership wisely did not fire Coach Steve
Mariucci, who has yet to lose a regular-season home game, but
brought back Bill Walsh, the man who won four Super Bowls in the
1980s, as general manager. Terry Donahue, a former UCLA coach, was
hired as the team's director of player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   What do all the changes mean? Clearly, coaches like Bill
Parcells of the New York Jets and Dan Reeves of the Atlanta Falcons
have changed the rules of the game. Both men took sorry
organizations and turned them around in just two years, Parcells
leading the Jets to the American Football Conference title game
this year and Reeves leading Atlanta into Super Bowl XXXIII. It is
the fourth Super Bowl for Reeves, who has lost in his first three.
</P>
<P>
   Quick turnarounds like those create pressure on every other
team. It is a part of what at times can be a cruel profession.
</P>
<P>
   Or a joyous one. The key for three of the four teams that
reached the final four _ the Jets, Atlanta, and Minnesota _ is that
each team worried about right now, not five years from now. One of
the first critical moves of these franchises was to sign a veteran
quarterback. The Jets signed Vinny Testaverde, Minnesota signed
Randall Cunningham and Atlanta traded for Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had been with Tampa Bay, Cleveland and Baltimore,
where he was cut last year. But he excelled in the Jets' system,
playing with more weapons than ever. The same could be said for
Chandler, who had been with Indianapolis, Tampa Bay, Arizona, St.
Louis and others before having a Pro Bowl season with the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waiting to develop a quarterback, these coaches took
their chances with veterans, and the gambles paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to win this game as best you can,'' Parcells said this
month. ``People get caught up in `You've got to make this move for
next year.' Then next year never comes.''
</P>
<P>
   More pressure to win also means more responsibilities and less
time to have a life. Johnson cited this as one reason he almost
stepped down this month. The stress of the job almost certainly
contributed to Reeves' having heart surgery about five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get less time to relax, way less time,'' Parcells said.
``It used to be after the last game of the season was over unless
you went to the Super Bowl. Between then and the draft, you could
work at your own pace. Now, the minute we're out of the playoffs,
I've got the expansion list to turn in. I'm a month from free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go from one thing to the other, then the combine, the
draft, minicamps. Then you can't take rookies until June 1. That
takes your summer. There's less time to recharge. That's what gets
some of these guys. One thing to the other and the other and
other.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, getting to a Super Bowl can ease all pains. Just
ask Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb Moves Into Top 10  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse quarterback Donovan McNabb has impressed scouts so much
that some think he has improved his draft position significantly,
and is now not just a bottom pick in the first round. He has most
likely elevated himself to the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   National Football League scouts like McNabb's strong arm,
mobility and smarts.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants would love to take him at No. 16, but he probably
will not last that long. Some scouts think the St. Louis Rams,
tired of the inconsistent Tony Banks, will grab McNabb at No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the Giants will take an offensive lineman, like
Wisconsin offensive tackle Aaron Gibson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1540EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BISHER-COLUMN24-C     01-23 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BISHER-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not a bad carreer for Torre
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Torre holds one record unmatched in the major leagues,
probably in all baseball. He played for three teams, later managed
all three, then was fired by all three. Eventually he will be fired
by a fourth, for isn't that the inevitable fate of every manager of
the Yankees? Billy Martin holds the record of four, Steinbrenner
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Torre was first a victim of the New York Mets, a short cab ride
from the borough where he grew up. The Braves came next, to be
followed by the St. Louis Cardinals, but it is Atlanta with which
he has had an ongoing relationship from the time he was 13 years
old, going on 14. He came to visit his brother, Frank, who was
playing first base for the highly esteemed Atlanta Crackers, and
who would win the Southern Association pennant in 1954. Whitlow
Wyatt managed, Dick Donovan, Leo Cristante, Frank DiPrima and Chuck
Tanner, the same, were stars.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the ones I remember best,'' Torre said. ''I remember
the all-star game, too. They had to put up ropes to hold back the
crowd in the outfield.''
</P>
<P>
   He suited up and worked out, but no one would ever had suspected
that that fat little kid would ever see the inside of a major
league uniform. Hit the first home run in a National League game in
Atlanta Stadium, set a record for home runs by a Braves catcher,
that still stands, and win the Most Valuable Player prize, as he
did as a Cardinal in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he burst into bloom so fast created early problems
in his life. The trade to St. Louis cleared his head. He was a
carouser in Atlanta, lived in the fast lane, and too often drove in
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't dodge that,'' he said. ''When you get traded for the
first time, it opens your eyes. You take stock of yourself. The
Cardinals had just won two pennants and the year I left, the Braves
won a championship. I knew I'd better get my act in order.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during a party in one of those beachside villas at Palm
Beach, during spring training in 1969, that Paul Richards came down
the stairs, announcing with unbridled happiness that Torre had been
traded to St. Louis for Orlando Cepeda. Later, though, Torre and
Richards would bury the hatchet, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ran into him at Dodger Stadium one day, when I was managing
the Braves, and we shook hands and made up,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   He never played in a World Series, and ''that left a void in my
career.'' Now he has managed and won two, in his hometown, only
home-grown New Yorker ever to manage the Yankees. All the way from
Clark Griffith down through Miller Huggins, Casey Stengel and the
not so immortal Stump Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't imagine how exciting it is. You walk into a
restaurant and they give you a standing ovation. That makes New
York a small town to me. I remember when I was first with
Milwaukee, a reporter asked me what my ambition was, and I said,
'To play in the big leagues.'
</P>
<P>
   ''An old timer sitting close by said, 'No, you want to star in
the big leagues.' I never forgot that.''
</P>
<P>
   In between managing the Braves and the Cardinals, Torre spent
six seasons broadcasting Angels game on television, hand-picked by
Gene Autry. During most of this time, Marietta was his home. Like a
first date, there's nothing like first memories, the year of '54.
They cling like ivy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tallest building in town was the Fulton National Bank.
Ponce de Leon Park was a ballplayers' dream. I stayed just up the
street at the old Poncey Hotel. Cokes cost a nickel. Earl Mann
owned the Crackers, all those things still stick in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He had returned this time, the American League Manager of the
Year, as the main man at the Georgia Tech Baseball Benefit at the
Marriott Marquis. He spoke to a sold-out house, like a hero
returned. ''Last night,'' he said, ''I spoke at the Rochester
Institute of Technology. Now tonight at Georgia Institute of
Technology.''
</P>
<P>
   He grinned. ''How's that for a guy who took four and a half
years to get through high school?''
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the Sports Editor of the Atlanta Journal,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: furman(AT)ajc.com
</P>
