<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside Pro Basketball: Hill has no great love for ex-Dukie
Laettner
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fun is only beginning in Detroit, where Grant Hill has made
it clear he does not have a warm relationship _ or any other sort
of relationship _ with his old Duke teammate Christian Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently what he thought about his ``buddy'' Laettner
joining the Pistons, Hill shot back, ``Who says he's my buddy?''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, although they won two NCAA titles together at
Duke, Hill and Laettner never were buddies and haven't had a
relationship since Laettner left school in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to popular belief, us Dukies don't stick together all
that much,'' Hill said. ``He's a different person now, and I am a
different person. I don't know him as well now as I did then.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill concedes that he admires the former Hawk forward's
competitiveness, but he qualifies that after Laettner's indifferent
season with the Hawk. ``Any time you bring in free agents, you're
rolling the dice,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Dumars told me that you never really know a guy until you
play with him,'' Hill said. ``You think you know from afar, but
until you go through a season, through all the practices and
travel, only then do you know what a guy is truly like.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think Christian is at a point where he wants to win.
Some things didn't go well in Atlanta, for whatever reason. But he
knows how to play, he's been an All-Star, and he knows how to win.
He will make us a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   McDyess' angst
</P>
<P>
   Antonio McDyess' coming home party in Denver turned into farce
Thursday night, the Nuggets calling off a 3 p.m. press conference
while McDyess suffered a severe case of angst over his decision to
accept $20 million less than the Suns were offering him to remain
in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   A tearful phone call brought three Suns players, Jason Kidd, Rex
Chapman and George McCloud, to McNicholds arena, site of the news
conference, in hopes they could bring McDyess back with them. The
players sat in a long white limo for hours awaiting McDyess'
decision before he finally agreed to the deal at 1 a.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess apparently could not deal with the news that the Nuggets
were renouncing his friend LaPhonso Ellis in order to make cap room
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Rice surgery a ploy?
</P>
<P>
   Agent David Falk denies that Glen Rice's flirtation with surgery
on his non-shooting elbow is linked to unhappiness with his
contract. Rice's injury is not ``a thinly veiled attempt at a
holdout,'' Falk insists, although Rice has complained for two years
because the Hornets refuse to rework the remainder of his contract,
which calls for salaries of $5.4 and $7.1 million. Rice has a
floating chip in his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's ever going to hold out, he'd have done it last year,''
said Falk, who asked the team to renegotiate last year on a deal
that would have paid him an average of $9 million per year through
the year 2003-04.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rice's absence from camp came five days after he told
The Gaston Gazette he wouldn't rule out the possibility of a
holdout if his contract were not reworked.
</P>
<P>
   Dark days ahead for Bulls
</P>
<P>
   File these items away for future reference:
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls can become the second NBA champion to finish below
.500. That happened last to the Celtics after Bill Russell retired
in 1969. Satch Sanders recalls, ``We all got on Russell and begged
him not to quit because we knew without him there would certainly
be, to put it mildly, difficulty. But he felt his time was up. He
wanted to get into other things, so he left.''
</P>
<P>
   First-round pick Robert ``Tractor'' Traylor says he wants to be
a Milwaukee Buck for life. ``I was pushing my agent all summer to
let me buy a house in Milwaukee,'' Traylor said. ``Milwaukee is a
good place for me. This is where I want to be. I don't want to be
one of those guys bouncing all over the league. I want to make a
commitment here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the newly rotund Shawn Kemp says he actually missed Mike
Fratello during the lockout. ``Mike is similar to George Karl,''
Kemp said. ``He challenges me, and I enjoy playing for a coach who
challenges me. He has no problem asking you to go out and do
something maybe you didn't do the week before. You miss him getting
on you about that.'' Kemp must have really missed Fratello when he
sat down to eat. He came in 30 pounds over his playing weight.
</P>
<P>
   Aching Pacers
</P>
<P>
   Is the Indiana Dynasty to be stillborn? Before camp even
started, Rik Smits complained of sore feet, Dale Davis a neck
injury and Derrick McKey a back strain.
</P>
<P>
   Said Smits: ``It might be in some practices I can only go an
hour and a half or so. It will probably be the same as last year.
But maybe (the feet) will be better.''
</P>
<P>
   McKey had offseason knee surgery and now is having back
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Laker promises
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West started the week in L.A. talking about Tom Gugliotta,
Scottie Pippen, Kevin Johnson and Derrick Coleman. He ended up with
Travis Knight and Derek Harper. ``I don't know nothing,'' Shaquille
O'Neal said. ``They asked me who do I want. I said a couple names.
I look around, those couple names signed somewhere else. So, I
don't know what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
