<HEADER>
A5588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-720&AMP;AD     01-23 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MEDICARE PLAN MEANS BIG DEBATE IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., La.)  (lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is proposing a major expansion of
Medicare to cover prescription drugs, a change long sought by older
Americans, and a federal advisory commission may soon endorse the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   But drug companies are gearing up to fight any plan for the
government to provide prescription drugs as a basic benefit in the
traditional Medicare program. They fear that it would lead to
federal regulation of drug prices, which is anathema to the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Drug makers also fear that private insurers would follow the
government's example and demand discounts as deep as any made
available to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is thus preparing for a major debate over prescription
drugs. Rep. Pete Stark of California and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts, both Democrats, are drafting bills to authorize
Medicare coverage of prescription drugs. Rep. Tom Allen, D-Maine,
has a bill that would help Medicare beneficiaries get drugs at
reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans agree that there is a need to help the elderly with
drug expenses, though they tend to favor more modest plans.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union message last week, Clinton said that
he wanted to use the federal budget surplus to shore up Social
Security and Medicare and that Medicare should cover ``the greatest
growing need of seniors: affordable prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton foresees a total of $4.4 trillion in surpluses over the
next 15 years, and he would use $1 of every $6 _ $650 billion to
$700 billion _ for Medicare. The White House said on Thursday that
Clinton wanted to replenish the Medicare trust fund while also
providing ``a long-overdue prescription-drug benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   For many elderly people, drug costs are a heavy burden. Spending
on prescription drugs has increased at a brisk pace, not so much
because the prices of older drugs are rising as because people are
using more drugs, and some new, highly effective medications have
high prices _ $10,000 a year or more. The Food and Drug
Administration is approving more drugs, and doctors say that many
of the new products are clearly superior to the old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and lobbyists for the elderly said that
prescription drugs, though often costly, were essential to any
respectable health insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., chairman of the federal advisory
commission studying the future of Medicare, said, ``Drugs are as
important today as a hospital bed was in 1965,'' when Medicare was
created. Breaux said that drug benefits would simply update
Medicare to make it comparable to the health insurance offered by
most private employers with more than 25 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs are likely to become even more important, because the
industry, in the words of its lobbyists, is entering a golden age
of medical and scientific discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies have developed dozens of products to treat
afflictions of the elderly, including heart disease, stroke,
rheumatoid arthritis, Parkinson's disease and osteoporosis.
Researchers are working on drugs to treat or prevent Alzheimer's
disease and may soon be able to tailor drugs to genetic needs.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of Medicare prescription-drug coverage would depend on
the generosity of the benefit and other factors, but even the
strongest proponents admit that it would be expensive. The Medicare
commission is studying several options. A relatively modest drug
benefit would cost the government $10 billion to $15 billion a
year, it said, and could add $9 or $10 to the monthly Medicare
premium, now $45.50, which is deducted from a person's Social
Security check.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare generally does not pay for drugs used by patients
outside the hospital. But Medicare officials said that 80 percent
of beneficiaries regularly used prescription drugs, reflecting the
high incidence of chronic illnesses among the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   A new government study says that 65 percent of Medicare
beneficiaries have supplemental insurance to help pay drug costs,
while 35 percent have no such coverage. Premiums for private
insurance covering prescription drugs are often high, and there is
no guarantee that the people who need coverage can get it.
</P>
<P>
   Another study, published this month by the Commonwealth Fund,
said that 11 percent of beneficiaries spent more than $100 a month
of their own money on prescription drugs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Martin Corry, director of federal affairs at the American
Association of Retired Persons, said: ``We have long favored the
addition of prescription-drug coverage to Medicare. The lack of a
drug benefit is really dumb medicine. Drugs keep people healthier
and out of hospitals.'' Drug therapy often reduces the need for
hospitalization, surgery and nursing-home care, which can be much
more expensive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Holmer, president of the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America, the main trade association for drug
companies, said, ``Any expansion of prescription-drug coverage for
Medicare beneficiaries should come through the private sector and
not through the traditional fee-for-service Medicare program.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said: ``It's very important that any reform should
be fully financed, without resorting to government-imposed price
controls. Such controls distort the marketplace, they reduce the
incentive to innovate and our industry would vigorously oppose
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare commission is considering a proposal under which
the government would offer a fixed amount of money to each
beneficiary to buy insurance covering a comprehensive package of
health benefits, including doctors' services, hospital care and
possibly prescription drugs. Under such a plan, drug companies say,
Medicare patients could obtain drug coverage through competing
private health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Many employers provide coverage of prescription drugs for their
retirees, and many health-maintenance organizations offer drug
coverage to elderly subscribers, though they are not required to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies and members of the Medicare commission want to
maintain these sources of drug coverage. If Congress establishes a
drug benefit under Medicare, they say, it must be careful not to
create an excuse for HMOs and employers to drop the drug benefits
they now provide.
</P>
<P>
   If the government created a Medicare drug benefit, it would
become acutely concerned about drug costs. Drug companies insist
that the government must not establish a list of approved drugs for
Medicare beneficiaries or a uniform national price list. On the
other hand, administration officials and congressional Democrats
say Medicare ought to get substantial discounts because it would be
one of the nation's biggest purchasers of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Private insurers often follow Medicare's payment policies, and
that possibility worries drug companies. ``Seniors account for
one-third of the market,'' said Holmer, the president of the
pharmaceutical association. ``Any practices that would affect such
a large proportion of patients become trend setters for all health
plans, for better or for worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
