</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-DEPOSITS-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLCKER AUDIT ON HOLOCAUST COULD YIELD $750 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
 (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ A search by independent auditors for unclaimed deposits
placed in Switzerland between 1933 and 1945 is expected to conclude
by the end of March and to turn up funds that would now be worth
about three-quarters of a billion dollars with interest, Swiss bank
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The audit, which is overseen by a committee headed by Paul
Volcker, the former Federal Reserve chairman, was the result of a
1996 agreement between Swiss banks and Jewish organizations to
search for funds deposited by people who died in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on both sides stressed that the commission had not yet
obtained all the audited data, but that it had so far found about
100 million Swiss francs, the equivalent of about $73 million at
current exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that not all the funds had been deposited by
people who later died in Nazi death camps. Moreover, the task of
matching the names of depositors with those of Holocaust victims is
only about one-quarter done and could take years to complete, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The audit has progressed independently of a settlement reached
in August by Swiss banks to pay $1.25 billion to Holocaust
survivors to resolve class action suits in the United States and
thus avoid a possible boycott of the banks' business. It has been
overshadowed in recent months by a flurry of lawsuits against banks
and insurers in other European countries and manufacturers accused
of profiting from the use of forced labor during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss banking groups say they hope the results of the audit will
lay to rest disputes over how much money from Holocaust victims
remains in Switzerland. But even as the work draws to a close, some
Swiss bankers are complaining of excessive costs for the audit,
which they say could run as high as $700 million. Other officials
say such estimates are overdrawn, but several regional banks
announced recently that they were suspending payment of the
auditing fees, which the banks agreed to cover, until the matter of
pricing is cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   Since last June, more than 200 auditors from four international
accounting firms _ Arthur Andersen, KPMG Peat Marwick, Deloitte &AMP;
Touche, and PricewaterhouseCoopers _ have scoured the records of 26
private and publicly owned Swiss banks, including the two largest,
UBS and Credit Suisse, after an agreement was reached in May 1996
to search for unclaimed funds deposited between 1933 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Banking officials say the auditors have largely completed that
task and are now engaged in matching the names of account holders
with lists of Holocaust victims. Earlier this month, the Swiss
banks agreed to put up $4 million to match a contribution from the
World Jewish Congress to pay for computer storage of the lists of 3
million Holocaust victims from the Yad Vashem memorial in Israel.
These are intended to facilitate the matching of names.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the commission headed by Volcker, with three members
each appointed by Jewish organizations and the Swiss banks, is
expected to meet in Zurich, Switzerland, to discuss the auditing
process and to begin preparing a report.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Swiss weekly, Sonntagszeitung, reported
that Swiss banking officials expected the audit to turn up about
100 million Swiss francs. Michael Bradfield, a spokesman for
Volcker, refused to confirm the figure, saying, ``We are just
beginning to get hard data'' from the auditing firms.
</P>
<P>
   But Swiss bank officials, who requested anonymity, said they
believed the figure to be accurate. They said 100 million Swiss
francs would be equivalent today to 1 billion francs, based on a
formula developed by a team of experts appointed by Volcker to take
account of inflation and interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   Bradfield, who was general counsel at the Federal Reserve under
Volcker, said that not all the funds had been deposited by people
who died in the Holocaust, adding that only about 28 percent of the
matching work has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the $8 million spent on computerizing the Yad Vashem
files, many account holders may never be identified. Spellings of
names often vary, and some depositors who later perished may have
used lawyers, fiduciaries, and financial trustees inside
Switzerland to open accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonntagszeitung said officials at three cantonal banks,
citing the high costs of the audit, said they had suspended payment
of auditing fees. The newspaper quoted Kaspar Ottiger, director of
the cantonal bank in Schaffhausen, as saying that the costs of the
audit ``are in no proportion to the result.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marc Felix, spokesman for the Swiss Bankers Association,
said: ``Our interest is to bring the process to a successful
conclusion, to produce a report with a clear statement about the
role of the banks in the period of the war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
