A5597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     01-23 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: L.T. FITS THE CRITERIA FOR THE HALL OF FAME TO AN
L.T. 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla.) (js) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was a Giants linebacker, you never had to search for
Lawrence Taylor. He was always right where he was supposed to be,
charging the quarterback he hoped to sack or chasing down a
ballcarrier.
</P>
<P>
   He's much harder to find now.
</P>
<P>
   When the chimes rang inside L.T.'s big brick home in Upper
Saddle River, N.J., nobody answered. On the icy doorstep was a Fed
Ex envelope, addressed to him, that appeared to have been there for
several days. The sender was John Bankert, the executive director
of the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the package of information we sent each of the 15
finalists about a week ago,'' Bankert was saying now over the phone
from his Hall of Fame office. ``We ask each one, `Should you be
elected, where can we contact you at about 11:30 next Saturday
after the vote?' We haven't heard back from Lawrence.''
</P>
<P>
   Even two of Taylor's attorneys, Larry Lustberg and Thomas
Melani, didn't know exactly where Taylor was, other than
``somewhere in Florida,'' where he has a part in an untitled Oliver
Stone movie.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is believed to be in Miami, where the Hall of Fame
selection meeting will be held the morning before the Super Bowl.
If elected, he would be invited to a noontime news conference
there. And if the voters abide by the ``criteria for election,''
Taylor will ``go in on roller skates,'' as his Giants coach, Bill
Parcells, once predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only criteria for election to the Pro Football Hall of
Fame,'' reads Section 3, Item C, of its bylaws, ``is a nominee's
achievements and contributions as a player, coach, or contributor
in professional football.''
</P>
<P>
   As the most feared defensive player of his time, Taylor defined
the position of outside linebacker. If all 36 members of the
selection committee abide by the Hall of Fame's criteria, he was
dominant enough in helping the Giants win two Super Bowls to
deserve to be a rare unanimous choice.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he were not unanimous, 29 votes, equivalent to the
required 80 percent, would be enough.
</P>
<P>
   But just as there was only one L.T. as a linebacker, there has
been only one L.T. since then: two drug arrests, false federal tax
returns, Chapter 7 bankruptcy, questioning by a grand jury
investigating organized crime, suspended driver's license for
outstanding parking tickets, three traffic summonses for leaving
the scene of an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the resume of a model citizen.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter how the Hall of Fame criteria read, assuming
Taylor gets to the final yes-or-no vote along with five other
nominees, some of those 36 selectors, out of self-righteousness or
self-importance, surely will wince at Taylor's rap sheet and not
vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: How many won't? Two or three? Five or six? Even
if it's seven of 36, Taylor will still be elected.
</P>
<P>
   But if it's eight or more, Taylor won't be elected. And
according to the criteria, that would be an injustice.
</P>
<P>
   If Taylor had been a baseball player, Hall of Fame voters would
judge him on ``integrity, sportsmanship, character'' as well as his
``record, playing ability and contributions'' to his team. But the
Pro Football Hall of Fame, for whatever reason, has no morals
clause, so to speak, in its criteria.
</P>
<P>
   With a minimum of four, and a maximum of six, inductees each
year, three other first-time candidates could be measured this year
for their bronze busts _ Eric Dickerson, Howie Long and Coach Marv
Levy _ along with two holdovers from last year's yes-or-no vote,
Ozzie Newsome and Steelers owner Dan Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   The other nine finalists up for discussion are Coach George
Allen, Carl Eller, Ray Guy, Tom Mack, John Stallworth, Lynn Swann,
Ron Yary and Jack Youngblood, and in a separate yes-or-no vote, the
old-timers committee's candidate, Billy Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Taylor is elected Saturday, will the Hall of Fame be
able to find him in time for the news conference?
</P>
<P>
   In searching for Taylor on Friday, one of his attorneys provided
the cell phone number for one ``Eric,'' who supposedly is always
with Taylor somewhere in Florida these days. But when Eric
answered, he was not with Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm driving; I'll be in Lawrence's presence in half an hour,''
Eric said. ``Call back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later, Eric was ``still 10 minutes away.'' Ten
minutes later, ``Lawrence is still on the set, call back in 20
minutes.'' Twenty minutes later, ``He has a break in five
minutes.'' Five minutes later, ``Things are hectic here, call back
in 10 minutes.'' Ten minutes later, ``Give me your number, Lawrence
will call you back.''
</P>
<P>
   As of early Saturday morning, Lawrence had not called.
</P>
<P>
   In the confusion, the Giants alerted the news media on Friday
that ``Lawrence Taylor will be on a conference call'' Monday at
noon. He will presumably be discussing his Hall of Fame candidacy
from somewhere in Florida, if he can be found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
