<HEADER>
A5611 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOLS-INQUIRY-70     01-23 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-INQUIRY-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOVERNOR ANNOUNCES A SCHOOLS INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-SCHOOLS-CONSTRUCTION) 
(lb) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Voicing scorn for the performance of New York City
educators, Gov. George Pataki appointed a special state commission
Saturday to investigate wrongdoing in the construction of the
city's public schools and accusations that some administrators
inflated student attendance to reap more government aid.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki directed the commission to examine the School
Construction Authority, the state agency that was created in the
late 1980s to improve how city schools are built, but has since
become known for deadly accidents, cost overruns and seemingly
inexplicable design problems that in one case left a $300,000
wheelchair ramp under the hoop on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education hopes to spend $11 billion on
construction and repairs over the next five years, refurbishing a
system that remains overcrowded and antiquated, with scores of
schools still using hand-stoked coal burners as if caught in some
Dickensian time warp. The authority's checkered history, though,
has stirred concerns that no matter how much money the government
pours in, the results will be lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki acted without consulting Mayor Rudolph Giuliani or the
city schools chancellor, Rudy Crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do better,'' the governor said in a statement,
delivering an unexpectedly biting critique of the city schools.
``It is time to demand better. I understand and fully expect the
education bureaucracy and its allies to rise up in protest, howling
with doom-and-gloom predictions to divert attention from the
system's obvious failures. They have thrived on the status quo for
so long they don't know any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also instructed the panel to examine how principals and
other administrators compile and report attendance figures, which
help determine education aid and the size of a school's budget. The
city's Board of Education has had chronic difficulty keeping track
of the 1.1 million students in the sprawling system, and there have
been inquiries in recent years into whether schools have falsified
attendance figures to collect more for their budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Though the commission will concentrate on these two areas, it
has the authority to look into other aspects of the school system.
</P>
<P>
   By establishing the panel, Pataki is making his most forceful
foray into the operation of the city schools since he took office
in 1995. The state wields considerable influence over local school
districts, but in his first term, the governor shied away from
getting deeply involved in the often fractious disputes over
education policy among Giuliani, the schools chancellor, the Board
of Education and other prominent officials.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic leaders in the state Legislature on Saturday
questioned why Pataki waited until his second term to focus on the
system, contending that so late in his tenure he shares the blame
for school conditions. The authority has spent $7 billion since it
was created.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's comments Saturday could be interpreted as
somewhat of a rebuke of Giuliani. The mayor does not control the
system, but Giuliani has formed a close alliance with Crew, and has
championed what he says are the changes that he and Crew have
wrought. Giuliani has also tried to turn around the School
Construction Authority by installing a former top aide as its
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has a cool relationship with Pataki, his fellow
Republican, seemed surprised Saturday by the news of the
commission. The governor did not notify the mayor about the panel
before announcing it, though he did brief his Republican allies in
the state Senate on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really at a loss to explain to you what the basis for it
is,'' Giuliani said, defending the construction authority's recent
record under the latest chairman, Howard Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Saturday, the governor said his
decision to set up the commission without consulting Giuliani and
Crew did not indicate that he was displeased with either of them.
Pataki said he thought both men had done an excellent job, adding
that he strongly supported long-stalled legislation in Albany that
would give the mayor more control over the system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The deputy schools chancellor for operations, Lewis Spence,
declined to comment on the commission, saying he was waiting to
learn more about its scope and intent.
</P>
<P>
   In concentrating on the School Construction Authority, Pataki is
not going after some agency far removed from his administration.
While Giuliani appointed the authority's chairman, the governor
named one of the other two board members; Crew is the third. So
Pataki has had the opportunity to exert control over the authority.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Pataki's appointee to the board, Paul
Atanasio, resigned after investigators criticized his role in the
hiring of a supervisor at an authority project in Brooklyn in which
a falling brick killed a girl. The governor has not yet nominated a
replacement for Atanasio and has said he wants to let the mayor
appoint someone for that position.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Steven Sanders, D-Manhattan and chairman of the
Education Committee, said that because Pataki helps to supervise
the School Construction Authority, he did not need a panel to
figure out what was wrong with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a little bit like George Steinbrenner was having
trouble with how the Yankees are doing,'' Sanders said, ``and
instead of calling in his manager, whom he appoints, he appoints a
committee to find out what is going on with the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to such criticism, Pataki said, ``I would hope that
they would be interested in finding out whether or not we are
getting a fair return for what we invest in our schools. I don't
think that people believe that we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor named his state inspector general, Roslynn
Mauskopf, to head the commission, which is scheduled to complete
its work by Dec. 1. Its budget is to begin at $300,000, with the
administration adding money when necessary, the governor's aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   In naming the commission, Pataki invoked the Moreland Act of
1907, which grants the governor the authority to establish panels
with the power to subpoena documents and witnesses. Pataki has not
used the authority before. His predecessor, Mario Cuomo, invoked it
only a few times, most notably when he set up a panel to examine
government ethics in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous recent Moreland investigation occurred
in the 1970s, when a panel under Gov. Hugh Carey looked into abuses
in the nursing home industry.
</P>
<P>
   The new panel is not the first to examine the School
Construction Authority; Sanders is holding hearings on the
authority, and state Sen. Roy Goodman, R-Manhattan, has also led
investigations into its activities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mauskopf acknowledged those inquiries, but said hers would
be the definitive one. ``A lot of these questions have been asked
in the past,'' she said. ``But for too long, the individuals and
the institutions involved have just pointed fingers at one another,
in an attempt to give quick answers or excuses. It's now time to
take a hard look at the problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
