</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-STATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATURES ACROSS U.S. TO TAKE UP INTERNET ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., N.Y., Wash., Calif., Nev., Va.)  (mk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The contentious and complex debates over protecting
children from the evils of cyberspace, controlling unwanted
commercial e-mail and protecting consumer privacy online are
expected to move to statehouses in the coming months as state
legislatures convene around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-nine of the 50 states will hold legislative sessions this
year, with 46 of those scheduled to be under way by Feb. 2. At
those sessions, some 1,200 to 1,500 proposals dealing with the
Internet are expected to be filed, said Paul Rusinoff, state policy
counsel for the Internet Alliance, the largest high-tech and
Internet trade association in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting if you look at this context,'' Rusinoff said.
``We saw some of the first state bills dealing with the Internet in
1995. There were three of them. Last year, the association looked
at over 700. And I think as more and more legislators go online
themselves, and start hearing from constituents, the issues are
going to multiply.''
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list, he and officials with the National Conference
of State Legislatures and the U. S. Internet Council agree, will be
bills intended to protect children from adult material and online
predators, and measures to outlaw or regulate unsolicited
commercial e-mail, known as spam.
</P>
<P>
   But well-intentioned efforts to protect children from indecent
materials and online predators, and even measures involving spam
e-mail, often raise constitutional questions regarding free speech
and censorship. Another problem is that federal and state laws are
aimed at regulating a global medium.
</P>
<P>
   Civil libertarians have won virtually every court challenge of
efforts to limit minors' access to the dark side of the Internet,
including a lawsuit against the original Communications Decency
Act, passed by Congress in 1996, and state laws passed in recent
years in New Mexico and New York. A second federal law, named the
Child Online Protection Act, which was passed last year, is being
challenged in federal court in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think, personally, that there is going to be much
appetite for content-control legislation in state legislatures
because they realize that is going to be very difficult to
accomplish,'' said Mark Rhoads, legislative director of the
Internet council, a coalition of Internet and high-tech companies
formed in 1996 specifically to work on Internet legislation at the
state level.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rhoads said he expected that several bills aimed at
controlling content on the Internet would be proposed, he said
lawmakers ``are more likely to move in the direction of trying to
empower parents to more intelligently supervise their children's
online time'' with filters and other new technology.
</P>
<P>
   A number of bills to curb unsolicited commercial e-mail are also
expected. Last year, legislation seeking to control such e-mail was
introduced in 17 states. Bills were passed in two states,
Washington and California, bringing to three the number of states
with such laws. Nevada was the first, passing a bill in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While some argue that it seems futile for a state to try to
regulate e-mail on a global network, proponents say such laws can
help slow the barrage of unsolicited messages that often advertise
get-rich-schemes and adult-oriented products.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington law prohibits companies from sending e-mail with
a misleading subject line or false return address to Internet users
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   California's law also requires that all unsolicited commercial
e-mail sent to users in that state contain the word
``advertisement'' in the subject line.
</P>
<P>
   California enacted a second law that allows owners of computer
systems in the state to sue the senders of spam e-mail in an effort
to recover losses caused by network clogs or computers crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoads and Rusinoff said they also expected the federal debate
over whether laws are needed to protect consumer privacy online to
move to the state level. Other proposals they expect to see, Rhoads
said, include those seeking to outlaw online gambling, and several
to establish digital signatures, online notary publics and other
means of verifying identities on the Internet so that more private
and government business can be conducted online.
</P>
<P>
   Because Congress has passed a three-year moratorium on new state
and local taxes on Internet services and Internet commerce,
Internet taxes are not expected to be an issue in state
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Rusinoff and Rhoads said they thought few of the bills would
become law. But the flurry of legislation should raise the
awareness of the importance of forming new committees and state
offices to deal with Internet issues, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the odd features of the state policy environment right
now is that there is not really a committee structure to deal with
the Internet,'' Rhoads said. ``Only four or five states have
science or technology committees.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusinoff, whose group worked with Virginia to write the first
comprehensive state Internet policy agenda, says his group will be
urging other states to follow that model.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia proposal calls for tougher laws against
sexually-oriented solicitation of minors via the Internet and the
posting of information on how to contact a child on a pornographic
Web site; a requirement that Web sites clearly post what private
information they collect and how it is used, and a law that would
allow the prosecution of senders of unsolicited bulk e-mail that is
``fraudulent, unauthorized, or otherwise illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   It also proposes making online transactions and contracts
legally binding and would require the state to offer more
government services over the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
