<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BIAS-LAWSUIT-680(3     01-23 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BIAS-LAWSUIT-680(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIAS LAWSUIT OFFERS A GLIMPSE OF THE SHELF LIFE OF A TV
ANCHORWOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ohio, Ind., Calif., Texas, Mass.)  (js) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ She was the blonde, green-eyed Action News
anchor who brought Hollywood sizzle to Connecticut television,
racking up top ratings and zipping around town in a red Jaguar.
Rival stations warred over her services, driving her yearly salary
to $250,000 in the nation's 27th largest television market.
</P>
<P>
   But Janet Peckinpaugh knew she was living off a fleeting asset.
And when three big-city television stations made what she called
million-dollar job offers, Ms. Peckinpaugh made a trade-off. She
decided to stay with her Hartford employer in return for what she
says was a promise that she could grow old on the airwaves here.
Ms. Peckinpaugh said she recognized ``that female anchors are often
in perilous positions once they are 40 and over,'' but banked on
statements by station executives that she was so beloved by viewers
that they would always have a place for her.
</P>
<P>
   If there ever had been such a deal, it did not last. Ms.
Peckinpaugh, now 48, has fallen down the anchor ladder and now
rises at 2:30 a.m. to read the morning news at another station,
where she has no desk and no direct-dial telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh, the divorced mother of a 10-year-old, says it
was not just the years that caught up with her. In an age- and sex-
discrimination lawsuit against her former employer, which owned the
CBS station here, she maintains she was blacklisted after she
complained that the anchorman who was the other half of
Connecticut's dream team had groped her in a hotel room after a
late-night telethon. He says it was just a friendly hug and a kiss,
like the ones the two had exchanged many times before. Ms.
Peckinpaugh also maintains she was dropped from the evening
newscasts in favor of two younger women.
</P>
<P>
   Now 56, the silver-haired anchorman, Al Terzi, remains the dean
of Connecticut anchors, drawing an annual salary of about $325,000.
</P>
<P>
   In commercials and on billboards and buses, the anchor teams of
local television news have the grin and glow of newlyweds, or
perhaps a mom and dad who never fight. But the dark side of these
arranged marriages spilled out last week as Ms. Peckinpaugh and
Terzi told their stories for a jury in U.S. District Court in
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh is suing Post-Newsweek Stations, a division of
The Washington Post Co., which owned WFSB Channel 3, Hartford's CBS
affiliate, when she worked there. The station has since been sold
to the Meredith Broadcasting Group.
</P>
<P>
   A divorce often bares dark secrets, and the professional one
between Ms. Peckinpaugh and Terzi is no exception. The litigation
has resulted in the disclosure of thousands of station documents,
offering an unusual peek at how the glamour couples of television
news are chosen, coddled and _ if their ratings sag _ jettisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis House, a Channel 3 anchor-reporter, said in a deposition
that when his contract came up for renewal in mid-1995, he won a
promotion by mentioning to management that he had heard about two
promising openings in Houston. House, now 34, said his agent had
told him a Houston station was ``looking for white males'' so they
could ``pair them up with a female or something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In TV, you are cast in these big piles _ blonds, or
whatever,'' House explained. ``We are pieces of furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ryan, the president of Post-Newsweek Stations, said women's
longevity on the air depends simply on performance. ``The standards
that exist apply to both men and women _ on-air performance,
communication skills, writing skills, journalistic credentials,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh's fate may not have been inevitable. Don
Fitzpatrick, a television news talent consultant in San Francisco,
said the top anchors in several major markets are well into their
50s, and said aging baby boomers do not want to see familiar
figures removed. ``In the early '70s there was pressure to hire
women, and by the late '70s, there was pressure to put out to
pasture some of the older women,'' he said. ``I don't think that's
true today.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Peckinpaugh, the wild ride in television news began in
Richmond, Va. She had grown up in Ohio, majored in history and
communications at Indiana University, then worked in public
relations for an airline and cut radio spots for the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   It was front-page news in The Hartford Courant when she was
recruited to Connecticut in 1984 to be the star anchor at WTNH
Channel 8, the ABC affiliate in New Haven. (Like the CBS and NBC
stations in Hartford, it serves the entire state.) Initially, she
was part of a team that unseated Terzi, but by the next year they
were paired and their evening newscasts became the highest-rated in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh played along with what some journalists consider
the humiliations of television news, including lip-synching the
words ``You'll love it!'' in a station promotion. She bought a
shore-front condominium and vacationed in Europe and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Both she and Terzi testified that they had a warm relationship.
Then during Memorial Day weekend in 1987, they worked in New Haven
until after midnight on the Children's Miracle Network Telethon,
then headed to the Park Plaza Hotel, where organizers had provided
rooms for them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh said that after a reception for telethon
workers, Terzi insisted on walking her to her room. He went into
her room and checked the bathroom and under the bed, which she said
made her uncomfortable. ``I felt like he was in my space,'' she
said in a deposition. Then, she testified, ``He grabbed me and
tried to kiss me and tried to stick his tongue in my mouth, and I
was totally thrown back.'' She said she pushed him, but he just
grabbed tighter.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing his folksy bass to the witness stand, Terzi, who is
married, gave a very different account of the incident. He said
that in the elevator on the way to her room, she had thrown her
arms around him and given him a big hug. ``She said we made a great
team,'' he testified. ``I said, `I agree.' I hugged her back.''
</P>
<P>
   Terzi said that did not strike him as unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the kind of a person that liked to put her arms around
people, be very friendly,'' he said. Terzi said that when they
reached her room, he had checked around just to reassure her that
the room was safe. ``Given Ms. Peckinpaugh's popularity,'' he said,
``anything is possible.'' Then, he said, they had a good-night hug
and a kiss. ``I just said, `It's great working with you,''' he
recalled. He said he then left.
</P>
<P>
   Terzi said that during the next week, he detected a coolness
from Ms. Peckinpaugh, but said he did not know it had anything to
do with him. Eventually, they talked in the station parking lot.
``She said she thought the kiss and the hug went too far,'' he
said. ``I said, `What do you mean? We do that all the time.' '' He
added, ``It made no sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel 3, the CBS station in Hartford, had been recruiting Ms.
Peckinpaugh, and shortly after the incident at the hotel, she
jumped ship. She was the anchor for the 5 and 6 p.m. editions of
``Eyewitness News,'' which had soared to No. 1 one in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1991 that Ms. Peckinpaugh decided to trade what she
said were rich offers from Boston and Dallas stations for long-term
security in Hartford. As part of the deal, which brought her salary
to $250,000 by mid-1994, she won a provision that her primary
assignment throughout the four-year contract would be as anchor of
early evening newscasts, or else be paid off under a provision
called ``pay, no play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh testified that in March 1993 she was happily
presiding over the 5 and 6 p.m. newscasts. But she was going
through her second divorce, and, as she contemplated refinancing
her house, she sought out the station manager, Christopher J.
Rohrs, to check on her job security. She quoted him as saying,
``The people in the state of Connecticut love you'' and, ``You can
grow old at this station.'' Rohrs denies making such a statement,
and said he would not advise an employee about financing a house.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That summer, she said, Rohrs called her into his office and
said, ``We have a present for you.'' The station was hiring Terzi
away from its competitor, leading to the possibility of a
Terzi-Peckinpaugh reunion. His contract prevented him from
immediately appearing on the new station, leading to months of
tense speculation about who would be chosen as his co-anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh, and many other Channel 3 journalists, assumed
Terzi would be paired with her, according to testimony. But station
executives said no such decision had been made. Ms. Peckinpaugh
said she began getting subtle hints that her luster was dimming.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, she said, her news director began complaining
about her wearing glasses instead of contacts while delivering
brief newsbreaks. She said that another night, after she had her
bangs styled off her face, a group of colleagues gathered around a
television monitor to poke fun. Another time, she said, the news
director waited by the elevator to complain about a mangled word.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our business, when you're a star player, you are treated
differently,'' she testified. ``All of a sudden, I was being
treated just the opposite _ and that's death.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh asserted that Terzi persuaded the station not to
pair the two of them because she had protested the Plaza Hotel
incident. Terzi said he was ready to move on and was ``hot'' that
she brought the matter up. He said he thought, ``Here we go
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Station executives, who call her lawsuit ``a simple case about a
contract, not a conspiracy,'' said they had begun having concerns
about her the year before, based on declining ratings and viewer
research.
</P>
<P>
   By April 1994, she learned that she was not assured of being
Terzi's partner when she and two other anchorwomen were asked to
tape brief segments with him. A research firm hired by the station
then showed the clips to shoppers at malls to test the reaction. At
the time, Channel 3 had three anchorwomen and two anchormen.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh asserts that over the next several months,
several station executives said they had ``too many women,'' and
wanted to use the testing to decide which one to get rid of. On the
stand, Rohrs, the former station manager, said he simply had ``too
many anchors.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman S. Hecht, a market researcher from Syosset, N.Y., who
specializes in television, conducted about 400 telephone interviews
and showed the tape to about 300 shoppers. On Thursday, he
testified that his research showed Ms. Peckinpaugh was
``polarizing'' _ while she had fans, she also had many viewers who
chose her as their least favorite. He said many found her to be
unprofessional _ ``silly, goofy.'' After asking several questions
about the anchor teams' appeal, Hecht computed a ``net enjoyment
score'' in which Ms. Peckinpaugh came in last.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the results of the tests, the station decided to
pair Terzi with the woman who tested most favorably: Denise
D'Ascenzo, who is eight years younger than Ms. Peckinpaugh and
remains Terzi's partner today.
</P>
<P>
   After losing her anchor assignments, Ms. Peckinpaugh left the
CBS station in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ms. Peckinpaugh is the wake-up anchor for Hartford's NBC
station, WVIT Channel 30, which she said in an affidavit was ``the
only news anchor position I have been able to obtain since leaving
WFSB.'' At her new station, she started in 1995 at $45,000 a year
and now makes $80,000. Her son does not go to bed until 9:30 p.m.,
leaving her with about five hours of sleep. ``You never get used to
it,'' she said. ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   She does have a consolation. Since she went on, her station's
ratings for that time slot are way up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
