<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5624 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-N     01-23 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SELFLESS SPREWELL, OR THE SELFISH ONE?
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KNICKS-JOHNSON) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the off-kilter jokes subside, and Latrell
Sprewell, the basketball player, supplants Latrell Sprewell, the
national anger-management spokesman, the Knicks will learn what
kind of player and teammate they have gambled to acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Will he be the impatient guy who goes one-on-five, monopolizing
the ball because he has no faith in his teammates? Or will he stop
living for each possession and make use of good help?
</P>
<P>
   Will Sprewell return to the player who blended seamlessly with
Chris Webber, Tim Hardaway and Chris Mullin early in his career, or
revert back to the one who forced shots and sometimes made awful
decisions 14 months ago?
</P>
<P>
   What of the locker room, where either the miserable person who
often brought down his teammates could resurface, or the quiet guy
who quickly dressed and left whether he scored 30 points or 6?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was put in a situation where he had to succeed and be the
guy,'' said Muggsy Bogues, the Warriors' veteran point guard. ``I
thought he was a great teammate, but he developed tunnel vision on
the court sometimes, taking too much responsibility and doing
whatever it took to win. Now he's got other guys around to help
him. It's different. I think New York will be good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's former teammates characterized him as determined,
loyal and unbelievably talented. Bimbo Coles called him the best
shooting guard in the National Basketball Association behind
Michael Jordan. ``He was a guy who could do everything,'' Coles
said. ``He never gets tired, comes into camp ready and plays hard
on both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   But they also portrayed Sprewell as a player who may be more
comfortable as a role player than someone expected to rescue a
slumping franchise, a role he will assume soon with the Knicks of
Patrick Ewing, Allan Houston and Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the only things I thought he should work on was that he
needed to trust his teammates a little more,'' said Donyell
Marshall, the Warriors forward. ``He would try and do so much on
his own. But a lot of that had to do with our personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the guys he's going to have on that team, you've got no
choice but to trust those guys. We really didn't have a veteran or
a leader, someone to say, `Let's slow it down,' or `Let's take good
shots.' I don't think that will be the case there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player, but he doesn't really like the limelight
where he's the man,'' Coles said. ``He's just a player that wants
to play. As far as playing the role of getting on guys, he doesn't
want that responsibility. He doesn't want to jump on somebody.
Here, they wanted him to play a role as a leader. It just didn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back with regret on Friday after being traded to the
Knicks for John Starks, Terry Cummings and Chris Mills, Sprewell
asked not to be judged solely by the events of Dec. 1, 1997. ``One
bad day,'' he called his choking of P.J. Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   But the month leading up to his violent outburst alone hardly
portrays a model teammate. Buried in the transcripts of his
arbitration case against the NBA and the Warriors is Sprewell's
testimony to the grievance arbitrator, John D. Feerick. Feeling
like a scapegoat and wanting to be traded, Sprewell helps construct
an unflattering portrait of himself as a team captain at the
beginning of the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell admitted to laughing in the middle of a blowout loss,
missing a team flight because he overslept, questioning daily his
coach's authority and, finally, wondering why everyone was blaming
him for the Golden State's woes.
</P>
<P>
   For more than six pages of Feerick's findings, Sprewell emerges
as an agitated young star, hypersensitive to criticism and
unreliable as a team leader. Saying Carlesimo once called him ``an
idiot,'' Sprewell testified: ``I don't see why he would. ... I just
felt really offended by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with his rookie year in 1992 and leading to the attack
on Carlesimo, Sprewell said he was fined or disciplined numerous
times for missing practices or breaking team rules. He talks about
fights with former his teammates Byron Houston and Jerome Kersee.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of Sprewell's on- and off-court incidents have been
documented, he addressed them personally during the hearing last
year.
</P>
<P>
   After an altercation with Kersee a few years ago, Sprewell
testified he said, ``I'm gonna get my peeps,'' and that he might
have said, ``I'm going to kill you,'' to Kersee, but that he did
not mean it. He then said he retreated to the locker room, picked
up a 2-by-4 and threatened to hit two teammates if they did not let
him go. He said he eventually put down the piece of wood without
incident.
</P>
<P>
   If his short temper stands out in the transcripts, so, too, does
Sprewell's utter lack of respect for Carlesimo and his stewardship.
Sprewell admits to missing a flight to a game in Utah because ``he
fell asleep and did not wake up on time.'' On Nov. 9, 1997, he
begins laughing during a blowout at the hands of the Lakers after
Coles jokes that he wants to foul out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo benched Sprewell, who uses a profane word before
calling his coach ``a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Feerick, ``He said he thought it disrespectful to be taken
out of the game and that Carlesimo did not shake his hand after the
game.'' Over and over, Sprewell comes across as a disconnected
athlete who refuses to hold himself accountable for some of the
team's failings.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a year later, his teammates from last season
contend that the frustration of losing and the feud with Carlesimo
overcame him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have already judged him because of the incident, but I
think you'll see a different person than the one perceived to be a
bad guy,'' Bogues said. ``You see the hairstyle and the scowl, and
that's image. But that's not Spree. He works hard and he doesn't
like to step on toes. I think he'll be a great addition.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I just hope with everything that's happened he
doesn't lose his aggressiveness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
