<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5629 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-730&AMP;ADD     01-23 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING REPUBLICAN GRANTS `REASONABLE PEOPLE' CAN DIFFER ON
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Fla., Ark., Minn., Ill., Calif.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS,
IMPEACH-BIBLE-BELT, IMPEACH-WITNESSES-REVIEW)  
(mk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the leading members of the Republican
prosecution conceded Saturday that even if the Senate thought
President Clinton was guilty of perjury, ``reasonable people''
among its members could disagree on whether he should be removed
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a written question from Democratic senators, Rep.
Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., one of the 13 House prosecutors, or
managers, in Clinton's trial, said he was convinced that both
perjury and obstruction of justice, the offenses covered by the
impeachment articles, fell within the constitutional category of
``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   But before voting to convict the president, he told the
senators, who are sitting as a court, they must ``consider what's
best for this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham continued: ``It's never been hard to find out whether
Bill Clinton committed perjury or whether he obstructed justice.
That ain't a hard one for me. But when you take the good of this
nation, the upside and the downside, reasonable people can disagree
on what we should do.''
</P>
<P>
   That concession was the most dramatic moment of the second and
last day of questioning, following three days of presentations by
the managers and by the president's defense lawyers. Charles Ruff,
the White House counsel, said later that Graham had ``stated for
you the essential of the role'' the Senate must play.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if, indeed, reasonable people can differ,'' Ruff said,
does that not mean that ``whatever conduct you believe the
president committed,'' it would be difficult for the Senate to
legitimately determine whether he should be removed?
</P>
<P>
   He said the essence of the problem was unchanged: ``Is there a
sufficient danger to the state, danger to the state, to warrant
what my colleagues across the aisle have called the political death
penalty? And I think that the answer to that is no.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case for the last several days, maneuvering
outside the chamber influenced what went on inside. Just as the
Senate was convening, shortly after 10 a.m., word spread that a
federal judge had ordered Monica Lewinsky, whose sexual
relationship with Clinton led to his impeachment, to meet
informally with the House managers.
</P>
<P>
   Right from the start, Democratic senators bombarded the managers
with angry questions: Why had they not consulted with senators
before asking the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, to seek
Saturday's ruling? Did they notify the president's lawyers? Did
they think their actions had raised fundamental questions of
fairness and due process?
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., answered that no one had talked to
the senators because the Senate's rules had not been involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a witness that you're going to produce, you have a
right to prepare that witness,'' he said. ``It's as simple as that.
It has nothing to do with the formal proceeding of taking the
deposition, which is covered by the rules that you've passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff's perspective could not have been more different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we really say that it's just normal, just OK,'' he asked,
``to have one side using the might and majesty of the independent
counsel's office, threatening a witness with violation of an
immunity agreement if she doesn't agree to fly across the country
for this friendly little chat?''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, he said the ``looming presence'' of the
independent counsel would intimidate Ms. Lewinsky during any
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ms. Lewinsky or anyone else is called as a witness
remains an open question. On Monday the senators will vote first on
a motion to dismiss the case and _ only if that fails _ on whether
to call witnesses to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The managers continued to press their demand for witnesses. Rep.
Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., listed numerous conflicts he said witnesses
could help clear up: between the testimony of Ms. Lewinsky and
Clinton; between that of Ms. Lewinsky and Vernon Jordan, who tried
to get her a job in New York, and between that of Clinton and his
secretary, Betty Currie, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``White House counselors say this is going to drag on for
months,'' Hutchinson said. ``Well, if it drags on for months, it is
because they want it to drag on for months. We'll do all we can to
end this in a timely fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ruff and his colleagues, they continued to insist that
all the material questions had already been asked of the major
players.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., asked Ruff a question of special
import, in view of Graham's suggestion that the good of the nation
was an important element in deciding whether to convict Clinton.
Supported by many commentators in the news media, Democrats have
argued off the floor that it would be folly to remove a president
who is given favorable poll ratings by almost three-quarters of the
public. Wellstone wanted to know if that mattered at all.
</P>
<P>
   Polls themselves were not the whole answer, Ruff replied, but
``only one clue as to what the American people are thinking.'' But
the American people have certainly given strong suggestions that
they did not feel that the political structure needed the
``cleansing'' the managers have spoken of.
</P>
<P>
   ``The will of the people, the belief of the people in this
president's ability to govern, must educate each of you,'' the
counsel said, ``not mandate a result, but surely guide the result
that you reach in this proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the 25-year veteran of the House
Judiciary Committee who is serving as chief prosecutor, rose in
response, thanks to a friendly question that was read out later by
Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not delegates who are sent here to weigh our mail every
day and then to vote accordingly,'' he said. ``Our work here is not
an ongoing plebiscite. We are elected to bring our judgment, our
experience and our consciences with us here. I have always believed
that there are issues of transcendent importance that you have to
be willing to lose your office over.''
</P>
<P>
   Equal justice under the law was one such issue, Hyde said,
adding a few words that made clear how beleaguered he has come to
feel as pressure has mounted from almost every side to abort the
trial early next week: ``Despite all the polls and all the hostile
editorials, America is hungry for people who believe in something.
You may disagree with us, but we believe in something.''
</P>
<P>
   Still later, Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., another manager,
provided a footnote to the debate that Graham had begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, in apparent pique with his Republican
colleague, ``reasonable minds can differ as to whether the
president should be removed from office. But reasonable minds can
only differ if those reasonable minds come to the conclusion that
enforcement of the sexual harassment laws in this country is less
important than the preservation of this man in the office of the
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky came to light as the
result of a sexual harassment suit against him by Paula Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
