<HEADER>
A5631 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-JOHNSON-NY     01-23 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON RETURNS TO KNICKS WITH RELIGIOUS FERVOR FOR BASKETBALL 
</HEADLINE>
 ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also KNICKS-SPREWELL) 
(DW) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bacon is crackling and popping in the frying pan, and the
man who looks carved out of a sequoia is feeling weak. But Larry
Johnson has two sons sitting at the kitchen table, so he keeps
flipping the bacon as his mouth waters and his stomach growls for
the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   The player who still brings home the bacon now forces himself to
turn his back. For six months, Johnson has had little use for a
fork and knife. Passing vegetarian initiation, Johnson learned the
value of a spoon for all the bean pies he ate during the league's
lockout, part of a diet that has left 20 pounds lighter entering
the Knicks training camp last week. The pressure on his perennially
aching back and bad ankle has been lifted.
</P>
<P>
   But this weight loss is not only about a diet. Johnson's new
sleek physique comes as a result of his exploration with the Muslim
faith. He leaned on the religion's discipline nearly every day as
his alarm went off at 5 a.m. and cut through the sultry Texas air
like a fog horn.
</P>
<P>
   Slipping out of his Dallas home before dawn, he arrived at the
community center he built in his old neighborhood for a workout
with his personal trainer. Two hours in the morning, two hours at
night. That was hard enough. On Dec. 20, just before the winter
solstice kicked in, Johnson's days actually seemed longer.
</P>
<P>
   A month of Ramadan had begun. About 6:50 a.m., after
weight-lifting and running, Johnson would gulp down a protein
shake, inhale a Power Bar and then wait until nightfall before
eating or drinking again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not believe at around 3 or 4 p.m. just how grouchy
and how ready I was to bite someone's head off,'' said Johnson,
during the second day of Knicks' training camp on Friday. ``By 5:30
p.m., I could eat grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 7 p.m., the veggie burger on his plate was as good as a
prime rib.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you the essence of meat,'' Johnson said with a smile.
``There's no taste. The taste is me piling on about 15 pieces of
pickle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan ended last week. So far, Johnson has been tempted by the
McDonald's Happy Meals his sons tote around the home he recently
bought near the Knicks' facility. ``I see those french fries and
hamburgers,'' Johnson said. ``And I say to them, y'all are killing
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has resisted a dive into the deep fried foods. And he
attributes his newfound willpower to the Muslim religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the discipline of it,'' Johnson said. ``It's just
the straight-up discipline of being a man. It's not just about
eating, but about being a husband, a friend and all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the mentally and physically fitter Johnson will have a lot
on his plate to deal with this season. The addition of Latrell
Sprewell means Johnson will be forced to play well undersized at
power forward, especially in his lighter form. But as a weathered
and worn player at age 29, Johnson wants to be able to run in the
more up-and-down offense the nuevo Knicks will turn on this season
and still keep his injury risk low by playing under 240 pounds.
Last year, he crested at 257 pounds after he severely sprained his
right ankle in November. He missed nine games, still felt great
pain, but returned.
</P>
<P>
   After Patrick Ewing crashed down on his wrist in December,
Johnson forced himself to play on an ankle that was as wobbly as a
flat tire by season's end. In a way, the lockout was a rebirth for
him. He had a chance to rest the chronic back problems that have
haunted him for several years and to heal his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   While other Knicks took the layoff as an opportunity to let
themselves go just a bit, Johnson was in the weight room filling in
his smaller frame with more muscle mass, a bulk that he believes
will help him bang against larger power forwards. Coach Jeff Van
Gundy isn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Johnson is the perfect example of a guy who has been
able to focus in on what's important,'' said Van Gundy, who has
marveled at Johnson's conditioning and questioned that of his other
teammates. ``I think he's been a great example the first two days
of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is also an example for Sprewell to follow. Johnson once
arrived in New York with a reputation for being a difficult
teammate in light of his head-bumping with Alonzo Mourning in
Charlotte. He was seen as the brash, gold-toothed Grandmama from
the shoe commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But while he has been caustic and moody with reporters at times,
he has been nothing but the model teammate. If anything, Johnson
came to the Knicks two years ago and deferred too much to Ewing.
The once assertive Johnson became the wallflower. It took Ewing's
injury last season to bring out the star player in Johnson again.
Even though Ewing has returned this year _ and Johnson still
believes the offense has to revolve around their center in the
half-court _ this is not the plodding old Knicks, not with Sprewell
on the floor. Instead of resisting change, Sprewell's presence is
welcomed by Johnson, who understands what it's like to be the new
guy with a past.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was coming in here, I didn't think too much about what
the guys thought of me,'' Johnson said. ``I knew inside who I was.
So I'd tell everyone to forget what you've read. You don't know
Spree by what you've read or seen on TV. You make mistakes all the
time. I learned that long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson plans on being a supportive caretaker of his
controversial teammate. ``We're not going to introduce him to New
York,'' Johnson said. ``We're going to keep him low profile and
have him think nothing but basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was Johnson's focus during the tedium of the lockout.
Instead of letting up, he pressed on with the discipline of a new
religion. It won't be easy to carry on in his new way of living.
Some mornings, it's especially tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm getting up in the morning, fixing breakfast for my
boys, and they're eating turkey bacon,'' Johnson said. ``Man,
that's smelling good.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
