<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-COLUMN-REFORM-NYT     01-23 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COLUMN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHANGE IS DEMANDED TO RIGHT THE OLYMPIC WRONGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also OLYMPICS-SCANDAL) 
Robert H. Helmick, a lawyer in Des Moines, was president of the
U.S.Olympic Committee and a member of the IOC from 1985 to 1991. He
remains a member of the USOC board of directors. 
(js) 
 By ROBERT H. HELMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scandal surrounding the selection of Salt Lake City for the
2002 Olympics is only a symptom of a more deeply rooted problem,
which will require a major shake-up of sport's international ruling
bodies if we are to preserve and protect the Olympic ideal. This
crisis requires a drastic reform of the International Olympic
Committee and its overly pampered ``lords'' and a renewed focus on
its real purpose: the athletes and fair competition.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing short of the departure of the IOC's president, Juan
Antonio Samaranch, and his close associates will allow the sweeping
changes needed to restore public confidence in the Olympic Games
and their leadership, so badly tarnished by disclosures of cash
payments and perks made to influence the choice of the Utah site.
Without a thorough housecleaning, future scandals cannot be
avoided.
</P>
<P>
   The sordid story of the selling of the Olympics came as no
surprise to me and others familiar with the recent history of IOC
excesses. Rather than concentrating on the needs of athletes and
fair competition in the winter and summer Games, a culture built
around their own comfort became the norm for the 114 IOC members as
they girdled the globe to consider competing city bids.
</P>
<P>
   They got accustomed to being treated like royalty: first-class
air tickets, luxury hotel suites, limousines, lavish entertaining
and endless rounds of gift giving to win their favor _ and votes.
One of the Salt Lake City organizers protested that the IOC was
allocated $2.6 million for hotels, including a $60,000 suite for
Samaranch, and an additional $1.1 million transportation budget,
including chauffeurs for IOC members. With this atmosphere, it's no
wonder that an extra $25,000 to influence a site-selection vote was
considered small change in this twisted version of a free market in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   It is a system that almost encourages corruption to flourish.
Aware of the worldwide uproar, the IOC hierarchy has once again
settled on the ``few bad apples'' solution to deal with the most
flagrant offenders. Designated villains have already been fingered
to take the fall and perhaps the go-along-get-along IOC survivors
will even (gulp!) adopt a code of ethics. But this would be
applying a Band-Aid to a cancerous growth when radical surgery is
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   So, rather than just expelling 10 or a dozen IOC members caught
with their hands in the Olympic cookie jar, systemic change must be
made to prevent future scandals. Or else it will be, in the words
of a sports sage, deja vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   What must be done? Samaranch's idea of concentrating greater
power in a smaller group is exactly the wrong solution. Instead,
the right course is to make the IOC more democratic, more
accountable and more open in its decision-making processes. The
self-perpetuating IOC members are now virtually installed for a
lifetime and owe their loyalty primarily to the reigning president.
As a result, internal criticism or even policy differences are
practically nonexistent. Limiting the terms of IOC members, ending
the practice of secret voting, mandating a larger percent of
athlete-members and opening IOC records to public scrutiny are
reforms whose times have come.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch must also go. He has made great contributions to the
Olympic movement but he will be too defensive and too focused on
defending the past rather than adapting to a new future. So, he
should not remain in office until his term ends in 2001, when he
will be 81 years old. A new leader would have a freer hand to
introduce and advocate the overhaul to clean up the current mess
and renew confidence in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Samaranch must take responsibility for the Salt
Lake City fiasco, even if he was not personally involved, because
it happened on his watch. After all, the leaders of the Salt Lake
Organizing Committee stepped down to accept responsibility for its
members' actions. Samaranch's resignation would advance the Olympic
cause and dramatize the need for an overhaul in international
sport.
</P>
<P>
   I know: in 1991, when I was accused of impropriety, I resigned
as president of the U.S. Olympic Committee, even though I felt
then, and still believe now, that the conflict-of-interest
allegations were not justified. It was a difficult choice, but I
left because it was necessary in the greater interest of sports and
the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the corporate sponsors of the Olympic Games should
demand far-reaching reforms. Companies that contribute millions of
dollars to support the games have the right and the responsibility
to make sure their reputations remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics are a global treasure. They are held so dedicated
athletes can demonstrate the upper limits of human achievement, and
we may see the best athletes the world has to offer in competitions
that often have a spiritual dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget those heart-stopping moments when an underdog
U.S. ice hockey team defeated the Soviet Union or when U.S. female
gymnasts overcame adversity to capture a gold medal?
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the shabby perks and payoffs to Olympic officials
are simply fool's gold and must be relegated to last place. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
