<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-REFORMS-6     01-23 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-REFORMS-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN OFFICIALS CALL FOR REFORMS
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: UGANDA, KENYA, UTAH, NIGERIA, ARGENTINA, COLOMBIA,
THAILAND) (see also OLYMPICS-SCANDAL) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Australian Olympic officials, under pressure
at home and abroad after revelations of questionable payments
during Sydney's successful bid for the 2000 Summer Games, last week
called for change in a selection process that allows aspiring host
cities to offer substantial aid to national Olympic committees.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the officials defended the Sydney bid
committee's decision to promise money for sports programs to
African members of the International Olympic Committee on the eve
of the vote for the 2000 Games. Sydney's bid won by a margin of two
votes over Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, including Australian Olympic Committee president
John Coates and IOC vice president Kevan Gosper, also asked for
quick assurances from the IOC that the Games would still take place
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking for a vote of confidence,'' said Greg Thomas, a
spokesman for Sydney's organizing committee. ``We're very hopeful
that will happen. Salt Lake City has been guaranteed it will host
the Winter Games for 2002. I would be remarkable if the IOC did not
offer the same guarantee to Sydney in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney needs reaffirmation because of the stir caused by the
payments that Coates, a key member of the Sydney bid, offered to
Charles Mukora of Kenya and Maj. Gen. Francis Nyangweso of Uganda
on Sept. 22, 1993 at a Monaco hotel. That was the night before
Sydney defeated Beijing, 45-43, on the final ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Coates has acknowledged he made the offers of $35,000 each
because he felt he needed to shore up Sydney's support in Africa.
``You have to create a sense of them having some obligation to you
when they go into that room,'' he said of the vote. But Coates said
the offers, which were made in the name of the Australian Olympic
Committee, did not constitute bribery or break IOC rules because
they were between national Olympic committees and not between
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper confirmed that IOC regulations do not prohibit a national
Olympic committee from ``supporting the development of sport in
another part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be changed,'' Coates said of a system that is open
to abuse, ``but that is a process that we went into with our eyes
wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't win it on the beauty of the city and the sporting
facilities we had to offer, and we were never going to,'' Coates
added, saying that Beijing and Manchester, England, also had
programs to aid Olympic committees in Africa. Coates also said his
Africa strategy was influenced by the belief that Atlanta had used
a similar approach in its successful bid for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a good case for reviewing regulations and
process,'' said Gosper, a member of the executive board that met in
Lausanne, Switzerland, this weekend to hear evidence in the IOC's
investigation of corruption in Salt Lake City's successful bid for
the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Two IOC officials have resigned because of that inquiry and as
many as 11 others face expulsion or suspension. But now that
documents released Friday by Coates and the Australian Olympic
Committee have provided evidence of the final-hour payments, the
IOC had another incident to assess.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the Sydney committee spokesman, said there was growing
concern about the impact on sponsorship. ``We'd be naive to think
that if all this continues, it won't have an effect on the Olympic
brand,'' he said. ``Our sponsors have raised general concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said Sydney had raised $700 million (Australia) in
sponsorship but needed $200 million more to complete its budget. He
said fund-raising was on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Coates said he had no intention of resigning, and Gosper, who
had been critical of the cash payments and suggested Sydney could
be stripped of the Games, tempered his comments Saturday after
speaking with Coates by telephone from Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the issue here is it was a continuous dialogue on a
program that was already documented and being audited,'' Gosper
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Australian Olympic Committee began providing formal aid to
athletes and coaches from the Oceania region in 1990, offering them
grants to travel to Australia and train at the Institute of Sports
in Canberra. According to Australian committee documents,
approximately 80 people benefited from that program in the first
three years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, in the heat of Sydney's Olympic chase, the Australian
Olympic committee extended a similar invitation to 11 African
nations. It also offered more limited aid to Argentina, Colombia
and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   The documents released Friday include copies of the cooperation
agreements signed with several of the African nations, including
Uganda and Nigeria. The Ugandan agreement was signed on Aug. 14,
1993; the Nigerian agreement on Sept. 6: 17 days before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of a letter dated Aug. 25 that was sent to all 11 African
nations outlined the training grants in more detail. Whether or not
Sydney won its bid, the Australian Olympic Committee agreed to pay
for airfare, accommodations and meals for two persons from each
country for three months to the sports institute in Canberra. It
also agreed to pay a weekly living allowance of $40 (Australia).
</P>
<P>
   If Sydney won, the Australian committee agreed to extend its
annual offer through the 2000 Games and to pay for the African
Olympic teams to train one month before the Games in Australia with
free coaching, medical and physiotherapy services. The cost of the
14-nation program was estimated at $1.842 million (Australia).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was considered a good thing to do in the bidding process,''
Gosper said of the program. ``We were already doing it with
Oceania. It was openly done, and it was done generally, and it
wasn't in any way linked to a specific voting pattern. I knew about
it and was quite comfortable with it. The I.O.C. knew about it and
was quite comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gosper, who was part of the bid team, said he did not know
about Coates' decision in Monaco to offer Uganda's National Olympic
Committee, headed by Nyangweso, $5,000 a year for seven years to
support the Uganda national games and the same amount to the Kenyan
Olympic Committee, headed by Mukora, for unspecified ``Olympic
sports projects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is discomforting,'' Gosper said of the payments.
``But as Coates has said, it was a sustained effort up to the
decision. It was not introducing a new program. And it's very
important to say the program related to money going to the programs
of the NOC's. It was not going to personal improvement of bank
accounts or scholarships or favors to family members.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
