<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTEBOOK24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves won't spoil fun for players, families
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves has done this Super Bowl
thing eight time previously, but he's still scratching his head
trying to figure out just how to go about it.
</P>
<P>
   He was 1-1 as a player with the Dallas Cowboys, 1-2 as an
assistant with Dallas, and 0-3 as coach of the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   So he's mixing up a few things as the Falcons (16-2) prepare for
Super Bowl XXXIII against Denver (16-2) next Sunday in Miami. The
most notable development is that Reeves decided to allow players to
have their families stay with them at the Miami Airport Hilton and
Towers hotel.
</P>
<P>
   There's a fine line between coaches being too strict the week
before the Super Bowl, thus creating unnecessary anxiety, and
running too loose a ship, thus losing concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to enjoy it,'' Reeves said. ``It's not going to be
one of those things where we bunker down and take away everything
and not allow them to have a life this next week. They just got to
realize what is important, and get themselves ready for the biggest
game they've ever played in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our families are staying with them at the hotel. That's
something not many teams would do, but that's the way we've
approached the whole season. Hopefully, we'll handle that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves will eliminate curfews tonight and probably Monday nigh,
but later curfews are possible, even probable, every night as the
earnest preparation begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of lecturing from Reeves, the 14 other members of the
coaching staff and front office with Super Bowl experience, or the
team's four Super Bowl veteran players -- Cornelius Bennett, Eugene
Robinson, Tony Martin and Randy Fuller -- can prepare first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't realize until we get to the hotel that it's not
like a normal hotel on a road trip,'' Reeves said. ``Everything is
intensified.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has done a great job all year preparing . . . under
different circumstances. We had the week off to get ready for the
playoff game, where I missed two weeks (after heart bypass surgery)
. . . injuries . . . this group has done a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
