A5640 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS24-COX     01-23 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta prepares big sendoff for Falcons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Chuck Smith and his Falcon teammates roll through
Centennial Park at about 1:30 today in three buses, he'll be a bit
out of sorts while waving to fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (16-2) have had one week to get used to the idea of
playing the Broncos (16-2) in Super Bowl XXXIII next Sunday, but
there are still times it's hard to believe they beat the Vikings
30-27 in overtime in last Sunday's NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   So fans should forgive Smith if he looks a little bug-eyed
during today's official ``sendoff'' as the Falcons head to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time he and his teammates act like they belong in
the biggest game in sports.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything happened so quick,'' said Smith, a seventh-year
Falcon and native of Athens who was around when the team went 3-13
in 1996, and started last season 1-7 before winning 22 of 26.
``It's kind of strange how long we've been playing (this season).
Usually, I'm in Jamaica by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve linebacker Keith Brooking is usually hitting the books
about about now. The rookie from Georgia Tech, who grew up in
Senoia, south of Atlanta, occasionally finds himself in a state of
shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly overwhelming for me, and one of the reasons is I
grew up here and followed the Falcons,'' he said. ``I try to pinch
myself to make sure it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as fans began to take interest while the Falcons piled up
win after win in the midst of their franchise-record 11-game
winning streak, there was no predicting the reaction of the past
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There have been rallies in Buckhead with overflow crowds, signs
all over the city, merchandise on sale every where, and talk of the
team dominates local radio and TV airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has surprised me how quickly the fans have caught on, and
supported us,'' said linebacker Henri Crockett. ``It's like
somebody flipped a switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is perhaps the best example of how confident the Falcons
are in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat the (stuffing) out of a lot of teams,'' he said.
``Even when (the Vikings) scored that touchdown (to take a 27-17
lead in the fourth quarter last Sunday), I still felt like, 'We got
to hold up our end. I just felt like we were going to win.' I kind
of envisioned all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Kicker Morten Andersen, the native of Denmark whose 38-yard
field goal with 3:08 left in overtime is big on visualization. He
did a lot of it before that game-winning field goal, and he's
having fun visualizing today's sendoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are special moments in your life. Hey, that's why you
play the game,'' he said. ``It's been great, fantastic. You just
see people smiling everywhere. I hope there are thousands of people
there. Good vibes. . . . that's what I'm looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen can count on that.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
