u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-0124     01-23 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-0124-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NETANYAHU FIRES DEFENSE MINISTER WHO WAS CONSIDERING RUN AGAINST
HIM
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Leader of a country famous for pre-emptive strikes
on the battlefield, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
Saturday night fired Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai before
Mordechai could resign to run against him.
</P>
<P>
   The move was the biggest surprise in a young election season
already full of surprises. Israeli television stations broke into
regular programming to show Netanyahu, at a press conference
flanked by other cabinet members, reading a letter firing
Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
   In it, and in Mordechai's response minutes later, Israelis saw
the two highest-ranking members of their government trading angry
statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent days,'' Netanyahu read, ``I have seen that your
personal ambition is stronger than anything else . . . A man who
betrays the principles of the voters is not worthy of being in our
ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai responded standing in front of his heavily-secured
home near Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Netanyahu) sent me a letter full of lies and slander and
inaccuracies, which are typical of a petty politician,'' he said.
``He is not fit for my trust or the Israeli peoples' trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, 54, was a general in the Israeli army until
two-and-half years ago when he was heavily courted by both
Netanyahu's Likud Party and the rival Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the right-wing Likud Party and his active campaigning
was instrumental in helping Netanyahu edge out then-Prime Minister
Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being a highly-decorated military commander,
Mordechai was born in Iraqi Kurdistan and was the most prominent of
the Sephardic Jews, whose families immigrated to Israel from Asia
and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly half the Israeli population, they are an important
voting block but have long felt alienated by Israeli Jews from
Europe and are under-represented in the political elite. The
Sephardic vote went to Netanyahu in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Netanyahu and Mordechai had become
increasingly strained over the last year. Mordechai, a moderate on
Israeli security issues who ept close contact with American
officials, complained openly about the slow pace with which
Netanyahu was handling the peace process with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   He also had a rivalry with Ariel Sharon, the right-wing former
general who Netanyahu appointed foreign minister in October.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai's abrupt firing, though surprising, is indicative of
this prime ministerial election. The Israeli parliament, with
Netanyahu's coalition steadily losing support, in December moved
elections forward from the year 2000 to May 17 of this year. Since
then, the election season has been marked by defections from both
major parties, and a series of mysterious break-ins at Labor Party
offices.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Mordechai was negotiating with a newly-formed
centrist political block seeking to unseat Netanyahu. The group was
headed by former Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak. Shahak was reportedly
willing to let Mordechai head the group, and thereby be the
candidate for prime minister, if he had the better chance of
beating Netanyahu. They were reportedly close to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Mordechai let pass a deadline for getting on the
Likud Party list for seats in parliament, though he had not said
whether he had decided to leave the party. There appeared to be an
ongoing bidding war between Netanyahu and Shahak for Mordechai's
loyalties, until Netanyahu fired him Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Netanyahu) obviously thought he had him until the last
minute,'' said Israeli political scientist David Newman. ``If
anyone will take votes away from him it is Mordechai.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has seen a handful of supporters vow to oppose him in
the elections, but Mordechai is the most important.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said he was not sure if any previous Israeli prime
minister has fired a defense minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Israel has) lost a certain moderating influence in the
government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television reported Saturday that Netanyahu intended to
replace Mordechai with another former general, Moshe Arens, a Likud
member who had already announced that he was running against
Netanyahu in the party primary.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
