<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5642 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PAMREEVES-COX     01-23 1600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PAMREEVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Credit Mrs. Reeves with husband's successes
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the school bus rumbled across rural Georgia, teen
matchmakers paired off a sophomore football player named Dan Reeves
with a cheerleader named Pam White.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was 15, White 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a mushy story,'' Pam Reeves recalled. ``The head
cheerleader used to ride the bus with Dan, and she believed we
would be a good couple. She finally pointed me out to him. He
called me and our first date _ a double date _ was a sock hop.''
</P>
<P>
   What attracted her to Reeves? ``Probably what attracts most
young girls to someone,'' she said with a rolling drawl. ``I
thought he was so cute.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost four decades later, Dan and Pam Reeves are still
together. They wed in 1964 at First Methodist Church of Americus
while both finished up college: Dan at the University of South
Carolina, Pam at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   As Dan Reeves has become a legendary figure in the National
Football League _ the Falcons head coach has played or coached in
nine of the 33 Super Bowls _ his wife has provided the loyalty,
courage and flexibility for him to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be where I am without her,'' Dan Reeves said.
``When it comes right down to it, I just always wanted to do
whatever would make her proud. It was true in high school, it was
true when I married her and it's still true today.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Reeves' stoic nature is credited for helping her husband
recover from a quadruple heart-bypass operation on Dec. 14 _ at the
heart of a pressure-packed season. Despite her private nature, she
provided moral support at a very public press conference, and
shielded him from ill-timed visits from well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   Extremely reserved _ she originally said she didn't want to do
an interview for this story because ``it is not part of my job
description'' _ Pam Reeves is described by friends as a Southern
lady, a Steel Magnolia whose loyalty to friends, family and
marriage comes first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pam is a very good balance for Dan,'' said Betty Manders of
Dallas, a friend of the family since 1965. ``She's the one who
keeps things in perspective. She's very grounded. But she's also
very witty and she's able to keep things from getting too somber.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a skill she's honed over the years as a football wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get too high on victory,'' Pam Reeves said. ``I
always tell my friends who congratulate me, `Be careful, or you'll
have to send me condolences next week.' But it also teaches you not
to get too low when you're getting beat. You always have to
remember to focus on the next game. Because in football, there's
always another game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Reeves, the youngest of four children, was introduced to
football by her father, W.D. White, a former state patrolman and
director of the local division of the Georgia Housing and Finance
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a lot with my daddy,'' she said. ``He taught me how to
drive.... He taught me how to shoot a .22. And he taught me about
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, she developed a deeper understanding of the game
as her husband traveled the country first as a pro football player,
then as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   A love for the game grew more slowly. Although she will watch a
``good college game'' by herself, she is not a full-fledged
fanatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably developed a passion for it when it started putting
bread on the table,'' she said. (Dan Reeves has a five-year, $9
million contract with the Falcons.)
</P>
<P>
   She also mastered an understanding of the NFL culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the great thing about Pam Reeves is she understands
that everyone does better _ husbands and wives, coaches and players
_ if they're all on the same page,'' said Billy ``White Shoes''
Johnson, the Falcons' player programs coordinator. ``It's important
to see this at the top. It's good for all of us to see how
important they are to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   When a garage sale fund-raiser was held last year at the
Falcons' training camp in Suwanee, Ga., Pam Reeves came in _ and
pitched in _ before anyone even realized who she was, Johnson said.
``She was just one of the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Reeves equates her life to that of a military wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like being in the Army,'' she said. ``You learn to
be flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first NFL stop was Dallas in 1965, shortly after she was
married. Reeves, a former quarterback, became a running back for
the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The move to Dallas was hard on her, because the young couple was
hundreds of miles from their families. ``I had never been west of
the Mississippi before that,'' she said. But they had their babies
_ two girls and a boy _ and over 16 years, established roots.
</P>
<P>
   Manders and her husband, Dave, who also played with the Cowboys,
became friends with the Reeveses while they were neighbors in
adjacent apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Michigan, and she's from the South, so it took us a
while just to understand each other,'' Manders recalled. ``She
introduced us to so much about Southern culture, though. I like
grits now. And I remember when she brought over a sweet potato pie.
I had never heard of such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when he a coach with the Cowboys, Dan Reeves got an offer
to be head coach of the Denver Broncos, and the family was uprooted
again, this time leaving behind decade-long friendships in Dallas.
But it was particularly hard on the oldest child, Dana, who was on
the cusp of 16 and had been attending a private Christian school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dragging my feet too, but I think she had the toughest
time,'' Pam Reeves said of her daughter. ``Of course, we were all
thrilled that Dan had this opportunity and we moved forward. But at
times, it was difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reeves family fell in love with Denver, however, and stayed
there for 12 years, until Dan Reeves was fired and then signed up
to head the New York Giants in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Pam and Dan Reeves moved as a couple, because their
children by then were in college or on their own. And the Reeveses
were captivated with the landscape of New Jersey. Yes, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when people think of New Jersey, they think of
Newark,'' Pam Reeves said. ``But it was one of the most beautiful
states I've ever seen. In many ways, it's very similar to Atlanta.
In fact, it has more pink dogwoods than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the call came from the Falcons, the couple were ready
to return to their native Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The couple settled in a French country home, throwing oriental
rugs on the heart-pine planks and filling the house with antiques
and the photos of their family.
</P>
<P>
   Most of their free time was spent with two of their children,
Lee and Dana, and grandchildren. (Laura, their third child, still
lives in Dallas with her husband and child.)
</P>
<P>
   Both love books, with Dan preferring historical pieces and Pam
``reading anything I can get my hands on.'' Monopoly is their
favorite board game. And the couple often face off with a game of
gin or a round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   The last two months have been tough. From Dan's bypass surgery
to the grueling NFL playoffs, both Dan and Pam have had to tap into
reserves of strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly was not my nature,'' she said. ``I typically get
my strength from Dan, but I guess when the main man goes down, you
just do what you have to do. I didn't have time to think about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she doesn't go into the particulars _ preferring to
merely say ``it's like childbirth _ it sort of all fades away'' _
family and friends say Pam Reeves is the one who keeps things on
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Mom holding everything together, '' said her son Lee, a
31-year-old Atlanta lawyer. ``It was Mom who led the prayers for
Dad. It was Mom who kept up the smiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``She says she is not a pillar of strength, but she is, for my
kids and for myself,'' he said. ``I wouldn't be where I am today
without her.''
</P>
<P>
   The trauma of the heart surgery led Dan Reeves to shed some of
his stern image. While discussing his bypass surgery during a press
conference, the coach broke into tears. His wife held his hand.
</P>
<P>
   For Pam Reeves, that moment was wrought with emotion. She was
happy he felt secure enough to share a little more of himself with
the outside world. But intensely private herself, she also was
protective of how his tears would be interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, crying is just part of being a heart patient,''
she said. ``But I was glad that everyone could finally see that Dan
is the sensitive person I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the couple is concentrating on the Super Bowl, although
their hallmark steadiness carries over in the preparations. Dan
Reeves has received more than 2,000 letters and cards of support,
and they were both touched by the turnout at the airport when the
team returned from their victory over the Minnesota Vikings in last
Sunday's NFC championship game. But Pam Reeves said the family is
trying to enjoy the hoopla without losing focus.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no special meal, bedtime or routine the night
before the Super Bowl, she said. Although the couple does plan to
get a nice seafood meal in Miami _ a bow to Dan's heart surgery and
low-fat diet _ things will probably be as routine as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a special game, but I don't see a lot of uptightness,''
she said. ``We'll probably come back (from dinner) and he'll do
whatever he normally does. And that will be that.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
