INDY RACING lEAGUE HAS AN EYE OUT FOR NEXT SUPERSTAR 
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three seasons and 24 races into its checkered history, the Pep
Boys Indy Racing League has produced a bonafide marquee driver.
</P>
<P>
   And bid him ``adieu''.
</P>
<P>
   Former series champion Tony Stewart will not be in the starting
lineup for the season-opening TransWorld Diversified Services Indy
200 at Walt Disney World Speedway today. The original IRL ``Poster
Boy'' with Team Menard, Stewart's immediate racing future lies in
NASCAR's Winston Cup Series, where he is preparing to begin his
rookie season with Joe Gibbs Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two-time Indianapolis 500 winner Arie Luyendyk, the
IRL's all-time victory leader with four, plans to compete only in
the 83rd edition of that famed event on May 30 before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the irony. Stewart _ the prototypical American-born,
short-track, open-wheel driver for whom Tony George founded the
series in 1995 _ racing with fenders. And a roof. In front of
sold-out grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Luyendyk _ the series' first established ``name'' driver
_ never racing again at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth.
Luyendyk made national headlines there after being slapped to the
ground by rival team owner A.J. Foyt in Victory Lane after the
inaugural True Value 500K night race in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the IRL once again having to audition for an undisputed
superstar. Not that the garage area is lacking marketable talent.
Reigning series champion Kenny Brack and 1998 Indy 500 champion
Eddie Cheever Jr. have spent the offseason preaching the IRL gospel
_ and dutifully dropping the names of Greg Ray, Billy Boat, Davey
Hamilton, Scott Sharp, Scott Goodyear, Robby Unser, Sam Schmidt and
Jason Leffler.
</P>
<P>
   Are any of the above capable of carrying the league through its
fourth season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem filling Tony Stewart's shoes,'' said Ray,
who has replaced Stewart as the lone IRL driver at Team Menard.
Ray, whose best IRL finish to-date is a second-place finish behind
Boat at TMS, will make his debut for millionaire car-owner John
Menard in Orlando today. But Ray already is matching Stewart on the
brashmeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, I was begging _ dying _ to go drive the
car with Tony on the same day,'' Ray said during a preseason test
in Fort Worth. ``Same car. Right now. Because I expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Stewart's a great guy and a great driver. I'll take him
on any day, anywhere, any time. I just hear that `Tony Stewart sets
the standards.' Well, knowing what I know, he didn't set the
standards. I just feel like he's gotten way more credit than he
deserves. Bring it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever, at 41 one of the series' elder statesmen, believes the
IRL can sell that kind of irreverent attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing drivers,'' said Cheever, ``are not ordained like the
Pope. They're created. The way you create them is to have racing
drivers competing against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRL has done an incredible job understanding what the
American public wants _ oval racing. You'd be hard put to find a
series where the racing is harder. The IRL is emulating a lot of
things NASCAR did _ and racing on ovals is one of them. It's
probably the fastest racing series in the world. And as we've seen
\Rwith the crowds\S in Texas, once they see a race in person,
they're hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack, in fact, suggested that the real ``star'' of the IRL at
this point is the racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good racing, very good racing,'' said Brack, a native of
Sweden who won a record three events in 1998. ``We need to draw
people's attention to the races.''
</P>
<P>
   H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler, the president of Charlotte Motor
Speedway and a NASCAR diehard, said IRL superspeedway races are
throwbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have no respect for each other,'' said Wheeler,
whose track is scheduled to play host to the IRL's Indy 500
``tuneup race'' on May 1. ``It looks like stock cars from 1958, on
dirt. They dart and do things that stock cars can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Auto Club Silver Crown graduate Donnie Beechler, who
qualified for eight IRL events as a rookie last season, agreed the
racing is the league's hook for another reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the IRL is that we are not in everybody's
living room every weekend like the Winston Cup series,'' said
Beechler, who posted a best finish of 10th last season. ``We run 11
races. When you are \Ron TV\S every Sunday or Saturday night, the
names become familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack has talked up the series during a slew of nationwide
public relations visits this offseason. But Brack, who drives for
four-time Indy 500 champion Foyt, remains reluctant to tag himself
as Poster Boy II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel like a star?'' Brack said, rhetorically. ``I feel
like my normal self. For me, I've proved myself, and people know I
can drive. I get respect for that. But I don't look upon myself as
a star. I think being yourself is the best way, always.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack's reserved off-track style stands in contrast to that of
the ever-aggressive Stewart, who leaves the IRL having led the most
laps in series history with 1,502. That is 1,085 more laps than
runner-up Jeff Ward. But even with the resources of Team Menard at
his disposal, Stewart has yet to win the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest thing the IRL has going for it is the Indy 500,''
Wheeler said. ``The Indy 500 is still the greatest race in the
world. If Kenny Brack wins the Indy 500 this year, everybody in the
free world is going to know that _ at least for 48 hours.''
A star is born? A look at 10 drivers who could emerge as the next
star performer in the Pep Boys Indy Racing League: Driver Age Team
Entrant Comment Kenny Brack 32 A.J. Foyt Enterprises Racked up
three wins in 1998 Greg Ray 32 Team Menard His dream ride has
arrived Eddie Cheever 41 Team Cheever Articulate owner/driver Billy
Boat 32 A.J. Foyt Enterprises Fearless style suits Foyt Davey
Hamilton 36 Galles Racing Two-time points runner-up Scott Sharp 30
Kelley Racing Shared first IRL championship Scott Goodyear 39
Panther Racing LLC Savvy veteran series supporter Robby Unser 31
Team Cheever Top '98 rookie has name appeal Sam Schmidt 34 Treadway
Racing LLC Racing with a big-time budget Jason Leffler 23 Treadway
Racing LLC Won two USAC titles last year
</P>
</TEXT>
