<SLUG> BC-PORNOGRAPHY-RULING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGE DOES NOT VIOLATE LAW ON PORNOGRAPHY, JUDGE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The crude, cut-and-paste renderings of a
homeless Olathe laborer did not violate a Kansas law designed to
outlaw computer ``morphed'' child pornography, a Johnson County
judge ruled Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that raised potential constitutional issues, the
decision boiled down to one picture that showed the head of what
prosecutors alleged was a child pasted onto a picture of an adult
woman's nude body.
</P>
<P>
   District Judge John Anderson III ruled that he could not find
beyond a reasonable doubt that the face depicted a child under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Though Randy Shores possessed hundreds of pictures of women and
girls and many written notations describing sexual activity with
children, the judge found that only the one picture possibly
violated the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case absolutely disgusts me,'' Anderson said. ``But I
swore to uphold the law.''
</P>
<P>
   He then found Shores not guilty of sexual exploitation of a
child and ordered him released from jail, where he had been held
since August.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he would not release to Shores his book filled
with hundreds of pictures of nude women and pictures of young girls
cut out of catalogs and magazines. And he said he would not allow
Shores to have his journal, in which he chronicled graphic
descriptions of his sexual fantasies involving young girls.
</P>
<P>
   He called the journal the ``single most shocking, disgusting and
really absolutely terrifying piece of evidence in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the journal and the ideas expressed in it were not
illegal under Kansas law.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Toth, an assistant district attorney, had presented the
journal as evidence of Shores' state of mind in possessing the
allegedly illegal pictures.
</P>
<P>
   For Shores to be found guilty, Toth had to show that Shores
possessed the pictures with the intent to satisfy his sexual
desires.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing to have the case dismissed, defense attorney Blithe
Cravens Leece said Friday that the state was overreaching in trying
to apply the law to Shores' case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to judge his ideas, whether you find them
disgusting or not,'' Leece said.
</P>
<P>
   Shores, 43, who has a prior conviction for a misdemeanor sex
offense involving a child, was the first person in Kansas
prosecuted under the law that went into effect in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1711EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
