A5649 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-SCHOOLS-2ND     01-23 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-SCHOOLS-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANIKA WHITE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ a plus for adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   Students never leave their little corner of the school. There
are four classrooms to a pod. Each classroom has a bathroom and a
``focus room,'' where students can go to cool off, study quietly or
work with a learning specialist or a peer. The classes eat lunch
one room at a time, in a common area two feet outside their
classroom door.
</P>
<P>
   The students wear uniforms _ blue or khaki pants and a
company-issued polo shirt. There are two or three teachers for
every class of 18 to 24 students.
</P>
<P>
   The school provides individualized education plans, using books,
videos and personal computers. Instruction focuses on the basic
skills required for high school graduation. The course work is
accelerated and intense, so there is no homework _ one less thing
for a student to forget or leave at home.
</P>
<P>
   The company contracts with local law enforcement agencies,
courts and public and private social services agencies to address
the needs of the whole child _ on site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we're more than just an alternative school,''
said Anthony Edwards, administrator of Houston's newest Community
Education Partners school. ``We feel like we're a community
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   In Houston and in Dallas _ the latest district to sign on with
the company _ school board members and teachers union leaders rave
about the results achieved in the partnership schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so grateful to have them here,'' said Gayle Fallon,
president of the Houston Federation of Teachers. ``It's really made
a difference for the students. It's made a difference for the
teachers.''  &LR; brk:Students satisfied  &LR; tx:And students like the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Jaclyn Perez, 17, should be in the 11th grade. But she skipped
so much school, she's classified as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hanging with the crowd, skipping school, not doing
my work, arguing with the teacher. I was bad,'' Perez said. ``I
regret that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But if she stays in a partnership school for three semesters,
she'll have earned enough credits to go back to her home school.
Perez could return after two semesters, but she's doing so well at
the school, she's reluctant to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay here as long as I can,'' Perez said. ``And
go back just in enough time to graduate. ``Cause if I go back there
(now), I'm just going to start messing up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Eiland hated the partnership school his first few months. He
wanted to wear jewelry and flirt with the girls. His teachers say
he came to the school loud, belligerent and vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is the school's first student council president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so much better now,'' Eiland said. ``I've been on the
honor roll...I can't see why I couldn't do this at my home school,
'cause it's so easy to me. I learn fast and I work fast. This is
like the me I was in middle school. I'm proud of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Results like those obtained with Perez and Eiland are just what
the Kansas City school district needs, said Jim Dougherty, director
of De La Salle Education Center, a privately run alternative school
that works with the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that the district is thinking of doing this, because
God knows we need it,'' said Dougherty, who also made the trip to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll support them, but I'll also be concerned that the
district realize that they're part of the problem. We can't just
look at it as, `We have to fix the kids.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1712EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
