<HEADLINE>
MANAGEMENT COMPANY'S SCHOOL SETUP `FITS A NEED,' KC SAYS OF
HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANIKA WHITE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With his shiny gold jewelry and outgoing personality,
17-year-old Adrian Eiland was quite the ladies' man at his Houston
high school.
</P>
<P>
   His skills on the drums were second to none. And, man, could he
sing.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to schoolwork, Eiland just didn't have time.
</P>
<P>
   So Eiland frequently skipped school. When he was there, he made
it difficult for the teachers to teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of friends,'' Eiland said. ``And I got caught in
the mix. I got so into not going to school, it became an everyday
thing. After three years, when it got closer to graduation, and I
realized I wasn't going to graduate, I decided to come to CEP.''
</P>
<P>
   Community Education Partners is a private management company
that contracts with school districts to control behavior and
accelerate learning so sixth- through 12th-graders who are behind
in their studies can return to their home schools. This week,
Kansas City School District representatives visited Eiland's school
and others run by the company to see whether the model will work
for Kansas City's disruptive students.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Houston Independent School District
contracted with the education company to help steer the thousands
of students like Eiland back on course.
</P>
<P>
   Eiland started at Community Education Partners this school year
as a junior. He's worked so hard that by June, he will be eligible
to graduate with his public school friends. He's talking about
pursuing a music career at a college in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the spotlight,'' Eiland said, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City district officials came away impressed by their
visit this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very positive, what they're doing for the children who
are labeled at-risk in the urban environment,'' said Board
President John Rios. ``This definitely fits a need that this
district has....I was very impressed with its management, and I
think it's something we definitely need to look into.''
</P>
<P>
   Rios said he may recommend to the board by next month that the
district contract with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials have said they would like to work with at
least 1,200 Kansas City students who are violent or chronically
disruptive and at least two years behind in reading and//or math.
</P>
<P>
   The company would spend at least $10 million to renovate empty
retail space or build a one-level facility to house the students
and furnish and stock it with state-of-the-art equipment. The
school district would have to pay a daily per-pupil fee to cover
operating costs and provide transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost to the Kansas City district is not yet known. But
the price may be worth it, Rios said, considering the program's
results.
BREAKER HEAD: The three Bs The program's motto is simple: Be here.
Behave. Be learning.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, so far, the three B's seem to be working wonders, say
district officials and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the schools opened, crime in the Houston public schools
has dropped 22 percent. The average student enrolled at a Community
Education Partners Partnership School, as they are called, advances
about two grade levels in reading and a little more than one year
in math. Students go to school about 20 percent more often than
they did before.
</P>
<P>
   When students return to their home schools, after an average of
one year, company and district officials say the students continue
to attend school more regularly, have fewer behavioral problems,
earn more credits and finish high school.
</P>
<P>
   So far, evidence of the company's success is mostly anecdotal.
District officials are developing a method to track whether program
benefits continue once students return to their home schools.
</P>
<P>
   Though the school buildings are colorful and plant-filled, the
Community Education Partners format is a rigid one:
</P>
<P>
   Students come through metal detectors every day. They are
thoroughly searched, relinquishing any jewelry and money or other
personal items over $5. No watches, jackets, backpacks or other
distractions are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Students are separated into pods by gender and by progress in
the program. The more students achieve and the better they behave,
the faster they move up in levels. The higher the level, the more
privileges they are given. For example, the highest level is coed _
a plus for adolescents. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
