<SLUG> BC-ECONOMICS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSANS COULD USE A `HANCOCK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The difference between Missouri's willingness to continue
extending substantial tax relief and the cold shoulder Kansas
taxpayers appear to be getting this year can be summed up in two
words:
</P>
<P>
   Mel Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Without a legal restraint such as the one Missouri's Hancock
Amendment imposes on government's insatiable appetite for money,
taxpayers will always be vulnerable. A tale of two states provides
a good example why:
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's Gov. Mel Carnahan this week proposed tax cuts of $191
million despite the prospect of a state revenue bonanza that will
trigger another round of rebates to taxpayers, including Kansans
working in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing rebates are the result of a strong economy that
boosts state income beyond levels allowed by ceilings engineered
nearly two decades ago by Hancock, a Springfield businessman who
went on to serve in the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's taxpayer-protection crusade was driven by his belief
that governments shouldn't fare better than those providing
government's money. His efforts brought forth a protective shield
for Missouri taxpayers that bears his name. Under the law, the
state is required to refund excess tax revenue or offset it with
tax reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan emphasized how the state's booming economy prompted his
tax-cut push, but it's a good bet that few such decisions are made
in Missouri without considering the constitutional constraints
voters approved at Hancock's behest in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who doubts the restraining effect of this sort of
external discipline need only look at similar doings in Topeka,
where Kansans are at the mercy of whatever their elected
representatives deign to give them in the way of tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   With the worries of getting re-elected now conveniently behind
them, Kansas pols seem in no hurry to continue pursuing substantial
tax relief. The governor's budget, for instance, recommends new tax
cuts of just over $15 million. This compares to the $250 million in
tax cuts enacted when elections loomed.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's budget even proposes ending the moratorium begun
a few years ago on unemployment compensation tax collections from
business, even though the fund's balance still appears well above
the level needed to finance a typical year of claims. Meanwhile,
the Kansas jobless rate remains well below the national rate.
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium is estimated to save Johnson County businesses
$90 million a year and upward of $160 million annually for all
state businesses. So, if the fund is healthy, why repeal this very
attractive tax break for business?
</P>
<P>
   While there's some concern about Boeing layoffs in Wichita, a
proposal to restore the tax in its entirety appears a reaction that
is both extreme and premature.
</P>
<P>
   The governor decries speculation that his commitment to tax
relief will wane in his final term, but his actions so far as a
lame duck reflect anything but a strong dedication to fight for the
taxpayers' best interests. Nor does there seem to be much interest
in the Legislature to push further tax relief. All of which is to
be expected in the absence of a legal device that forces elected
representatives to do right by taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lesson here, if Kansans want to ponder it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1714EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
