<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5661 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-23 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE IMPEACHMENT TRIAL TURNS SHARPLY PARTISAN OVER LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton
turned sharply partisan Saturday after the Republican House
prosecutors took preliminary steps to have Monica Lewinsky testify
at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The move touched off Democratic senators who complained that the
House prosecutors were preparing Lewinsky to testify even though
the Senate hasn't decided whether there will be witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors defended their action, arguing that they have
a right to prepare witnesses for depositions or live testimony
before the Senate, in case the Senate decides to have witnesses.
They prepared to interview her Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, wrote Chief Justice William Rehnquist
to ask him to keep Lewinsky from being interviewed by House
prosecutors. Harkin argued that such an interview violates ``the
Senate's sole authority...of the Constitution to try
impeachments.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said it is up to the Senate and not a judge or the House
prosecutors to decide the procedures under which witnesses can be
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators showed that their senatorial sensitivities were
ruffled by the House. Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., criticized the
step was an ``arrogant disregard for the Senate.'' Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., said the House prosecutors' action ``invited the division
of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats sent a letter to Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the
chairman of the House prosecutors, asking him to ``take no action
related to the proposed interview of any witness until such time as
the Senate has given you the authority to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde responded that he believes interviewing Lewinsky will help
prosecutors determine whether to call her as a witness. Hyde said
he is still determining which witnesses to ask the Senate to call.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules...do not require that the House obtain the
permission of the Senate merely to conduct an interview of a
potential witness,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the professed outrage by Democrats, many Republicans
said there was nothing wrong with the effort by House prosecutors
to interview Lewinsky, the former White House intern who had a
sexual relationship with Clinton. The president was impeached for
allegedly lying about that relationship to a federal grand jury and
obstructing justice in an effort to cover up the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., said the House prosecutors had the
right to interview prospective witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are allowed to call witnesses, obviously the name Monica
Lewinsky comes up,'' Bryant said. Because Lewinsky was given a
grant of immunity last year in return for her testimony before
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury, her legal situation
is more complicated and the House prosecutors needed to get a head
start. He said there would likely be no similar delay in talking to
other potential witnesses such as Clinton secretary Betty Currie
and Clinton friend Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they afraid of? Are they afraid of our talking to
Monica Lewinsky?'' Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., one of the House
prosecutors, said. ``We're not doing anything abnormal. We are
exercising our privileges, our rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul McNulty, a spokesman for the 13 Republican House
prosecutors, said the interview was necessary for the prosecutors
to decide whether to submit Lewinsky's name to the Senate as a
possible trial witness.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky can resolve some of the crucial conflicts in previous
testimony, McNulty said. ``This is lawyering 101 _ any good lawyer
would talk to a witness before deciding to put her on the witness
stand.''
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles Ruff groused that Starr had become
``the moving force in the development of the truth and the facts,''
a role the Constitution had reserved for the senators.
</P>
<P>
   The flap over Lewinsky began when Hyde asked Starr to ask U.S.
District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson whether Lewinsky's immunity
agreement with Starr requires her to cooperate with House
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson ruled Saturday that Lewinsky had to submit to an
interview request by House prosecutors. Lewinsky could also decide
to have the interview conducted by Starr's office with House
prosecutors present. She flew to Washington from California and was
expected to be interviewed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, House prosecutors will seek to persuade the senators
that they need to hear from certain witnesses in order to help
resolve the many conflicts that have come out during the trial. If
the Senate does approve calling witnesses, it might also authorize
that only written depositions be taken of each witness. The Senate
would decide after seeing each deposition whether to call any of
the witnesses to appear before the Senate to testify in public.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will also hear arguments from both sides Monday on a
motion offered by Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., on a motion to
dismiss, or end, the trial. Byrd's motion to dismiss is expected to
be defeated along party lines. Republicans have 55 seats while the
Democrats hold 45 seats. The vote on whether to call witnesses is
too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., said he and Sen. Susan Collins,
R-Maine, have asked Bryd to reconstruct his motion to allow a
separate vote on whether to dismiss each article.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one way to at least test the strength of the House
managers case on each article separately,'' Feingold said. Another
partisan battle began brewing Saturday as Lott floated the idea of
blocking floor debate on the motions to dismiss the case and to
call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate impeachment rules lawmakers can debate each motion
for up to 16 hours each behind closed doors, but only if they vote
to do so, according to John Czwartacki, Lott's press secretary. He
said Lott opposes giving the Senate time to debate because he
believes lawmakers' minds are already made up on each issue and
that it would only delay the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Republicans would make a final decision on the debate
issue on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned,'' Daschle said of Lott's idea. ``It's an
extraordinary new development to gag senators.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
