Undated: be fair.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   SURHOFF WANTS A CUBAN SEASON
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Surhoff would like the Orioles to play the Cuban national
team in Havana and in Baltimore before the coming season, but he
doesn't know if the exhibition series will be scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody would like to play the games,'' said
Surhoff, an Orioles outfielder, who was a member of the delegation
that visited Cuba last week. ``From a baseball standpoint, I think
it would be fun. It would be an interesting experience. But a whole
lot of things have to be considered. A lot of them are beyond the
players' control. There are issues that are stumbling blocks, and
there are significant issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-game series must be approved by the State and Treasury
departments on the governmental front and by Major League Baseball
and the players association on the sports side. Just as
fundamentally, the Orioles and the Cuban government have to agree
on the recipient or recipients of the proceeds of the games. They
failed to reach agreement during the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials initially expressed concern about the
possible ramifications of a Cuban series. They were concerned that
all players could be at risk if Cuban-Americans reacted badly to
the idea of the games. Those fears, however, seem to have
dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials also were not sure that players would support
such a series, but have received no indication that serious
opposition exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played against them before; I know they can play,''
Surhoff said, referring to the 1983 Pan-American Games and an
international tournament in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, Surhoff said, was educational. ``It was a lot
different than I thought it would be,'' he said. ``I just didn't
know much about Cuba. It's a Caribbean island, and it has some
beautiful spots to it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
