<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POPE-0124-COX     01-23 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-0124-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPE ELEVATES MEXICO'S ROLE IN CATHOLIC CHURCH, URGES DIGNITY
FOR POOR
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In a homily that could set the stage for
Catholicism in the new millennia, Pope John Paul II on Saturday
assigned Mexico a special role in bolstering faith while scolding
governments in this hemisphere for practicing torture, racism, the
death penalty and other ``intolerable evils.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's homily in Mexico City's Our Lady of Guadalupe
Basilica, observed by millions here watching television and
listening to radios, underscored the church's concern for the poor,
with special recognition for indigenous Americans.
</P>
<P>
   During mass in the cavernous Basilica, Indians speaking various
tongues -- including Peru's Quechua, Mexico's Nahuatl and the
United States's Navajo -- offered readings of liturgy, alongside
speakers of English, Portuguese, French and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our cry: life with dignity for all. For all who have
been conceived in their mother's womb, for street children, for
indigenous peoples and Afro-Americans, for immigrants and refugees
. . . for those who suffer any kind of poverty or
marginalization,'' the pope said, speaking briefly in English,
among other languages he used during the mass.
</P>
<P>
   The pope added, also in English: ``No more violence, terrorism
and drug trafficking. No more torture or other forms of abuse.
There must be an end to the unnecessary recourse to the death
penalty. No more exploitation of the weak, racial discrimination or
ghettos of poverty. Never again.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the pope's visit to Mexico -- before he heads to
St. Louis, Mo., on Tuesday -- is primarily to respond to a bishops'
meeting last year on the future of the church in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   In a written exhortation released Saturday that is the pope's
response to that meeting, the pontiff instructed the church to love
the poor in a ``preferential manner.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the aging Catholic leader said, that love should not be
interpreted as ``exclusive'' of the wealthy or a nation's social
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this evangelization of the leadership sector is neglected,
it should not come as a surprise that many who are part of it will
be guided by criteria alien to the Gospel and at times openly
contrary to it,'' said the pope, who is worried about the spread of
Protestantism and secularism in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is known for his critical view of ``liberation
theology,'' a trend in Latin America in the 1970s and 1980s that
enmeshed clergy in leftist movements -- some armed -- on behalf of
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall of communism, however, the Polish-born pope has
become more vocal in his criticism of capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   In his exhortation, the pope criticizes the spread of a
``neo-liberal'' or free-market system that appears to have ``profit
and law of the markets as its only parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of Mexicans crowded around the Basilica on
Saturday, along the pope's motorcade route and in plazas where they
watched his homily on large television screens. The pontiff is
scheduled to make several more public appearances before his
departure.
</P>
<P>
   He thrilled Mexicans on Saturday by calling on Mexico's
dark-skinned Virgin of Guadalupe to help shape new faith in the
church and social justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Queen of Peace,'' the pontiff said in Spanish, his hands
shaking as he grasped his scepter and read his homily. ``Make all
of us, governments and citizens, learn to live with true freedom,
in accordance with justice and respect for human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Virgin of Guadalupe, so legend goes, appeared to an Aztec
Indian in 1531 and asked that a church be built on the site of
today's Basilica. The sighting of the dark-skinned Virgin helped
fuel the conversion of an entire continent to Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The pope called the Virgin of Guadalupe ``Mother of America''
and declared that Dec. 12 -- the day Mexicans celebrate the Virgin
-- should from now on be celebrated by all Catholics in this
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's announcement prompted cheers around the city.
</P>
<P>
   A joyful Alvaro Ulloa, 19, of Mexico City, said it was only fair
to honor such an enduring symbol of the church in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin has existed for centuries,'' he said, ``and the
pope, well, he might not be here tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Sanchez, a 19-year-old domestic servant, was also among
the adoring crowds who flooded the streets to catch a glimpse of
the pope.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said she defied her employer, who wouldn't give her the
time off to watch the pope on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they fire me, I don't care,'' she said. ``At last I've seen
the pope. He speaks so well and all his words are so sincere. . . .
What I like most about what is said is that the Virgin of Guadalupe
will now be everywhere, not just in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Religion specialist and anthropologist Elio Madferrer said the
pope's decision to make the Virgin of Guadalupe a hemispheric
symbol is an attempt to create a stronger ``macro-identity'' for
Catholics who speak different languages and are devoted to
different religious figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Irish Catholics in the United States are going
to abandon St. Patrick, though,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Theologian Alfonso Vietmeier of Mexico City's Center for
Ecumenical Studies said the pope's remarks in general were a ``very
clear, precise message from the church that it should defend
victims.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the use of the words ``never again'' when referring to
torture will resound in Latin America as an attack on dictatorships
because those same words are slogans against abuses in Guatemala,
Argentina and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's use of English to denounce the death penalty,
Vietmeier said, could be interpreted as a direct jab at the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
