<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S SPECIAL BRAND  

</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ Elton Brand greeted a visitor to Duke University
last week by warmly reaching out to shake hands with his right
hand, which is the size of a baseball mitt. Then Brand wrapped his
left hand over the top of the handshake, creating a baseball mitt
sandwich of sorts. He grinned and offered his official welcome to
Cameron Indoor Stadium, his basketball home. It seemed natural to
smile with him.
</P>
<P>
   It seems equally natural to say that Brand is special. The
adjective is vague for describing perhaps the most ferocious and
best college basketball player in the country, but it is the word
that those who know Brand best frequently use.
</P>
<P>
   Special player. Special person. Special combination of
athleticism and intelligence. A special Brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a special human being,'' said Duke Coach Mike
Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   He is a 6-foot-8-inch, 260-pound giant who is as difficult to
budge as an oak tree once he establishes position near the basket,
yet he is so quick that he routinely beats guards up the court in
transition. He is a 19-year-old sophomore whose oval-shaped face
becomes radiant when he talks about his mother, his stepbrother or
his grandfather. He is special enough to realize that special is
often just another word.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I think when people say I'm special?'' Brand asked.
``It depends whose saying it. If it's people from back home, people
who know what I've been through and know I've made it, then that
means a lot. If others say it, I try not to let it affect me.''
</P>
<P>
   His reaction is smart, because everyone is saying it. From
Peekskill, N.Y., which is Brand's home, to Madison Square Garden
Sunday, which is where second-ranked Duke (18-1) opposes No. 9 St.
John's (16-3). Brand said he played with or against at least six
St. John's players while he was at Peekskill High School or on AAU
teams and, playfully ignoring his own hype, wondered if they might
be astonished by his ascension.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that I can play, but they might be surprised,''
Brand said. ``They might remember me as that player back then and
I'm a totally different player.''
</P>
<P>
   There is strong speculation that Brand will become the first
Duke player with eligibility remaining to leave school for the
National Basketball Association. He would be a lottery pick in the
NBA draft if he decides to enter it. But Brand showed no sign of
tension over such speculation. As he answered a question about his
future, he rocked back and forth in a chair as if he were trying to
decide between pepperoni or sausage on his next slice of pizza. No
pressure, no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need to look that far ahead,'' Brand said of the
possibility he might turn pro. ``I don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he decides he is ready, the NBA will be there for
Brand. Despite playing with a deep and talented team, Brand is
averaging 18.3 points and shooting 65 percent from the field while
also grabbing 9.2 rebounds a game. He is the first brutish pivot
player Krzyzewski has had at Duke, and the Blue Devils' offense
revolves around him. The idea is to get the ball to Brand inside,
where he either overpowers defenders or slithers around them.
</P>
<P>
   Overplay Brand and he will pass to Trajan Langdon (18.3 points a
game) or William Avery (14.9) for smooth jumpers or sweet drives.
Ease off Brand and he will toss up the 12-footer he is honing and
crash with Battier and Chris Carrawell. Beware if Brand perfects
his short jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has given him some special gifts,'' Krzyzewski said. ``He
has a huge body, but he's very much finesse. He has huge hands, he
has long arms. With all his physical skills, if you're going to be
a really, really good player, you have to be intelligent. I think
he's really intelligent. He has a chance to be special.''
</P>
<P>
   There is that word again. So where does this special player
envision playing a year from now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd be back at Duke,'' Brand said. ``I can get more
out of the academics. I'm having a great time in college. My family
is not the richest family, but we're not the poorest either. We're
all right.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
