<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC &LR; - &UR; DUKE-BRAND-2NDTAKE-     01-23 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BC - DUKE-BRAND-2NDTAKE-NYT 
DURHAM, N.C.: all right.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still, Brand said he must weigh his options, and took particular
glee in revealing how he competed against the Charlotte Hornets'
Anthony Mason in pickup games last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I held my own,'' Brand said. ``I more then held my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski talked about how Brand must learn to face the basket
on offense and help out more on defense, but he knows some of the
learning may occur in the pros, where Brand would be smallish as a
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not dependent on Elton to be here for two years or four
years. You know what I mean?'' Krzyzewski said. ``I'm fine. I'm
going to tell him something based on the truth. He understands
that. If that means that he stays here for four years or less, I
will always give him an honest answer about where he's at.''
</P>
<P>
   With caution in his voice, Marty Blake, the NBA's scouting guru,
said: ``I think Brand is a good college player. Hopefully, he'll
stay in school four years and polish up his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand started polishing his game during hoop skirmishes at the
Dunbar Heights apartments in Peekskill, which he recalled as if
they happened eight days ago, not eight years ago. There was a half
court with cracked blacktop, a double rim and a metal chain for a
net, all within 30 seconds of Brand's apartment. Brand was tall and
pudgy as an 11-year-old, so he played with high school kids who
treated him like a tackling dummy. Forget Air Jordans. He needed
shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd foul me real hard on purpose,'' Brand said. ``I didn't
fight it. That's where I got tough. You get banged up playing with
older guys. You want to quit or call a foul, but you don't. You get
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand had a tooth smashed into the roof of his mouth during a
game against Nyack High School as a freshman and desperately needed
a dentist. He left the game for about a minute, somehow pushed the
tooth back in place and wound up scoring 21 points in a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Brand became a Duke hero last season when he returned in just
eight weeks after fracturing a bone in his left foot. The
rehabilitation was supposed to take four months, but the Cameron
Crazies were again hoisting their ``Tickle me, Elton'' and
``Branded for Life'' signs much sooner than expected. Trace it back
to Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I see those guys when I'm home and they'll say,
`Remember, what I used to do to you?''' Brand said. ``I say, `Yeah,
right.' But they're right. They're the reason I'm tough.''
</P>
<P>
   As a single parent with two sons, Daisy Brand worked tirelessly
to make sure that the young Elton was busy when he was not playing
basketball. She checked his homework. She took him to three-hour
church services on Sunday. She signed him up for Boy Scouts. He
lasted about one week. She enrolled him in tae kwon do classes and
he quit. So she sent him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to walk around looking like a karate guy,''
Brand said. ``I almost cried.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother explained: ``I wanted him to know self-defense
because people pick on the bigger kids. I wanted him to be in
balance with his body.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also balance in Brand's life, as a player and a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main motivation is just to be the best,'' said Brand.
``Besides school, I'm concentrating on basketball and I'm going to
push myself to be the best. I don't want anyone to think or to feel
they're better than Elton Brand.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
