<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-COACH-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN SOCCER COACH BEGINS FROM THE GROUND UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Bruce Arena is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JACK BELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Arena, the new coach of the U.S. men's national soccer
team, does not have a rebuilding job ahead of him. It is more like
buying a new house that is a handyman's special. The foundation is
there, but there is much work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of refurbishing needed became obvious last summer at
the World Cup in France, where the overrated and underachieving
U.S. team lost all three of its first-round games and finished last
in the 32-team field.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sampson, whose attempt to integrate younger players into
the team blew up in his face, resigned as coach after the debacle,
and now it is yet another new era for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Arena, 47, who was born and reared in New York, has had success
wherever he has coached: his University of Virginia teams won five
national titles, and his D.C. United club won major-league soccer's
first two championships and this past year captured the Concacaf
Champions Cup and the Interamerican Cup.
</P>
<P>
   For at least the next year, Arena will be the man in the white
lab coat, merrily experimenting with new players and new
combinations. He has directed the national team in one game, a 0-0
draw with Australia, since being named coach in October, but his
debut on the international stage truly begins Sunday when the
United States plays Bolivia in a full international ``friendly''
match in Santa Cruz, Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   Arena's 18-man traveling roster includes some national team
veterans (Tony Meola, Jeff Agoos and Claudio Reyna), but also eight
players who have appeared fewer than five times for the United
States and two who have never played for the senior national team
(goalkeeper Tom Presthus of D.C. United and Imad Bab of the New
England Revolution).
</P>
<P>
   ``The national team program accomplished a lot in the 1990s,''
Arena said recently by telephone from the team's training camp in
Orlando, Fla. ``We were one of only a few countries to have played
in the last three World Cups. But at this point I'm not concerned
totally with results. I am concerned with building a team that is
prepared to qualify for 2002, whether that means by winning games
or by developing a new team. It's about developing a new pool of
players, and with that there needs to be patience.''
</P>
<P>
   That new pool of players is certain to be a fluid one as Arena
prepares for the 2002 World Cup, which will be in Japan and South
Korea. The first regional qualification matches will be played in
November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce told us at our first meeting with him at training camp
that he was going to look at some young guys,'' said Meola, who is
likely to start in goal today in Bolivia. ``We will see a lot of
new faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will face Germany on Feb. 9 in Jacksonville, Fla.,
and Chile on Feb. 21 in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., then play in the
four-nation Nike U.S. Cup '99 in March in Southern California. They
will travel to Mexico this summer for the Confederations Cup, where
they will be grouped with Germany, Brazil and New Zealand in the
first round.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Arena's expansive approach has opened up opportunities for many
players, particularly young Americans who have been gaining
experience in MLS. And he is not shy about selecting players he is
familiar with: Roy Lassiter, Tom Presthus, Eddie Pope, Agoos and
Richie Williams all played for Arena's D.C. United club, and Meola
was the goalkeeper on Arena's first national champion Virginia
team.
</P>
<P>
   Arena has also made some inspired choices, such as Chris Armas,
a rapidly developing midfielder who plays for the Chicago Fire.
Another player in training camp, goalkeeper Zach Thornton (Meola's
former backup on the MetroStars), also shows much promise. An ankle
injury, however, kept Thornton off the traveling team.
</P>
<P>
   Arena has been the beneficiary of the winter break in some
European leagues and was able to put Reyna (VfL Wolfsburg in
Germany), Gregg Berhalter (Cambuur Leeuwarden in the Netherlands)
and Jovan Kirovski (Fortuna Cologne in Germany) on the roster for
the Bolivia game. Another young American playing in the
Netherlands, the attacking midfielder John O'Brien (F.C. Utrecht),
was picked for the training-camp roster but missed the sessions
because of a badly injured toe.
</P>
<P>
   Some other Americans playing overseas, including Kasey Keller
and Brad Freidel in England, were unavailable, and some were not
picked by Arena (such as Frankie Hedjuk of Bayer Leverkusen). That
is a situation that Arena (and all national team coaches) will have
to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we need new blood,'' Arena said. ``The decisions are
tough and it's not like coaching a club team, because when you're
the national team coach you need to look at a four-year cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to tell the players that it's an honor to play for
the national team and get away from all the other stuff. It's great
to be able to play soccer and make money, but this is something
different. It's shouldn't be about the money.''
</P>
<P>
   By the ``other stuff,'' Arena meant the meltdown in France of an
American team stocked with players who helped MLS get off the
ground and who were promoted more, perhaps, for their colorful
personalities than for their skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things would never get to that point with Bruce,'' Meola said.
``Bruce lets everyone know where they stand every single day. There
are no secrets with Bruce. He will just put the best 11 on the
field and have his next-best 11 on the bench. There will be nothing
else involved with his decision. I've always known him as the kind
of guy who gets the most out of his players.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, Arena has carte blanche from the U.S. Soccer
Federation to recast the national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last two World Cups all the international experience
has gone through a small group of players, which is good and bad,''
he said. ``If there was ever a time we can step away from those
players, it's now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
