<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COLUMN-SCORING-96     01-23 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COLUMN-SCORING-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S GETTING HARDER TO SCORE IN THE NHL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When North America plays the World in the National Hockey League
All-Star Game on Sunday in Tampa, Fla., the two high-powered teams
might combine for 15 goals, the way they did last season. They
might even score 22 goals, as they did in 1993, the most ever. Even
with Dominik Hasek of Buffalo starting in goal for the World, a
shutout _ even for one period _ is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But the expected goalfest will be a stark counterpoint to the
real games. Despite rules altered last summer to help the offenses,
NHL goal-scoring is down slightly from last season and down
significantly from earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The winter of 1999 is a chilly time of great goalies,
sophisticated neutral-zone traps and institutionalized obstruction
techniques executed by bigger, faster, more skillful players who
skate on sheets of ice that have stayed the same size.
</P>
<P>
   Compare and contrast: In 1981-82, Wayne Gretzky led the league
with 92 goals and 212 points. Last season, nobody scored more than
52 goals or 102 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different era,'' said Steve Yzerman, a 16-season
veteran who is captain of the Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red
Wings, and who will miss the All-Star game because of a facial
injury. ``There is more emphasis on keeping the puck out of our
net, being good defensively, and strong goaltending. A lot of
goaltenders are in the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Hasek, the goalies in the All-Star spotlight are
Nikolai Khabibulin of Phoenix, Arturs Irbe of Carolina, Ed Belfour
of Dallas, Martin Brodeur of the Devils and Ron Tugnutt of Ottawa,
who has replaced the injured Curtis Joseph of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   With more than half the regular schedule completed, NHL teams
are combining for an average of 5.2 goals a game. Last season ended
at 5.3 goals a game, the lowest since 1955-56, when it was 5.1. As
recently as 1992-93, the average NHL game had 7.2 goals. And in
1981-82, Gretzky's greatest season, the average was 8.3.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, there were 160 shutouts, the most ever. So far this
season, there have been 95, 10 more than at this point last season.
Hasek leads the league with eight, on pace to break his career best
of 13 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Should anything be done? Perhaps, suggested Brian Leetch of the
New York Rangers, teams should play with three skaters against
three, instead of five against five. He was speaking with tongue in
cheek, and a bit ruefully. His team had just lost its second
consecutive game by a 2-1 score. Leetch, one of the game's best
attacking defensemen, has not scored for 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really explain goal-scoring,'' said Leetch, captain of
a team with three goals in its last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned with dwindling scores and the perception of lessened
entertainment value, the league last summer changed several rules
in an effort to help offenses. The goal nets were moved out from
the backboards, from 11 feet to 13 feet, to give shooters more
space and better passing angles around the cages. The sides of the
goal creases were shaved, reducing the area that is forbidden to
attackers and lessening the chances of goals being disallowed after
video review.
</P>
<P>
   For 25 percent of the games, the league is using two referees
instead of one in the belief that restraining fouls will be
discouraged. And the size of goalie equipment is being more
strictly monitored. Still, at least one goalie is among the three
stars of most games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the goaltenders of our day are so good and
the defensemen are faster than ever,'' said Luc Robitaille, who
leads the Los Angeles Kings with 25 goals and has scored more than
500 in his career. ``The other thing is, as soon as teams are up by
a goal or two, they play the trap.''
</P>
<P>
   In the trap formation, the players on defense wait back between
the blue lines for attackers to come to them. Then the defending
team swarms the area, cutting off passing lanes, frustrating the
puck carriers and creating turnovers that trigger counter-rushes.
The New Jersey Devils perfected the system while winning the
Stanley Cup in 1995. Among the teams successfully employing the
style now are the Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   What else can be done to combat the trap and encourage
aggressive attacks? Some suggest that the center red line be
ignored for offsides rulings, as it is in college hockey, to allow
longer passes over two lines. Now even a 10-yard forward pass is
illegal if it begins behind the blue line and ends over the center
red line.
</P>
<P>
   But others, including some in powerful positions, suggest
leaving things the way they are. One is Commissioner Gary Bettman,
who predicted ``a swing back up'' in goal scoring as players get
accustomed to the new rules. ``The new rules have been terrific and
the flow of the games has been great,'' he said. ``I don't think we
are looking at any more specific rule changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said the new rules have encouraged more forechecking,
with attacking teams venturing deeper into opposing territory. He
said games are closer now than they used to be, with more decided
by one goal. ``We have less 8-1 or 9-2 games,'' Bettman said. The
games are also taking less time, down seven minutes this season to
2 hours 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richter, the Ranger goalie, said the use of two referees
discouraged interference behind the play. Paul Kariya, the Anaheim
sniper, said more room behind the net was helping the power plays.
But both he and his teammate Teemu Selanne said that taking that
space away from the neutral zone, between the blue lines, hurt
teams that wanted to build speed on the rush in the middle of the
rink.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his suggestion to improve the game, Kariya said, ``I'd
tell the league that if they want to open up scoring, they should
open up the neutral zone.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who leads the NHL with 61 points, 20 of them goals,
played in college at Maine and is used to the red line being
ignored for offsides passing. Another player with a college
background is Chicago's Tony Amonte, fourth in the league with 24
goals. He supports the disappearance of the red line for offsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in favor of that for sure,'' he said. ``I'd love to see
that changed. That one rule would totally eliminate the trap. The
trap doesn't work without a red line. I think that's a great way to
get some more offense. I don't know if they are going to do that,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely, according to Bob Clarke, the Philadelphia
general manager, who is influential among his colleagues when they
recommend rules changes to the Board of Governors. In recent years,
Clarke has urged elimination of the red line for offsides, and the
league experimented with it during a few exhibition games last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see it tried,'' Clarke said. ``I don't think it
can be implemented without good players using it for a while.''
Asked about support for the idea, he sighed and said: ``I don't
think there is a lot. I think I am in a minority.''
</P>
<P>
   In the majority is the Devils' general manager, Lou Lamoriello,
who coached at Providence College and knows the rule well. ``It
won't help anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a school of thought in hockey that low scores
don't necessarily mean bad games. Goals per game averaged from 4.8
to 5.4 from 1952-1957, during the six-team era some recall as the
NHL's golden age. Richter, the Ranger goalie, noted that some of
the best moments of a 2-1 loss to Ottawa last week came when teams
exchanged odd-man rushes without scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were going crazy,'' he said of the audience in New
York's Madison Square Garden. ``As a player, you love to be in
that, a one-goal game, back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gainey, general manager of the Dallas Stars, made the same
point. Although his team has the league's best record, he said two
of its most exciting games this season were a 1-0 loss to Calgary
and a 2-0 loss to Vancouver. ``They were well-played,'' Gainey
said, ``and the goalies were good.''
</P>
<P>
   And the goalies in those games were not even among the elite.
The best is Buffalo's Hasek, who has won the Hart trophy the last
two seasons as the league's most valuable player. Darcy Regier, the
Sabres' general manager, said that Hasek ``is on the cutting edge''
and that other goalies are imitating his style of dropping the
stick and using both hands to glove loose pucks.
</P>
<P>
   Regier said the great goalie era took hold in the late 1980s,
when Patrick Roy, now with the Colorado Avalanche, led the Montreal
Canadiens to the Stanley Cup, prompting the best young athletes in
French-speaking Canada to choose his position _ players like the
Devils' Brodeur and the Rangers' Dan Cloutier. Brodeur said the
goalie used to be the kid who skated poorly, but no longer.
</P>
<P>
   Regier said, ``I would pay to see a goalie like Dominik Hasek.''
But, when asked if a great save was as exciting as a great goal, he
replied: ``Is a great save as exciting as seeing an end-to-end rush
by Pavel Bure? I guess, probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bure, a speedy, opportunistic attacker with tricky moves and a
great shot, rejoined the league last week after forcing a trade
from the Vancouver Canucks to the Florida Panthers. He scored three
goals in his first two games, including one on a breakaway against
Richter in a victory over the Rangers on Thursday night. Even
Richter was impressed. ``I want to see guys make a play like Pavel
Bure, come across the line, get that breakaway pass,'' Richter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Irbe, the Latvian goalie playing for Carolina and for the World
All-Stars, said the new rules had made goalie equipment smaller,
but it was still so protective that goalies felt confident blocking
even the hardest shots. He said goalies work out harder than they
used to. Although new rules give better flow to the games, Irbe
said that goal-scoring ``comes and goes like fashion'' in clothing
styles, as hard to alter as an ocean wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it has gone away,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
