</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-ABORTION-WAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ONE CASUALTY IN ABORTION'S GUERRILLA WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Melinda DuBois has had recurring dreams about
Dr. Barnett Slepian, the slain mainstay of the abortion clinic she
helps run _ dreams in which he is very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   In one dream, the slight, unassuming doctor had fled to Canada
and had sent her an indistinct e-mail message. In another, the two
are chatting and she says to him, ``How weird it is that you're not
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But these are just dreams, for it is clear not only in her
waking mind but also by the repeated crises of staffing at her
clinic, Buffalo GYN Womenservices, that Slepian has been dead for
three months now. In recent weeks, when 60 inches of snow buried
Buffalo and its airport, the clinic has had to scramble to bring in
one of the handful of out-of-town doctors who have volunteered to
take his place.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after Slepian's murder on Oct. 23, four workers _ a
fourth of the clinic's staff _ quit, with some saying their
families could no longer endure the threat of violence and others
explaining they were simply too overwrought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very close to Dr. Slepian, and they couldn't deal with
the fact that he wasn't going to be here,'' said Ms. DuBois, the
assistant director of the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Making sure there is a competent staff in place every day is
crucial since the clinic's poor and working-class patients cannot
wait long. The clinic performs abortions only up to the 19th week
of pregnancy. Marilynn Buckham, the clinic's executive director,
said that not all the volunteer doctors have been capable or
congenial. ``We've had the good, the bad and the ugly here,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been catastrophic in many ways,'' said Ms. Buckham, who
also has been haunted by Slepian's death. ``I've had to work here
nonstop since he was shot, trying to qualify physicians, flying
them in, wondering how good they are and how responsible. It's been
a nightmare, an absolute nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Most ominous of all, perhaps, is that the names of Ms. Buckham
and Ms. DuBois have been added to an Internet site known as the
Nuremberg Files that lists abortion providers as if they were
wanted fugitives. Slepian's name was on that list, and ad a line
was crossed through it the day after he was slain.
</P>
<P>
   So worried is Ms. Buckham about her colleagues' safety that she
will not disclose the number of doctors who work with her or where
they come from.
</P>
<P>
   There are two things about the clinic that have not changed
much. One is the daily clutch of sidewalk demonstrators who shout
exhortations at the women who enter. On Tuesday, four demonstrators
with bluntly worded signs draped around their hooded parkas were
pacing among the snow ranges of Main Street even though a freezing
wind was biting into them at 35 miles an hour and they had to stamp
their feet to keep warm. One protester, Hetty Pasco, is 73.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please let your baby live,'' screamed Mrs. Pasco, at a car
pulling into the clinic driveway. ``Don't kill your baby. In the
name of Jesus Christ, let your baby live.''
</P>
<P>
   The other thing that has not changed is the crowd in the clinic
waiting room, because Slepian's death has not curtailed the demand
for abortions. At any time, the room is filled with a dozen women,
white and black and mostly young, who wait with their boyfriends or
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Some prattle nervously as if they were about to undergo a
procedure no more momentous than filling a cavity. Others wring
their hands in what seems like intense inner agony. Every once in a
while a nurse opens the door and calls out the first name of a
young woman, who stands, often with an embarrassed grin since
everyone in the room knows what she is here for.
</P>
<P>
   Slepian, who was not a crusader but asked only to be allowed to
perform the full spectrum of gynecological procedures, was shot by
a sniper firing from behind the Slepians' home in suburban Amherst.
The 52-year-old doctor bled to death on the kitchen floor in front
of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has issued a warrant for the arrest as a ``material
witness'' of James Kopp, a 44-year-old anti-abortion soldier who
has spent recent years wandering the country from demonstration to
demonstration and, taking the nickname ``Atomic Dog,'' growing
increasingly militant.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that seems to have drained out of the clinic is the
gallows humor. Glenn Edward Murray, a friend of Slepian and the
lawyer for the Slepian family and the clinic, remembered how in
July he helped Slepian draft his will in the family's kitchen. At
one point, Slepian turned to his wife, Lynne, and with mock bravado
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``They take me out and it's all yours.''
</P>
<P>
   As his mind recaptured the picture of his friend, Murray smiled,
his eyes moist.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Slepian has busied herself trying to sell Slepian's
private practice, earn income as a civilian escort for female
suspects arrested by the Amherst police, and maintain as much
normality as possible by chauffeuring her four sons to their
after-school practices (a job Slepian used to help with).
</P>
<P>
   ``She puts up a good front,'' said Ellen Fink, a close friend.
``When she's out in public, she's amazing. I'm sure she does a lot
of emotional release when nobody is around.''
</P>
<P>
   What rankles the community that once surrounded Slepian is that
the enemies of abortion are slowly achieving through the bullet
what they could not through political means. GYN Womenservices is
the only clinic left in this city of 350,000 and now it has again
become the focus of abortion opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a national group, Operation Rescue, is planning a
reprise of two-week protests it held outside Buffalo clinics in
1992. The rallies, called the Spring of Life, led to 600 arrests
and stirred up those abortion antagonists who see their movement as
something of a guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can eliminate access, with rare exceptions, there will
be no safe and legal abortion in Buffalo,'' Murray said. ``The
affluent will go elsewhere. The indigent will face the choice of
having an unwanted child or an abortion that is self-induced or
amateurish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
