<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCK-CLUB-REVIVE-450&AMP;     01-23 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-CLUB-REVIVE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 AN EFFORT TO BRING THE STONE PONY IN NEW JERSEY BACK TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASBURY PARK, N.J. _ It was home to Bruce Springsteen, Jon Bon
Jovi and Southside Johnny, not to mention an album's worth of
not-so-famous Garden State Tchaikovskys, but the only sound at the
Stone Pony these days is the solemn bass line of the ocean breakers
slapping at the nearby shore.
</P>
<P>
   After serving more than 20 years as the mecca of New Jersey
rock-and-roll, the legendary bar went out of business in September.
And as if silence were not the ultimate affront, the club that gave
birth to the rude guitar riffs of Bruce Springsteen's ``Hungry
Heart'' and ``Born to Run'' was instantly reopened as a swanky
disco called Vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, a new round of musical chairs has started. A few
months ago, Vinyl, too, closed, and a move is now afoot to bring
the old Stone Pony back to life. Led by one of the nightclub's
former booking agents, a group of investors is discussing a plan to
buy the shuttered building and restore live rock-and-roll acts to
its darkened stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring the tradition back and continue as a rock
club,'' said Kyle Brendle, a booking agent who is leading the
effort. ``We might try to put up a variety of shows, but even if we
do, there will definitely only be a single dance night.''
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, the Stone Pony was the one place that garage
bands and basement rockers across New Jersey dreamed of playing. It
was gritty. It hung with folds of week-old cigarette smoke. It drew
a crowd of hundreds every weekend for shows by national and local
acts.
</P>
<P>
   But fans no longer drop in for a shot of bourbon or a
Springsteen cover tune. The building's windows have been painted
black, and its ``WE ARE OPEN'' sign has been reduced to a cheerless
jumble that reads ``AR OPE.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendle has drawn support from several investors, including
former workers at the bar, and expects to raise enough money to
bring the Stone Pony back to a semblance of its former self.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a weird way, the failure of the last project may lead to
the club being brought back to something decent,'' he said. ``The
possibility is real. I mean, the building is sitting there
completely empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Springsteen legend surrounding the club, most
musicians said they doubted that Brendle would succeed in reviving
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could actually resurrect the two former owners, they
might be able to bring back the old days,'' Lee Mrowicki, the Stone
Pony's manager and disk jocky from 1978 to 1991, said. The club's
original owners, Butch Pielka and Jack Roig, declared bankruptcy in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that would be hard to do these days,'' Mrowicki continued.
``People are older. I mean, I have a wife and kids. Springsteen has
three kids. Look, we really don't go out much anymore.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asbury Park has long been famous for its journeyman musicians,
hard-working rock-and-rollers who produced an earnest, bluesy type
of music that perfectly matched the noisy, summertime rhythms of
the local boardwalk. When the Stone Pony first opened here in 1974,
it was no more than another roadhouse in a town that teemed with
jukebox bars. But within three years, the club became ground zero
for a blend of rhythm and blues and denim-jacket rock that was
known as the Jersey Shore sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asbury Park is surrounded by the Atlantic and two lakes, so
it's kind of an island unto itself,'' said Mrowicki, who was the
Stone Pony's manager and disk jockey from 1978 to 1991. ``Back in
the day, New York had punk. Philly had the disco stuff. But we were
more interested in R &AMP; B, soul, funk and reggae.''
</P>
<P>
   As the years went by, the city degenerated from a vibrant shore
community to a blighted stretch of beachfront plots, and the Stone
Pony suffered with it. When the bar's original owners, Pielka and
Roig, declared bankruptcy Mrowicki tried to buy the club. He lost
his bid to a local businessman named Steven Nasar, who retained the
tavern's name while trying to drum up business by introducing a
vastly different style of music.
</P>
<P>
   When that, too, failed, said Brendle, Nasar tried his hand at
Vinyl, a dance lounge with dim lights and a full-time disk jockey
that tried to attract a Manhattanesque martini scene. It closed so
quickly, Brendle and others said, because the vision of the club
went against the rock-and-roll heritage of Asbury Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would come from all over Europe, Japan to see the Stone
Pony,'' said Louie Appel, a drummer for a band called John Eddie
that started playing at the club in 1976. ``For a bar owner to take
the Stone Pony with all its history and change it into a dance
club? How stupid is that?''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the strangeness of Vinyl's momentary presence on the
music scene is that Nasar has not been seen by anyone who used to
work at the dance club since it closed last fall, and despite
several attempts, he could not be reached by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Though Brendle, who managed the Stone Pony for Nasar, said he
was perplexed by his former boss' disappearance, he said that he
would rather concentrate on overcoming the obstacles to reopening
the club.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest seems to be attracting a core following that has
aged over the years. Instead of the flocks of Springsteen fans in
tight blue jeans and biker jackets who packed the nightclub's
concrete floor in the late 1970s, the crowd a decade later was
somewhat more sedate in their baseball caps and flannel shirts,
musicians said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd look out and mostly see people in their 30s who may have
listened to Springsteen in high school but were still going out to
bars because they weren't married yet,'' said Mike Stanzilis, a
bass player who started performing at the club in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
