<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX LOGO DIMS ESPN AMERICA'S CUP DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an America's Cup outcome quite easy to imagine: the New
York Yacht Club's sailing syndicate prevails against 14 other
challengers in the cup trials. Its sailboat ends up racing New
Zealand's defender next February in a match for yachting's oldest
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN, the sports cable network, broadcasts the ocean races for
U.S. television from Auckland, New Zealand. The camera lens fills
the screen with a view of the two 75-foot yachts and their
billowing sails: Team New Zealand and New York's Young America.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong with this pretty picture?
</P>
<P>
   A lot, if you're a producer for ESPN. That's because the New
York boat's hull and sails are plastered with huge logos of Fox
Sports Net. The division of Fox Television surfaced last week as
Young America's biggest cash sponsor. The network also happens to
be ESPN's most serious cable competitor worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has set itself up as a thorn that won't be easily plucked
from ESPN's side. The deal has also angered sailors, who blame the
New York Yacht Club for jeopardizing television rights, which
ultimately pay for the America's Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking the high ground,'' John Kolius, skipper for the
Aloha Syndicate of Hawaii said. ``We're all in sponsor hell. But we
decided that asking Fox for money was not where we wanted to go.''
</P>
<P>
   New York organizers, on the other hand, don't see it as a
compromise. ``Fox will not be doing any broadcasting that will be
poaching on what ESPN is doing,'' said John Marshall, president of
the Young America team. ``It's in ESPN's best interest to have an
event sponsored by companies that step forward with good
communication skills, and are activists in promoting the America's
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN could pull out of its television deal in protest. Its
agreement is not yet signed. ``This is obviously a serious
situation and we're in the process of reviewing all our options,''
Geoffrey Mason, executive producer of ESPN's America's Cup
coverage, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Barry Frank, the agent for America's Cup
television rights, that probably won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fox sponsorship certainly doesn't make our task any
easier,'' said Frank, senior group vice president for International
Management Group, the sports marketing firm that negotiated ESPN's
$4 million America's Cup cable contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox hasn't done anything to break any rules or regulations,''
Frank said. ``But will there be a rule against this happening in
the future? Probably. This is a classic case of ambush marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the hardball side of television sport, the push to gain as
much exposure as possible out of a single event. But when it comes
to the actual programming, the effort by one cable network to gain
name recognition for coverage of an event ends up, more often than
not, becoming a trade-off with another network.
</P>
<P>
   A sideboard at an ice hockey rink carries ESPN signs, but the
event is sometimes telecast on Fox. On the flip side, a baseball
game involving the Los Angeles Dodgers, a team owned by Fox, plays
on an ESPN telecast.
</P>
<P>
   The America's Cup format, however, is different. ESPN faces a
three-hour race with one or two yachts often filling the screen for
long periods, sail logos and all. ``I don't think ESPN will be
exactly rooting for Young America,'' Frank said in understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Wladika, a senior vice president at Fox Sports, disagrees.
``I fail to see why ESPN would be bent out of shape,'' Wladika said
last week. ``This kind of thing happens every day on sports
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox was apparently interested in the 80 hours of U.S. television
rights that ESPN negotiated, but saw it as too costly a deal.
Wladika calls it a ``pre-emptive $4 million,'' referring to the
figure ESPN agreed to pay.
</P>
<P>
   For ESPN, the America's Cup package is a matter of pride. The
network has a longstanding relationship with the event. Since its
first involvement in the 1983 competition off Newport, R.I., the
cable channel has enhanced its coverage with on-board cameras,
television graphics, and spectacular distance shots.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who tuned into the late-night coverage of the 1986-87
races feasted on up-close-and-personal America's Cup coverage in
the turquoise waters off Fremantle, Australia. It was the first
time in a century of cup matches that anyone on shore had had such
a bird's eye view of the action.
</P>
<P>
   But America's Cup for ESPN tends to be more of a signature piece
nurtured by in-house interest than a cash cow producing sizable
revenues. ``I think they consider it one of the seminal events in
their history,'' Frank said. ``When Dennis Conner won the cup off
Australia, people were staying up until 2 a.m. all over the country
watching.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
