<HEADER>
A5684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-HOTEL-SELLOFF-7     01-23 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-HOTEL-SELLOFF-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING ASIAN COMPANIES UNLOAD THEIR HOTELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Hawaii, Ill., Mass., N.Y., CANADA)  (js) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Japan Airlines bought the Essex House, a grand Art
Deco hotel on Central Park South, 15 years ago and turned it into a
flagship for its Nikko hotel chain in a city where real estate
always seems like a good bet for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the airline is struggling with declining profits in a
turbulent Asian economy, it is selling the Essex House to a U.S.
company, Strategic Hotel Capital, for about $250 million, real
estate executives say. Eight blocks away, the Lai Sun Group of Hong
Kong is selling the luxurious Four Seasons Hotel, as well as the
Regent Beverly Wilshire Hotel in Los Angeles, for similar reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Asian companies that have poured billions of dollars
into U.S. real estate, particularly trophy hotels in New York,
California and Hawaii, are now selling out. With the hotel market
booming in the United States, some foreign companies are making
huge profits. Others, like Japan Airlines, are breaking even, or
even losing money. But there is no question that the Asian shopping
spree is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Asian companies are trying to liquidate assets and
convert them to cash because of problems at home,'' said Arthur
Adler, a partner at Sonnenblick-Goldman Co., a real estate
investment bank. ``And the timing's not bad, because there's a
feeling that the market is peaking.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of buyers. At the Essex House auction,
Laurence S. Geller, chairman of Strategic Hotel Capital, which owns
26 hotels including the Marriott East Side in Manhattan and the
Ritz-Carlton Laguna Niguel in California, had to fend off rivals
like Marriott, Intercontinental Hotels and the Blackstone Group's
Savoy Hotels. Strategic signed a contract earlier this month to buy
the Essex House and is set to close the deal in late February or
March.
</P>
<P>
   Geller said Strategic would be spending money to ``upgrade the
hotel and position it at a higher level than it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Essex House will be one of our flagship hotels in the
United States,'' he said Friday. ``We believe that lodging in
Manhattan is rock solid. It's one of the few great world tourist
destinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts say that the market for hotels reached a high
point last summer, but that hotels will remain very profitable in
cities like New York because business remains so strong. Even
without the latest round of hotel sales, room rates have been
rising swiftly. During most of the year, it is almost impossible to
find an available room in New York City. As a result, the average
room rate in Manhattan has jumped 36.9 percent to $213.83 since
January 1996, according to PKF Consulting, a hotel consulting
company. And rates are expected to rise 7 percent this year in New
York, and 5 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see an increase in room rates in 1999, but it's a factor
of demand, not the purchase price of the hotel,'' said John Fox, a
principal at PKF Consulting. ``The profits in this industry are
still very good.''
</P>
<P>
   The sales mark the end of what was actually the second wave of
Asian investment in U.S. real estate. Between 1985 and 1992,
Japanese companies spent $77 billion on real estate in the United
States, buying everything from the former Exxon Building to
Rockefeller Center. No price was too high for the Japanese, who
were confident of the long-term value of the office buildings,
hotels, golf courses and shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   But they took a beating during the recession in the early 1990s.
Since 1992, the Japanese have sold about one-third of those
properties for a little more than half the original purchase
prices, according to the E&AMP;Y Kenneth Leventhal Real Estate Group.
</P>
<P>
   As the Japanese retreated, a second wave of investors from Hong
Kong, Singapore, Indonesia, Taiwan, Brunei and South Korea swept
into the United States between 1993 and 1996, snapping up $6.3
billion worth of real estate, most of it hotels, at bargain prices.
But even as real estate prices started skyrocketing in New York and
California in 1997, the Asian economy began falling apart. Faced
with steep debts and falling sales at home, many of the new
investors decided to sell at what turned out to be the top of the
market in the United States. During the first six months of 1998,
Asians bought only $160 million worth of real estate, but sold
nearly $1 billion worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike the Japanese who made long-term investments in prestige
properties, the Asians were opportunistic,'' said Dale Strickland,
a senior manager at E&AMP;Y Kenneth Leventhal, in Los Angeles. ``We
didn't expect them to hold onto it. But the problems in Asia are
probably accelerating the sell-off.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   According to hotel and real estate executives who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, Strategic is betting that it can raise room
rates at the 597-room Essex House and take advantage of a better
reservations system. Strategic, in turn, has hired Westin hotels to
manage the Essex House. Westin, which is owned by Starwood Hotels
and Resorts, already runs the nearby Westin Central Park South.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Airlines had lots of company on its trip to the auction
block.
</P>
<P>
   Taisei Corp. of Japan sold the Sheraton Grande Torrey Pines in
La Jolla, Calif., last month for $82.5 million to Hilton Hotels,
which promptly renamed it the Hilton La Jolla Torrey Pines.
</P>
<P>
   A troubled Hong Kong company, Paliburg Holdings Ltd., is selling
its stake in Regal Hotels, a chain that has 13 properties in the
United States and Canada, including the U.N. Plaza in New York, the
Biltmore in Los Angeles, the Knickerbocker in Chicago and the Regal
Bostonian in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a company controlled by Ong Beng Seng, the Singapore
billionaire, sold its 40 percent stake in the Pennsylvania Hotel,
across Seventh Avenue from Madison Square Garden. And Sinar Mas
Group, the second-largest conglomerate in Indonesia, sold a real
estate portfolio that included the Pasadena Hilton in California
and the Melrose Hotel in Dallas to pay off mounting debts.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Nippon Life Insurance Co. is close to selling
the Century Plaza Hotel and Tower, the luxury hotel that was known
as the Western White House when President Ronald Reagan was a
frequent guest.
</P>
<P>
   The Lai Sun Group will reap the benefits of the boom in recent
years. The company paid $190 million two years ago for the Four
Seasons Hotel on East 57th Street, one of the most lavish hotels in
the world, and is now selling it for about $260 million, a
relatively quick profit of $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Airlines is not so lucky. The company bought the Essex
House in 1985 for $190 million, closed it for two years and spent
$100 million more on renovations. The rooms at the Essex House are
usually full, and it has two highly rated restaurants, but the
hotel has never been an economic powerhouse for the airline,
according to hotel executives. Under pressure in Japan, the company
is now being forced to sell many of its hotels and resorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Essex House is a large hotel in a prime location,'' said
Fox, of PKF Consulting. ``It's a significant addition to anybody's
roster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
