</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUIT-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Leary pads running game with commitments
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary closed the week with
commitments from a pair of running backs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets got commitments from William Glover of
Tampa's Jesuit High and Jermaine Hatch of Cathoic High in Baton
Rouge, La. Georgia Tech, which also got linebacker Ather Brown of
Jones County this week, now has 25 commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Glover, a 5-foot-10, 190-pounder, rushed for 1,585 yards and 20
touchdowns as a senior, adding 38 receptions for 520 yards and
seven scores. Glover also was recruited by Michigan, LSU and Miami.
Hatch, a 6-2, 190-pounder, missed his junior season because of a
knee injury, but he recovered to draw interest from Northwestern,
Miami and Memphis as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets are down to a handful of prized prospects,
including quarterback Willie Simmons of Quincy, Fla., wideout
DeAndre Green of Prichard, Ala., offensive lineman Alex Jackson of
Quincy, Fla., and linebacker Recardo Wimbush of Blakely, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Watson switches
</P>
<P>
   Running back Derek Watson, South Carolina's Mr. Football, has
jilted new Gamecocks coach Lou Holtz for national champion
Tennessee. Watson, a 6-foot-1, 205-pounder from Williamston's
Palmetto High, committed to South Carolina earlier this month.
After taking an unofficial visit to Knoxville last week, however,
Watson committed to Vols coach Phillip Fulmer late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who rushed for 2,573 yards and 44 touchdowns as a
senior, is the third highly regarded recruit from South Carolina to
choose the Vols. Defensive linemen Albert Haynesworth and Terriea
Smalls also committed to Tennessee. Two others, wideout Durrell
Robinson of Duncan and offensive lineman Kevin Breedlove of
Clemson, have narrowed their lists to Georgia and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer also pulled off the unthinkable Friday _ grabbing a top
prospect out of FSU coach Bobby Bowden's backyard. Defensive end
Constantin Ritzmann of Tallahassee's North Florida Christian High,
a first-year foreign exchange student from Berlin, Germany, chose
the Vols over the Seminoles. Ritzmann, dubbed ``The Germanator'' by
teammates, had a school-record 26 sacks and 150 tackles in 14 games
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
