<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-MEETING-0124-COX     01-23 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-MEETING-0124-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OLYMPIC OFFICIALS STRUGGLE WITH FATE OF NEXT TWO HOST CITIES IN
LIGHT OF SCANDAL REVELATIONS
 &HT;    With IOC-SAMARANCH-0124.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The push to investigate allegations of
corruption in previous Olympic bids lost momentum Saturday as
Olympic officials struggled to cope with the expanding scandal
involving the next two host cities.
</P>
<P>
   Top Olympics officials, who came here this weekend hoping to get
a handle on the Salt Lake City scandal, now are being consumed by
revelations that Sydney bidders may have bought the votes of IOC
members to win the right to host the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need to go back into previous bids now,''
said Kevan Gosper, the senior IOC member from Australia and a
member of the committee's executive board. ``There's no real point
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   IOC officials say they will investigate any evidence of
wrongdoing related to previous Games, but they say none has been
brought to them. And for now, the beleaguered committee has its
hands full with the largest scandal in Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the IOC executive board is expected to discuss the
Sydney bid to determine whether a special investigative commission
should be formed to assess the new information.
</P>
<P>
   An Australia Olympics official on Friday admitted he offered
$70,000 in inducements to two African IOC members the night before
Sydney won the 2000 Games by two votes. John Coates, the president
of the Australian Olympic Committee, said that he offered $35,000
each to the National Olympic Committees of Kenya and Uganda through
their respective IOC members, Charles Mukora and Francis Nyangweso.
</P>
<P>
   Coates, one of the leaders of the Sydney bid, said he offered
the money in the hope that it would help persuade the IOC members
to vote for Sydney. ``I thought it was necessary for us to show our
commitment to those NOCs with a view to winning those votes,''
Coates said. ``My view was that it might encourage them to consider
their votes for Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Saturday, Gosper defended Coates' actions,
saying he was only working aggressively to secure the votes he
needed until the last minute. Sydney won the Games in 1993 by
narrowly defeating closest rival Beijing by a 45-43 vote on the
final ballot the day after Coates made the offer. Because the vote
is taken in a secret ballot, it is impossible to determine how the
members actually voted.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper said the inducements were an extension of a legitimate
assistance program for African athletes. Even though the money was
offered contingent on Sydney's winning the IOC vote, Gosper denied
that Coates' actions amounted to vote buying.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gosper had said that he was concerned that Coates had
apparently offered the inducements to buy votes and raised the
prospect of demands to strip the Games from Sydney. However, on
Saturday he said his view was changed after he spoke to Coates
personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in position with more information to clarify what
happened,'' Gosper said. ``I have no reason to believe that was
bribery.''
</P>
<P>
   Under tight security at IOC headquarters on the banks of Lake
Geneva, six IOC members accused in the Salt Lake City scandal
appeared before a special investigative panel to respond to
allegations that they acted improperly in the bid for the 2002
Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Uniformed security guards and barriers kept back scores of
reporters, while IOC members were driven into an underground
parking lot or entered the building through a private entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen IOC members have been implicated over cash payments,
scholarships, free medical care and other favors accepted from Salt
Lake bidders. Two have resigned and five have submitted written
responses to the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The special commission, led by Canadian IOC member Dick Pound,
worked late into the night Saturday. IOC Director General Francois
Carrard cancelled a scheduled appearance at an evening news
briefing as the deliberations continued.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is to make its final report to the executive
board on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch said as many as seven
others face the possibility of expulsion. The full IOC will hold a
special session in March to address the scandal and perhaps expel
any of the accused members who refuse to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day,'' said Jacques Rogge, a Belgian member of
the inquiry panel. ``There are cases among them that are just
unacceptable, brutal corruption, when simply money was asked for.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive board member Chiharu Igaya, a member from Japan,
called for strong measures against his accused colleagues.
``President Samaranch should clean the house, that's the first and
most important thing he should do.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
