<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU _ JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
abruptly fired his defense minister Saturday, following growing
rumors that his former ally was planning to run against Netanyahu
for prime minister. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POPE _ MEXICO CITY _ Spot coverage of Pope John Paul II's
first full day in Mexico. Developing. (Ferriss, Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   w/POPE _ Pope John Paul II comes to the Midwest as the American
Catholic Church and its 61 million members struggle harder than
ever to evangelize Generation Y and to hold on to young people who
have grown up in the church but drifted. Priest shortages are
rampant and the number choosing religious life dwindles. Crowds of
youth will come to see the pope, but dismiss his moral mandates. As
the aged pope nears the end of his papacy, the future of the church
lies in their hands. Will they accept church law which Jean Paul
has declared ``immutable'' on issues such as celibacy of priests,
birth control, abortion, homosexuality, and women in the pulpit? A
contrasting of their views with older Catholics. (Lyles, Dayton
Daily News). 30-35. MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-REPORT _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The IOC completes its
report on the bribery scandal in Salt Lake, and the ethics panel
meets with as many as 13 members accused of irregularities. Many of
them face expulsion at a future meeting (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) general and (s) sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Atlanta out.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-VICTIMS _ BEIJING _ When Chen Linna was a 14-year-old
schoolgirl, she had a recurrent dream: should she kill her father
after a wall poster declared him to be a ``criminal''? It was 1957,
and Chen's father had just been denounced by Mao's communists as a
``bourgeois rightist.'' A respected Chinese journalist with proven
communist revolutionary credentials, he was shipped off to one of
China's first forced labor camps. Now, after four decades, the
Communist Party is finally debating behind closed doors whether to
expunge Mao's verdict against the ``rightists'' as a historic
error. (Albright-Kunstel, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ECONOMY _ HAVANA _ At a crowded farmer's market in Old
Havana, Jose Marquez laments the high fees he must pay to the
government in order to sell tomatoes and melons at a small stand
for a few pesos a piece. He says that the Cuban government seems to
be doing everything it can to stop the spread of private
entrepreneurship on this socialist island. On Jan. 1, Cubans
celebrated the 40th anniversary of Fidel Castro's revolution. But
there's little to celebrate. The economy is a mess. In recent
months, the government appears to have back-peddled on economic
reforms that were so highly touted only a year ago. Spurring the
government on is economic turmoil in Asia, Brazil, and other parts
of the world, ``proof'' that capitalism doesn't work, at least
according to Castro. (Emling, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., Jan. 20, in both the International and
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With photos.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ISRAEL _ BEIRUT, Lebanon _ After 17 years of warfare,
people in the rolling hills and olive orchards in south Lebanon
wonder if they might finally again have peace _ a time when Israeli
troops might not occupy their land trade artillery with Lebanese
Hezbollah guerillas. For them, the war represents episodes like
last week's, when several civilians were killed by Israeli bombing
runs. For Israel, the war that many call ``Israel's Vietnam'' has
now outlasted the actual Vietnam War. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With photos.
</P>
<P>
   w/LEBANON-FIGHTERS _ BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Will try to find an
ideological recruit into the Hezbollah underground (he won't want
his name or photo used) and ask him why he's decided to risk his
life as a guerrilla in the anti-Israel resistance, then compare him
to the Israeli soldiers who are drafted into the war. (Kaplow, Cox
News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With photos.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS _ LEBANON (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for
the current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-US _ MOSCOW _ It is not exactly the Cold War, but it is
chilly. U.S. Secretary of State Madeline Albright arrives in Moscow
for meetings with senior officials amid strains in U.S.-Russian
relations over policy toward Iraq, the Balkans and U.S. sanctions
against Russian institutions allegedly supplying help to Iran to
build its nuclear program. Advance setting up Albright's three-day
visit. (Holmes, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORES _ WASHINGTON _ Bill and Al, Hillary and Tipper.
Bill and Hillary, Tipper and Al. Either way, it's a family of
political soul mates with contrasting styles, and it has held
together with remarkable consistency through a painful year of
scandal. The First Foursome will be on display more than ever in
the months to come, as Gore steps increasingly from the shadows for
his own presidential bid and the administration uses Mrs. Clinton
and Mrs. Gore to help articulate the goals and policies of a
popular president with a serious credibility problem. (Deans, Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUSINESS _ WASHINGTON _ When business talks, Congress
listens. The first two hearings held by Chairman Bill Archer,
R-Texas of the House Ways and Means Committee after President
Clinton's State of the Union address were on the economy's health
(Wed. Jan. 20) and Social Security reforms (Thurs. Jan. 21). Those
topics are top priorities on the legislative wish lists compiled by
the capitol's biggest business lobbies, which range from the
upstart National Federation of Independent Business to the old
familiar U.S. Chamber of Commerce. In Wednesday's Billion-Byte
March, the chamber and NFIB also helped fund the first big email
lobbying blitz of the year on any topic other than impeachment.
What else they want, and why. The odds they face. (Mollison, Cox
News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With sidebar list of the NFIB and chamber lobbying
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has proposed
that, for the first time, the government invest part of the money
in the Social Security trust fund in the private market. Economists
are split on the idea with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
giving thumbs down, while former Social Security Commissioner
Robert Ball gives it thumbs up. A look at the pros and cons of the
issue at the heart of the Social Security reform. (Lipman, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MLK-THE-THIRD _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He was only 5 when his father,
Martin Luther King Jr., gave the ``I Have a Dream'' speech in
Washington, D.C. He was 10 when his father was shot to death in
Memphis, Tenn., in 1968. But Martin Luther King III's prominent
role in this year's Martin Luther King Jr. Day celebrations and his
new post as president of the organization his father co-founded,
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, show that he may be
coming into his own. (Thatcher, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BEETHOVEN-BABIES _ LOS ANGELES _ Former Georgia Gov. Zell Miller
was right; playing Beethoven for an unborn child may have positive
consequences on the child's well-being. A group of researchers
report on new findings about the consequences of early child care
at the annual meeting of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW _ ATLANTA _ As the Georgia Supreme Court opens its
January term on Monday (Jan. 25), there's one important case
pending that it apparently does not want to consider: whether to
allow death-row inmates the right to have appointed lawyers during
their post-conviction appeals. The issue is a thorny one for the
court because it doesn't want to require the Legislature to pay for
death-row lawyers, but it is also aware that about two-thirds of
all death-row convictions are ultimately reversed. And there are
dozens of former death-row inmates who have been found to be
innocent, including a couple in Georgia, and they obtained their
relief in the courts through habeas corpus petitions. Their claims
would never have gone anywhere without competent counsel to
represent them. The case before the Georgia Supreme Court involves
Exzavious Gibson, who is without a doubt guilty of stabbing
repeatedly a grocer during an armed robbery. But Gibson, who has an
IQ of 76, had to represent himself during his post-conviction
hearing, the procedure of which has been described as complicated
as any in the legal system. Georgia is one of only two states in
the country (Wyoming being the other) that does not appoint counsel
for death-row inmates filing habeas corpus petitions. (Rankin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/DEATHROW-HABEAS _ ATLANTA _ What is habeas corpus, anyway?
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
