<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEETHOVEN-BABIES-ADVI     01-23 0201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEETHOVEN-BABIES-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   EDS: The Atlanta Journal-Constitution story slugged
BEETHOVEN-BABIES will not move tonight, IN ITS PLACE is:
</P>
<P>
   CHILD _ ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Day care for American children is, in
general, ``fair'' - neither outstanding nor terrible, say
researchers conducting the nation's most comprehensive study on
early child care. The latest findings from the ongoing research
backs up results from several smaller studies and what many parents
already know from their own experiences: That the better the
quality of care provided a young child, the better off the child
will be socially and linguistically. In presenting their findings
Saturday at the annual meeting of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science, the researchers pointed out that the
federally-funded study, which has followed 1,300 families and their
children nationwide since 1991, was spurred by the rapid increase
in the use of day care in the United States in the past two
decades. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   If you have any questions, please call CoxNet at (404) 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
