<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-COX     01-23 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Study shows improvements could be made to American child care
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Day care for American children is, in general,
``fair'' - neither outstanding nor terrible, say researchers
conducting the nation's most comprehensive study on early child
care.
</P>
<P>
   The latest findings from the ongoing research backs up results
from several smaller studies and what many parents already know
from their own experiences: That the better the quality of care
provided a young child, the better off the child will be socially
and linguistically.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting their findings Saturday at the annual meeting of
the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the
researchers pointed out that the federally-funded study, which has
followed 1,300 families and their children nationwide since 1991,
was spurred by the rapid increase in the use of day care in the
United States in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, nearly 40 percent of mothers with children under age 6
worked outside the home; today, 64 percent of mothers do. As a
result, more than half the babies under age 1 are being cared for
on a routine basis by someone other than their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ''For many families, then, day care is an absolute necessity,''
said one of the researchers, Cathryn L. Booth of the University of
Washington. ''That's why this research is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   She and other researchers from 13 other universities found that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents have an important influence on their children's
development regardless of how much outside-the-home care the
children experience.
</P>
<P>
   _ Factors such as family income, mothers' psychological
well-being and motherly behavior have more of an influence on
children's social competence at age 2 and 3 than does the
children's day care program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Children benefit from being cared for in a group with others
their age: they have fewer behavior problems at both ages 2 and 3
years old than those not part of a group.
</P>
<P>
   _ Children who are in several day care arrangements tend to have
more behavior problems than children who are in a consistent day
care program.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also suggested possible ways for improving the
nation's child care: by having at least one caregiver for about
every three children, by increasing the caregivers' levels of
education, and increasing the safety and intellectual stimulation
of children in day care programs.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which is funded by the National Institute of Child
Health and Development, may be expanded to include
elementary-school age children to determine the impacts of early
day care on their development.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-SAMARANCH-0124-CO     01-23 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-SAMARANCH-0124-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OLYMPIC PRESIDENT STEADFAST, BUT LEGACY AT STAKE IN MIDST OF
CURRENT SCANDAL
 &HT;    With IOC-MEETING-0124.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Late Friday night, tired and worried
International Olympic Committee members streamed in and out of Juan
Antonio Samaranch's suite at the elegant old Lausanne Palace Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   News was breaking of a new bidding scandal out of Sydney: An
Australian Olympic official reportedly offered $70,000 in
inducements to sway the votes of two African IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, the IOC president, was furious. Sydney was to be the
final Olympic Games of the Samaranch era, a triumphant close to a
20-year career at the top of the Olympic world. Now, Samaranch, 78,
who already was wrestling with the nasty implications of the Salt
Lake City bidding scandal, suddenly faced a potentially more
damaging controversy over the Games for which he has had so much
hope.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, IOC members who visited him described him as a man who,
while clearly upset, was nevertheless in control and moving quickly
to get ahead of the new crisis before daylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an iron man,'' said Alex Gilady, an IOC member from
Israel since 1994. ``Could you imagine a man of his age in a
position such as this? It's quite amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite calls for Samaranch's head as the bidding scandal has
unfolded, the IOC president, if anything, seems to have
strengthened his grip on power. While IOC members are pointing
fingers at one another, none has yet broken ranks with Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   There is a clear belief bordering on faith among IOC members
here that only Samaranch with his experience and command of the
Olympic institution is capable
</P>
<P>
   of steering the committee safely through this storm.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss IOC member Mark Hodler, the strongest advocate for
expelling members found guilty of corruption, strongly defended
Samaranch. ``If all the honest people go away, then what remains of
the IOC?'' he asked reporters Saturday in the lobby of the Lausanne
Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Kevan Gosper, the influential Australian IOC member, also
defended Samaranch, saying he had the full support of the IOC
leadership and rank-in-file membership. ``You don't look at a
president who has brought you through so many tough times and done
so much for the Olympic movement and tell him to leave,'' Gosper
said. ``If ever we needed a good president, we need it now. He will
come out of this even better and stronger than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Samaranch's hold over the IOC stems from the simple fact
that 92 of the 113 members were elected during his presidency, each
with his personal blessings. Only 21 members predate Samaranch's
election to the presidency in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, they owe their much-coveted positions to Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC is built on patronage, and a patronage that depends on
his creation of IOC members,'' said Sir Bob Scott, who headed two
unsuccessful bids for Manchester, England. ``I don't think he's
under any pressure to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to exaggerate Samaranch's standing in the Olympic
world. Bidding cities treat him as royalty, providing him with the
finest suites in the finest hotels their cities have to offer. He
has the ability to call personally on heads of state -- including
presidents of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He is paid no salary, but Samaranch is a wealthy man with a
number of lucrative business interests, primarily in his native
Spain. He doesn't vote in the IOC, but as Canadian IOC member Dick
Pound puts it: ``It's the loudest non-vote imaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   When he took office in 1980, the Olympics were on the verge of
going broke.
</P>
<P>
   The 1976 Montreal Games were considered a financial disaster and
the U.S. boycott of the 1980 Moscow Games -- an event that
Samaranch remembers with considerable bitterness directed at the
United States -- threatened to issue the death blow.
</P>
<P>
   In those dark days, only Los Angeles bid for the 1984 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The LA organizers, free to experiment by a weakened IOC,
reinvented Olympic commercialism and generated a $235 million
surplus. Los Angeles Games chief Peter Ueberroth, refused to share
with the struggling IOC, a humbling experience that left a deep
mark on Samaranch. ``The Los Angeles Olympics gave the IOC a little
lesson in commercialism,'' he said years later.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lesson he took to heart, leading the financial revival
of the Olympics by careful marketing and lucrative television
deals. Each Games under his presidency has turned a profit, and the
IOC has flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, through it all, he has been the object of scorn, the
lightening rod for accusations that the IOC was a pampered,
self-interested band of elitists whose members care more about
retaining their perks than the sports or ideals they are supposed
to represent.
</P>
<P>
   He has been criticized most harshly and personally for his
association with former Spanish dictator Franco. Samaranch says his
role under Franco is no secret, but he describes it as modest --
first as director-general of sports and later as a parliamentary
leader of Franco's Falangist movement. In 1977, two years after the
dictator's death, he became Spain's first ambassador to Moscow
since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   He has seen the Olympics through the bad financial years, the
boycotts and near warfare between North and South Korea, but now he
faces the challenge of his career.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy now is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is most important to him,'' said Manchester's Scott said.
``And until all this, if he had retired after Atlanta, he would
have been remembered as the man who presided over the great revival
of the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he must fear that he may be remembered for presiding over
its demise.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
