<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5707 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-1STLD-WRI     01-23 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS LEWINSKY TO SUBMIT TO QUESTIONING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite with new reporting, including more
details on the judge's ruling and the pending session with
Lewinsky. Expands by 200 words.) (Eds: See also IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-FITZGERALD,
IMPEACH-BIBLE-BELT, IMPEACH-LINCOLN, IMPEACH-WITNESSES-REVIEW)  
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge ordered Monica Lewinsky Saturday to
submit to questioning from the House Republicans prosecuting
President Clinton or from the independent counsel's office, drawing
a bitter White House attack on the prosecutors' effort to force Ms.
Lewinsky's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Chief Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, issued
moments before senators resumed a second day of interrogation in
the impeachment trial, ignited a furious question-and-answer
session on the Senate floor and left unclear how _ or how soon _
the trial would be brought to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats assailed the fairness of the House prosecutors' using
the authority of the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, to compel
Ms. Lewinsky's cooperation, while Republicans demanded to know how
the Senate could untangle important conflicting testimony without
hearing from witnesses like her.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling came in response to a request from Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., the lead prosecutor, after Ms. Lewinsky rejected a
request to meet with the House prosecutors last week.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Johnson ordered Ms. Lewinsky to ``allow herself to be
debriefed'' by House prosecutors or, if she preferred, by Starr's
lawyers, or forfeit her protections under her immunity deal with
the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr's aides question Ms. Lewinsky, the House prosecutors
said they would be able to attend the meetings and feed questions
to the independent counsel's staff.
</P>
<P>
   As the trial reconvened Saturday, Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla.,
one of the 13 House prosecutors, or managers, explained that they
merely wanted a routine meeting with Ms. Lewinsky before deciding
whether to ask the Senate to take a deposition from her.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House counsel, Charles Ruff, ridiculed a claim by
the House prosecutors that they were seeking an innocent
get-together to discuss the case. ``Can you imagine what that
little conversation is going to look like, held in the independent
counsel's office, with the people there who have the capacity to
put Ms. Lewinsky in jail?'' Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors had no right under Ms. Lewinsky's immunity
deal with Starr to force her to submit to their questioning. But in
her brief one-page decision, Judge Johnson ruled that the
independent counsel could compel Ms. Lewinsky to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers have balked at allowing her to meet with
the House managers, arguing that it would cast her in ``a partisan
light.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to trail along with the House managers struck us as
wrong,'' Jacob Stein, a lawyer for Ms. Lewinsky, said in a
telephone interview Saturday. Stein said it was unlikely that Ms.
Lewinsky would appeal Judge Johnson's order, and he did not know
when the interview might take place.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the House managers said they had been told that
Ms. Lewinsky was en route to Washington from Los Angeles, and that
discussions between her lawyers and the prosecutors would probably
ensue on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky would face intense questioning from Starr's lawyers
or the House prosecutors. It was unclear Saturday night which
questioners she would choose.
</P>
<P>
   One of the House prosecutors, Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., said he
would oppose having the independent counsel's staff in the same
interview room, if that would intimidate Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thought would be to sit down and talk to her like I would
anyone else,'' Bryant said. ``I would not want any possibility that
she would feel intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors believe that her answers could be pivotal
as the Senate decides early next week whether to call witnesses or
to decide Clinton's fate without witnesses, the managers say.
``She's certainly at the core of all this,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Lewinsky's testimony has never been more important than it
is now,'' Paul McNulty, chief spokesman for the House managers,
said in a statement. ``In the last four days, the White House has
challenged the reliability of her testimony in a number of key
instances relating to her conversations with the president'' and
Betty Currie, Clinton's personal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Under the procedures adopted by the Senate, senators would have
to vote separately on whether to depose witnesses and then whether
to call any to testify in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces charges of perjury and obstruction of justice. Ms.
Lewinsky was interviewed extensively by grand jurors and Starr's
prosecutors, and her testimony about her relationship with the
president was the basis for much of Starr's case against him. The
House managers relied heavily on her testimony to show that Clinton
lied to the grand jury.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several managers emphasized Saturday that although it might seem
that Ms. Lewinsky had already been asked every conceivable
question, they felt it was essential to meet with her themselves,
face to face, to present their best case to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes between the House managers and the White House
counsel spilled over to Senate Republicans and Democrats during
recesses of the trial Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the 45 Senate Democrats signed a letter to Hyde
Saturday, urging him to drop his request to interview Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions by the managers,'' the letter says, ``undertaken
without notice to the Senate or the president's counsel, raise
profound questions of fundamental fairness and undermine the
ability of this body to control the discovery procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Democratic senator not to sign the letter was Robert
Byrd of West Virginia, a senior Democrat who is a guardian of
Senate traditions and who issued his own statement on the matter.
Byrd angrily criticized the House managers in his statement for
compelling Ms. Lewinsky to cooperate: ``This is clearly an attempt
by the House managers to pre-empt the coming vote by the Senate on
whether or not to depose witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republicans said the House managers were merely
exercising the same rights to interview a potential witness that
the White House surely has with witnesses friendly to its side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with that,'' said Sen. Frank Murkowski,
R-Alaska. ``The defense has all kinds of access to the people in
question, Vernon E. Jordan Jr. and so forth. There's a procedure
under way that the court has determined to be quite appropriate,
and we'll have to see where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The House managers entered the Senate chamber Saturday morning
well aware of the swirling talk among senators about ending the
trial, and of the pressure on the prosecutors to reverse that
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is not on what individual senators may be saying,''
Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., said on CNN on Friday night. ``Our
focus is on trying to do our job and present this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of the trial begins on Monday, when senators are
to begin debating whether to dismiss the case and whether to depose
witnesses. Votes on one or both motions could happen later in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd shocked the Capitol on Friday when he announced that he
would introduce the motion to dismiss. Byrd, an 81-year-old dean of
the Senate, said he did not believe witnesses would add any
meaningful testimony and that the two-thirds vote required to
convict Clinton was not within reach.
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate on dismissal and witnesses takes place, in
open and closed sessions on the Senate floor, Democrats and
Republicans said Saturday that they expected an intensifying of the
flurry of private meetings and mini-negotiations over how best to
end the trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1836EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-BUZZ24-COX     01-23 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BUZZ24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta radio station WSTR-FM (Star 94) has found a
sure-fire method of securing celeb interviews _ promise listeners
Super Bowl tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the station began its ``Superstars for the Super
Bowl'' contest, guaranteeing tickets to the listener who can get
the biggest star to phone in during the ``Steve and Vikki in the
Morning'' show. The celebrities who have called in so far: former
First Lady Rosalynn Carter, ``Diff'rent Strokes'' star Todd
Bridges, ``Partridge Family'' mom Shirley Jones, Archbishop Desmond
Tutu, talk show host Maury Povich and Falcons quarterback Chris
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Par-TEEEE....
</P>
<P>
   Estimates are that150,000 people will show up for the Super Bowl
in Miami. Pro Player Stadium's capacity is 75,000, so many visitors
obviously are making the trip for reasons other than attending the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much going on,'' said Alex Munoz, executive
director of the South Florida Super Bowl Host Committee. ``You can
go to a Super Bowl, not go to the game and still have a great
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to go through life drunk, fat and stupid,''
said Jeff DeForrest, a local radio talk-show host and veteran of 12
Super Bowls. ``But if you do, Super Bowl week is the way to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ...But be careful
</P>
<P>
   The feds are warning ravelers headed for the Super Bowl to make
sure package tours include tickets to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department says that every year there are
people fooled by tours that appear to be a bargain, but then don't
include game tickets.
</P>
<P>
   If a travel agent or tour representative claims that a game
ticket is included, the buyer should demand that the ticket _ or a
written confirmation of a ticket _ be provided at the time of
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The department also suggests buyers pay with a credit card,
which affords some legal protection.
</P>
<P>
   The view from here
</P>
<P>
   Denver Post writer Jim Armstrong, in today's paper, tells
Coloradans why Falcon Fever is a new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the possible exception of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers _ OK,
with no exceptions _ the Falcons have been the NFL's worst
franchise of this generation,'' writes Armstrong, on location in
Suwanee, Ga. ``When they were born, somebody should have slapped
the doctor. They used to have a bumper sticker in these parts that
read: `Go Braves ... And Take The Falcons With You.''' Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Overscene
</P>
<P>
   Falcons defensive linemen Chuck Smith, Lester Archambeau, Travis
Hall, Shane Dronett and families in an upstairs, private dining
room at Maggiano's Little Italy in Buckhead. The players ordered
multiple plates of New York strips, linguini with red clam sauce,
stuffed clams, veal and shrimp. Said manager David Clark: ``They
kept our kitchen busy. Those guys can throw down some food!''
</P>
<P>
   Richard L. Eldredge writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Our wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
