<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-EAGLE-WATCHING-630     01-23 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EAGLE-WATCHING-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLACE TO SEE EAGLES SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORESTBURGH, N.Y. _ Great wings outstretched, a bald eagle
soared over the open water of the Mongaup Reservoir, giving the
group of observers a brief, brilliant sighting before it rose
behind the tall white pines. The number of eagles wintering here in
the Upper Delaware watershed of Sullivan County has grown steadily
in recent years. So has the phenomenon of eagle watching.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen bundled and layered visitors, some of whom
traveled many miles for a glimpse of the eagles, took shelter from
the brisk January winds in a public viewing blind. Trained
volunteers were directing them in using telescopes to spot the
elusive birds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people who make the trip do not consider themselves
avid bird watchers. Instead, they are drawn by the mystique of the
endangered bald eagle. And that is exactly what Sullivan County
officials are counting on _ that their natural resources, including
the largest wintering population of bald eagles in the Northeast,
can make their area an attractive destination for people from the
New York City region interested in a one-day or weekend excursion.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists could provide a much needed economic boost for the
Catskill Mountain region.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Schmidt had seen bald eagles before, in Nova Scotia and
Alaska. Still, she chose to spend three hours driving here from
Long Island with her husband, her 15-month-old son, two nephews,
and her sister-in-law to see eagles in flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more special to see them here, so close to your own back
yard. And I wanted them to see them,'' she said, referring to her
husband, Steven, and 6-year-old nephew, Kyle Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll come back again when Steve Jr. is older,'' she said.
``Next time it would be nice to stay over.''
</P>
<P>
   The county manager, Jonathan Drapkin, said the county was trying
to overcome the loss of many resort hotels. ``So many people have a
fixed memory of the large, self-contained hotels as they were,'' he
said. ``We want people to know there's some of the best fly fishing
in the Northeast here; that you can canoe or raft the Delaware.''
</P>
<P>
   The eagles migrate here primarily from Canada. It is the sight
of open fresh water that attracts them.
</P>
<P>
   They can have their fill of fresh fish and then perch in the
pines among large tracts of undisturbed land, including 12,000
state-owned acres managed strictly for the eagles' protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general shifting and recognition by the county that
our natural resources are an economic resource,'' said Lori
Danuff-McKean, who works with the county as founder and volunteer
president of the nonprofit Eagle Institute, a year-old organization
dedicated to the protection of the bald eagle and other birds of
prey.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 15 institute-trained volunteers can be found each
weekend during prime viewing season _ January through March _
beside roads and rivers and in the Mongaup blind. They act as
guides for group field trips, like the one arranged by the Schmidt
family. They staff popular viewing locations, equipped with
binoculars and telescopes, where they help visitors who come
unguided and advise on proper etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   They are trained to monitor eagle activity and weather
conditions and to look for birds tagged and banded for
identification by the state Department of Environmental
Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a beautiful day, we can expect to see 40 to 50 people who
have come on their own to a designated viewing area,'' Ms.
Danuff-McKean said.
</P>
<P>
   As of mid-January, a record 179 bald eagles were counted in the
Upper Delaware watershed and its associated reservoirs. Peter Nye,
who heads the state's endangered species unit in Albany, said 89
adults and 90 immature birds were spotted from the air during the
annual midwinter count on Jan. 11.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many reservoirs are very low now, and there is not much ice-free
water, Nye said. ``But no matter how bad the conditions, this area
still provides some amount of suitable habitat for bald eagles, and
we've still recorded record numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mongaup Valley Wildlife Management Area, just below
Monticello, was created in 1990 when the state bought the 12,000
acres as a reserve for the bald eagle. It is the best place to see
eagles in New York state, Nye said. But the eagles are extremely
sensitive to the presence of humans, and that creates some
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to ensure that in five or seven years we will have the
habitat to support the numbers of breeding pairs,'' Nye said. ``The
new challenge is to identify enough suitable habitat, then manage
and protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Lamoriello, president of the Sullivan County Visitors
Association, said that although the county was working to draw
visitors, ``We recognize that if you overwhelm a delicate balance,
you lose your attraction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
