<HEADER>
A5714 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-HISTORY-TEX     01-23 1658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-HISTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS AND CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The highlight films roll en masse this week, turning those
classic sports networks into so many Super Bowl Channels.
</P>
<P>
   From Max McGee's one-handed catch to Joe Namath's I-told-you-so
finger waving, the Super Bowl has given us sites and sounds and
scenes; heroes and anti-heroes football fans can practically see
with their eyes closed.
</P>
<P>
   There's Garo Yepremian trying to throw a pass. And Scott Norwood
missing a field goal. And Jackie Smith dropping the would-be
touchdown pass. And Desmond Howard returning a kickoff 99 yards for
a touchdown. And Duane Thomas saying, ``if it's the ultimate game,
why do they play one every year.'' And Doug Williams leading the
Redskins to 35 points in one quarter. And Thurman Thomas looking
for his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bills and Vikings losing again.
</P>
<P>
   So as we count down to Super Bowl XXXIII next Sunday in Miami,
the NFL's final ultimate game of the 1990s and the last before the
clock turns 2000, here is a highlight reel of the great moments,
great plays and great games from the previous XXXII:
BEST GAMES
</P>
<P>
   1. Super Bowl XXV, New York Giants 20, Buffalo Bills 19
</P>
<P>
   For just the second time in Super Bowl history, the game was
decided on the final play. The Giants rallied from a 12-3
second-quarter deficit with a ball-control offense that accumulated
a Super Bowl record 40:33 in time of possession. Still, the Bills
had a chance to win in the end. Quarterback Jim Kelly no-huddled
his club breathlessly down the field for the game-winning kick. But
when Scott Norwood was wide right on a 47-yard field goal attempt,
the Giants had escaped with the victory. Giants running back O.J.
Anderson was named the game's MVP with 21 carries for 102 yards and
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   2. Super Bowl XXIII, San Francisco 20, Cincinnati 16
</P>
<P>
   Joe Montana solidified his place as one of the best clutch
quarterbacks in league history with a heart-pounding, fourth
quarter drive to give his club its third world championship. Down
16-13 with a little more than five minutes to play, Montana drove
his team 92 yards in 11 plays for the victory. The drive culminated
with Montana's 10-yard touchdown pass to wide receiver John Taylor,
who beat Ken Horton on a short slant route in the end zone. Montana
wound up with a Super Bowl record 357 yards, but Jerry Rice was the
MVP with 11 catches for a Super Bowl record 215 yards.
</P>
<P>
   3. Super Bowl XIII, Pittsburgh 35, Dallas 31
</P>
<P>
   Both teams held seven-point leads in the game's first 30 minutes
before Pittsburgh got some breathing room with 14 points in a 19
second span of the fourth quarter. But no lead is safe when the
opposing quarterback is Roger Staubach. The Cowboys quarterback,
who made fourth-quarter comebacks fashionable while John Elway was
still in high school, led the Cowboys on two late touchdown drives
to get within four points. But the comeback fell short when
Steelers running back Rocky Bleier recovered an onsides kick with
17 seconds remaining as the Steelers became the first team to win
three Super Bowls. Super Bowl MVP Terry Bradshaw threw four
touchdown passes and was 17 of 30 for 318 yards.
</P>
<P>
   WORST GAMES
</P>
<P>
   1. Super Bowl XX, Chicago 46, New England 10
</P>
<P>
   This game was the best excuse to visit your in-laws. When the
Patriots upset the Miami Dolphins in the AFC Championship Game two
weeks earlier, the luster of this Super Bowl was truly lost, for
the Dolphins were the only team to have beaten the Bears all year.
The Bears had one of the most dominating defenses in history. The
Patriots, who made the Super Bowl as a wild card team, were
overmatched. But they tried to make a game of it, turning a fumble
into a field goal just 1:19 into the game. The opening score was
the quickest in Super Bowl history. But it would be a Bears Super
Bowl shuffle the rest of the way, as Chicago recorded seven sacks
and held the Patriots to seven yards rushing, a Super Bowl record.
</P>
<P>
   2. Super Bowl XXIV, San Francisco 55, Denver 10
</P>
<P>
   You only watched the beginning of this game because you thought
the John Elway-led Broncos, who were competing in their third Super
Bowl in four years, would make a game of it. Hah. The 49ers scored
touchdowns on four of their six first half possessions in setting a
record for points and margin of victory. The 49ers domination
included first downs (28 to 12), total net yards (461 to 167) and
time of possession (39:31 to 20:29).
</P>
<P>
   3. Super Bowl V, Baltimore 16, Dallas 13
</P>
<P>
   OK, the game did go down to the wire and was decided by a
32-yard field goal with five seconds to play. But boy, before that,
what a stinker. The game featured 11 turnovers, a Super Bowl record
that still stands. The teams also combined for just 24 first downs,
also a Super Bowl record. The Cowboys punted a Super Bowl record
nine times, and committed 10 penalties for a Super Bowl record 133
yards. The Colts were equally offensive, with seven turnovers. BEST
INDIVIDUAL PERFORMANCES
</P>
<P>
   1. Doug Williams: The Redskins quarterback overcame a
first-quarter knee injury to throw four touchdown passes _ of 80,
27, 50, and 8 yards _ in the second quarter as Washington routed
the Broncos, 42-10 in Super Bowl XXII.
</P>
<P>
   2. Marcus Allen: The Raiders running back had what was then a
Super Bowl record with 191 yards rushing as Los Angeles defeated
the Redskins, 38-9, in Super Bowl XVIII.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lynn Swann: The Steelers receiver made some of the prettiest
catches in Super Bowl history, four in fact, for 161 yards and a
touchdown as the Steelers defeated the Cowboys, 21-17, in Super
Bowl X.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PLAYS
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXI, 1997
</P>
<P>
   Packers returner Desmond Howard brought a kickoff back a Super
Bowl-record 99 yards for a touchdown to cap a 35-21 victory against
the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XVII, 1983
</P>
<P>
   Redskins fullback John Riggins ran 43 yards for a touchdown on a
fourth-and-one situation, giving the Redskins their first lead of
the game in the fourth quarter and sparking a 27-17 victory against
the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl IV, 1970
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs receiver Otis Taylor caught a short pass, broke two
tackles and high-stepped 46 yards to the end zone to cap a 23-7
victory against the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTBREAKING PLAYS
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXX, 1996
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh quarterback Neil O'Donnell and the Steelers rallied
from a 13-point and appeared on the verge of a great Super Bowl
upset against the favored Cowboys. However, trailing 20-17 with
4:15 left, O'Donnell broke the hearts of the Steelers fans
everywhere with an errant pass that was intercepted by Cowboys
cornerback Larry Brown. The Cowboys finished the momentum-turning
sequence with a touchdown by running back Emmitt Smith to close out
a 27-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXV, 1991
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo kicker Scott Norwood was wide right on a 47-yard field
goal with eight seconds left that would have given the Bills a
22-20 victory over the Giants. Instead, the miss resulted in a
20-19 loss, the first of four straight Super Bowl losses for the
Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XIII, 1979
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys tight end Jackie Smith ended a Hall of Fame career with
a catastrophic bobble. With the Cowboys trailing Pittsburgh 21-14
in the third quarter, quarterback Roger Staubach found Smith wide
open in the end zone. However, he slipped and dropped the ball. The
Cowboys settled for a field goal and eventually lost 35-31.
</P>
<P>
   GREATEST MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl III, 1969
</P>
<P>
   The Jets 16-7 victory against the Colts proved to be monumental
for the team, quarterback Joe Namath and the league. It was the
first by an AFL team over an NFL team and it was ``guaranteed'' by
Namath.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXII, 1998
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback John Elway and the Broncos get rid of the loser tag
forever with a 31-24 upset of the Broncos. It marked for the first
Super Bowl win for Elway after losses in three previous
appearances. It was a first also for the Broncos, who avoided
becoming the first team to lose five Super Bowls.  &LR; name:Clarence E.
Hill Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXV, 1991
</P>
<P>
   As our nation's soldiers risked their lives in Operation Desert
Storm, the rest of the nation tuned in to watch the beginning of
Super Bowl XXV between the Giants and Bills. And what a beginning
it was. Whitney Houston sang a stirring rendition of the National
Anthem (although later we found that she lipsync the whole way)
that made you feel proud to be an American. In the crowd shots
taken during Houston's performance, people were waving flags,
clapping, and crying.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXII, 1988
</P>
<P>
   Denver may still be asking if anybody caught the license number
on the truck that hit them in the second quarter. That would be the
volcanic quarter when the Redskins scored a record 35 points. The
driving force of that scoring spree was Washington quarterback Doug
Williams who threw four touchdown passes in the quarter, including
ones of 50 and 80 yards to Ricky Sanders. Williams reigned as the
game's MVP and is still the only African American quarterback to
win a Super Bowl.  &LR; name:Mitchell Krugel
</P>
<P>
   TALE OF THE TAPE ``Comparing the AFC's performance in the Super
Bowl to the NFC:'' Category AFC NFC Record 12-20 20-12
</P>
<P>
   1960s 1-2 2-1
</P>
<P>
   1970s 8-2 2-8
</P>
<P>
   1980s 3-7 7-3
</P>
<P>
   1990s 1-8 8-1 Win streak 5(73-77) 13(85-97) Margin of victory
12.7 points per game 18.7 points per game Biggest victory L.A.
Raiders 38, Washington 9 (1984) San Francisco 55, Denver 10 (1990)
Best overall team Pittsburgh(4-1) San Francisco(5-0) Worst overall
team Buffalo(0-4) Minnesota (0-4) Best player-Terry Bradshaw Joe
Montana Best quarterback Jim Plunkett (Oakland) 122.8 QB rating Joe
Montana (San Francisco) 127.8 QB rating Best running back Marcus
Allen (Raiders) 9.6 yards per carry Tim Smith (Washington) 9.3
yards per carry Best wide receiver John Stallworth (Pittsburgh)
24.4 yards per catch Ricky Sanders (Washington) 23.4 yards per
catch
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
