<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 1/23/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- CASPIAN-COMPETITION-REVIEW,
1-23 -- An oil tanker transporting Caspian oil through the Bosporus
Strait, one of the busiest waterways in the world. With the
discovery of great energy reserves in countries around the Caspian
Sea, a vast new region has catapulted onto the world stage. It not
only offers oil companies the prospect of great wealth. It gives
outside powers a place to test their strength. (Staton R.
Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ORLANDO, Fla. -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- SOC-U.S.-COACH, 1-23 --
Bruce Arena, 47, the new coach of the U.S. men's national soccer
team. For at least the next year, Arena will be the man in the
white lab coat, merrily experimenting with new players and new
combinations. ``I am concerned with building a team that is
prepared to qualify for 2002, whether that means by winning games
or by developing a new team,'' says Arena. ``It's about developing
a new pool of players, and with that there needs to be patience.''
(Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-JOHNSON, 1-23 --
The New York Knicks foward Larry Johnson, on a vegetarian diet, has
lost weight, but gained muscle. He is aiming to play at under 240
pounds to help keep his injury risk low. Johnson's new sleek
physique comes as a result of his exploration with the Muslim
faith. ``It's just the discipline of it,'' says Johnson. ``It's
just the straight-up discipline of being a man.'' (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ROCKPORT, Wash. -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- NATURALIST-EAGLES-2,
1-23 -- Libby Mills, 46, a naturalist with the Nature Conservancy,
has spent every winter Wednesday for the past 17 years counting the
number of bald eagles along an eight-mile stretch of the Skagit
River in Washington. Ms. Mills' data are used by the Nature
Conservancy for measuring the health of the river, the salmon and
the eagles' breeding success along the river, home to one of the
largest winter concentrations of eagles in the country. (Dan
Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ROCKPORT, Wash. -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- NATURALIST-EAGLES-1,
1-23 -- A bald eagle soaring over an eight-mile stretch of the
Skagit River in Washington, home to one of the largest winter
concentrations of eagles in the country. The number of eagles in
the Skagit River area has increased significantly over the past
decade, primarily because of the reduction of logging in the
eagles' nesting areas, and the banning of the pesticide DDT. (Dan
Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ANNANDALE, N.J. -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- PHYSICS-CURRICULUM-2,
1-23 -- Tom Palma, the science department chairman at North
Hunterdon High School in Annandale, N.J., teaching a ninth-grade
physics class. Nationwide, the push to reorder science education
and put physics first in high-school curriculums, seems to be
catching on. ``I really think this sequence helps students stay
with science, by presenting it logically,'' he says. (Laura
Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ANNANDALE, N.J. -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- PHYSICS-CURRICULUM-1,
1-23 -- Bibi Deitz, left, and Kelly Edwards using a slinky, as part
of an energy test in their ninth-grade physics class at North
Hunterdon High School in Annandale, N.J. Nationwide, the push to
reorder science education and put physics first in high-school
curriculums, seems to be catching on. One measure of the success
has been the enormous growth in the number of students taking
advanced courses at schools that have flipped their sequence.
(Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LUTOU, China -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- CHINA-FEMALE-SUICIDE,
1-23 -- Isolation and low self-esteem contribute to a high rate of
suicide among Chinese women working farms, whose method of choice
is often to drink pesticides. Officials have only recently begun
efforts to address the problem. China is the only country where
more women than men die as a result of suicide each year -- twice
as many in the age group under 45. (Elizabeth Rosenthal/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Jan. 23, 1999 -- Y2K-MEDICINE, 1-23 --
Laureen West holding a vial of her medication which helps contain
her brain tumor. As a nurse turned computer systems manager, Mrs.
West is able to describe how Year 2000 computer malfunctions could
interrupt the distribution of medicines. But as a brain tumor
patient who needs daily doses of synthetic thryroid and other drugs
to stay alive, the 43 year-old Mrs. West has no rivals when it
comes to convincing listeners it matters. (Angel Franco/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
