<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MODULAR-HOMES-REAL-3R     01-23 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODULAR-HOMES-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: greater spans.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One drawback to modular construction is that it doesn't allow
for on-site design changes. And while technical quality is high
among all companies that are doing a reasonably good business,
Hallahan said, some allow less customization and detail than
others. Buyers should shop around.
</P>
<P>
   And buyers should keep in mind that modular efficiencies only go
so far. Homes with extremely complicated roof lines or tricky floor
plans don't really lend themselves to modular design, noted Peter
Curto, president of Curto &AMP; Curto in Smithtown, N.Y. The houses his
company builds tend to be the old-fashioned shingle houses that are
so popular in the Hamptons, on Long Island, these days, with
elaborate staircases, lots of porches, and masonry chimneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason for modular is to save construction time
and cost, but with a fairly detailed home, you begin to lose the
cost-effectiveness,'' Curto said. ``I'm building a house now that
is 80 by 120 feet wide in one point. It's got varied roof lines and
a tower. I don't know how you'd do that on a modular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Campbell estimated that Westchester Modular Homes really
built only about 30 percent of the mansion in Greenwich. The
modular frame included insulation, sheetrocking, and rough plumbing
and electrical wiring, but all of the exterior and interior details
were added on-site. ``I hoped to save money and I think I saved a
little, but what I really saved is time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greater emphasis on work that can be done in advance in the
factory can result it greater savings. Jaime and Leslie Klein
figure their modular home in Cranbury, N.J., cost them as much as
50 percent less than a comparable stick-built home.
</P>
<P>
   Situated on six acres, the 5,300- square-foot colonial was
erected from six modules in just two days by LDM Homes. The Kleins
added some amenities, including granite in the two master baths,
commercial kitchen appliances, and cherry floors, as well as a
stick-built garage. But even after their additional investments,
Klein said, the house is worth considerably more than they've
spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our home insurance company appraised it at $822,000, not
including the land and improvements,'' said Klein, an insurance
executive with Wharton/Lyon &AMP; Lyon in Livingston, N.J. ``We didn't
spend that much for the whole place. And I would think the market
value is in excess of $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Klein, a curtain designer, said they designed the home
themselves with the help of a computer program, and then relied on
factory engineers to fix any technical problems. Eventually, she
said, they hope to finish the third floor and add a module onto the
back as a sun room to give them a total of 7,800 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   It's been nearly a year since the couple moved in, and so far
they've found nothing to complain about. The construction is solid
and the walls are thick, Klein said. ``It's so quiet,'' he added,
``my wife and I can yell at each other from different rooms and not
hear each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
