<HEADER>
A5724 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRO-WRESTLING-TEX     01-23 1885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-WRESTLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAKE OR `REAL,' PRO WRESTLING IS SILLY AND SUCCESSFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH RICHLAND HILLS, Texas _ Walk into the Texas Indoor
Speedway Arena on any Friday night and cringe at the writing on the
dimly lit wall _ ``Wrasslin' Is Real!''
</P>
<P>
   Right off the mat let's get something straight: Not only is
professional wrestling not real, it's more fake than Marv Albert's
hair and Jimmy Johnson's retirement and Pamela Anderson's
television lifeguard character.
</P>
<P>
   As if there were any lingering doubts, the results are rigged
and the combat staged. It's not just coincidence that the seemingly
unconscious hero always rolls out of the way just before the
300-pound villain jumps on him from the turnbuckles. That every
referee somehow can't count to three on his first two tries, and
that he consistently misses the supposedly illegal 12-pound
lugwrench in the bad guy's bikini briefs. Or that no one in the
history of the sport has ever won a decision without moments before
being perilously close to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're pulling the wool over people's eyes,''
said a local wrestler who requested anonymity for fear of ostracism
from his peers. ``If we were really beating the crap out of each
other it would have been banned long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   And, for those of you nodding ``a-men,'' there's one more small
detail about pro wrestling: Like it or not, it's the hottest thing
on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Sure it's fixed. But apparently _ from the raucous local arena
to tomorrow night's sold-out WCW event at Reunion Arena, to the
spawning of a state governor, a local preacher and two wildly
popular television shows _ professional wrestling is fixed just
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't watch it because we think it's real, we watch because
it's fun and entertaining,'' said 17-year-old Country Day High
School student Jay Key, who maintains a wrestling web site on the
Internet between weekly visits to the 8,000-square-foot arena
opposite North Hills Mall. ``We know shows like Seinfeld and ER
aren't real either, but we watch them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   This side of the Hare Krishnas, name something avidly and
obsessively consumed by millions while, at the same time,
completely ignored by the rest of the world. While at it, name
something since Beavis burped in the general direction of Butt-head
that's been so silly, yet so successful. And, name another
``sport'' that can't even prompt bet-driven Las Vegas to post odds
on it, or that has changed its competitive rules exactly as often
as The White House has changed colors.
</P>
<P>
   Either you get it, or you don't.
`IT'S JUST SO FUNNY'
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the perspective, professional wrestling is either a
gripping soap opera drama with the added allure of violence, or a
'90s Three Stooges with Moe again putting Curly's head in the vice
grips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so funny,'' said Lauren Cole, a recent Keller High
School graduate. ``It's all fake. It's so obvious. The people who
come here are basically trashy people who are easily entertained.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes after her seething critique of the sport and its
fans, Cole climbed into the ring and jumped into the arms of local
wrestler Kit Carson for a $5 photograph. And so is revealed
wrestling's dirty little _ and oh-so-real _ secret: The sport's
most positively tangible asset is its muscular bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s era of bluster, exaggeration and excess, Hulk Hogan
and Andre the Giant starred in Wrestlemania III in 1987 that set
the attendance record for an indoor event at 93,173 in the Pontiac
Silverdome. In May of '94, 32,123 turned out to watch wrestling at
Texas Stadium. Plano-based promoter Ken Taylor, who runs the weekly
card on Grapevine Highway, is convinced both records will fall
before the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves it, from the forklift operator to the CEO,''
said Taylor. ``It's the same reason people love Jerry Springer and
Cops. Bottom line, we desperately want to be entertained. Say what
you will about our sport, we entertain people.''
</P>
<P>
   Boasting way-larger-than-life stars like Stone Cold Steve Austin
and Bill Goldberg, wrestling is pinning down outrageous television
ratings. Against the strong seasonal pulls of ABC's Monday Night
Football and Fox's Ally McBeal, combined viewers watching USA's WWF
RAW Is War and TNT's WCW Monday Nitro approached 10 million per
Monday, a 36-percent jump from last year.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF produces 12 hours of new programming each week, seven of
which consistently wind up in TV's top 10. Simply put, wrestling is
more popular among its target audience than The Simpsons or The
X-Files.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Kiss concert from the '70s, only more
interactive,'' said Carson. ``One guy thinks it's a great sport and
another think it's a freak show, but they're both watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Last July alone, fans bought $400,000 worth of Goldberg caps and
T-shirts. The WCW sponsored a car in NASCAR's Busch series. The WWF
is planning a casino in Vegas and a theme restaurant in Times
Square. NBC was considering showing wrestling instead of its
canceled NBA All-Star Game on Feb. 14, and wrestling reports that
its core business jumped from $24 million to $200 million in the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hotter than ever,'' said Taylor, pointing to his Friday
night crowd of around 150 on Dec. 18 despite rain and temperatures
in the 30s. ``People can't get enough of it right now.''
VERY DIFFERENT NOW
</P>
<P>
   For those who thought pro wrestling died along with the Von
Erichs, Black Jack Mulligan, Fridays at Will Rogers, Saturdays at
The Sportatorium and Sundays with former masked Star-Telegram
``rasslin''' columnist Betty Ann Stout, this is not your father's
professional wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very different now,'' said Mark Lowrance, who made the
peculiar ring-to-pulpit leap from Sportatorium announcer in 1980-90
to pastor at Ovilla United Methodist Church. ``Back then there was
a great sense of community, the regulars would come early and eat
together. But I think they've gone from regional communities to
national conglomerates. And somewhere in there they've lost the
allure of the wrestler's struggles imitating life's struggles.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Fan's daily hurdles rarely include a 360-pound behemoth
talking to a stick horse, another dousing three enemies with
gasoline and approaching with a blowtorch, a man apparently wetting
himself in terror, or a supposed psychopath rendering an opponent
unconscious with a sock so dirty and repulsive that only he can
stand its stench. On a recent Monday night, each happened on live
television.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the warring WWF and WCW employ 200 wrestlers, none
of whom would be mistaken for your neighbor, YMCA guidance
counselor or even political leader. A far cry from the days when
NFL hall-of-famer Bronko Nagurski held the heavyweight belt in '38,
today's ``heels'' (bad guys) are characters like
Hulk-turned-Hollywood Hogan, WWF president Vince McMahon and a
6-foot-10, 340-pounder named The Undertaker. The ``babyfaces''
(good guys) include Goldberg, who once played for the Atlanta
Falcons, Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura and Stone Cold Steve Austin.
</P>
<P>
   You say America needs role models? From Victoria in South Texas,
the 33-year-old Austin has risen to the top with raunchy language
and an upturned middle finger. Reluctant to steal the ``Steve
Austin'' character from the 1970s bionic series The Six Million
Dollar Man, Austin _ born Steve Anderson _ added the Stone Cold to
his stage name after watching an HBO documentary about serial
killer Richard Kuklinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically just a redneck from Texas who worked his way up
from the loading docks,'' Austin said.
</P>
<P>
   But no one has done more to hurl wrestling in the spotlight than
NBA stars Dennis Rodman and Karl Malone and, of course, the new
governor of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who shocked the nation when he won his state's race on
the Reform Party, gives unscripted speeches, promises $1,000
kick-backs to all taxpayers, is open to the idea of
government-controlled prostitution and showed up for last weekend's
NFC Championship Game at the Metrodome wearing a buckskin suit,
Jimi Hendrix T-shirt, bandana and a large hoop earring.
SKILLS ARE REAL
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, there is wrestling reality.
</P>
<P>
   First, prospective wrestlers must learn the fundamentals at a
three-month wrestling class in Dallas or at the Speedway Arena. The
most ambitious will then go to Atlanta's Power Plant, an intense,
three-day boot camp where participants pay $250 for a chance to be
discovered by the WWF and WCW. For most, however, the lifestyle is
akin to being a rodeo clown, traveling town to town, dressing up in
costume and putting on semi-dangerous shows for meager salaries.
</P>
<P>
   At the local National Wrestling Alliance Southwest _ practicing
in America since '48 and currently the only weekly performance in
Texas _ the lifestyle is more Class A than Major League. Instead of
$5 million salaries like Hogan, there are $50-$150 checks at the
end of the night. Instead of a limo waiting to usher the wrestlers
to the airport and a flight to the next sold-out pay-per-view
extravaganza, there is a carpool driving across the street to
Hooters for dinner and a date the next night in Wichita Falls or
Glen Rose.
</P>
<P>
   On this dreary December night, fans have driven from Mesquite
and Weatherford to hold up signs and exchange obscenities with a
340-pound character named Bullman Downs. He wears a set of horns on
his head, a huge ring through his nose and couldn't be hurt by a
bulldozer, yet he somehow gets pinned by a clean-cut wrestler half
his size.
</P>
<P>
   There is a $10 admission, a dusty Foosball table in the corner,
real spit, real sweat, enough missed calls to make NFL referees
look competent, and, of course, wide-eyed fans believing every
second of it.
</P>
<P>
   One fan wears a Stars jersey and holds up a sign that reads
``Spare.'' Near the walkway leading to the curtained-off locker
room, an overweight fan waits for her attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey you ugly moose!'' the girl screams at Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're so fat they probably made you buy two tickets,'' he
yells back.
</P>
<P>
   As the Patsy Cline music blares to signal intermission, the girl
high-fives her friend and rushes off for nachos before the night's
main event, a bout in which the loser will have to leave the arena
wearing a dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you can release the fantasy,'' said 43-year-old
computer programmer William Jenkins of Colleyville. ``I know it's
silly, but I'm so calm and relaxed when I leave here. It's like a
another world where you can just drop your inhibitions. It just
gets your blood boiling. Not just the wrestling, but the sub-plots
when they grab the microphone and talk trash to each other. It's
great.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Taylor will continue to run his weekly shows in
relative obscurity while the big-ticket events stream through
Dallas. He said he envisions a day when he can bring 2,000 a night
to venues in Fort Worth and Dallas and increase his television
exposure from the 600,000 cable homes in seven cities he currently
boasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't like hearing it, but America wants
wrestling,'' Taylor said. ``My vision is to return to the glory
days of the '80s when it was about the hottest thing in town. I
think we can do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
