<HEADER>
A5727 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLSTARSNOTES-COX     01-23 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLSTARSNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Want scoring? All-Star Game usually has goals aplenty
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The average NHL team is scoring less than three
goals per game. The good news, for the league's panicking marketing
department, is scoring trends seldom hold for one of its showcase
events.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive season, the NHL All-Star Game will
pit U.S. and Canadian players against Europeans tonight at the Ice
Palace. But regardless of the format, goaltenders tend to come out
of this game with a nervous twitch.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen goals were scored in last year's All-Star Game in
Vancouver. Teams have combined for an average of 16.5 goals in the
eight games in the 1990s, including 22 in 1993, when the Wales
Conference defeated the Campbell Conference 16-6. One has to go
back to 1986 to find when there even was as few as seven goals
scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the season most teams play with four lines and each one
can do something different,'' said Boston defenseman Ray Bourque,
who is playing in his 16th game. ``Here, all four lines are the
same. They all have firepower. Don't ask these guys to check. It's
all about scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of players surveyed Saturday were against the idea
of the league changing more rules in an attempt to increase scoring
in the regular season.Ferrall on the bench
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Thrashers are talking with national sports radio
talkshow host Scott Ferrall about being a member of their broadcast
team, possibly as the play-by-play announcer. Ferrall now has a
late-night syndicated show. Ferrall never has done play-by-play but
would bring a certain celebrity status to the booth.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement watch
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky admits he has ``thought about the fact this could
be my last All-Star game,'' given the chance he may retire after
the season. But he quickly added, ``I wouldn't read too much into
that because I thought the same thing going into last year's
All-Star game in Vancouver.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
