<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-HISTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTILITY HELPS TITLE SNEAK UP ON ATLANTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUWANEE, Ga. _ When the football cleared the crossbar, Mr.
Falcon froze.
</P>
<P>
   Here it was, the moment he had been waiting for, literally since
Day 1, and Tommy Nobis didn't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a strange, weird, awkward feeling,'' Nobis said.
``Like, what do I do? Do I cheer? Jump up and down? What?''
</P>
<P>
   Forgive his confusion. Nobis has spent the last 33 years with
the Atlanta Falcons, a franchise that has been a model of futility
throughout much of its existence. Indeed, to Atlanta, Nobis, the
first player in Falcons' history and a team executive since his
retirement in 1976, is still the most recognizable symbol of the
team _ which might not necessarily be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   So when Morten Andersen's field goal in overtime last Sunday
completed a remarkable upset of Minnesota that put the Falcons into
the Super Bowl for the first time, Nobis expected a flag, an
inadvertent whistle _ anything that would bring him back to
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the stuff that's happening, where they bring the
trophy up and all that, and you're saying to yourself over and
over, `Those are our guys up there,' '' he said. ``It's a very
exciting time, but it's almost like you're waiting for someone to
come and take this away from us, or maybe someone's going to wake
me up. Reporters would come up and ask me for a comment, and I
didn't make any sense at all. I was just wondering, is this really
true?''
</P>
<P>
   As hard as it is to believe, the Atlanta Falcons, the team that
had an all-time winning percentage of .383 coming into this season,
a team that has hired the losingest coach in NFL history twice, is
going to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the Falcons going to the Super Bowl is akin to
Willie B., the famed gorilla at the local zoo, reciting
Shakespeare. Something so shocking, so ridiculous that it defies
the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't say, `The Falcons are going to the Super Bowl,'
without laughing,'' said Marc Roth, an Atlanta engineer and
self-described long-suffering Falcons fan. ``As I was driving home
after the game last week, I kept saying it over and over. I just
can't believe it.'' From the abyss In their 32 previous seasons,
the Falcons won a grand total of one division championship and
advanced to the playoffs only five times. Their greatest moment
came when they led the Cowboys by 14 points in the fourth quarter
of a 1980 divisional playoff game. One of their worst came that
same afternoon, when Danny White led the Cowboys to a 30-27
comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there weren't lowlights by the truckload. Once, in the
early days, a fistfight broke out in the Falcons' offensive huddle.
In a game in 1970, Jim ``Cannonball'' Butler, who the season before
was chosen the team's player of the year, set two club records _
yards rushing in a game (127) and fumbles (4).
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, team officials stopped the season's final game to honor
Dave Hampton when he became the first Falcon to crack 1,000 yards
rushing. On the next play, he lost six yards and finished the
season with 995. When the team threatened to move to Jacksonville
in the late '80s, fans were so disillusioned with the city's
then-woeful professional sports franchises that a popular bumper
sticker read, ``Go Falcons! And take the Braves with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The low point came in 1989, when the Falcons slogged to a 3-13
record and had to deal with the deaths of two teammates in traffic
accidents and the firing of coach Marion Campbell with four games
left. They finished with a seven-game losing streak capped by a
31-24 home loss to Detroit on Christmas Eve before an all-time low
crowd of 7,792.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly every decision backfired. The team's owners, insurance
executive Rankin Smith Sr. and his four children, were derided as
``The Clampetts,'' those naive hayseeds in ``The Beverly
Hillbillies''. Smith was notorious for bringing in ineffective
coaches _ he hired Campbell, who owns the lowest winning percentage
in NFL history for coaches with more than 60 games, in 1974 and
again in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to stay as positive as possible, and optimistic that
one day it'll happen,'' said linebacker Jessie Tuggle, who has
spent his entire 12-year career with the Falcons. ``My brother
would tease me all the time. `How can you be so positive? You guys
are terrible.' He'd always tell me the team's not ready, and I'd
always think, no, we're going to do it, we're going to do it. Then
we'd start losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this year. Just two seasons removed from their latest 3-13
debacle, the Falcons blew through the regular season at 14-2, the
best record in their history. They knocked San Francisco from its
customary perch atop the NFC West standings and beat the 49ers
again in the playoffs. And they roared back from a 10-point
fourth-quarter deficit on the road last week to upend the heavily
favored Vikings and win a trip to Miami to face defending champion
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just reaffirms my belief that anyone can win the
lottery,'' said Mike Kenn, a five-time Pro Bowl tackle who played
17 seasons in Atlanta. Bittersweet success But this isn't merely
luck. The Falcons are playing for the NFL title because on Jan. 20,
1997, Smith finally hired the right man, bringing in former Broncos
and Giants coach Dan Reeves as coach and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation did not happen immediately. Halfway through
his first season, Reeves' Falcons were 1-7 and floundering. But
that didn't last long. Atlanta won five of its last six to finish
at 7-9, and then took off this year. Since their horrid start in
'97, the Falcons have won 22 of their past 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy to this newfound success is that Smith, who was
awarded the expansion franchise for $8.5 million in 1966, didn't
live to see it. He died of heart complications at the age of 71 on
Oct. 26, 1997, hours before his team lost to Carolina to drop to
1-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Mr. Smith died, he came in to see me,'' Reeves said.
``We were 1-6 at the time. He walks in _ it's the first time I'd
seen him all season _ and I was apologetic about where we were. But
instead of agreeing that I needed to apologize, he talked about how
happy he was about the direction we were going and how we had a
chance in every one of those games and how competitive we'd been
and how he knew we were going to turn it around. That was the last
time I saw him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant an awful lot to have an owner come in and tell you
he feels you're going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans, however, weren't so quick on the uptake. Jaded by
years of disappointment, they had abandoned the team long before,
and a strong finish in '97 wasn't enough to bring them back. Only
42,866 showed up for the '97 home finale and as late as Nov. 1,
only 37,996 attended a victory over St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   When the 71,229-seat Georgia Dome at last sold out for a
first-place showdown with San Francisco two weeks later, it marked
the Falcons' first sellout in three years.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the fans are surely getting it. Some 4,000 met the
team at Hartsfield International Airport when it returned from
Minneapolis last Sunday, and an equal number were turned away by
officials for safety reasons. When the players arrived at the
team's facility in Suwanee, thousands more were waiting. Each day,
they crowd the entrance to the complex before and after practice,
hoping a player will stop on the way out to sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an amazing difference,'' defensive tackle Travis
Hall said. ``There's this grocery store I go to almost every day,
and once in awhile someone might recognize me or say something. The
other day I went in there and all of a sudden 15 people want my
autograph. Before, I never had anyone ask me for tickets during the
season, but by the end of the year I had people calling me up, `Can
you get me tickets?' for sold out games. Because we never had that
problem before.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tuggle: ``We knew once we started winning, the fans would
get behind us, and, oh, my God, they're really behind us. It's just
crazy here. But this is the kind of craziness we've all been
waiting for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
