<HEADLINE>
(RE)-INTRODUCING THE ROOKIE CLASS OF 1999
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They don't know the loopholes in illegal defense, or how much to
tip, or that crossing referee Steve Javie could severely reduce
their walking-around scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, they are...the rookie class of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And they're not all stuck in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, in the seeming eternity since they were embraced by the
NBA with a handshake from David Stern and a baseball cap, you may
have forgotten who they are.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a remedy, an examination of which newcomers may join
the sign-and-trade, catch-and-release free agents in shaping a new
NBA. We're not offering a comprehensive list, just a roll call of
those rookies who may provide the most intrigue:
</P>
<P>
   Jason Williams: Here's a relatively short (6-foot-1) white point
guard who was kicked off the Florida team last year. Williams
received the `violation of team rules` sentence, but was acquitted
of the charge that he didn't shoot enough.
</P>
<P>
   Did this cause him to drop in the draft? Absolutely, all the way
to No. 7, where the new-look (as opposed to no-look) Sacramento
Kings made him their own. So ... is he the juvie-hall edition of
Pete Maravich, or a not-exactly ground-bound version John Stockton?
</P>
<P>
   Robert `Tractor` Traylor: This guy was landed by Dallas with the
sixth pick, then air-lifted to Milwaukee. At 6-8, 300 pounds, the
ex-Michigan post monster was a risky acquisition. But he's
misplaced a lot of weight and is prepared to make Bucks fans forget
about Jamie Feick.
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Nowitzki: He was imported from Germany by Milwaukee with
the ninth pick, then presented to Don Nelson and the Mavericks in
the Traylor deal. This 6-11 20-year-old has skills that suggest
he's the love child of Toni Kukoc and a relative of Detlef
Schrempf. Since Kukoc couldn't guard a lawn jockey, Dallas goalie
Shawn Bradley may be busy.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Benjamin: This Fontana kid was drafted by the Bulls with
the final pick in the first round. He's 6-6 and capable of banging
dunks, which should make him the favorite of those Chicago fans who
bother to watch.
</P>
<P>
   In his second (and final) season at Oregon State, Benjamin
improved his scoring average by five points per game, and his
field-goal percentage rose from 43 to 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter: The ex-Tar Heel was drafted by Golden State with
the fifth pick, then sent to Toronto in exchange for Carolina crony
Antawn Jamison. He has enough talent and flair to at least star as
Michael Jordan in a made-for-TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   subhead Snake eyes for McDyess?
</P>
<P>
   Antonio McDyess and Nick Van Exel are buds, which is the popular
explanation for why Antonio signed with Denver instead of
re-signing for more money with a better team (Phoenix).
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Van Exel was in L.A. while McDyess was shooting 47 percent
from the field during his first two seasons with the Nuggets. But
he also wasn't in Phoenix last season when McDyess made 53 percent
of his field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect in these high-quality, percentage-boosting dimes is
Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead Not ready for prime Tim
</P>
<P>
   With freshman forward Quentin Richardson and his young DePaul
entourage maturing at a rapid rate, the Bulls may have gone from
the best hoop team on Earth to the second best in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   At least they have a young genius in new coach Tim Floyd. But
aside from the notion of Randy Brown in the starting lineup, Bulls
are concerned about something else: if Floyd is such a wonderful
coach, why did only one of his teams reach the NCAA Tournament's
Sweet Sixteen in his 10-plus seasons?
</P>
<P>
   Subhead Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Point forward Scottie Pippen should feel comfy with the Rockets,
who - like the Bulls - haven't had a point guard in years. ... When
his ego is considered, it looks doubtful that the melon of Chicago
GM Jerry Krause will ever have enough cap room. ... You'll want to
be in D.C. on Feb. 25 for the return of new Sacramento King Chris
Webber. ... The pre-draft buzz indicates that European prospects
will add little depth to the already shallow 1999 pool. What a
shame. ... Spike Lee, No. 1 fan of the New York Knicks and director
of the hit hoop joint `He Got Game,` is expected to direct a film
on the life and crimes of new Knick Latrell Sprewell. The working
title is `He Got Away With It.` According to sources beyond our
control, Sprewell recently turned down the opportunity to provide
his voice for a role in Eddie Murphy's claymation sitcom `The PJs.`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
