<HEADER>
A5734 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLEAST24-COX     01-23 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eastern Conference notes: I'm fired
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After firing himself as coach for the second time in two years,
New York Islanders general manager Mike Milbury at least could be
comforted by one thing. ``I didn't get any applause for it (from
the players),'' he said ``But they might do that later.'' They
should. Milbury, who has more than four years remaining on a
contract that pays him $750,000 annually, resigned just a few hours
before the Isles won in Pittsburgh for new coach Bill Stewart.
Stewart went into the All-Star break with a 1-0 record, after New
York had gone 0-10-1 in the previous 11 under Milbury. But he
should not count on much job security. Stewart is the team's fifth
coach in six seasons, following Al Arbour, Lorne Henning, Milbury,
Rick Bowness and Milbury again. Milbury took over as general
manager in 1995. His record as an Islanders coach is 56-111-24.
Fans in Nassau Coliseum recently had taken to chanting, ``Mike must
go.'' Truth is, he tried to go before the season, shopping himself
as a candidate for the Thrashers general manager's position. But he
never was interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Closeout sale
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay general manager and coach Jacques Demers is asking new
owner Art Williams to be patient, but the Lightning's turnaround
will be slow in coming. Demers is in the middle of a housecleaning.
He traded forward Craig Janney to the New York Islanders for the
marked-down price of a sixth-round draft pick. He is expected to
complete another deal this week, probably involving either goalie
Bill Ranford or forward Stephane Richer. At 11-30-4 and in the
Southeast Division basement, Demers is kissing off the rest of the
season, even if he doesn't quite put it in those words. ``I'm
trying to stockpile some draft picks,'' Demers said, ``and if I can
reduce the payroll a little we can go after some free agents next
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Scandal sheet
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a great season by Ottawa, Senators captain
Alexei Yashin finds himself in the middle of a mess. Yashin
committed $1 million over five years to the National Arts Centre
but closed his checkbook after his first annual $200,000 payment.
Why? Yashin said he had a side deal with former arts center chief
John Cripton that mandated the center pay his parents $85,000
through Tatiana Entertainment Inc. Other officials knew nothing
about the deal and never made the payment. Cripton recently lost
his position. Ottawa lawyer David Scott said he thinks the
agreement is ``illegal, unenforceable and could not possibly be
honored by the NAC.'' Yashin's parents were to provide some
undefined services for the annual payments, but Scott said, ``It is
now recognized that the intent was that such payments would not be
dependent upon the actual delivery of services.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.:
</P>
<P>
   Forward Peter Nedved got off to a fast start after the Rangers
signed him _ eight goals and 13 assists in 16 games _ but has only
one goal and one assist in the last 10. ``He's been dried out for
how many games?'' coach John Muckler asked. ``That's where the
goals have to come from.'' . . . Philadelphia is 12-1-5 in its last
18 and 19-4-6 in the last 29, outscoring opponents 100-52 in that
span. . . . Tampa rookie Vincent Lecavalier is a plus-three in his
last 22 games on a horrendous team, evidence of his improvement
since early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
