</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-MEXICO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE OFFERS VISION OF THE FUTURE FOR AMERICAS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA AND RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Inside one of Roman Catholicism's holiest shrines,
Pope John Paul II unveiled a sweeping vision Saturday for the
church's next century in America, exhorting it to minister to the
needs of poor and rich alike and to follow Jesus by championing a
society free of torture, drugs, and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Giving parts of his homily in Spanish, English, French, and
Portuguese, the 78-year-old pontiff called on Catholics to make
America a ``continent of life. This is our cry: life with dignity
for all!''
</P>
<P>
   ``For all who have been conceived in their mother's womb, for
street children, for indigenous peoples and Afro-Americans, for
immigrants and refugees, for the young deprived of opportunity, for
the old, for those who suffer any kind of poverty or
marginalization,'' John Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Summarizing a 24-page document on the most important day of his
six-day tour of Mexico and the United States, the pontiff balanced
criticism of capitalism and financial speculation with a call for
the church not to ignore the movers and shakers of society.
</P>
<P>
   His guideline for the church in the Americas also touched on
pressing regional issues such as rights, foreign debt, narcotics
trafficking, political corruption, and the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 30 years, the church in Latin America has been
guided by a ``preferential option for the poor,'' John Paul said _
a philosophy the pope believes had certain Marxist undertones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in part because of an approach to the pastoral care of
the poor marked by a certain exclusiveness that the pastoral care
for the leading sectors of society has been neglected and many
people have thus been estranged from the church,'' the pope said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this evangelization of the leadership sector is neglected,
it not should come as a surprise that many who are a part of it
will be guided by criteria alien to the Gospel and at times openly
contrary to it,'' the pope added.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers here saw that comment as an attempt to bury any
more debate of liberation theology, the ideology used for 30 years
among some Latin American clergy and nuns to challenge economic
inequities and oppressive goverments.
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff made public his landmark document at a special Mass
inside the massive Basilica of Our Lady of Guadalupe, the site
where the church says a dark-skinned Virgin Mary appeared to a
peasant boy in 1531 and became the spark for Catholicism to take
root in the new world.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the sacred place the shrine occupies in church
history, it was perhaps a fitting arena for John Paul to offer a
comprehensive blueprint designed to re-energize the church in the
Americas, home to half the world's 1 billion Catholics and crucial
to the future of the faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this moment in her history, the church in America is called
to respond to the fundamental task of evangelization,'' John Paul
said on the second day of his four-day visit to this city, where he
has been welcomed by millions of adoring people. ``A fresh
encounter with Jesus Christ will make all the members of the church
in America aware that they are called to continue the Redeemer's
mission in their lands.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope said the drive for social and economic justice must be
balanced with clear spiritual direction, or the church will
continue to lose Catholics to other denominations that place great
importance on the life of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church can in no way be confused with the political
community nor tied to any political system,'' he warned during the
liturgy. It was broadcast on two giant screens erected outside the
basilica, which was surrounded by thousands of people, some of whom
had camped out overnight to catch a glimpse of the pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   Looking rested and energized, John Paul began the morning with a
ride to the basilica on the northern fringes of the city, where
inside he prayed to the Virgin Mary's image. Along the way millions
of people greeted the pope with the kind of ardor that has endeared
John Paul to Mexico _ a country surpassed only by Brazil in the
number of Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the basilica, Adriana Saldana, 39, cried as she
described how the pope waved in her direction. ``He is Christ's
representative on earth,'' Saldana said, her hands shaking.
</P>
<P>
   While the pope's vision for the Americas did not break major new
theological ground, it probably will provoke intense debate within
the church, and it may serve as a statement for local Catholic
churches throughout the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the statement will be received in the United
States, where there is a wide gulf between lay people and the
church hierarchy. The document is the end result of a conclave of
bishops of the Americas held in Rome in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some theologians who studied the documents that emerged from the
1997 synod said they were not impressed with the ideas put forth
then. Many of them were incorporated into Saturday's papal
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The synod papers ``did not excite the imagination, inspire
enthusiasm or encourage hope,'' the Rev. Thomas J. Reese, a Vatican
scholar, wrote in the Jesuit magazine America.
</P>
<P>
   The statement is also being examined closely by the Mexican
government and its critics, who have castigated attempts to put
down indigenous uprisings, particularly in the southern state of
Chiapas. Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, John Paul met privately with the Mexican
president, Ernesto Zedillo, who expelled six priests from Chiapas
and accused them of fomenting rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   The apostolic exhortation, as John Paul's statement is
officially called, broadly reflected the criticisms the pope has
long held about a Western society _ strongly influenced by the
United States _ that he believes devalues life, worships money, and
denigrates religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays in America a model of society appeares to be emerging
in which the powerful predominate, setting aside and even
eliminating the powerless,'' the pope said. ``This model of society
bears the stamp of the culture of death, and is therefore in
opposition to the Gospel message.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americas, he said, are facing ``social sins which cry out to
heaven'' and are the consequence of a ``deep crisis caused by the
loss of a sense of God and the absence of those moral principles
which should guide the life of every person. In the absence of
moral points of reference, an ubridled greed for wealth and power
takes over, obscuring any Gospel-based vision of social reality.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul urged faithful lay Catholics to assume active
leadership roles in society and not to be afraid to be guided by
religious principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is urgent to train men and women who can influence public
life and direct it to the common good,'' he said. ``A deeper
knowledge of Christian ethical principles and moral values will
enable them to be exponents of these in their own particular
setting, proclaiming them even where appeals are made to the
so-called `neutrality of the state.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lorena Zarate, a Globe researcher, contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
