<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5739 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATORS-BOS &LR;      01-23 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS SENATORS FRUSTRATED BY TRIAL DUTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Edward M. Kennedy stood in his office,
waiting for the ritual. When reporters burst through the door,
Kennedy smoothed his jacket, ready to deliver what by now might be
called The Impeachment Statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there's a general sense that this doesn't rise to
the constitutional standard,'' he began, responding to a question
about the day's proceedings. ``I think it becomes clearer and
clearer that this, as reprehensible personal conduct as this
represents, it's personal conduct, and not conduct that undermines
the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, it was a frustrating _ and familiar _ reply. No
specifics. No hints about bipartisan negotiations. No opinion on
the details of the trial, no outrage at the latest comments by
Republicans. Nothing but the vagueness of a senator who can get
away with saying nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kennedy, too, might have reason to be frustrated. He has
been repeating himself for weeks, and he knew where he stood on
President Clinton's impeachment well before charts and videos were
dragged in.
</P>
<P>
   His doubts are, to a degree, shared by Senator John F. Kerry.
Despite their differences, both Massachusetts senators have felt
that the facts were there, and that they could be judged without
the proceedings that have taken place.
</P>
<P>
   But each has constructed his own justification for why the trial
should end, and the reasons differ. Kerry refuses to say whether he
would convict Clinton on the two counts of impeachment, only that
he thinks the facts are sufficient to take a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a former prosecutor,'' Kerry said last week. ``I've read
about it ahead of time, read up on it, and I came to the issue with
a strong interpretation of the facts as I saw them. Before the
trial started, before we ever sat down at our desks, I'd been
reading about this for a year, almost to the day . . . And I came
to the conclusion . . . that we had a very extensive record in a
case that is not particularly complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors, led by the Judiciary Committee chairman,
Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, have argued the opposite. They have
maintained that the factual details of the case require a full
hearing as well as witnesses to sort out discrepancies. In three
days, the 13 House ``managers'' also laid out arguments that
Clinton's alleged offenses _ perjury and obstruction of justice _
are ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' that meet the standard for his
removal.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy disagrees. But rather than deal with the details of the
prosecution _ where Clinton touched Lewinsky, what exactly the
president said to his secretary Betty Currie _ Kennedy has
concentrated on the second part of the case, the standards of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As the impeachment case made its way through the House of
Representatives, Kennedy favored censuring the president, and
hoped, aides said, that the ordeal would end quickly with a censure
motion.
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear in December that it would not, Kennedy
gathered up books on impeachment _ ``Grand Inquests,'' by Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist, and another on the 1868 impeachment
of President Andrew Johnson _ and brought them home for the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after that, Kennedy said, he had reached the conclusion
the House had no case. ``This is sort of a feeling you get,'' he
said in an interview. But, unlike Kerry, Kennedy said it was not
the factual disputes that troubled him most.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in the end of these two years, Mr. Starr feels there
ought'' to be a criminal trial, ``this ought to be reviewed,''
Kennedy said. ``That's always out there. That's not what we're
deciding here.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kennedy has been the constitutional historian, Kerry has
thought more like a defense attorney. He talks like a textbook
about the perjury charge. Perjury requires that several criteria be
met, and, Kerry said, ``there are serious questions on specific
intent and materiality that leap out at you by virtue of the White
House case.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry also says that there is a weak criminal case against
Clinton, and that the House would have needed to prove these
charges were true, and would hold up in a court of law, ``beyond a
reasonable doubt,'' before they could be used as a basis for
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry declined to point to specific flaws in their legal
argument, saying he would wait until the case is finished to speak
for the record.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``Since they have specifically marketed these as
felonies, and the president shouldn't stay in office because he's
committed a felony, we must find out first whether or not he has.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the senators' attitudes might seem obvious: Both
are Democrats, and both represent the state that gave Clinton his
highest margin of support in the 1996 election. Both have tried to
play a role in the politics of the trial, helping to guide the
Democratic position.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Kennedy joined a longtime adversary, Republican
Senator Phil Gramm of Texas, in forging a bipartisan agreement on
the impeachment rules.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kerry said he would like to see an early vote on the
articles of impeachment. This prompted a flurry of discussion about
whether witnesses needed to be called.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, their efforts are at the mercy of the Republican
majority. But any political maneuverings they manage to achieve are
likely to be their legacy from the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that will work its way through the processes
of discussions,'' Kerry said. ``Hopefully, the Senate will work in
its special way here to sort of pull together and bring this to an
end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
