<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5744 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PRICE-FUNERAL-COX     01-23 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PRICE-FUNERAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Service remembers the best of Price
 &HT;    By Emily Morris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKWOOD, Texas _ Katrina Price knew how to pack a house.
</P>
<P>
   In life, her fans rallied around her at Ladyjack games where she
made a name for herself as Stephen F. Austin's leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   In death, she left behind a legacy that will long be remembered
by fans both near and far.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest church in Oakwood, Texas was overflowing Saturday
with the family, friends and fans of Ms. Price.
</P>
<P>
   With her family to the left of her casket and her teammates to
the right, the people who loved her the most said their goodbyes
during a tearful two-hour funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Price committed suicide last Monday at her sister's
apartment in Nacogdoches.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers from areas across the state offered condolences during
the ceremony, but it was her sister who offered what might have
been regarded as the most meaningful words of all.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Price was the only witness to the tragedy that resulted in
Katrina's death.
</P>
<P>
   She pleaded with mourners Saturday to remember her sister not
for the way she died, but for the way she lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Katrina knew how to pack a house,'' Lucy said as she looked
out over the crowd. ``I've thought about what I was going to say
today, and I can tell you from the bottom of my heart that I mean
all of it. Katrina will always be my big sister, and she will
always be my best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   With her family by her side at the podium, Lucy Price remembered
when her mother used to dress her two youngest daughters like
twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we got older, Katrina grew into her own person, and I grew
into mine,'' Lucy said. ``She showed us all the person she was when
she played basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy said she never minded following in the shadow of Katrina,
and she was always proud to be Katrina's sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her last week how proud I was of her,'' Lucy said.
``She was sitting on the edge of my bed at my house, and I told her
I never minded being the sister of Katrina Price.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy said one of the ways she expressed her pride in Katrina was
by writing about her for The Pine Log, a student publication of
SFA.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to commemorate the 75th anniversary of SFA,
Lucy was given the assignment of writing a story in honor of the
occasion. When she was short on ideas, her professor suggested
writing a story about Katrina.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy agreed to do so and decided to interview her sister
personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fought her battles, and she fought mine,'' Lucy said. ``I've
lived her life. She was my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy said the story she wrote was the easiest assignment she
ever completed for school.
</P>
<P>
   During the one-on-one interview, Katrina told Lucy she wouldn't
have played basketball for any school but SFA, which inspired Lucy
to interview the women's basketball coach, Royce Chadwick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he had heard all about the girl from LaVega, (where
Katrina attended high school,) and that she was just like the girl
next door. And she could play,'' Lucy said. ``When Katrina read my
story, her eyes kept going back to that one sentence. She just had
this smile on her face, and she asked me if he really said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy said another quote from Chadwick has replayed itself over
and over in her mind since Katrina's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that in years to come, Ladyjack faithfuls will still
be talking about Katrina Price,'' Lucy said. ``She was a loving,
caring person. She was the most excellent, outstanding example of
what a young lady should be. It's not about how she died; it's
about how she lived. That's what people need to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy told the mourners to laugh with the people they love and
cry with them, because there's no assurance of tomorrow for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   SFA President Dr. Dan Angel offered remarks next.
</P>
<P>
   ``SFA knew Katrina Price, and we loved her,'' he said. ``I can
think of many vignettes of Katrina, and I remember the night we had
a special stand set up to record the points she scored, becuase she
was about to become the highest scorer we ever had. There was a
packed house that night, and the crowd celebrated every point with
her. She was a very special person both on and off the court. She
was a very special person in our minds and in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Katrina's high school basketball coach spoke next and told the
family what a rare and wonderful opportunity it was to coach a
person like her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was, but she had it,'' he said. ``On
behalf of LaVega, I extend my sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ministers and speakers offered their condolences and sympathy,
and resolutions were read in honor of Katrina and her family.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers from Houston, Waco, Clifton, Mineola, Oakwood,
Fairfield, Lufkin and Nacogdoches introduced themselves
individually, and members of the Ladyjacks basketball team were
recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Katrina's life was documented in a six-page program handed out
before the funeral, and pictures illustrated her life from her
childhood through the time she was a star player at SFA.
</P>
<P>
   Katrina attended Oakwood Public Schools through the fifth grade,
then LaVega Public Schools. She received a basketball scholarship
to SFA, and graduated cum laude with a degree in kinesiology in
May, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While at SFA, Katrina was an All-American basketball player,
SFA's all-time leading scorer, a GTE Academic All-American (1st
team), and on the dean's list every semester.
</P>
<P>
   She was the seventh overall draft pick of the American
Basketball League, and played for the Philadelphia Rage.
</P>
<P>
   Katrina was working on a master's degree in kinesiology and was
employed by Nacogdoches ISD at the time of her death.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Morris writes for The Daily Sentinel, Nacogdoches, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
