<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BIPARTISAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVES ON LEWINSKY UPSET SENATE BIPARTISANSHIP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In party caucuses and private meetings, the Senate
struggled Saturday to revive the bipartisanship that many members
said gave dignity to the unpleasant task of sorting through
President Clinton's liaison with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to be a losing battle.
</P>
<P>
   Just when many senators believed the Clinton trial was calmly
reaching its final stage, anger erupted over news that Lewinsky had
arrived in Washington after House prosecutors secretly won a court
order to compel her to answer more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats do not want witnesses to appear at the trial, and the
House move was a reminder that their effort to end the trial
quickly must overcome the desire of many Republicans for a
lengthier trial that includes witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been heading into calm water,'' said Senator Robert
Kerrey, Democrat of Nebraska. But the House prosecutors' approach
to Lewinsky made it unlikely that the trial will conclude swifty
and without rancor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a judicial act of terrorism that has left everyone
befuddled,'' Kerrey said. ``An explosion has gone off, and
everyone's ears are ringing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a climate, a feeling that we maybe could find a way
to conclude this,'' said Senator Byron Dorgan, a Democrat from
North Dakota. But that feeling is slipping away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, said Democrats are ``all
in a lather'' about the House prosecutors' move. But he dismissed
their complaints, saying the Senate prerogative to call or not call
Lewinsky or other witnesses was intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a technical diversion that doesn't amount to a gnat,''
Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Senator Robert Byrd, a West Virginia Democrat who is
respected by both parties, announced that he would introduce a
motion as early as  &UR; tomorrow &LR;  to dismiss the charges against
Clinton and end the trial. Democrats said they hoped Byrd's motion
would draw support from the six Republicans they need for a
majority among the 55 Senate Republicans and 45 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the revived partisanship Saturday, some Democrats began
talking up a proposal they called ``motion to dismiss plus,'' which
would combine Byrd's proposal with language censuring Clinton in an
attempt to draw Republican votes. The motion might cite the
president for bringing ``shame and dishonor'' to his office, said
Senator John Breaux, Democrat of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a properly worded motion to dismiss can garner enough
votes to pass,'' Breaux said in an interview in the Capitol
basement, where a subway whisks lawmakers from the House and Senate
chambers to their offices nearby. Some Republicans want to end the
trial, he said, but they would only vote to do it if they could
also show their disapproval of the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But if there were signs of movement Saturday, the movement was
away from a quick end to the trial. Only Friday, Senator Orrin
Hatch, Republican of Utah, raised hopes of a speedy finish by
proposing that the Senate should halt the trial if it was clear the
constitutionally required two-thirds margin to convict the
president did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, however, Hatch said his proposal always included the
caveat that the trial not end until both sides have ``a full chance
to present their case,'' which might require the Senate to move
beyond depositions and take time to hear witness testimony in the
well of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans opposed a ``motion to dismiss plus'' outright.
Senator John Warner, Republican of Virginia, said the idea would
deprive him of the right to vote on the articles of impeachment.
``I want the opportunity to stand up and face my state, and 99
other senators, and say where I stand on whether to remove or not
remove'' the president, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rancorous feelings also rose Saturday as Democrats
complained that Lott, the Repubican leader, was aiming to shorten
the trial by eliminating a proposed debate among senators on the
motion to dismiss, which could have lasted as long as 16 hours.
</P>
<P>
   That discussion was to be held behind closed doors, but it would
have been the first chance for debate among the senators, who must
remain silent in the Senate chamber during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Lott's motion would not only deprive them of a
chance for debate, but that the debate in fact should be held in
public. Lott sidestepped questions about whether debate would occur
in private, in public, or even at all.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat, Senator Kent Conrad of North Dakota, summed up his
colleagues' frustration with the Republican display of muscle:
``They have fractured a sense of fair-dealing,'' he said. ``I just
think they've left people with a bad taste in their mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators met twice in private Saturday, but there
were no signs that either Lott's proposal or a ``motion to dismiss
plus'' had enough votes to succeed. ``We're discussing
everything,'' Lott said after emerging from a lunch meeting with
his GOP colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Dorgan, the North Dakota Democrat, said that one thing was sure:
New proposals on how to end the trial would emerge soon. ``In
weather terms, there are a lot of fronts moving,'' he said. ``The
weather in any one spot is variable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
