<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-STARSADVANCE-     01-23 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-STARSADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commissioner non-committal on Olympics question
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ One month after saying television coverage would
be the single greatest determining factor in whether the NHL
participates in the 2002 Winter Olympics, league commissioner Gary
Bettman waffled on the subject Saturday night, saying ''a whole
host of issues'' will determine the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman, meeting with the media on the eve of the NHL All-Star
game, denied he was backing off previous comments. But it was the
strongest indication yet that the NHL has not and will not receive
any assurances by NBC as to how high of a priority men's hockey
will rate in its coverage from Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not backing off on it,'' Bettman said. ''I'm just choosing
not to be specific as to where the discussions are at this time.
Television is important. (But) I'm more comfortable not discussing
what NBC has or hasn't indicated to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman last month said, ''The threshold issue is what kind of
television coverage we get in the U.S.'' NBC spokesman Ed Markey
subsequently told the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, ''We're not
close to making any programming decisions for Salt Lake City. We're
still working on Sydney (2000 Summer Olympics).''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman, who met with the league's owners earlier in the day,
reiterated that a decision likely would come in late February. But
he made a point of saying that the ''overwhelming sentiment'' from
players is that they want to participate in the Games. He also
happened to mention that ''fan polls'' indicate they want the NHL
to return to the Olympics, despite the fact the league's maiden
voyage in Nagano was disastrous: Neither the U.S. nor Canada
medaled, and a few American players trashed two dorm rooms in the
Olympic Village hours after being eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, who will be retired by 2002, said the league
should participate in Salt Lake City regardless of the TV coverage,
saying, ''It's still an opportunity to get some great exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Brendan Shanahan said that if NBC decides against
slotting hockey in prime time, ''I think they'll be sorry when it's
over. Team USA in hockey will be one of the most publicized teams
going into the Olympics, whether it's for good reasons or bad
reasons. Women's figure skating got its big boost from a beating
(the Tonya Harding-Nancy Kerrigan saga). So maybe men's hockey will
get its boost from a room trashing.''
</P>
<P>
   The players involved in the room trashings never stepped
forward. The league suspects three players but decided against
disciplining them because it had no proof.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't care whether they stepped forward or not,'' said
Shanahan, who is Canadian. ''There's all these people stepping
forward in America today. I admire their silence. These guys really
should be working for (Bill) Clinton. He wouldn't be in the trouble
he is today if Team USA was working for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said the majority of the league owners want to
participate in the Games ''if it makes sense.'' He said revelations
of corruption by the IOC and Salt Lake City organizing committee
would not impact the NHL. If the Games are moved, he said, ''We'd
have to look at that. But I think they'll get their house in
order.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
