<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS STILL A POSSIBILITY FOR CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM DESERT _ The eyes of a nation remain focused on Washington,
where the contentious relationship between Rod Strickland and the
Wizards (well, his agent, David Falk, and their owner, Abe Pollin)
may be keeping the engine of Sherman Douglas on idle.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, New Jersey's free-agent point guard, still may end up
as the No.1 floor leader in Washington if Strickland is moved.
Meanwhile, the Nets have hired Eric Murdock to take Douglas' place
as insurance for Sam Cassell, and the Clippers _ a leading player
in the Sherman Sweepstakes _ re-signed incumbent Darrick Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But this doesn't guarantee that Douglas won't become a Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   According to a league source, that window hasn't closed. The
Clippers still have $3.2 million in beneath-the-salary-cap booty,
which should be more than enough for a 32-year-old reserve point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   But the cap room could be saved and used to facilitate a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kandi'' gram: While the official liberation date of top draft
pick Michael Olowokandi remains Feb. 15, the Clippers are hoping
the 7-foot-1 rookie can be sprung a bit sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi, whose contract with Italy's Kinder Bologna has an
escape clause, may be able to break out after a game on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Kinder may go a bit more gently on this issue because Olowokandi
could be replaced by Sean Marks, a 6-foot-10 rookie from Cal.
Marks, like Olowokandi, is represented by agent Bill Duffy, who
still couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Juaquin in place: Former Lynwood High and Long Beach State
forward Juaquin Hawkins is one of five free agents in camp. The
6-foot-7 lefty has been going places since finishing his college
career in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerary: Lakers camp, seven months in Taiwan, four months
in China, a season with the Long Island Surf of the USBL and... a
tour with the Harlem Globetrotters. Hawkins, who brings a
reputation for defense, was traveling with the Globetrotters when
the Clippers called.
</P>
<P>
   With NBA teams allowed to keep 14 players for the season's first
two weeks, Hawkins likes his chances to stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really optimistic,'' he said. ``There are a lot of good
players here, but I feel like I'm a good player, too. I'm just
thankful that they (Clippers) were nice enough to invite me.''
</P>
<P>
   Free hoops: The Clippers' public scrimmage will be held from 7
to 9 p.m., Feb. 2 at the Sports Arena. Admission and parking are
free. The Clippers Spirit dance team will be dancing and an
interactive fun zone will be open.
</P>
</TEXT>
