u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-JANEFRO     01-23 1755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-JANEFROST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROST HELPS OUT THE BEST OF 'EM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jane Frost put the winter behind her last week when she went to
Florida, but she got more than warm weather once she arrived in
Orlando. She also spent some time with LPGA legend Nancy Lopez, and
when you have committed your life to teaching this great game, it
doesn't get much better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had met before, last year, when I was named to the advisory
board of her equipment line,'' said Frost, who was back at the
Holly Ridge Golf Course pro shop in Sandwich just a few days after
giving lessons to arguably the finest player in LPGA history.
``Apparently she must have liked what I was saying because she
asked for some putting help in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the start of the LPGA season's first event, the
HealthSound Inaugural, Frost spent the better part of two days
watching Lopez putt and offering advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't try to change my stroke,'' said Lopez, citing a
fear that prevents many players from seeking out instructors. ``She
just helped me get into my routine.''
</P>
<P>
   That Lopez would seek out Frost is an honor for the local pro,
but it should not come as a surprise. Frost's resume speaks
volumes. In 1994, she was named LPGA Teacher of the Year, and just
recently she was cited by Golf Magazine as one of America's Top 100
Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way she teaches,'' said Lopez, who, as a Hall of
Fame player, is a creditable source.
</P>
<P>
   What defines Frost's personality, though, is her passion for
teaching, whether the student is a three-time major winner who has
earned more than $5 million or a youngster who gets her kicks by
beating her father in contests at the Holly Ridge putting green.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that days after the thrill of giving lessons to Lopez,
Frost was equally proud to hear the news about Brittany Weddell.
Playing at Holly Ridge last Sunday, Weddell scored a hole-in-one at
the 113-yard fourth hole, a memorable shot to say the least, but
even more so if you are just 7 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Frost has watched Weddell the past few years and gets a charge
out of the girl's enthusiasm for the game. It will be fun to watch
her grow and compete, said Frost, who devotes a lot of her time to
junior golf _ so much, in fact, that in 1997 she was honored by the
LPGA with the Budget Service Award in recognition to her work with
children just learning the game. She has been seen on The Golf
Channel's ``Academy Live,'' talking about junior golf, and her
approach is to keep it simple and enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   It must work, too, for even legends want in on the teachings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Life in the fast lane
</P>
<P>
   On the range, he found himself hitting balls next to Curtis
Strange and Tom Watson and fought to maintain his composure. On the
course, he found some bad spots with his driver and battled to make
some putts. Welcome to the PGA Tour, Geoff Sisk. The 32-year-old
Marshfield golfer missed the cut in his Tour debut at the Sony Open
at Hawaii, shooting 77-72, though he felt he hit it better than
that. ``But I had two penalty shots with my driver (in the first
round) and I can't remember the last time that happened,'' he said.
``I usually drive it straight.'' Sisk opened the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic Wednesday with a 2-under 70 (on the PGA West Arnold Palmer
Course) but wasn't especially pleased. ``I bogeyed the last hole, a
par-5. I chipped in for a birdie on my first hole and hit a lot of
good golf shots but just didn't convert. And you can't do that
against this type of competition.'' . . . Sisk showed his rookie
stripes when he got to the first tee at the Hope Wednesday and did
not know his amateur partner. It was Richard Ferris, who, as
chairman of the PGA Tour Policy Board, is a rather important person
in pro golf circles. ``I said, `Oh, my God,' '' said Sisk. ``I
should be up to date with this stuff. But he couldn't have been
nicer. It's what golf is all about, meeting people like that.'' . .
. Unheralded Cameron Beckman was leading the Sony Open until he
made a 9 at the par-4 15th in the second round. Ouch. He finished
in a tie for 24th at 2-under 278; had he parred that 15th, he would
have tied for second at 273 . . . Serves them right for going so
low. When players got to Waialae CC in Honolulu for the Sony Open,
they found the rough up and the par dropped to 70, a direct result
of the assault led last year by John Huston's Tour-record 28-under
finish. Last year, 4 under missed the cut; this year, 2 over made
the cut and Jeff Sluman's winning score was 9 under . . . Sluman's
tidy little two-week trip to Hawaii for the Mercedes and Sony
yielded these numbers: 73-67-72-72, 69-70-66-66, good for $531,050.
In his 42-year PGA Tour career, Sam Snead earned $620,126 in prize
money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How they stack up
</P>
<P>
   We're not quite at the stretch run, but a glance at the US Ryder
Cup standings offers a good dose of the expected (David Duval, Mark
O'Meara, Jim Furyk, Tiger Woods, Davis Love are Nos. 1-5 and figure
to be the heart of the team), with a pinch of the unexpected: Billy
Mayfair (No. 8), Sluman (10th), Fred Funk (11th), and Hal Sutton
(16th) in strong contention. With Top 10 finishes worth more than
they were in 1998, the real jockeying for position will take place
over the next few months, with particular interest in the four
majors, where points are doubled. There has been much talk about
players cutting back their schedules with the addition of three
World Golf Championship events, but it would seem to make sense for
people such as Payne Stewart, Mark Calcavecchia, Huston, Scott
Hoch, Tom Lehman (recovering from shoulder surgery, but due back
soon), and Paul Azinger to keep a busy dance card and chase
valuable points for that trip to Brookline in September. Keep in
mind, points are for Top 10 finishes only, not for money earned . .
. The Kemper Open is not one of the elite tournaments, and it drew
a rough date this year _ squeezed between popular stops (Colonial,
Memorial) and two weeks before the US Open. Fearful of not drawing
stars, officials at the Kemper came up with a novel approach that
involves that always popular word: Money. In addition to bumping
the purse to $2.5 million, Kemper officials will attempt to sign
the tournament winner to a logo contract, a deal that could be
worth $200,000 if that player wins a major . . . Arnold Palmer took
part in this week's Hope. Back before pleated pants, titanium
drivers, and the Sam 2000, Palmer owned this event. He won it five
times, including the inaugural in 1960, and it was his final
triumph on Tour in 1973. Palmer said last week that he would play
in the Masters but did not know about his own Bay Hill event (March
18-21) . . . Whenever she stepped into the spotlight, Lopez would
give credit to her father. Now she is paying tribute in a unique
way _ by naming a new wedge after him. The Domingo Wedge, part of
the Nancy Lopez Golf line, will make its debut at next weekend's
PGA Merchandise Show in Orlando . . . The announcement that Jane
Welch was named to the LPGA Board of Directors should have a
familiar ring because her husband Jack, the CEO of General
Electric, is an independent director on the PGA Tour Policy Board .
. . US Amateur champion Hank Kuehne (Southern Methodist) has
committed to the upcoming AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am, but
fellow collegiate star Matt Kuchar (Georgia Tech) declined . . . A
round of double bogeys, if you will, for tennis star Pete Sampras.
He was too fatigued to play in the Australian Open (that's a major,
Pete), but he mustered up enough strength to play in the Hope. Way
to give back to your sport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I'm 64
</P>
<P>
   He was never in the hunt to win, but by finishing in a tie for
29th at last week's Sony Open, Craig Stadler moved to 64th in the
world rankings. Ho hum? Well, yes, except being 64th _ for good or
bad _ means something now. The first event of the World Golf
Championships _ the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship _
will be limited to the Top 64 as of Feb. 15. If the event were to
start  &UR; today &LR; , Stadler would have a shot at earning $1 million. The
bad news: He would face the world's No. 1, Woods, right off the bat
. . . Another year, another quick exit for Chip Beck. He shot 75-74
and missed the cut at the Sony . . . Lennie Clements's opening
round at the Hope: two triples, a double, no birdies, an 84, then a
WD . . . The talent is getting younger and deeper every year.
Proof: Brittany Straza, a standout golfer at Lehigh High School in
Fort Myers, Fla., was given one of two sponsor's exemptions into
this week's LPGA Memorial in nearby Naples; and Beth Bauer, the
superb freshman at Duke, rolled to an eight-shot victory in the
recent Harder Hall Invitational in Sebring, Fla., which serves as
the traditional kickoff to the women's amateur championship season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A day at the Beach
</P>
<P>
   A round at Pebble Beach figures to be memorable, all the more so
if it happens to be while you are winning a tournament. And if you
throw in a hole-in-one, well, you have yourself quite a week. That
was the case last week for the Dever brothers _ Jack and Thomas of
Danvers, and James of Plaistow, N.H. _ along with Kevin Camell of
Wilmington as they won the Cadillac Invitational National Kidney
Foundation event. In a scramble format, the group shot 62 at Pebble
Beach, 61 at Spanish Bay, then 60 at Del Monte as they roared from
five shots back for a two-stroke victory. For Jack, a 6-handicapper
who plays out of Sagamore Springs, it was a trip made more
memorable by his second career ace, coming at the 202-yard 12th
with a 5-iron. There were 110 teams entered, said Jack Dever, and
``you don't go out there to win.'' The golfers did not get to play
the much-talked-about par-3 fifth, which was redesigned by Jack
Nicklaus and has been praised mightily. It will play about 160
yards and is right along the water, but won't make its official
debut until the AT&AMP;T . . . Kenny Lewis of South Dennis is 16th in
the latest GolfWeek/Titleist amateur rankings . . . A historical
note the Massachusetts Golf Association can take pride in: In 1927,
the first group to represent the US in the Ryder Cup included five
golfers who had won, or would win, the Mass. Open: Walter Hagen
(1915), Johnny Farrell (1927), Leo Diegel (1928), Joe Turnesa
(1930), and Gene Sarazen (1935). In addition, alternate Mike Brady
was a three-time State Open winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
