<SLUG> BC-FBN-ATLANTA-SUPERBOWL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY IN ATLANTA IS SUPERCHARGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The wind was not gone from the corner of Peachtree and
10th streets, not far from downtown Atlanta. That pesky wind was
blowing strongly from the vague direction of Alabama, as storm
after storm ventured from deeper in Dixie. No, the wind was not
gone.
</P>
<P>
   One lonely house sits at the corner of 10th and Peachtree.
Traffic whizzed by in all directions, making the 19th century house
seem all the more out of place, out of time, almost out of focus.
</P>
<P>
   But that one lonely house is a must-see for many visitors to
Atlanta, the home that author Margaret Mitchell called ``The
Dump,'' the place where she struggled for years in the 1930s to
write ``Gone with the Wind.'' Which, of course, captured Atlanta as
Atlantans for so long wished it to be captured.
</P>
<P>
   A sports bar is across the street from Mitchell's home. Such a
juxtaposition, such a perfect juxtaposition for the Atlanta of
1999. Inside that sports bar, there was a supreme mix of happiness
and joy that Atlanta's Falcons _ to the surprise of all _ were
going to the Super Bowl. But there was also an undercurrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where were you when the Falcons were real bad?'' asked one fan
to another. ``You're just jumping on the bandwagon now. I was there
for it all, I went to see 'em play when they were bad. I didn't
just become a Falcons fan last Sunday when they went to Minnesota.
I've been there. I've suffered through it all.''
</P>
<P>
   All through Georgia, the same words could be heard. Such joy,
the truly innocent emotion when a football team makes its first
trip to a Super Bowl, but joy mixed with disdain by the true
believers for the newly converted. It is human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Back across the street, at Margaret Mitchell's home, the wind
still was not gone. That famous line from ``Gone with the Wind''
could almost be heard in the swirling wind: ``Frankly, my dear, I
don't give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Atlanta. That was how Atlanta felt toward its wretched
Falcons. But Mitchell's Atlanta was a long-ago Atlanta, just as
Atlanta's disdain for its football team was long ago _ as far back
in time as two or three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, my dear, everybody gives a damn about the Falcons now.
They're a mania in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Disturbing the peace
</P>
<P>
   On a beautiful hill on the opposite side of Atlanta is a huge
complex, with a library, museum, and other buildings. It is the
Jimmy Carter Center, and when visitors enter the complex, they are
told of the former president's role in attempting to make peace
between Arabs and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure all of Georgia is going to want to be in Miami,''
said Ezra Slocum, a visitor to the Carter Center. ``After the
football players themselves and those guys who draw up the X's and
O's and the guys with the Gatorade, I think one person has to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Who?
</P>
<P>
   ``The President. There's going to be some peace-making needed to
be done down there. Coach (Dan) Reeves and that coach in Denver
seem ready to do some strangling of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   New Englanders might feel that the uproar surrounding the
Patriots' last visit to the Super Bowl might never be topped. When
the long-simmering rift between Bill Parcells and Bob Kraft
exploded into the open during Super Bowl week, it caused a circus.
</P>
<P>
   This year's circus is already tromping toward Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say things in a coaches meeting as far as critiquing a
player that you would never say to a player,'' Reeves said last
week at the Falcons' practice facility. ``If John (Elway) ever got
any bad feelings about something I said, it was never done
publicly. It had to be something coming from a staff meeting. Now,
does that mean Mike (Shanahan) did it? I have no proof of it.
Nothing. But I did what I felt was best for our football team. It
wasn't an easy decision because I knew he was a great football
coach. But I didn't think he had my best interest at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan, Reeves's former offensive coordinator in Denver,
reacted angrily when he heard Reeves publicly say what had been
privately whispered six years ago: that Shanahan was so allied with
Elway that he repeated to the quarterback what Reeves had said
about Elway in private meetings. This only inflamed the tense
feelings between Elway and Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has been saying this for years, said Shanahan. ``For him
to bring this up now, and never address it to me, ever, and then
address it in the press, is something that I've lost a lost of
respect for,'' said Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves fired Shanahan in Denver. Broncos owner Pat Bowlen soon
fired Reeves. And this unhappy triangle _ Reeves, Shanahan, and
Elway _ is heading to Miami for a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where (Carter) is now,'' said Slocum. ``But he
ought to be thinking of going to Miami. He used to go to Braves
games and do the (Tomahawk) Chop. He needs to do some peace-making
before these coaches chop each other up.''
</P>
<P>
   A time for dreams
</P>
<P>
   On the same side of Atlanta, and not far from the Carter
complex, is the Ebenezer Baptist Church and the Martin Luther King
complex, a Visitor Center, King's gravesite, and a memorial. King's
uplifting speech _ ``I have a dream'' _ permeates the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   This may be Atlanta's true shrine. Visitors from around the
world, make a point to stop here for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Dreams also accompany those Atlantans who pass along Auburn
Avenue day by day, dreams as lofty as those that ooze from the
neighborhood or more mundane ones. But in this area, as throughout
the city, there is one dream that few, if any, can truthfully say
they had six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody, no way, thought this was going to happen,'' said Jack
Fuller. ``Even two weeks ago, nobody dared think of this. I think
if you're an honest person, and you answer honestly, no way there's
anybody in Atlanta who can say they'd thought of this. That's what
makes it sweet. It's happening _ and nobody thought it would.''
</P>
<P>
   Rallying around
</P>
<P>
   Far across the city is the Buckhead section, and the other night
the flare of Falcon frenzy burned hot. A night spot held a rally
for the Falcons, the streets were filled with dancers doing the
Dirty Bird, and Gov. Roy Barnes did what few governors are ever
allowed to do _ he incited a mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win,'' the governor shouted to the mob, which
got rowdier. The Broncos are ``going to be sorry,'' Barnes went on,
``and thank God they sent us Dan Reeves.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the city, the same euphoria was present. Wide
receiver Terance Mathis, an Atlanta native, returned to his high
school to wild cheers and adulation. The birth of a baby to Diane
Chandler, wife of quarterback Chris Chandler, was greeted as if the
Chandlers were a royal couple. The statistics for the new daughter
_ 6 pounds 10 ounces, and 20 inches long _ may be as well known in
Atlanta as Greg Maddux's earned run average used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves?'' shouted George Brown, 28. ``They never win the
big ones. Now we've got the Falcons. Look what they did in
Minnesota. The Falcons win.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange, strange times in Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
