<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5754 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-KHRISTIC     01-23 1895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-KHRISTICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHRISTICH ADAPTATION A GOOD STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is the Bruins' leading scorer at the All-Star break, having
hit the 20-goal plateau for the sixth time in his nine-year career.
He is an All-Star for the second time and will play for the World
Team in this Sunday's annual salute to the NHL's best and brightest
at Tampa's Ice Palace.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Dmitri Khristich's hockey gifts, the 29-year-old
winger remains something of an enigma. He arrived in Boston on Aug.
29, 1997, along with goalie Byron Dafoe in a deal that sent Jozef
Stumpel, Sandy Moger, and a fourth-round choice to the Los Angeles
Kings. The Bruins knew they were acquiring a talented forward with
a knack for scoring on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of personality, Khristich is nearly impossible to read.
If Ray Bourque is stately and Dafoe is ebullient and Rob DiMaio is
blunt and Joe Thornton is down to earth and Jason Allison is funny
. . . well, how would one describe Khristich?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an introverted guy,'' said Bruins president/general
manager Harry Sinden. ``It's difficult for me to talk to Dmitri.
It's difficult for (coach Pat Burns) to talk to him. It's been
difficult for anybody on any team in his career to talk to him.
It's the cultural change he's had to go through. I don't know how
outgoing I would be if I had to live in Hungary or somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's well known as a pretty talented player around the league.
There was a question about his work ethic and his commitment to the
team that he played for. But we haven't really noticed anything
that has bothered us very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden believes Khristich's reserved manner is a product of his
roots in Kiev, Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's quite sure of himself as a person living in
a society like this,'' Sinden said. ``It's hard to know. With
players, I try to put myself in their place and wonder how I'd
react. When you get a guy like Dmitri, he's never been like Pavel
Bure, who just takes North America like, `This is great, let's have
a good time.' He has never been able to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from the Ukraine, he probably came from an
agricultural-type, rural background and in the Ukraine, he'd
probably have some inhibitions. To come to a country like the
United States, I would think that would be really difficult to cope
with. He's a kid that seems to want to talk but can't bring himself
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden thinks part of the problem is that Khristich is easy to
misunderstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up here the other day to make sure his arrangements
were in order to go to the All-Star Game, and I happened to be here
and I congratulated him,'' said Sinden. ``I said, `Is this your
first game?' I didn't realize he'd been there once before. You know
what his answer was? He said, `No, I've been there once before.' It
wasn't like an American kid or a Canadian kid who would've said,
`Yeah, I'm really excited. This is going to be great.' I think he
felt that way but he just didn't communicate it. If you're not
careful, you take that as he's not interested in talking to you or
anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' boss has given a great deal of thought to Khristich
not only as a hockey player but as a person, and he said a
substantial amount of consideration should be given to the
individual's circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand what must happen to these kids when they leave
their homeland,'' he said. ``It's a tremendous change. I couldn't
do it. I would completely withdraw. The younger they are, perhaps,
the better. Sergei (Samsonov) brings his family with him so that
connection remains and it helps a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look and talk to Dmitri, I wish the communication was
better with him and with the coach and with me and the (media) and
with his teammates, and maybe it's not bad with his teammates. I
understand why it possibly isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said Khristich's discomfort, already evident when he
arrived, could have been exacerbated by last summer's arbitration
hearing. At the time, there was rampant speculation that if they
agreed to pay Khristich the $1.95 million he was awareded, which
they did, that he would then be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to arbitration, it's not a nice experience for
the player or for management,'' Sinden said. ``You're trying to win
a case even though perhaps you don't believe it. We said a few
things that were tough on him right in front of him. I don't know
whether that hardened him more. I hated to say it because there
wasn't that rapport to begin with and now you were breaking it down
even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's producing, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the roles Khristich has played that hasn't been discussed
much is mentor to Samsonov. It has appeared to be more of a passive
role than an active one, although when Samsonov was going through a
slump at the end of last month, Khristich stepped to the
youngster's defense and fended off media questions about comments
made by the coach. Sinden said he didn't predict that Khristich
would take Samsonov under his wing but he is happy to see that he
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we were that smart,'' said Sinden. ``It probably
would've been good thinking on our part to say, `Let's get somebody
who speaks the language and who has been in the league for a while
to show him the ropes,' and Khristich could be the guy, but it just
happened coincidentally.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, as good as it has been for Samsonov, it might even
be better for Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few of those players, European players, who are
handed that responsibility throughout the league,'' said Sinden,
referring to leadership or motivation assignments. ``I doubt if
(Jaromir) Jagr plays that role at all in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khristich's role perhaps evolved, not to lead the team, but
what a neat responsibility of maybe helping out the team by
mentoring one of the top choices if not one of the top prospects.
So he came upon that responsibility probably by accident or
coincidentally, but he perhaps relishes it and it may be something
where we need to give the opportunity to more of these Europeans to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Primeau in his prime
</P>
<P>
   To say that Carolina captain Keith Primeau doesn't miss his days
in Detroit is an understatement. Primeau, who was taken in the
first round (third overall) in the 1990 entry draft by the Red
Wings, faced a lot of pressure in the Motor City. Eventually, he
asked to be dealt, which he was in October 1996, and he has 22
goals and 16 assists in 45 games this season. ``I've grown as a
player and I've grown as a person,'' said Primeau. ``And sometimes
it takes a move to get the chance to do that. I would say the Red
Wings expected too much from me too soon. I was expected to score
like Jimmy Carson and fight like Bob Probert, as an 18-year-old. I
understood their expectations in one respect because I led the
Ontario League in scoring as an 18-year-old. But I would say it was
unfair of them to expect so much from me at such a young age.
Detroit was never a happy place for me. I enjoy the game so much
more now than three years ago.'' . . . Edmonton defenseman Boris
Mironov made a splash last week when he aired his grievances with
general manager Glen Sather in public. Mironov, who wants to
renegotiate his contract, feels unappreciated. ``I have played for
the Edmonton Oilers 5 1/2 years,'' Mironov said. ``I never hear
from (Sather) that I'm a good player. He always says I play bad.
Maybe I'm not going to the All-Star Game because I'm looking for a
new deal for the last three months. Maybe it's more Slats's
decision that I'm not going. Maybe he's playing some game. I'm not
sure.'' Mironov had threatened a holdout and got in Sather's
doghouse when he was over his playing weight by about 10 pounds
during a recent weigh-in, and he hasn't always adhered to team
rules on the road. ``Players forget they're getting paid a hell of
a lot of money and they have to perform up to everyone's
expectations to get a new deal,'' said Sather. ``He's got to grow
up and play hockey. Maybe by getting mad at me he'll start playing
well.'' . . . Former Canadiens goalie Jocelyn Thibault, who beat
his former teammates Thursday night, 3-0, for Chicago said the
reason he asked for a trade out of Montreal in November had nothing
to do with the pressure of playing in the hockey-mad town. ``I
didn't see any alternative,'' said Thibault. ``There was a
combination of factors that went into my decision. But in the back
of my mind, there was always this feeling that the team didn't want
me. They didn't have confidence in me. They said one thing and then
they went looking for another goaltender. I knew there was no way I
was going to win their confidence. You don't think there was
pressure when I first came to Montreal and replaced Patrick Roy? I
thought I played well that season. I thought I handled the
pressure. I was 20 years old and I was replacing a legend. In the
three years I was there, I had some good memories. I regret that I
couldn't take the team further in the playoffs. But I'm proud of
what I accomplished in Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Old friends
</P>
<P>
   Kings forward Eric Lacroix picked up his first point of the
season when he had an assist against his former team, the
Avalanche, Tuesday night. It was his first game against his
ex-mates since Lacroix's father, Colorado GM Pierre Lacroix, traded
him to the Kings Oct. 29. ``Whenever you play against your old team
for the first time, it's a weird feeling,'' said Lacroix. ``I was
nervous. It helps that it's been a while. It would have been
tougher if I had to play them right away after the trade. I didn't
leave behind 25 enemies. I left behind 25 friends.'' Kings coach
Larry Robinson said it was hard on Lacroix, who missed nine games
with a fractured sternum. ``He's a great kid,'' said Robinson.
``Even when he's not playing well, he's not a disruption. Maybe
he's just a disruption to himself.'' . . . Twice within six weeks,
Detroit goalie Norm Maracle has been struck in the throat by a
puck. It's possible that Maracle will add a throat protector,
similar to one worn by Roy. ``That could potentially be a
life-threatening situation,'' said trainer John Wharton. ``I think
he needs to protect that area a little better.'' . . . Needham
native Robbie Ftorek, coaching the New Jersey Devils, was out in
his old haunt last week, Los Angeles. The former Kings coach said
it was strange. During his time there in the late '80s, Ftorek
dealt with the pressure by strolling on the beach. ``I'd walk the
beach at night, more than I probably should have,'' said Ftorek.
``It was relaxing. One night after a game, all I wanted to do was
take my shoes off and walk in some grass. But do you think I could
find grass? I ended up walking down the 14-inch strips of grass at
the Residence Inn.'' . . . The trade of Bure from Vancouver to
Florida has met with mixed reviews, but Canucks forward Alexander
Mogilny, for one, is relieved. ``It's good for us and for Pavel to
get back playing again,'' said Mogilny. ``It was a long wait for
him. It's tough to lose a friend, but he wasn't happy here. I can
understand a change of scenery. The same thing happened to me in
Buffalo. I don't think it was a distraction. How can you be
distracted when you're below .500?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
