<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ALLSTAR-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE STILL ENJOYS ALL-STAR SALUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ He has been a fixture on the All-Star scene for almost
his entire 20-year career. This Sunday, when Bruins captain Ray
Bourque takes the ice with his North American teammates for this
year's contest against the World team in the annual showcase of
hockey's greatest talent, Bourque will be a starter for a record
12th time and a participant for the 17th. He was the most valuable
player in the 1996 game at the FleetCenter, in which he scored the
winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   For the 38-year-old defenseman, it's still an honor to be voted
as a favorite by the fans, still an honor to be recognized _ and
rightfully so _ as one of the best at his position, but Bourque's
perspective on the experience has clearly changed.
</P>
<P>
   He's no longer bright-eyed and wonder-struck. However, his three
children are, and it's through their eyes that Bourque sees this
weekend. He and his wife, Christiane, relish the time they spend
with Melissa, Christopher, and Ryan, and that, more than anything,
is what Bourque looks forward to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what it was the first couple of times you go, but you
go there with a positive attitude and you try to enjoy the
festivities,'' said Bourque. ``It's a pretty hectic weekend but now
I try to kind of live it through my kids' eyes and I bring them
along and they really enjoy it. I know it's a big thrill for them.
It's going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he's looked upon as an elder statesman at the
event and possibly a good-will ambassador of sorts, Bourque
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it,'' he said, a wry smile spreading across his lips.
``I think they'll be looking at (Paul) Kariya, (Teemu) Selanne,
(Peter) Forsberg, and (Eric) Lindros and those guys because those
are the guys who are going to be lighting them up. I'll probably be
pulling a few pucks out of the net. It's not really a game made for
defensemen or goalies.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, it's not much of a game at all. It's a
reward for individual greatness, which Bourque certainly possesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you not put him in the class of athletes that is only
reserved for the very, very special?,'' mused Bruins
president/general manager Harry Sinden. ``The only reason you
hesitate to do it is because he hasn't won a championship _ like he
wins the championship. It's because he hasn't been on a team that
won a championship. If Babe Ruth hadn't won a World Series, then he
would've been nothing? That's just the way America is. If you can't
all alone lead the team to a championship, then you're not worthy
of recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, whose fitness and durability are as remarkable as his
on-ice skill and smarts, could be the Ernie Banks of hockey. But as
Sinden points out, he wouldn't be the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the greatest players in this league _ Brad Park is one
_ never won a Stanley Cup,'' said Sinden. ``It means nothing to my
estimation of Raymond, it should not mean anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it's in his favor that he can do this and continue to
do this without being on a championship team. He's never had the
advantage of being on the very best team in the league, though he's
come close a couple of times, which would've promoted his status a
thousand times.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have the status he's got without it, I think, is
incredible. Maybe we should turn it around and say, `How can you
play this well on teams that can't win championships?' ''
</P>
<P>
   A Stanley Cup is about the only thing Bourque hasn't been
rewarded with. He's a five-time Norris Trophy winner as the
league's top defenseman, he's third on the NHL's all-time assist
list (and gaining on No. 2 Paul Coffey), and he's the Bruins'
all-time leading scorer. He never loses his enthusiasm for the
sport he loves, and he's even looking forward to the thankless task
of trying to prevent goals in a showcase designed to highlight
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a pretty interesting game,'' said Bourque of the
North Americans' 8-7 victory. ``I think this year should be a good
game again. You're never going to have a rock 'em, sock 'em kind of
game. There's a lot of skill out there and you're going to see a
lot of goals no matter how they break it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives it a little bit of a rivalry in terms of all the
Europeans playing against the North Americans, so it worked out
pretty good last year. It's fun to still be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
