<HEADER>
A5760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-GRANT-BO     01-23 1828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-GRANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT'S APPEAL: HE'S UNLIKE MIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Grant knows what he is. In the eyes of many, he is the
anti-Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Grant is not only the leading prospect in the heavyweight
division at the moment but is also a soft-spoken, self-effacing,
religious knockout artist who seems the polar opposite of the
angry, violent, often foul-mouthed Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Everything Tyson is Grant is not _ except a punisher of
opponents _ and this has created a groundswell of interest in his
future, a future that had been on hold until Saturday night when he
takes on a former sparring partner named Ahmad Abdin on HBO's
``Boxing After Dark'' after a five-month layoff resulting from a
battle with hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Grant (28-0, 20 KOs) had not been in the ring since he
dismantled Obed Sullivan last May 30 in nine rounds, yet interest
in him has continued to grow for an assortment of reasons. First,
he is a massive man who looks more like a tight end or a power
forward than a heavyweight boxer. Second, he can do great damage
with either hand and frequently does. Third, he is trained by Don
Turner, the man who was in Evander Holyfield's corner the two times
he dominated Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   But a different reason may be the most important one: simply,
that he is not Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I accept that role, I live it,'' Grant said.
``That's who I am. I'm about being straight up, a stand-up guy. I'm
not hard to figure out. I'm clean-living, humble, teachable, and
looking to prevail. You won't see me involved with crookedness,
wrongdoing, unrighteousness. What I want to generate is to give
people some hope. I feel no pressure from that. I'm just living who
I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm one of the guys who can help market the heavyweight
division more. I'm looking to do for it like Sammy Sosa and Mark
McGwire did for baseball. But I didn't do this to try and impress
anyone. God has a plan for me. I don't know what it is, but it's in
the making.''
</P>
<P>
   What Turner and many others in boxing believe is that the plan
is for Grant to become heavyweight champion sooner rather than
later. With his size, athleticism, and power, they see someone who
could be champion for years, but to do that he must get by
Holyfield, his stablemate, role model, and the World Boxing
Association-International Boxing Federation champion.
</P>
<P>
   If that is a requirement for stardom, Michael Grant says he'll
just wait until later, thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really are not interested in fighting each other,'' Grant
said. ``Evander doesn't want to fight me and I don't want to fight
him. People are willing to throw money in my face but money can't
overcome a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander is a well-respected guy. When I was coming up I looked
at him and how he lived his life professionally and how he
respected the game. There's a great deal of respect there when
we're around each other. So that fight will never happen. As long
as I've got control of it, it won't happen. He's pretty much said
he's going to retire from boxing anyway and I'm not in a big rush
for this thing. I have youth on my side.''
</P>
<P>
   In growing numbers, he also has fans on his side, a fact that
could turn a future date with Tyson into a pay-per-view
extravaganza. It would be a fight that could sell on many levels.
It would be size vs. power, youth vs. age, inexperience vs.
experience and, yes, good vs. evil.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a promoter's dream if Grant continues to grow as a
draw as well as a contender and Tyson gets back some of the allure
he's lost, even in the eyes of a fellow fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pay any attention to it,'' Grant said of Tyson's
return against Frans Botha last weekend. ``I didn't watch the
fight. I've accepted he's a man looking to get back into the
business. He's drawing, but who is he drawing? I don't look at him
as a fighter no more. I look at him as an entertainer.''
</P>
<P>
   And the boxing world looks at Grant as a savior. It is he who is
supposed to pick up the torch Holyfield now holds and run with it.
He is the future, as surely as Holyfield is the present and Tyson
was the past.
</P>
<P>
   That can be a withering kind of pressure, but Grant seems not to
have noticed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only pressure if I let it be,'' Grant said. ``Boxing is
about hard work and having good people around you. I have that so I
don't worry about the pressure. When the fight comes, you've
prepared yourself for war in the time of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a time Michael Grant enjoys best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   Although Showtime was claiming it got 750,000 pay-per-view buys
at $49.95 for the Tyson-Botha fight, industry insiders claim the
number was closer to 650,000, which would be a financial disaster.
That may explain why the cable network had a national conference
call set up with Tyson's new trainer, Tommy Brooks, less than a
week after the fight. During it, Brooks conceded, ``I was a little
worried the first couple of rounds. He was the Mike Tyson who came
out and fought Evander Holyfield, not the Mike Tyson that I had
worked with the last couple of months.'' Brooks went on to say
Tyson readjusted in the fight and began using his jab. If he did,
it must have been to jab the referee. Brooks added that Tyson still
``has to re-instill the confidence in himself and his ability. I
don't think Tyson realizes how hard he hits. He just taps me and it
hurts through and through. Once he realizes the power he has and
reestablishes the confidence in putting his punches together,
you'll see a difference. Everything depends on Tyson. I can talk to
the guy until I'm blue in the face. I just show him what to do and
how to do it. It's all on him. The fighter makes the trainer.'' . .
. The first opportunity to see the difference after one fight will
come April 24, with Axel Schulz still the most likely victim. But
several other names were added to the Tyson Sweepstakes last week,
including Shannon Briggs, Vaughn Bean, and, of all people, Razor
Ruddock. Ruddock continued his comeback with a win last week over
club fighter Tony LaRosa in Marksville, La., and is now 3-0 since
returning to boxing last year under the direction of promoter Mike
Acri . . . Asked to grade Botha's performance, Brooks said, ``I
give Botha an A for effort and an F for getting hit.'' . . . Here's
another assessment of  &UR; today &LR; 's Tyson. ``Once you get past four
rounds, Mike Tyson is done,'' said former pound-for-pound champion
Pernell Whitaker, a longtime friend of Holyfield who is also
trained by Brooks. ``He's not Mike Tyson no more. He's so frantic.
He's set on two or three rounds. He can't crack the code. But Tyson
is the Eighth Wonder of the World. The kid done been knocked out
twice and still gets $25 million a fight. If you love watching
knockouts, you love Mike Tyson.'' . . . Although Briggs's decision
to pull out of a March 6 fight with Lou Savarese caused HBO
problems, it apparently did not cost Savarese a payday. He is
likely to fight Lance Whitaker that night on the undercard of
Olympic gold medalist David Reid's first title shot, a challenge of
154-pound champion Laurent Boudouani. Those scheduling changes also
resulted in HBO's decision to televise World Boxing Council
lightweight champion Cesar Bazan's (34-2-1, 23 KOs) rematch with
the man he took the title from, Stevie Johnston (25-1, 14 KOs),
Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Here's Holyfield's view of Tyson: ``Tyson looked like Tyson. I
wasn't surprised by the result, but he looked the same to me. Botha
refused to back down and that was the key. He had courage to stand
in there. Anybody has a chance to win if they have courage.''. . .
You may read from time to time that the George Foreman-Larry Holmes
fight has been rescheduled for late March at the Astrodome. Don't
believe it. Promoter/con man Roger Leavitt says he will raise the
$9 million he owes Foreman and the $3.6 million he owes Holmes by
then. Sure he will. If he robs a bank. Foreman has said the fight
is off, and until he says otherwise, the fight is off. Thankfully,
I might add . . . Scott Woodwirth, Terry Norris's manager, says
Norris is officially retired after losing a title shot to Boudouani
recently. Norris's balance is gone and he is completely shot, but
after losing to Dana Rosenblatt, he and his father demanded one
more fight. They were the only dissenting votes among those
privately urging him to retire. The father stopped the Boudouani
fight. Woodwirth said, ``I think that's how it had to end for
Terry. Now there's no dissent.'' . . . IBF middleweight champion
Bernard Hopkins is still smarting from the way his first fight with
No. 1 challenger Robert Allen ended. Allen (22-2, 18 KOs) was
clutching and grabbing him for four rounds, and when the two
refused to break, referee Mills Lane pushed them so hard that
Hopkins fell out of the ring and injured his ankle. The fight was
declared a no contest and will be decided Feb. 6 in Washington.
Hopkins (34-2-1, 26 KOs) promised, ``This won't be no encore of
WrestleMania.'' He will be making his ninth title defense . . .
Arizona Sen. John McCain, who is leading a fight to reform boxing,
told the National Association of Attorneys General at a hearing on
boxing reform in New York last week, ``Many aspects of the
professional boxing industry are far less admirable than the
courage and sportsmanship that most boxers bring into the ring . .
. Business practices which would be stricken as exploitative and
indefensible restraints of trade in any other sport are considered
standard operating procedure in boxing . . . The active and
sustained involvement of state attorneys general will help reform
boxing's unacceptable status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local bleatings
</P>
<P>
   Fast-rising New Bedford junior featherweight Jason Pires defends
his US Boxing Association junior featherweight title Friday in Bay
St. Louis, Miss., vs. Arturo Estrada. Pires (13-0) is ranked eighth
in the world by the IBF as he enters the rematch with Estrada, whom
he unanimously defeated in their first confrontation. The fight
will be shown delayed on Fox New England . . . Rosenblatt (33-1)
also fights Super Bowl weekend, at Foxwoods vs. tough Aaron Davis
(45-6) . . . A week ago, former World Boxing Organization super
middleweight champion Steve Collins held a press conference in
London to announce an April 17 comeback fight against Roy Jones Jr.
That was news to Jones and to HBO. Although there have been
discussions, no deal has been struck, and no negotiations either
with Jones's promoter, Murad Muhammad, or HBO have begun . . . Word
is Chelsea heavyweight John Ruiz will fight Canadian champion Shane
Sutcliffe March 13 on the Holyfield-Lennox Lewis undercard.
Sutcliffe is also scheduled to fight 45-year-old Trevor Berbick
Feb. 3 in Montreal for the Canadian heavyweight title. Things must
be kind of slow in Canadian gyms these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
