<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5761 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      01-23 1693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CASE OF OLYMPIC ROYALTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The best job in the world, International
Olympic Committee vice president Richard Pound is fond of saying,
is to be a hotel chambermaid after the Lords of the Rings have left
town.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci handbags, silk scarves, cut-glass ornaments, framed
watercolors, coffee-table books, boxes of chocolates, bottles of
vintage wine, overflowing fruit baskets _ anything the IOC members
can't crate up or carry with them _ get left in their rooms for the
cleanup crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Birmingham (where the vote for the 1998 Winter Games site
was held), there was a gift in our room every day,'' says Robert
Helmick, an Iowa attorney and former US member of the IOC. ``The
IOC opened up a parcel-post office so the members could pack them
up and send them home.''
</P>
<P>
   What many of the members took with them from other meetings _
mink coats, diamond brooches, personal computers, VCRs _ was part
of a culture of excess and access that has led to the worst scandal
in modern Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   That culture evolved over the the last two decades from a
cornucopia of lavish banquets and expensive mementos to
prostitutes, resort vacations, shopping sprees for IOC members'
wives, jobs and tuition payments for their children, medical care
(including cosmetic surgery), sweetheart land deals, and cash
payoffs up to $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has been a profound embarrassment to the august IOC,
which has always insisted that its 115 members are above
corruption. Each one takes an oath promising to ``keep myself free
from any political or commercial influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet 16 of them have been accused of taking payoffs and gifts
worth nearly $800,000 from the Salt Lake City organizers before and
after the Utah capital was awarded the 2002 Winter Games in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are cases that are just unacceptable, brutal corruption
where simply money was asked for,'' Jacques Rogge of Belgium, a
member of the IOC's special inquiry panel, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Two members, Finland's Pirjo Haeggman and Libya's Bashir Mohamed
Attarabulsi, stepped down last week and the IOC's executive board
is expected to demand the resignation of at least seven more and as
many as a dozen after it meets Sunday at the lakeside Chateau de
Vidy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC will act very decisively to make sure all of its
members adhere strictly to the rules and to the oath they all swore
to,'' board member Kevan Gosper of Australia said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has also promised to reform the bidding process, banning
individual members from visiting candidate cities and possibly
having its 11-member board, and not the full body, choose future
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system we have today is not working,'' conceded Juan
Antonio Samaranch, who has been the IOC's president since 1980 and
the chief architect, both for better and worse, of the modern
Olympics. ``We have to change the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The greater challenge will be to change the lavish culture of
entitlement that has helped create the most shameful chapter in the
IOC's 105 years. It is a culture of first-class air travel and
five-star hotels and chauffeured limousines, the culture of a
self-elected, self-perpetuating body that answers to nobody but
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC not only decides which countries (200 as of June)
compete in the Games, it decides which countries are countries. The
IOC did not allow East Germany to compete on its own until 1968 and
let Taiwan compete as China until 1980. Even after the Soviet Union
broke apart, the IOC kept it together as the Unified Team for the
1992 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nazis posted ``Dogs and Jews not allowed'' signs
outside stadium restrooms at the 1936 Summer Games in Berlin, the
IOC told Adolf Hitler to have them taken down. ``When the Olympic
flag rises, this is no longer Germany,'' Hitler was informed. ``It
is Olympia, and we are masters there.'' Hitler complied.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC members are not delegates ``from'' countries but
delegates ``to'' countries. They serve until they reach 80 years
old and those elected before 1966 are members for life. Though the
membership has expanded and diversified dramatically over the last
two decades, the IOC still has a healthy sprinkling of the royalty
that decades ago got its members labeled the ``Lords of the
Rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Samaranch, a Spanish marquis, the roster includes
Princess Anne of Great Britain, Prince Faisal of Saudi Arabia,
Prince Albert of Monaco, Princess Nora of Liechtenstein, the Duke
of Luxembourg, Prince Alexandre de Merode of Belgium, and Sheik
Al-Sabah of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Pierre de Coubertin, the Frenchman who revived the
Olympics more than a century ago, stocked the IOC with dukes and
barons and princes because he wanted the members to be above
political and financial influence. But after the IOC was criticized
during the 1970s as an exclusive club for rich, elderly, white,
European men with one foot in the 19th century, Samaranch moved to
expand and diversify the membership.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two of the members now are from Asia, 20 from Africa, 14
from Latin America. Nearly a dozen are women. Two of the four vice
presidents (Keba Mbaye of Senegal and Anita DeFrantz of the US) are
black and two of the board members (Chiharu Igaya of Japan and Kim
Un-Yong of South Korea) are Asian.
</P>
<P>
   But as the IOC has broadened itself, it has also broadened the
financial and philosophical range of its members. Many are now
middle-class and many come from countries where a quid pro quo, if
not an outright bribe, is considered a normal part of doing
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done nothing wrong,'' IOC member Jean-Claude Ganga of
the Republic of Congo told French radio earlier this month. Ganga,
who allegedly took $50,000 in cash from Salt Lake, made another
$60,000 on a land deal and also accepted free medical care for
himself and his mother. ``I will not become rich because I voted
for Salt Lake City. That is why I am so serene.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1980s, bribery was a non-issue with the IOC, both
because its members paid their own way to meetings and events and
because nobody was bribing. After Montreal lost a billion dollars
on the 1976 Summer Games, which were marred by an African walkout
before the opening ceremonies, the Olympics were considered
radioactive. Los Angeles, which had most of the facilities already
in place, was the only bidder for the 1984 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   But when Los Angeles turned a $215 million profit despite a
Soviet-bloc boycott, the Games quickly became a hot property.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1992 Olympics went up for bid in 1986, six cities were
clamoring for the Summer Games and seven for the Winter, and the
culture of excess began in earnest. IOC members were entertained at
lavish receptions, treated to free trips and expensive gifts, and
even provided with call girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had these new members and simultaneously all this money,''
says Helmick.
</P>
<P>
   Before Denver landed the 1976 Winter Games, which it later
conceded to Innsbruck over environmental issues, it handed out
paperweights to IOC voters. But by 1986, Barcelona was spending an
estimated $7 million, much of it pampering IOC members, to outbid
Paris for the 1992 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It began with Barcelona and Paris,'' says Helmick. ``It was
taken to a new height with Atlanta (in 1996) and Nagano (in
1998).''
</P>
<P>
   During the bidding for the 1996 Summer Games, Athens fed IOC
members a lavish banquet at the foot of the Acropolis and took them
on tours of the Greek isles. Atlanta treated members to rounds of
golf at Augusta and even provided a pet bulldog to the Cuban member
who'd been enthralled with the University of Georgia mascot.
Melbourne agreed to let the daughter of an IOC member play a solo
with its symphony orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Nagano, which couldn't match Salt Lake's overall bid package for
the 1998 Winter Games, spent $22,000 in ``negotiation fees'' on
each of the five dozen IOC members who visited the Japanese city,
including trips to hot springs resorts and helicopter tours. ``We
were handing out salt water taffy,'' said a Salt Lake bid official,
after Nagano had prevailed by four votes. ``They were handing out
Toyotas.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what Nagano handed out is unknown. Its organizing
committee burned the records in 1992, six years before the games.
</P>
<P>
   The next time, Salt Lake City apparently handed out whatever it
took to whoever was asking. ``They meticulously played by the rules
the first time,'' says Helmick. ``When they lost to Nagano, they
became discouraged and began playing by the unwritten rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The unwritten rules involved five-figure payoffs, often arranged
by middlemen who promised blocs of votes, usually from Africa.
``There had always been rumors of payoffs, but it was far more
subtle,'' says Helmick. ``You let people know what you desired and
things would be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   But by 1991, when the '98 Games were awarded, the requests were
direct, brazen and specific. After Salt Lake complained to the IOC
about middlemen and nothing was done, the Utahns played the bidding
game as they understood it.
</P>
<P>
   So, apparently, did Sydney. The night before Sydney edged
Beijing by two votes for the 2000 Games, John Coates, head of
Australia's Olympic committee offered $35,000 apiece to IOC members
from Kenya and Uganda for sports development in their countries,
contingent on Sydney winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is entitled to work right up until the last minute,
and sometimes a result comes in the last minute, just like a result
comes in the last meters of a race,'' Gosper said Saturday. ``But
I'm not saying that anything goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the IOC executive board will propose changes to a
bidding process that escalated from paperweights to payoffs in
three decades. More than likely, members say, it will ban
individual members from visiting candidate cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of IOC members never traveled,'' says DeFrantz. ``A lot
of them didn't like having host cities visit them. It was an
imposition. I think it will be easier if we just say, `none of the
above.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
