<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-INCENTIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INCENTIVE OR PAYOFF? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Australia's senior International Olympic
Committee member Saturday defended an apparent payoff by the Sydney
organizers seven years ago as a proper ``incentive scheme'' to help
the city land the 2000 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual in any bid process for encouragements,
incentives, to be part of the bid as long as they are out in the
open,'' said Kevan Gosper, adding that he would ask his colleagues
on the IOC's executive board Sunday to reaffirm their support for
both Sydney and Salt Lake City, the 2002 Winter Games site that is
at the center of the widening bribery scandal. ``I'm comfortable
with this behavior, but the executive board may want to discuss it
further on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, which had promised a ``clean, green'' Games, delivered
the latest blow to the embattled Olympic movement Friday when the
head of Australia's Olympic committee revealed that he had offered
to pay IOC members from Kenya and Uganda $35,000 apiece for sports
development in their countries if Sydney won the bid. Sydney
defeated Beijing by two votes the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very concerned that night before the vote,'' committee
chief John Coates told reporters in Sydney Saturday. ``I just felt
an unease, I knew these guys, and I just didn't think the next day
I was going to be able to count on them to vote for Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, which had promised to spend $37 million to help
countries bring athletes and equipment to the Games, said it was
merely trying to match inducements by Beijing and Manchester,
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw our votes being eaten away,'' Coates said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gosper originally said that the payments might cause
Sydney to lose the Games, he maintained Saturday that the maneuver
had been public knowledge at the time and there was nothing
sinister about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the facts I have, I have no reason to believe that was
bribery,'' Gosper said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the IOC's special inquiry panel Saturday grilled six
of the 13 members who allegedly took nearly $800,000 in payoffs and
gifts from the Salt Lake City organizers before and after the Utah
capital landed the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IOC would not reveal their names, citing due process,
Lamine Keita of Mali was seen entering the committee's barricaded
headquarters at the lakeside Chateau de Vidy and David Sikhulumi
Sibandze of Swaziland reportedly was in town. Keita allegedly was
provided with college tuition assistance by Salt Lake; Sibandze's
son allegedly received a job with the city's development office.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry panel, chaired by IOC vice president Richard Pound
of Canada, worked into the night Saturday to finish its report. The
11-member executive board, which includes five members of the
panel, is expected to demand at least seven resignations Sunday.
Pirjo Haeggman of Finland and Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi of Libya
stepped down last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
