<HEADER>
A5763 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-2006GAMES-SIONTUR     01-23 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-2006GAMES-SIONTURIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SION, TURIN SCORE WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The Swiss resort of Sion and the Italian
city of Turin, as expected, emerged as the front-runners for the
2006 Winter Games Saturday when the International Olympic
Committee's site-evaluation commission made its detailed report
here.
</P>
<P>
   Though the commission pointedly avoided ranking the six
candidate cities, Sion and Turin clearly received the best
technical grades for aspects ranging from venues to technology to
transportation to accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Helsinki (Finland) and Klagenfurt (Austria) face serious
barriers because they are proposing joint bids involving other
countries. Helsinki is paired with Lillehammer (Norway), which
hosted the 1994 Games. Klagenfurt is bidding with nearby towns from
Italy and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is interesting, but we have to deal with different
languages, different legal aspects,'' said IOC member Chiharu Igaya
of Japan, chair of the commission, which includes US Olympic
Committee vice president Paul George, a Wellesley attorney. ``This
is a big challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Zakopane (Poland) and Poprad-Tatry (Slovakia) are considered
long shots.
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC, in the wake of the Salt Lake City bribery scandal,
bans its members from visiting the bid cities before the June vote,
Sion would have a decided advantage, since it bid for the 2002
Games and is a familiar site. Turin is a first-time candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the members cannot come we will have to use another kind of
communication,'' shrugged Turin committee president Evelina
Christillin. ``We will use the art of arrangiarsi (making impromptu
arrangements). We Italians are masters of arrangiarsi.''
</P>
<P>
   What might have been
</P>
<P>
   Had the executive board chosen the site, odds are Beijing would
have landed the 2000 Games instead of Sydney, says Phil Coles, one
of Australia's three IOC members. ``I know of three or four of the
executive board before the decision was made who were committed to
China,'' said Coles, ``so if the decision were left to them, my
guess is that Sydney would not have won it.'' As it was, Sydney won
by only two votes (45-43) after IOC president Juan Antonio
Samaranch made it plain he favored Beijing. Had the board done the
choosing for the 1998 Winter Games, Salt Lake City (which had the
best technical package), also might have won instead of Nagano . .
. Salt Lake City isn't the only Olympic site with headaches.
Sydney, which is spending $3.7 billion on the 2000 Summer Games,
will be billing Australian taxpayers an extra $441 million to make
up a revenue shortfall that may exceed $1 billion. Which is one
reason why Sydney is hoping that sponsors don't start bailing out
in the wake of the IOC bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Americans on track
</P>
<P>
   Decent showing by the US long-track speedskaters, who earned
five spots for next month's world all-around championships in
Norway at the recent regional qualifier against the Canadians.
Besides Jennifer Rodriguez, the former in-liner from Miami who won
all four races, the Americans will send Sarah Shapiro, Catherine
Raney, KC Boutiette, and Derek Parra. Rodriguez also will go to
next month's world sprint championships in Calgary, along with
Christine Witty, Becky Sundstrom, Amy Sannes, and Casey
FitzRandolph . . . Bad break for the US bobsledders, who lost top
pusher Paul Wise for the rest of the season with fractured
vertebrae. The Yanks, who missed an Olympic medal by .02 seconds at
Nagano, haven't made a World Cup podium since November . . . Rough
winter for Somerville luger Erin Warren, who failed to qualify for
the US team for next weekend's world championships in Germany after
posting the top women's finish at the Olympics. Warren, who set a
track record on the Salt Lake run last fall, never came out of her
early-season slump. The Americans announced a trim initial roster
(Adam Heidt and the doubles teams of Chris Thorpe-Gordy Sheer, Mark
Grimmette-Brian Martin, and Christian Niccum-Matt McClain), but
could add up to three women (including Westborough's Ashley Hayden)
and another man Monday . . . As expected, the rebuilding US
biathlon team is taking its lumps on the World Cup circuit.
Promising showing, though, by 21-year-old Rachel Steer, who placed
26th in the sprint at Ruhpolding . . . Half a dozen athletes from
New England schools grace the barebones US roster for the biennial
World University Games now under way in Slovakia _ Alpine skiers
J.J. Hanley (Williams), Brad Nichol (Williams), and Wendy Scipione
(UVM); biathlete Clarissa Werre (Dartmouth); and short-track
speedskaters Tracy Northup (Harvard) and Chris Needham
(Northeastern). Also on the squad are New England natives Elizabeth
Sherry (New London, N.H., University of Utah, Alpine skiing), Eric
Tremble (South Hero, Vt., St. Lawrence, biathlon), and Sarah Lang
(Arlington, University of Calgary, short-track). The Americans, who
have been downscaling their presence in the WUGs in recent years,
are sending only 26 athletes in three of the nine sports.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Stanford
</P>
<P>
   Looks like Stanford's twice-thwarted bid for the world outdoor
track and field championships could be delayed another decade.
After this summer's meet in Seville and the 2001 event in Edmonton,
the IAAF is considering a package deal that would award the
championships to Paris and London (in either order) in 2003 and
2005, Tokyo in 2007, and Berlin in 2009. 2011, anyone? . . . Why
won't Mary Decker Slaney be showing up for her IAAF arbitration
hearing in Monte Carlo this week? Because USA Track &AMP; Field has
already cleared her of the testosterone doping charge from the 1996
Olympic trials and Slaney figures the beef is between the
international federation and the USATF . . . The Lords of the Rings
may have banned androstenedione, Mark McGwire's pump-up steroidal
supplement, but they have no beef with creatine. ``Creatine is
food,'' declared Prince Alexandre de Merode, the IOC's medical
chairman. ``You can't prevent people from eating food.'' Though
creatine's long-term effects are unclear, superdoses of the amino
acid protein can cause cramping and dehydration. ``You can get ill
if you take too much creatine,'' shrugs de Merode. ``But if a
person stuffs himself with 30 eggs or a kilo of foie gras, he'll
damage his liver, too.'' . . . Eleven members of last year's World
Cup team (including half a dozen Olympians) have made the US
women's field hockey squad that will be trying to qualify for
Sydney this summer. Top veterans are 32-year-old Tracey Fuchs,
Kelli James, Antoinette Lucas, and Kris Fillat, who have nearly 500
caps among them. New head coach will be Tracey Belbin, who played
in two Olympics for Australia and won gold in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Come again?
</P>
<P>
   No more visual sightings to determine false starts in Olympic
sailing. The Swatch people will use the Differential Global
Positioning System in Sydney to tell whether boats cross the line
early. That means instant recalls and shorter delays . . . It's not
enough that triathlon and trampolining have been added to the
bulging Olympic program for 2000. Athens wants fin swimming (using
32-inch wide rubber-and-fiberglass monofins) and water skiing on
the 2004 program. The Greeks are also considering karate and
billiards (yes, as in pool). The IOC will decide in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
