</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOU HEARD ABOUT THE BRUINS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what about the Bruins? What is their place on the totem pole
of New England sports franchises?
</P>
<P>
   Are they truly worshipped by a silent majority of devout fans,
recipients of weak coverage by a local media that cares not about
hockey? Or are they practitioners of a third-world sport, ranking a
consensus fourth in the minds of Greater Boston's sports fans?
</P>
<P>
   There is no reliable measure of this. What is beyond dispute is
the fact that the Bruins have a young, exciting team on the rise
with the most colorful, quotable coach in town _ and yet they rank
fourth with television news directors and newspaper sports editors.
And when it comes to that growing beast that is sports talk radio,
the local pro hockey team does not even exist.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins president Harry Sinden says, ``I did resent it for a long
time, but I don't anymore because it hasn't hurt us. The only thing
that's hurt us is our performance and our prices. The Bruins get
hurt if they don't have a decent team and if their prices are too
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to be candid. Hockey people are hockey people, and
they don't care whether there's anything in the paper or not. They
come to the games.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right about that. Since rolling back their prices (some
seats by as much as $21) after the 1997-98 season, the Bruins have
already filled the New Garden 11 times in the first half of this
season. There were only four sellouts all last year, a season that
came on the heels of the team's worst campaign in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   It can be said that Boston has a hockey culture like few other
American cities. You may not talk Bruins around the water cooler,
but chances are you've got someone in your neighborhood getting up
at 6 a.m. to drive a kid to hockey practice.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden says, ``I've seen no indication of a dropoff in the
fandom. You can't talk to one person that doesn't know another
person that's involved in hockey. You can't say that about any
other sport around here. Ask your neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Shaughnessy neighborhood, there's a former Yale hockey
player, a former Harvard women's player, and a large handful of
kids getting squired around in vans seeking ice at all hours. And
there's ubiquitous street hockey during vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Game on.
</P>
<P>
   But it's rare that anyone asks me about the Bruins. What's the
problem? Not enough scoring? Bad on television? Not enough star
power? Too many Russians? A snobbish media, ignoring the
blue-collar hockey fandom?
</P>
<P>
   ``We get plenty of coverage,'' says Sinden. ``We don't get the
guys that count in the columns. We take that as an indication that
you don't care, or you're afraid that you might not know how to
write about it. But in terms of coverage, you can read about the
Bruins every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always on the third page of the sports page. Now we're
on the fourth. I don't care if we're on the fourth. I just don't
want it to disappear. Just keep us on the fourth because we've been
there forever and it doesn't make any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the record state that Harry is not going around complaining
about coverage of his team. He's merely answering questions about
the issue. Like most hockey people, Harry looks you in the eye and
tells you what he thinks no matter how dumb or offensive the
question might be.
</P>
<P>
   And where does Harry think the Bruins would rank if we could
accurately measure the core constituency of the four Boston pro
teams (sorry, Revolution)?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we come right below the Red Sox,'' he says. ``I think
we would be second to the Red Sox without a doubt. It may not show
up in what you guys write. Because, what's the order of the day?
There's an ego involved in the media and if I were a writer, I'd be
the same way. I'd want to write about what's important to the
nation. Big-time news. That's important.''
</P>
<P>
   And how to account for the Bruins' invisibility on WEEI? Why are
there no calls? Could it be that Bruins fans have lives? Are the
Bruins people actually working during the day?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're totally ignored,'' says Harry. ``We don't get any
callers and we don't get any comments from the people on the air.
But we've survived in spite of all that. It's not good in terms of
exposure. But we don't go up or down based on how often there are
discussions about us on WEEI. We are what we are because of how we
play, and that's about it. If we end up with the best team in the
NHL, you can't get in here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins went into their All-Star break with a record of
20-16-7. They are probably bound for the playoffs. Last year they
played well enough to beat the Washington Capitals in the first
round, then watched the Capitals go all the way to the Stanley Cup
finals. They resume their schedule Tuesday night on Long Island.
They probably are closer to winning their next championship than
any other Boston sports team.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case you're interested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
