<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5768 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PALMER-B     01-23 2589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PALMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AGREEABLY TOUGH COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took someone like Chris Palmer to put Bob Kraft and Bill
Parcells on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Palmer's appointment Thursday as the
coach of the Cleveland Browns, both Kraft and Parcells gave ringing
endorsements when owner Al Lerner and club president Carmen Policy
inquired about the former Patriots quarterback coach. It's one of
the few things they've agreed on since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strong measure of the man that Palmer is someone both
Kraft and Parcells could endorse, because it means he can be a
coach's coach and an owner's coach. To a lesser degree, he is also
a players' coach, but Palmer understands that he is their coach,
not their friend, a point he made years ago after taking over the
struggling program at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his first acts at BU, Palmer cut the captain of the
team, feeling his attitude was a barrier to progress. That night he
got a call from BU president John Silber that he felt certain was
going to be a demand to reinstate the player, which in turn meant
he wouldn't be the head coach for long.
</P>
<P>
   But to Palmer's surprise, Silber congratulated him for the stand
he took. Thus began a process of leadership that has led to his
being handed the reins of one of the NFL's most storied franchises.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the interviews were done, Mr. Lerner and Carmen excused
themselves around 3:30 p.m. and said they had to talk,'' Palmer
recalled. ``They were gone about an hour. I felt like I was a
kicker and they were trying to ice me with three timeouts. I'm
sitting in a dining room. There are no books to read. I called my
wife three times. I'm finally thinking, `Come on, fellas. Either
you like me or you don't.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally they came back and offered me the job, and I asked if
there was anyone I needed to call and thank. They said Bill
Parcells and Robert Kraft.''
</P>
<P>
   When the week began, Palmer was a long shot in Cleveland because
Minnesota offensive coordinator Brian Billick was the hot
candidate. But after the Vikings were eliminated from the playoffs,
negotiations hit a snag when Billick said he wanted to talk with
the Ravens before deciding where he would go.
</P>
<P>
   Word in Cleveland is that Billick expressed reservations about
taking over an expansion team with no players, reservations Policy
took exception to, particularly since the other team Billick wanted
to visit was the team formerly known as the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Later Policy would say that Billick ``missed his opportunity to
put his thumbprint, his very DNA, on history.''
</P>
<P>
   As this was going on Monday, Palmer was driving from
Jacksonville, Fla., to Mobile, Ala., with Jaguars defensive
coordinator Dick Jauron, whose name also has been mentioned for
several head coaching vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer had interviewed in Cleveland the previous week but still
felt Billick and 49ers head coach Steve Mariucci were the leading
candidates. He also had interviewed with the Ravens and had an
interview scheduled with the Kansas City Chiefs Tuesday when he got
a message to call Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut the meeting with Kansas City short because they wanted
me to meet Mr. Lerner on Wednesday,'' Palmer recalled. ``This was
the job I wanted most. It was the one that fit me and my
personality. I was in the outside lane at the start of the race,
but I made the turn well.''
</P>
<P>
   He made it after a lengthy grilling from Lerner at MBNA
headquarters outside Cleveland during which he was asked ``about 10
questions that hit me between the eyes.'' One was to name the 10
best coaches and the common denominator among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensity with which he asked a question is second to
none,'' Palmer said. ``It's no b.s., answer it.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer did, because he has the presence of a head coach backed
by the track record of a winner, whether rebuilding small college
programs or building up powerful pro offenses like the one he ran
in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Cleveland were to get a young quarterback, he could not be
in a better situation,'' said Jacksonville quarterback Mark
Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Browns take Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch or
Texas's Heisman Trophy-winning running back Ricky Williams, their
new coach will run whatever offense suits its star. That has been
Palmer's specialty, in the USFL, where he directed an attack with
Doug Flutie and Herschel Walker in the same backfield, and the NFL.
That is what Policy and Lerner were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a strong influence on our offense,'' said Palmer.
``My philosophy is you run to win and throw to score. If Ricky
Williams is our guy, we'll load up and pound the ball. If we decide
on Tim Couch, who I haven't really even seen yet, we'll get him
some receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns already have the first building block of a solid
franchise. They have themselves a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came through the Bill Parcells School,'' Palmer told a
packed press conference Thursday. ``Bill Parcells makes you tough.
Every day he made me a better coach. But my personality is
different. I hope you can see that. Bill Belichick (another
Parcells assistant and the last man to coach the Browns) was his
guy. I'm my guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wants proof of that need only spend a moment in
Palmer's office, because in it is a plaque with a quote from the
greatest coach in Browns history, Paul Brown himself: ``I'm going
to do it my way . . . and I know it's right.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, a man who has moved his wife and family 11 times
in 27 years to pursue the football coach's life was given his
chance. Don't bet against him.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bob Kraft and Bill Parcells can agree on that.
</P>
<P>
   It's payback time
</P>
<P>
   Following a whirlwind trip home to Jacksonville to pick up some
laundry, Palmer joked that one of his five brothers told him their
wives were all calling each other saying they married the wrong
Palmer. That's because most of them are plumbers, and as of Sunday
Chris is a $1 million-a-year NFL head coach. But it wasn't always
that way. ``When Donna and I first got married, I was a coach and
she was an X-ray technician,'' said Palmer. ``We'd been dating for
six years and she made more money than me. I told her one reason I
married her was I couldn't afford to pay her back what I owed
her.'' . . . After witnessing the animosity in Jacksonville after
Kevin Gilbride left to become head coach of the Chargers and took
assistant Nick Nicolau with him, Palmer agreed not to infiltrate
the staffs of the Jaguars or Parcells's Jets. ``I never want to
leave a place and have hard feelings,'' Palmer said. ``I wasn't
told I'd be denied permission to interview anyone but they said
they wished I wouldn't do it. When it's your friends, you honor
that.'' . . . Baltimore's signing of Billick will only intensify a
natural rivalry between the new Browns and the old ones . . .
Billick will offer old friend and former Patriot quarterback Matt
Cavanaugh the offensive coordinator's job. Cavanaugh was last seen
coordinating the Bears' offense . . . Atlanta head coach Dan Reeves
knew exactly what he was doing last week when he talked openly
about his feelings of betrayal that led him to fire his former
offensive coordinator, Mike Shanahan, in Denver. Reeves believed
Shanahan violated his trust by repeating critical comments Reeves
made in staff meetings about John Elway to the Broncos'
quarterback. Shanahan denied that, and Elway said he was
``flabbergasted'' that Reeves would make such a charge on the eve
of their Super Bowl confrontation. But Reeves made a masterful
psychological move that Shanahan and Elway will have to deal with
all week. He has the high ground on this after being fired despite
taking the Broncos to three Super Bowls; many believe it was Elway
who submarined him, with Shanahan's assistance. ``You say things in
a coaches meeting as far as critiquing a player that you would
never say to a player,'' Reeves said. ``If John ever got any bad
feelings about something I said, it was never done publicly. It had
to be something coming from a staff meeting. Now, does that mean
Mike did it? I have no proof of it. Nothing. But I did what I felt
was best for our football team. It wasn't an easy decision because
I knew he was a great football coach. But I didn't think he had my
best interest at heart.'' So Reeves fired Shanahan and later
charged him with insubordination. ``It's totally untrue,'' Shanahan
said. ``When I was there, Dan never said a word about it. Dan
wanted to run the offense and he wanted complete control and he
really didn't want somebody with my type of personality around.''
You don't think Elway and Shanahan will be asked about this a few
thousand times, do you? Distractions? What distractions?
</P>
<P>
   Running a reverse
</P>
<P>
   Interesting turn of events that led Paul Boudreau to take over
as the Miami offensive line coach. Boudreau is made a sacrificial
lamb in New England because the running game is less than
overpowering but he's hired within days by a coach, Jimmy Johnson,
who wants nothing more than to be able to run the ball. Meanwhile,
Johnson fires Larry Beightol to make room for Boudreau, and who
tries to hire Beightol? New England. I could not make this up.
Beightol, however, feared that Patriot coach Pete Carroll could be
a lame duck, so he signed instead with new Packers coach Ray Rhodes
. . . Cowboys owner Jerry Jones had an unusual hour-and-40-minute
interview with five reporters from the Dallas Morning News last
week. Jones raised an interesting point when asked about his
insistence on being the club's general manager, a post he's
basically held for most of the 10 years he's owned the team. ``Hey,
we're in good shape,'' Jones said. ``The decisions are being made
on the same principles they were made over the last 10 years. I've
been very up-front from the first day I got here. The reason I own
the team is to manage the team. As long as I own this team, I'll be
running the football. I understand the criticism, and respect that.
But the question I have is, `How many years before you become a
football guy in the NFL?' Is it 20? Is it 10? Is it 15? When is
it?' I take a lot of input. It's wrong to think I'm sitting there
reading some football magazines and that's how we're making the
decisions with the Dallas Cowboys.'' Good point . . . In a league
supposedly trying hard to promote black assistants, nearly a third
of the head coaching jobs opened up this winter, and not one was
filled by a new black face. In fact, 25 of the last 26 head
coaching vacancies have been filled by white coaches. Some may try
to say it's progress that the Packers' job went to a familiar black
face, Rhodes, who was hired there after being fired in
Philadelphia; but five assistant coaches with little or no head
coaching experience and a sixth who was 8-14 at Oregon State were
all hired ahead of Art Shell, who won 60 percent of his games as
the Raiders' head coach, and longtime Packers offensive coordinator
Sherman Lewis. Lewis has to be particularly frustrated. At 58, he
has seen two of the quarterback coaches who worked under him,
Mariucci and this year Andy Reid, get head jobs ahead of him even
though he was running the Green Bay offense along with Mike
Holmgren. Apparently it's going to take a lot more than a library
of videotaped interviews on file at the NFL offices in New York to
create equal opportunity in the NFL. The only way it will really be
done is clear in Green Bay, which could have the first staff in NFL
history with three blacks on top. If it goes as planned, Rhodes
will have Emmitt Thomas as his defensive coordinator, as he was in
Philadelphia, and Lewis will continue to run the offense. Most of
the time, friends hire their friends in business. Every business.
Including the football business. So until black coaches get into
positions with hiring authority, it will be difficult for many of
their peers to get the opportunity they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Very hot tickets
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to pardon the sisters working at the Francis Heights
Senior Center in Denver if they ask for a little divine
intervention on behalf of the Broncos in the Super Bowl. Last week,
a Denver city councilman donated two tickets to the game for the
center to raffle off as it tries to raise $150,000 to repair its
pool. The sisters were hoping to sell 3,000 raffle tickets in three
days, but they sold out in three hours. A businessman had his jet
diverted to Denver so he could buy 20 raffle tickets . . . Things
are heating up again on the expansion front, with one of the Los
Angeles bidders adding a deep-pocketed ally in billionaire Eli
Broud. He joined Ed Roski's effort to refurbish the LA Coliseum,
and they plan to pitch the league's Finance Committee with a $1.1
billion proposal _ $750 million for the expansion team and another
$350 million to modernize the Coliseum. That puts them at odds with
a group headed by Michael Ovitz, the Hollywood mogul, and a group
in Houston that already has its financing and stadium plan ready.
All three groups will make another presentation next Thursday to
the Finance Committee in Miami. LA is still the favorite of some
owners, but Houston is looking so solid financially that it may be
difficult to deny . . . Don't be surprised if new Patriot receivers
coach Ivan Fears and Terry Glenn turn out to be oil and water.
There could not be two more opposite personalities . . . If I were
running the Patriots personnel department, I would focus my
attention and checkbook on the following free agent linemen:
tackles Orlando Brown (Baltimore) and Earl Dotson and guard Adam
Timmerman. Timmerman and Dotson are both 300-plus pounders who have
started regularly in Green Bay. As for receivers, I'd turn my
interest to Antonio Freeman, who caught 84 passes for 1,424 yards
and 14 touchdowns this season and could end up being named the
Packers' franchise player, or Arizona's Rob Moore. Moore is one of
the best receivers in the NFL but is lesser-known than most. He has
a 45-inch vertical leap and had two 1,000-yard seasons before just
missing (982) this time . . . The Jets have already restructured
the deals of Curtis Martin and Kevin Mawae to create salary cap
room. That's where the work of Needham native Mike Tannenbaum, the
Jets' capologist, pays off quietly for Parcells . . . New England
isn't the only place with a tough home crowd. Apparently, during
the AFC Championship game in Denver last Sunday, a fan hit the
sister of New York receiver Wayne Chrebet in the face for wearing
Jets gear . . . If you're a businessman, you might be interested to
know that Fox TV expects to haul in $142 million in ad revenue from
its seven-hour pregame show and telecast of the Super Bowl. If
you're like the rest of us, you'll be more interested to know that
an estimated $4 billion will be bet on the game, only $85 million
of it going down legally . . . After popping off two weeks ago
about the Dolphins after the Broncos pummeled them, Denver tight
end Shannon Sharpe does not expect to be received with open arms in
South Florida. ``I don't really think I'll be getting very many
free meals,'' Sharpe said . . . Anyone interested in getting into a
bidding war for Super Bowl tickets on the internet can bid online
on more than 60 tickets by contacting WWW.tickets.com. You also can
bid by calling 1-800-TICKETS . . . The Tennessee Titans have
interviewed fired Patriots wide receiver coach Steve Walters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
