<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5769 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-FIRST-HALF-TE     01-23 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-FIRST-HALF-TEX </SLUG>
 
NHL At The Break 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the NHL heads into its midseason All-Star break, much has
changed from the start of the season. The Stars are right where
they had hoped they would be, but a surge in Phoenix, a slump in
Detroit and a (Russian) Rocket launching in Florida have the rest
of the league looking quite different.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the season, here are a few of the key
stories to keep an eye on:
STARRY START
</P>
<P>
   Already, fans in North Texas are beginning to look at the Stars
as the new Cowboys _ and that's scary. While players and coaches
can try to play down the pressure, fans are making plans for a
Stanley Cup parade, and many so-called experts around the league
are penciling in the Stars as the heavy favorites to take the
silverware home in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it,'' center Mike Modano said. ``We know every team is
out to beat us on any given night. But, I think we like the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, talk is heating up that the Stars need to swing a deal
to get a physical, goal-scoring left winger to patch the final hole
in their lineup. Already, talk is heating up that Ed Belfour might
not be the goalie to take them there. Already, the expectations are
so great that a team that loses only nine of its first 43 games is
being asked to give more and do more.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a good sign, but fans can't hope to win the Cup in
January or March.
</P>
<P>
   All of which means, the team, the front office, the coaching
staff and the fans have to remember to be patient. The next five
months could be the greatest in the history of the franchise, but
that doesn't mean the Stars have to try to live them in the span of
a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that really bothers me about all this is we're
taking winning a little too lightly here,'' center Brian Skrudland
said. ``This is a good team that should be having a lot of fun
enjoying what is a great season. We can't lose sight of that while
we're trying to get to someplace that we want to go.''
FLY IN THE OINTMENT
</P>
<P>
   If Stars fans are Cup-starved, consider the pressure on the
Philadelphia Flyers. This is a team that has thought it was ``this
close'' in January for the previous eight seasons, only to have it
all fall apart in May or June.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers didn't even wait that long last season, getting
dispatched by the Buffalo Sabres in the first round of the
playoffs. That forced several changes, including new goaltender
John Vanbiesbrouck, handing more power to new coach Roger Neilson
and a public challenge by general manager Bobby Clarke to superstar
center Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke told Lindros in the summer that if he wanted to be paid
like a $10 million superstar, he'd better start acting like it _
which Lindros promptly did.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke also has made deals almost monthly to find the right
chemistry, acquiring Mikael Renberg, Keith Jones, Daymond Langkow
and Stephen Leach since the start of the season and dealing Chris
Gratton, Trent Klatt, Mike Maneluk, Shjon Podein, Mike Sillinger
and Petr Svoboda.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the season, the Flyers have put together a
15-game unbeaten streak and lead the Eastern Conference with 58
points. Yet if Clarke doesn't win the Stanley Cup this season, he
could be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of puts things into perspective, huh?
WHAT ARE YOU DOING HERE?
</P>
<P>
   Alexei Yashin obviously was concerned with money. The second
overall pick in the 1992 draft was peeved that he wasn't getting as
much as Ottawa Senators teammate Alexandre Daigle, the
underachieving winger taken first overall in 1993. But what really
hacked Yashin off was the fact he believed management had no clue
what it was doing.
</P>
<P>
   So Yashin held out in 1995 and told his owners that he wanted to
be traded to a team that wasn't quite so stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Brash move? Maybe. But the Senators fired GM Randy Sexton,
replaced two coaches and signed Yashin up to a long-term deal.
Today, Yashin is the team captain, and the Senators could be the
ultimate dark horse in the run for the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just have so much talent,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``They're fast, they play hard and they're well-coached.
That's a team to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the Toronto Maple Leafs, who have found great success
moving from the West to the East this season and picking up
West-slaying goaltender Curtis Joseph in the process. With Joseph
in net and new coach Pat Quinn stressing offensive play, the Leafs
are looking for home-ice advantage in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the other surprises?
</P>
<P>
   How 'bout the Phoenix Coyotes finally settling differences and
coming together as a team. The final proof is a long way off for
the injury-prone Coyotes, but at least the first step has been
taken.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres continue to excel with Dominik Hasek in net and
appear to be more than just a fluke. And the Carolina Hurricanes
and Florida Panthers both would like to try the role of spoiler for
the playoffs. And with the Panthers winning two games since
acquiring enigmatic superstar Pavel Bure, who knows what other
surprises await.
DIDN'T YOU USED TO BE...
</P>
<P>
   Two Stanley Cups might not be near big enough to hold all the
tears of frustration and fear that are being cried in Detroit
through the season's first half.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Red Wings are
foundering, posting a 23-20-3 record at the break. This after being
one of the best teams in the NHL for the past seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're struggling,'' winger Brendan Shanahan said. ``It's not
just one area, we're all struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wings aren't as physical as they were last season, they have
holes in their defense and they aren't getting the balanced scoring
they did last season. And yet, they are feared as a team that can
still put things together.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the defending champs,'' Hitchcock said. ``You have to
knock them out if you want them to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Avalanche might fall down a little easier. The
Avalanche likewise have fallen from the ranks of the mighty and
have been joined by the Washington Capitals (at 16-23-4 the worst
ever performance after a Finals appearance last season), the
Chicago Blackhawks (their 13 wins are second fewest in the NHL) and
the Montreal Canadiens (in jeopardy of missing the playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe the entire Western Conference is the league's real
disappointment as only four of the 13 teams have records above
.500. But can he balance a checkbook? The record of the Pittsburgh
Penguins is about the same as it was last season at 20-14-7, so why
should Kevin Constantine get your vote as coach of the year?
</P>
<P>
   Because the Penguins should be at the bottom of the NHL. Not
only did Pittsburgh lose versatile captain Ron Francis to free
agency, they also filed for bankruptcy. And all you have to do is
ask Stars fans how difficult it is to play well when your ownership
is falling apart to know exactly what Constantine has accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Give Constantine the lead for the Jack Adams coach of the year
award, but not without some great competition. The challengers in
order: Pat Quinn with the Maple Leafs, Jacques Martin with the
Senators and Jim Schoenfeld with the Coyotes.
BETTER THAN GOD?
</P>
<P>
   He is referred to as ``God'' in his native Czech Republic after
almost single-handedly winning the Olympic hockey gold medal for
his country last year. And Hasek is even better this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, the only goalie in history to win two Hart Trophies as
the league's most valuable player, is on his way to his third
consecutive trophy. Even after a recent slump, Hasek still has a
1.86 goals-against average and a league-best save percentage of
.939. He has eight shutouts and could challenge the modern era
season shutout record of 15.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some who are unconvinced that Hasek is the best
player in the NHL, and the fight for his trophy might be more
intense than in the two previous seasons. The list of potential
thieves: center Lindros in Philadelphia, center Yashin in Ottawa
and goalie Curtis Joseph in Toronto.
ALL-NHL
</P>
<P>
   With the season half over, several players have made their mark.
So here's Mike Heika's NHL All-Stars at the All-Star break:
</P>
<P>
   Center: Eric Lindros, Flyers _ Took challenge from Clarke and
shoved it back in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing: John LeClair, Flyers _ His penchant for goal-scoring
is baffling.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing: Theo Fleury, Flames _ To have 47 points and be a
plus player on the Flames is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   Defense: Chris Pronger, Blues _ Most ice time in the league, and
he does the most with it.
</P>
<P>
   Defense: Larry Murphy, Red Wings _ Maybe it's time to admit he
really is pretty good for an old man.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie: Dominik Hasek, Sabres _ No player can affect a game the
way he does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
