<HEADER>
A5771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-ABORTION-MARCH-CO     01-23 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-ABORTION-MARCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Demonstrators expect controversial legislation will pass in
TexasBy Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ About 500 people chanting ``Life yes, abortion
no'' marched to the Capitol Saturday in support of a proposed Texas
law requiring doctors to tell parents before performing an abortion
on their minor daughters.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the marchers believe, the divisive legislation will
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, the time for change has come,'' Dick Weinhold,
president of the Texas Christian Coaltion and the rally's main
speaker, told the crowd of young and old, whites, blacks and
Hispanics, who cheered and waved signs reading ``Restore Parent
Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The marchers had carried red, blue and white balloons in their
march to the Capitol. Members of anti-abortion groups such as the
Greater Austin Right to Life and Texans United for Life, they were
supporting Senate Bill 30 and House Bill 623, which are similar to
a proposed parental notification law that failed to pass in the
Legislature's last session in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Majek, 41, an Austin member of the Knights of Columbus
whose officials led the marchers, said he thought the law had a
better chance of passage this year because of support from Gov.
George W. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, both Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Austinite Donna Oberg, 70, who was passing out donation
envelopes to help defray the costs of the rally, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just do our work and our praying,'' Oberg said, ``God
will take care of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law did not sound so worthy on the other side of
the abortion debate, which has raged nationwide since a U.S.
Supreme Court decision legalized abortions 26 years ago Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't improve family communication,'' said Margot Clarke,
public affairs director for Planned Parenthood of Austin, which
refers women to some of the six Austin abortion clinics listed in
Southwestern Bell's Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it means that teens delay care, or seek unsafe care, or
force communication in an abusive family situation, then it's
clearly not in the young person's interest,'' Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   Since most minors already involve their parents in abortion
decisions, Clarke said, and only those who have difficulties with
their parents would be affected, she wondered if the law's true
intent was to reduce the number of abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, marcher Paula Lundgaard, 39, a mother of four children
who recently moved to Austin from New Mexico, said she'd marched
against abortion for 20 years and would continue to march.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like not to have a reason to do this,'' Lundgaard said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
