<HEADER>
A5773 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HOUSTON-TULANE-HN     01-23 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOUSTON-TULANE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Houston squanders lead, shot at road win
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS _ Seemingly on the verge of a rarity, the Houston
Cougars reverted to their earlier form Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Said UH's William Stringfellow, ``We could have made history.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cougars lost their 20th consecutive Conference USA
road game, an 89-84 loss to Tulane, which wiped out a 17-point
first-half UH lead and made the plays down the stretch that UH
failed to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't keep playing like we had when we were building the
lead,'' said disappointed coach Clyde Drexler, who calmly analyzed
the 7-11 Cougars' sixth loss in eight conference games this season.
``I was proud of the way they played after a terrible game before
this, but once again, we just didn't do what it takes to win
consistently enough. It was a very big missed opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially considering that after they saw their 38-21 margin at
4:39 before halftime quickly go down the drain, the Cougars
regained a 75-74 lead with 3:18 remaining. But the Green Wave then
scored seven straight points, including Dylan Osean's 3-pointer,
then his 18-foot banker for an 81-75 lead with 1:43 to play. UH
missed three point-blank shots during that span, pulled within
81-78 on Gee Gervin's trey with 50 seconds left but never got
closer.
</P>
<P>
   Winless in a conference road game since a victory at SMU on Feb.
28, 1996, the last year of the Southwest Conference, the Cougars
should have been in good shape late in the first half. Tulane, with
15 turnovers before halftime, was throwing the ball into the stands
at times as UH went on a 15-1 run with 12 points off Green Wave
errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we had three or four straight turnovers, they cut into
the lead, and they came out the second half and hit shots while we
didn't play with the same kind of intensity,'' Drexler said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Osean hit a pair of 3s and Byron Mouton and Wade
Mason made one each, Tulane (3-4 in C-USA, 9-7 overall) had a 56-50
lead six minutes into the second half. Osean's second trey finished
a 22-7 burst after halftime and an improbable 35-12 run in 10
minutes spanning the first and second halves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many offensive rebounds at the wrong time, too many
mistakes when there really wasn't that much pressure on the ball,''
Drexler said. ``I counted six missed layups in the last four
minutes, and in a game like this, that gets you beat. That was part
of our downfall today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin, the game's high scorer with 26 points, again forced
things at times but passed off for four straight baskets midway
through the second half when the Cougars regained the lead. Their
momentum didn't last, however, with Tulane shooting 58 percent
after halftime and 50 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just wasn't the same defensive intensity as in the first
half,'' said UH junior forward Kenny Younger (19 points, 10
rebounds, four steals).
</P>
<P>
   ``We played better than the last game (a 17-point loss at
Southern Mississippi on Thursday) but we didn't carry it through
like we have to do.'' Gervin said, ``We missed early opportunities.
Coach kept telling us over and over that we have to play defense in
the second half like we did in the first. But we didn't have the
same fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars made their first 12 free throws, then missed seven
of their last 13. They also were outrebounded 40-33 and did things
like inbound the ball wildly under their own basket, leading to an
easy Tulane basket during the Wave's big run. Stringfellow scored a
career-high 17 points but drew his fourth personal with 17 minutes
to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Wave, coming off an 80-64 upset of National Division leader
Alabama-Birmingham on Thursday at Birmingham, nearly sank at the
outset.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were forcing shots and trying to make passes that weren't
there until we got calmed down,'' Tulane coach Perry Clark said.
``I was very fearful of this game. I thought Clyde did a
magnificent job of getting his guys ready to play today after their
last game. It was very critical for us to get their lead down to
nine (43-34) at the half.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Clark: ``I told Clyde that he coaches like a guy with a
lot of money because he doesn't get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's because it doesn't show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
