<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5774 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-HNS &LR;      01-23 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUDGE RULES LEWINSKY MUST TALK; SENATE ERUPTS OVER SURPRISE MOVE
BY STARR, HOUSE PROSECUTORS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
By GREG McDONALD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's impeachment trial turned into a
highly partisan battleground Saturday after a federal judge ordered
Monica Lewinsky to cooperate with House prosecutors who want to
question her as a prelude to her possible testimony in the
historical Senate proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson issued her ruling
after independent counsel Kenneth Starr intervened in federal court
on behalf of the House Republican prosecution team, whose repeated
requests to interview the former White House intern had been denied
by her lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the 13 House prosecutors to ask for help from
Starr in forcing Lewinsky's cooperation outraged Democratic
senators as well as Clinton's legal team, who charged the
prosecutors with attempting to circumvent the Senate's rules that
call for putting off all decisions on witnesses until sometime this
week.
</P>
<P>
   As the impeachment trial continued on the Senate floor with
senators asking questions of the prosecutors and lawyers for a
second day, Lewinsky arrived in Washington from her home in
California to undergo yet another round of questioning about her
illicit affair with the president, which led to the House filing
impeachment charges of perjury and obstruction of justice against
him. Prosecutors said they would likely interview her today.
</P>
<P>
   Under hostile questioning from Democrats in Saturday's
proceeding, House prosecutors defended their decision to seek
Starr's help without informing the Senate as ``a normal'' procedure
that any prosecutor would undertake in an effort to ``prepare a
witness for testimony in a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., described their actions as simply an
effort ``to get to know'' Lewinsky, who has an immunity from
prosecution agreement with Starr, and to ``say hello'' before they
attempt to introduce her into the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``As anybody knows, if you have a witness that you're going to
produce, you have a right to prepare that witness. It's as plain
and simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   But White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff put a different spin
on it, saying ``what we have here is (the prosecutors) using their
... institutional role to get the independent counsel to join with
them and use the authority that he has under the immunity agreement
to threaten Miss Lewinsky with jail.''
</P>
<P>
   He characterized the prosecution's move as much more than
wanting to have ``a friendly little conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   The House action so angered Democrats that some suggested that
it was grounds for immediate dismissal of the impeachment charges
against Clinton. Several Democrats led by Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa,
submitted a written motion to Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who
is presiding over the impeachment trial, asking him to overturn
Johnson's order on grounds that she has no authority to determine
the procedures under which the House managers or White House
counsel may interview witnesses. Citing Supreme Court rulings in a
previous impeachment, Harkin said the justices ruled that the
Senate has sole authority over its proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate word on whether Rehnquist would act on
the request.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also charged that Starr's intervention had erased
any doubts about where he stands on the question of impeachment and
the removal of Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might as well provide a chair at the House prosecutors'
table for independent counsel Kenneth Starr, who has lost all
semblance of independence,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is turning into a three-ring circus. It's a spectacle,''
Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Starr shrugged off the charges, telling reporters
Saturday that he was ``duty bound'' to act on the prosecutors'
request for help because of the referral of evidence in the case
that he sent to them last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The events involving Starr and Lewinsky upset the bipartisan
spirit with which Democratic and Republican senators began two
weeks ago, when they agreed on the rules for conducting the first
impeachment trial of a president in nearly 131 years.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats warned Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
that ``all bets are off,'' as one put it, unless he exercises some
control over the conduct of the House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This political jockeying has got to stop,'' warned Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., who plans to offer a motion on Monday to dismiss the
case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., also blasted the
House's lead prosecutor, Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., for ignoring his admonition not to interview witnesses
until the Senate had voted ``to give you the authority to do so.''
He also requested that at the appropriate time, members of the
Senate be allowed to sit in on any preparatory interviews with
witnesses. Hyde said no to that request as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This unwillingness to cooperate with the Senate ... is as
clear a demonstration of raw partisanship as I have seen,'' said
Daschle. He called the House actions a violation of Senate rules
and a ``clear indication that this case ought to be dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., described the actions by Hyde and
Starr as ``a grandstand play'' aimed at trying to tip the scales
for conviction of the president in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned it had ``fractured everything,'' and that some
Republicans who were also angered by the move could end up
supporting Byrd's motion to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privately a lot of members _ Democrats and Republicans _ are
saying this is going nowhere ... and what the House (prosecutors)
did only makes things worse,'' Leahy said.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that things had gotten ``a little strange,''
Lott said that he was hopeful the trial would get back on track
Monday. He said there would be a motion to dismiss offered, but
indicated that it would likely fail unless the 45 Democrats are
able to pick up six Republicans to give them a majority of 51
votes.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to pick up support, Byrd added language to his
motion that would serve to censure the president for bringing
``dishonor'' on his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it would be a big mistake if the Senate voted to
dismiss,'' Lott said. ``I don't believe the American people would
be satisfied if we just stopped in the middle of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there would also be a vote on whether to subpoena
witnesses. Although most of the 55 Republicans in the Senate appear
to favor the idea of allowing some witnesses to testify, a number
of them have said publicly that they do not like the idea of
Lewinsky making an appearance on the Senate floor. That prospect
could help the Democrats pick up votes for their dismissal motion.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Lott said that he had asked White House lawyers
if Clinton would be willing to respond to questions in writing,
rather than making an appearance in the Senate chamber. The
president's lawyers at first said they would consider it, but then
later indicated that they would answer on the president's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the political theater surrounding Lewinsky's return to
Washington dominated the day, the Senate carried on with questions
to prosecutors and Clinton lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Ruff told the senators that they have an
obligation to consider more than just the facts in the case as they
struggle to reach a decision. He said, for example, the ``will of
the people'' ought to be taken into account as well.
</P>
<P>
   His comment drew an emotional response from Hyde, who told the
lawmakers that members of Congress ``are not sent here to weigh our
mail every day and then to vote accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are elected to bring our experience and our consciences
with us here,'' Hyde said. ``Despite all the polls and the hostile
editorials, America is hungry for people who believe in something.
You may disagree with us, but we believe in something.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Time/CNN poll, 54 percent of those questioned said
they disapproved of the Republican's handling of the Senate trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
