r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN     01-23 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SLOW DOWN MURRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE _ UCLA coach Steve Lavin made his list, he checked it
twice, then he instructed UCLA to be anything but nice to
Louisville point guard Cameron Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin scribbled Murray's name on the locker-room chalkboard as
the latest challenge for his guards: the ``victims'' list, he
called it.
</P>
<P>
   Like Arizona's Jason Terry, Arizona State's Eddie House, Cal's
Geno Carlisle and Stanford's Art Lee, Murray is the vortex of
Louisville's attack. When he plays well, so do the Cardinals. When
he struggles, so do the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he did not play well, and neither did they.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA guards Baron Davis, Earl Watson and Ray Young hounded
Murray into one of his worst performances of the season. He made 6
of 16 shots, committed seven turnovers and lost his composure
several times in the Bruins' 82-70 victory Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their guards did a great job overall,'' said Murray, the
former USC player whose brother, Tracy, played for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hat's off to (Young). When he was in the game, his job
obviously was to keep me from getting the ball. He frustrated me,
he pushed me, he tired me out. He did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   With their floor leader struggling, the Cardinals committed 16
turnovers in the second half and never found their offensive
rhythm, making 10 of 29 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Murray's seven turnovers came in the second half, with
Young defending him most of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear him getting frustrated,'' said Young, who
played a career-high 34 minutes. ``He was asking for fouls to be
called. When you get a player crying to the refs and asking for
fouls, you've got him right where you want him.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, a senior, finishes his college career winless against
UCLA in six games.
</P>
<P>
   How they stand: UCLA was the latest top-25 opponent for
Louisville, which has faced North Carolina, Kentucky and
Cincinnati. The Bearcats defeated Louisville 81-55 Thursday night,
holding Murray scoreless and forcing him into four turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Bruins) definitely could hold their own,'' Louisville
center Alex Sanders said. ``Cincinnati is bigger and stronger than
they are, but UCLA's guards are better.''
</P>
<P>
   Fright flight: The Bruins experienced severe turbulence on the
final portion of their flight from L.A. to Memphis on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Their Northwest Airlines plane banked hard and felt like it was
dropping out of the sky. Lightning was visible outside both sides
of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman JaRon Rush was so shaken, he refused to get on the
connecting flight to Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst flight I've ever had,'' Rush said. ``The wind
was banging us so hard, I thought we going to die. I was not
getting on that second plane. They couldn't do anything. I wasn't
getting on that plane.''
</P>
<P>
   So Rush and several UCLA officials made the six-hour drive from
Memphis to Louisville, arriving at 4 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After the game _ he scored eight points and grabbed nine
rebounds _ Rush said he planned to board UCLA's flight home
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be all right, but my palms might be sweaty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over or not: Louisville coach Denny Crum said it was UCLA's
decision to end the home-and-home series, which began in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they have schedule problems,'' he said. ``But they
want to renew it after two years. This stop is just temporary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
