<HEADER>
A5780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-MAYFIELD-COX     01-23 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-MAYFIELD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush and Perry seek spiritual guidance from Austin minister
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He's not the official state pastor, but he may
as well be.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas' top two political leaders seek spiritual guidance,
they go to Tarrytown United Methodist Church, the West Austin
church where the Rev. Jim Mayfield has been pastor for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush calls Mayfield ``a loyal member of the
flock.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry said Mayfield is well known for his
commitment to social concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every Sunday there is a different ministry he directs
the flock towards,'' Perry said. ``He speaks to me every Sunday
morning. As I'm squirming in my seat I'm sure he's talking directly
to me and the governor,'' he added with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Bush, who are Republicans, consider Mayfield a
confidant, Perry added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will become even more so, both to the governor and
myself, and I would suggest that Jim certainly has our ear,'' said
Perry, who recently named Mayfield chaplain for the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Mayfield is expected to be elected president of Austin
Metropolitan Ministries, an interfaith group representing 22 faiths
that work to help the disadvantaged and empower clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, by all accounts, is quite a regular guy. He likes to
fish. He's a poet and woodcarver.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job in this congregation, based on whoever comes, is to by
the grace of God enable them to be the best person they can be,''
Mayfield said last week.
</P>
<P>
   He makes it a point never to publicly discuss his relationship
with Bush and Perry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My perception is when they walk in the door they walk in the
door as children of God. I'm real clear about what my job is. My
job is not to be their policy adviser. My job is to be their
pastor.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, 62, was born in Austin but grew up in West Texas. He
has degrees from the University of Texas, Southern Methodist
University and Texas Christian University. He takes the most pride
in an honorary doctorate of divinity degree he received in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an honorary alum of Huston-Tillotson College,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield has held national and regional posts in the United
Methodist Church. Before coming to the Tarrytown church in 1988, he
was the Austin district superintendent for the United Methodist
Church. Austin Metropolitan Ministries is excited about Mayfield
heading its board of directors, said Patrick Flood, the
organization's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Mayfield is a great religious leader and has a strong
desire to enable the different segments of the faith community to
communicate with each other and work for the common good,'' Flood
said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Mayfield said he plans to concentrate on raising
money for the organziation and hosting events that will allow
clergy of different faiths get to know each other better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really trying to be a bridge and a place of
communication between the various religious bodies,'' Mayfield
said.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Mayfield has an easy-going personality
that makes it ``pretty easy to be comfortable around me.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his strengths is also one of his weaknesses, Mayfield
said. ``I basically have a fairly high level of trust of people so
it's easy for me to delegate,'' he said. ``The weakness is
sometimes I'm disappointed or taken advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   A nameplate in his office flashes his sense of humor. It reads:
``God so loved the world that he didn't send a committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
