<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5782 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-COSTS-LADN     01-23 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-COSTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES COSTLY PLACE TO DO BUSINESS, STUDY SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX, RICK ORLOV AND PATRICIA FARELL AIDEM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Despite pledges to make Los Angeles more business
friendly, the city remains one of California's most expensive
places to conduct commerce, according to a comprehensive study to
be released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two incorporated cities adjacent to the suburban San
Fernando Valley area of Los Angeles, Santa Clarita and Westlake
Village, are among 10 jurisdictions in Southern California ranked
among the best at courting business, said the report from Los
Angeles-based Kosmont &AMP; Associates, a commercial real estate
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   They make life easier for businesses by offering incentives and
tax breaks as relocation lures, said Larry J. Kosmont, the report's
author and consultant on such projects as Beverly Hills-based
Regent Properties' recently proposed $55 million hotel, retail and
commercial complex in suburban Burbank, Calif. The survey covered
200 communities in California and 12 cities in neighboring states
that compete for business.
</P>
<P>
   It found that California is making headway in shedding the
anti-business label it wore through the early part of this decade.
For the second consecutive year, there were more high-cost cities
in neighboring states than in California.
</P>
<P>
   For example, four California cities received a high-cost ranking
from Kosmont vs. five in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings run directly contrary to the widespread belief
that California is a high-cost state in which to do business,''
Kosmont said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth study by Kosmont's company and Los Angeles
received a ``high cost'' designation in each one. This year's
report concluded Los Angeles is the second most expensive place for
businesses behind San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Los Angeles, its size is the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with L.A. is that the (permit) process traverses
too many departments. There are too many decisions involved. It is
too much of a cooperative effort between divisions right now,''
Kosmont said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Efforts are under way to streamline a cumbersome business tax
system. Mayor Richard Riordan has proposed winnowing more than 60
business tax categories down to eight.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good idea, Kosmont said, and shows that Los Angeles is
doing better on the competitive front. But the Riordan plan won't
do much for costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make (Los Angeles) more competitive with other
high-cost cities such as Beverly Hills, Santa Monica and Culver
City,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of Riordan's program could bring a slight reduction in
taxes but neighboring cities are also holding the line on taxes and
not increasing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan did not dispute the study's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a lot but we still have to do more,'' he said.
``The tax reform is essential. So are continuing to have
public-private partnerships. That's the key to keeping business
here and attracting new ones.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Kosmont's study concludes that public-private partnerships are
especially critical now that Proposition 218, approved by voters
last year, requires voter approval of any new taxes.
</P>
<P>
   So the best way for cities to generate more revenue is by
attracting new businesses and reaping the benefits from the boost
to business, property and sales tax rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Kosmont gave Los Angeles high marks on this front. It was one of
10 Southern California areas that participated in 10 or more
public-private deals within the last 12 months or the last fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles is doing a lot of deals to induce businesses to
come to Los Angeles or stay in the city,'' Kosmont said. ``L.A. is
still on the expensive side and will never be able to compete with
areas like Calabasas and Westlake and Thousand Oaks.''
</P>
<P>
   But approving the mayor's plan will send an important message to
the business community, he said, and the city should consider
reviewing its business tax code every three years as well as
lowering taxes on small businesses. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Just making the permit process less cumbersome would satisfy
Victor Avakian, who has owned Casa Di Pizza in the San Fernando
Valley community of West Hills for 10 years. He wants to expand his
restaurant into an adjacent vacant building and install an arcade
with bumper cars and video games, making it a venue for birthday
parties and gatherings of various youth sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   It's a $50,000 project not made any cheaper by the city's permit
and license process, Avakian said.
</P>
<P>
   That could take up to six months and cost an additional $10,000,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are being fair with us. It's a two-way system, so you
have to follow the rules,'' Avakian said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist at the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corp., a nonprofit and nongovernmental agency, credits
Riordan with implementing business teams that are trained to help
businesses navigate the municipal bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   This helps mitigate the cost issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing continued strong demand for businesses locating
in Los Angeles County,'' Kyser said. ``I think people recognize
that we have a healthy and growing economy and there are lots of
resources here. If you are going to play the (business) game you
have to be in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Even being near Los Angeles helps. Westlake Village adopted a
``business friendly'' philosophy when it incorporated in 1981 and
it continues to pay off today, civic leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   ``That transfers into a commitment not to establish business
license fees and other similar taxes,'' said City Manager Ray
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Big international companies have taken notice.
</P>
<P>
   Dole Foods Inc. is building its 160,000-square-foot world
headquarters in suburban Westlake Village; Pinkerton Security &AMP;
Investigation Services, one of the world's largest security firms,
and tennis shoe manufacturer KSwiss recently moved out of the San
Fernando Valley and relocated their headquarters there.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
