<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5784 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-23 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
PROSECUTORS SCURRY TO MEND THEIR CASE AGAINST PRESIDENT
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By JOHN C. HENRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After three days of carving by President Clinton's
legal team, House prosecutors scrambled this weekend to repair
significant damage to their case for ending his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The best bandage for their impeachment drive, the House
Republicans say, would be to summon witnesses. And on Saturday, the
prosecutors won permission from a federal judge to interrogate
Monica Lewinsky as an initial step they hope will lead to her
testifying before the Senate about her affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, House prosecutors quietly enlisted the aid of
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's deputies to compel Lewinsky,
without Democratic senators or Clinton's defense team present, to
answer questions. Starr's office asked for U.S. District Judge
Norma Holloway Johnson's help, and on Saturday she ordered the
25-year-old former intern to meet with House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Whether she or any other witnesses will appear before the Senate
will not be decided until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, questions remain about whether fresh testimony from
the president's former paramour or anyone else would help make the
prosecution's case against Clinton whole again.
</P>
<P>
   Her sworn testimony from more than 20 sessions with a grand jury
and with Starr's investigators was turned over to the House in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Lewinsky's testimony has never been more important than it
is now,'' said Paul McNulty, a spokesman for the 13-member team of
House Republicans prosecuting the impeachment case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   After the three-day presentation to the Senate by Clinton's
legal team and two days of questioning from senators, legal experts
said, the House case against the president was in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers have ``put the House managers very much
on the defensive, and to recover they will have to come forward,
not with more speculation, but with hard evidence to support their
case,'' said Michael Gerhardt, a law professor at the College of
William and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Without additional evidence, the debate over impeaching the 42nd
president will boil down to the context in which senators examine
the facts known for months about Clinton's effort to conceal his
affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   During their Jan. 14-16 presentation, House prosecutors stressed
the need for senators to examine the case as a whole, each charge
in context, to see an ongoing effort by Clinton to lie under oath
and illegally hide evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Taken separately, as the president's lawyers did last week, some
of the allegations of wrongdoing may appear weak, the House
prosecutors cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   The president's legal team, which earlier had argued only that
the perjury and obstruction charges were not impeachable offenses,
last week offered a detailed rebuttal of the House Republicans'
version of the facts used to build their case.
</P>
<P>
   While the dissection by Clinton's lawyers revealed omissions,
contradictions and stretches in logic that make the House case far
less compelling, the new tack strengthened the resolve among some
Republican senators to accede to the House prosecutors' request to
summon witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start attacking the facts, it strengthens the
argument for bringing live witnesses to testify,'' said Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Summoning witnesses introduces an element of uncertainty to the
trial, a risk the White House opposes but the House prosecutors see
as essential to helping counter the presentation by the president's
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start getting witnesses, who knows where it is going to
lead?'' said Robert Dallek, a presidential historian and biographer
at Boston University. ``It is so hard to pin these things down.
Bringing witnesses before the Senate poses risks for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 days of public proceedings, Republican and Democratic
senators appear more in agreement than ever that they want a quick
resolution to the trial, which poses a danger to the hopes of House
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a large element of credibility that is now quite
clearly on the table,'' said Ronald J. Allen, a law professor at
Northwestern University. ``If the House tries to rehabilitate its
case, witnesses would be very helpful. Whether that means the
Senate will agree to hear witnesses is another story.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Senate is scheduled to begin considering motions,
including one to dismiss the charges and another to permit
witnesses to testify. Senate Republicans outnumber Democrats,
55-45, which means six Republicans would have to side with the
Democrats _ assuming they held firm _ to end the case.
</P>
<P>
   Outright dismissal is unlikely, according to several Republican
and Democratic senators. The outcome of a vote on calling
witnesses, even to provide depositions without televised testimony
from the well of the Senate, is less certain.
</P>
<P>
   While some Democrats might side with the GOP to not dismiss the
case and, perhaps, to summon witnesses, none has signaled that they
are willing to defect when it comes to a vote on conviction. There,
at least 12 Democrats would have to join all the Republicans to
provide the two-thirds majority, or 67 votes, needed to remove
Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lewinsky, the most likely witnesses would be key
figures already questioned at length and under oath as part of
Starr's investigation of the president. Starr's report to Congress,
18 boxes' worth, provided the bulk of evidence used by the House to
impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses like Lewinsky, Clinton friend and confidant Vernon
Jordan and presidential secretary Betty Currie could be called to
help clarify ambiguous circumstances or unresolved disputes that
remain in the wake of the 30 hours of presentations by the
prosecutors and Clinton's defense team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only purpose for calling any witnesses is that the
senators would get the opportunity to evaluate the witnesses'
testimony in person. There's nothing new that they will add,'' said
Robert Bloom, a professor at the Boston College Law School. ``The
House managers don't have a very strong case, legally. Will
witnesses help? It will create a spectacle. Live testimony isn't
going to enlighten anyone further.''
</P>
<P>
   The most likely candidate to create a spectacle would be
Lewinsky if, as one House manager suggested, she is asked to verify
her earlier testimony about their sexual trysts, details the House
says would prove that Clinton lied to grand jurors when he denied
that he had touched her breasts and genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff last week argued that the
differences between Clinton's account and Lewinsky's detailed,
often lurid, testimony amount to ``her oath against his oath,''
which is not sufficient to warrant a criminal conviction, much less
removal of a president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, a Florida Republican and one of the House
prosecutors, said: ``If you believe the testimony of Monica
Lewinsky, you can't believe the president.'' McCollum told senators
that if they had doubts about Lewinsky's credibility, they should
``bring her in here and let us examine her face to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Also unexplained is the drive by Jordan, a high-powered
Washington lawyer and frequent Clinton golf partner, to find
Lewinsky a job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers were unable to produce evidence that Clinton
conspired with Jordan to get her the job to keep her silent about
her affair with the president. While pointing out this flaw, the
president's lawyers were unable to provide an innocent explanation
for all the sudden interest in Lewinsky's employment prospects.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors also want to question Currie about the
presents she hid under her bed, a box of gifts given to Lewinsky by
Clinton. White House deputy counsel Cheryl Mills explained that
Currie was a friend, almost like a mother, to Lewinsky and hid the
gifts as a favor. No evidence points directly to Clinton as
engineering the concealment of the presents, as the GOP prosecutors
surmised. Unresolved is who initiated Currie's trip to Lewinsky's
apartment to pick up the box of gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also made much of the so-called ``coaching''
incident early last year, but the White House lawyers disputed its
legal significance. On Jan. 18, 1998, a day after testifying in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment case, Clinton called Currie to the
White House on a Sunday and asked her a series of leading questions
regarding his meetings with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is witness tampering, pure and simple,'' charged House
special counsel David Schippers last month.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said the White House lawyers, since Currie was not yet a
witness and Clinton was not tampering. Jones' lawyers had not asked
to hear from Currie as a witness, and no one in the White House
then knew the Starr investigation was about to expand into the
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors countered, however, by producing evidence that
Jones' lawyers added Currie to their witness list and subpoenaed
her within 48 hours of the Lewinsky controversy erupting in the
news media on Jan. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said in the end it did not matter because Clinton did not
know Currie would be called at the time of his conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are multiple versions of various stories,'' said
Northwestern's Allen. ``And that's where calling live witnesses
could make a difference because the story that's going to most
likely be believed is the one told under oath, in person to the
Senate. Of course, it depends on what they say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
