<SLUG> BC-BKW-TEXAS-OKLAHOMA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOONERS WOMEN CAN'T STOP LONGHORNS IN SECOND HALF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Oklahoma coach Sherri Coale said a Texas
second-half spurt at home is almost sure as a sunset over Mount
Bonnell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were a second-half team,'' Coale said. ``We
prepared for it. And it still happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns erased a six-point halftime deficit with a 13-2
second-half start and held off a late surge to defeat the Sooners,
81-73, for their sixth consecutive victory at the Erwin Center. Big
second halves also keyed Big 12 home victories over Colorado, No.
23 Nebraska and Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather win the second half than the first,'' UT coach Jody
Conradt said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas (10-7, 4-3) is unbeaten at home in conference play with
Kansas (14-6, 4-3) due in Wednesday fresh off handing No. 6 Texas
Tech (17-2, 6-1) its first Big 12 loss yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of our three losses on the road \RIowa State and Kansas
State\S were very disappointing,'' Conradt said. ``We said we had
to win all three games in this home stand to make up some ground.
We've won two of them. Every game is a big game for us now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns suffered in the first half when leading scorer
Edwina Brown and freshman spark Asha Hill got into early foul
trouble. They played only 16 combined minutes and scored eight
points. With them on the bench and senior Kim Lummus missing all
six shots, Texas lost an early 13-5 lead and trailed by as many as
eight.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown scored 11 of her 17 points in the second half. Hill
chipped in nine of her 11. Lummus added 14 after the break. Texas
also got a solid game from freshman center Rashunda Johnson (15
points, nine rebounds). And with Brown and Hill on the floor,
Texas' increased defensive intensity resulted in nine second-half
steals (of 13) and 14 OU turnovers (of 22).
</P>
<P>
   ``We started out wanting to press, but it didn't happen that
way'' because of fouls, said Brown, who leads UT in five individual
categories. ``We went back to it in the second half and started
jumping them in the backcourt. That's when things started going our
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown showed big late. She hit a free throw after OU closed to
66-65. She hit a follow shot to stretch a two-point lead to 71-67.
And she took an in-bounds pass coast-to-coast for a layup and a
74-69 lead with 1:33 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's definitely one of the best players in the league,''
Coale said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
