</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-GUADALUPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE DESIGNATES DAY TO HONOR VIRGIN OF GUADALUPE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CECILE S. HOLMES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, her countenance may be better known than the pope's.
She adorns billboards, home windows and tiny makeshift chapels.
</P>
<P>
   She is the Virgin of Guadalupe, and Pope John Paul II on
Saturday set aside Dec. 12 as a religious feast day in her honor
throughout the Americas. In Mexico, the day already is widely
observed, with many people taking time off work to honor the
Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's action, taken as he celebrated Mass at the Basilica
of Our Lady of Guadalupe in Mexico City, was an example of his
lifelong devotion to Mary, the mother of Jesus. It also testified
to the amazing staying power of a miracle said to have occurred
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 500 years ago, Roman Catholic faithful believe, the
Virgin of Guadalupe appeared on a hill to a poor Nahuatl Indian
named Juan Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance came just 10 years after the Spanish conquest of
Mexico. Life after the conquest was horrid for many Indians, with
disease and overwork taking many lives.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of the Virgin brought hope to an oppressed people
and helped convert Mexico's Indian masses to Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   According to the legend, a ``little Indian woman'' first
appeared to Juan Diego as he walked at daybreak near the foot of a
hill called Tepeyac. He heard birds singing, then noticed a white,
shining cloud and around it a rainbow of colors. He heard a woman
call his name. She told him that she wanted a church built on the
hill. There, she said, she would hear the weeping and prayers of
the people and bring them consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady he saw told him she was `the ever-Virgin Mary, Mother
of the true God by whom all live,' but she used the Aztec name
Tonantzin, or Mother of the Gods,'' Sally Cunneen writes in her
book In Search of Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The apparition directed Juan Diego to ask the local bishop to
build the church. Diego tried but was rebuffed. On Dec. 12, 1531,
Diego found roses blooming in the dead of winter at Tepeyac. He
gathered them into his coarse cloak and hurried to the bishop's
house.
</P>
<P>
   En route, he met the lady again. She arranged the roses in his
cloak and directed him not to open the cloak to anyone but the
bishop.
</P>
<P>
   When Diego arrived at the bishop's home and opened his cloak,
the bishop fell to his knees. On the cloak was printed the
now-famous image of Our Lady of Guadalupe, just as Diego had
described her. The cloak now hangs in the basilica in Mexico City
where the pope celebrated Mass on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Across Latin America and in the United States, the Virgin of
Guadalupe remains a potent symbol. Though some have criticized the
church's use of her image, others believe it symbolizes hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of Our Lady of Guadalupe has become the unofficial,
private flag of Mexicans,'' Richard Rodriguez writes in the book
Goddess of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin appears everywhere in Mexico. On dashboards and on
calendars, on playing cards, on lampshades and cigar boxes; within
the loneliness and tattooed upon the very skin of Mexicans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor is the image of Guadalupe a diminishing mirage of the 16th
century, but she has become more vivid with time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
