<HEADER>
A5798 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-CROWD-HNS &LR;      01-23 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-CROWD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FOR MANY MEXICAN CATHOLICS, JUST BEING NEAR POPE IS ALL THAT
MATTERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DUDLEY ALTHAUS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Maria Trinidad Zarate and her friends sit happy in
a glaring late-morning sun, straining to see anything, hear
anything of Pope John Paul II's visit to the mystical essence of
Roman Catholic Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Zarate and the others had traveled all night by bus from their
home in Colima, in western Mexico, to be outside the Basilica of
Our Lady of Guadalupe for the chance to catch a glimpse of the
Roman Catholic leader.
</P>
<P>
   Now they stand crammed with hundreds of other faithful on a side
street behind the sprawling structure, the shrine of the Virgin of
Guadalupe, their view of the building impeded by a pedestrian
walkway filled with people, their access to it blocked by high
fences and cordons of security men.
</P>
<P>
   Liturgical music beats with a tinny murmur from distant
loudspeakers. Street vendors hawk John Paul trinkets, paper hats to
block the sun, snacks to fill bellies that didn't have time for
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, at a Mass for Catholic bishops from throughout the
Americas, John Paul is presenting the church's plan for the coming
millennium. He's calling for greater economic justice and an end to
racism, he's urging moderation of the capitalist system that rules
much of the world and has left so many without.
</P>
<P>
   Zarate and her friends haven't heard any of that message. They
haven't seen John Paul. And they won't see him. But they don't
mind. Being here, being near, is all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Catholic,'' Zarate says with a shrug when asked why she
bothers. ``The pope means everything to us. It's the presence of
God, the maximum authority in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of other people agree with Zarate. They
line the Mysteries Road, the broad street leading away from the
basilica that John Paul will take to the house in the southern end
of the city where he is staying on his five-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
   They have spent hours in the morning sun waiting to see the
pope. A few people start chants. ``John Paul, John Paul.'' One man
loudly whistles Beethoven's Ode to Joy. Thousands upon thousands of
people stand quietly, fanning themselves. Shading their eyes.
Shifting from foot to foot. Waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if we are far away from him, we feel him,''
Juanita Huitron, a 50-year-old housewife, says of John Paul. ``The
last time he was here in Mexico, I felt his blessing, I felt his
hands upon my shoulders. We are all in his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic faithful believe that the Virgin Mary, mother of
Jesus, appeared to a poor Indian farmer on the site of the basilica
in 1531, a decade after the conquest of the Aztec Empire by the
Spaniards. The so-called Virgin of Guadalupe appeared to give hope
to the conquered Indians. She was copper-skinned like they were.
She was Mexican.
</P>
<P>
   In the centuries since, the Virgin had become the purest
expression of Catholicism for many, if not most, Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope knows this Virgin is suffering for how we are
suffering,'' Huitron says as she shoulders her way toward the front
of the waiting crowd. ``Mexico is being consumed, so many problems.
(The pope) has come to help this Virgin unite us, to rescue us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope wants peace, the pope wants justice, the pope wants
there to be no more poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   The service in the basilica over, John Paul whisks down the
Mysteries Road in a glass-sided bus, eyes fixed on the floor, not
even looking at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As the aging pontiff passes, Isabel Estrada lifts a tray laden
with rosaries, small statues of saints, images of the Virgin of
Guadalupe that she has brought for his blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Does John Paul bless Estrada's icons? Does he see them? Does his
proximity confer grace?
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to believe that it does,'' Estrada, 64, says as she
and her friend, Remedios Garduno, turn with satisfied smiles toward
their house that fronts the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not much, maybe,'' Estrada says, ``but it's the best we
can do. It's a blessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
