<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-WOMEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longhorns get it in gear, speed past OU
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Oklahoma Coach Sherri Coale told her Sooners all
week that the Texas women's basketball team was a second-half squad
that would rather speed up and down the court than sit back in a
half-court offense.
</P>
<P>
   And she reminded the Sooners again at halftime Saturday as they
gathered in the locker room at the Erwin Center to discuss their
37-31 lead and how they had held UT to a mostly half-court game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let them in the open court,'' Coale cautioned. ``You
can't let them explode like that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Coale said, ``We prepared for it, and it still
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the Longhorns all of 4 minutes, 7 seconds in the second
half to erase Oklahoma's lead on their way to an 81-73 victory in
front of 5,803 vocal UT fans.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, UT remained unbeaten at home this season in
Big 12 play. The Longhorns (10-7, 4-3) are tied for fourth place in
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Coale was correct in reminding her team about UT's late heroics,
especially at home. The Longhorns were clinging to a one-point lead
over Oklahoma State on Wednesday, but went on to win 75-53. UT was
ahead of Colorado by six points before winning by 18. Against
Nebraska, the Longhorns turned a four-point lead at intermission
into a five-point upset.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma was able to take a halftime lead mainly because UT had
three starters _ guards Edwina Brown and Asha Hill, and post Tracy
Cook _ in brief foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, UT's statistical leader in every major category, played
nine minutes in the first half, scoring only six points. Hill, who
started her second straight game at point guard, played seven
minutes and scored two points in the first half. She didn't have a
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Lummus, UT's most consistent perimeter weapon, was troubled
with early shooting problems, missing all of her six first-half
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't a whole lot of teams who can sit down three
starters and stay close,'' said UT Coach Jody Conradt. ``It causes
you to be really stressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our depth was the key. I feel really comfortable
playing a rotation of nine to 10 players. This is a pretty
versatile team.''
</P>
<P>
   By game's end, Oklahoma was the team with foul problems, as
starters Desiree Taylor, LaNeisha Caufield and key reserve Michele
Workman fouled out. Stacy Dales led both teams with 21 points. But
all-conference performer Phylesha Whaley had a quiet 18; she went
the first 14 minutes of the second half without scoring a point.
</P>
<P>
   Brown missed out on her fourth straight double-double
performance but still managed a workmanlike game, scoring 17 points
with six assists and six rebounds. Lummus made four of her seven
second-half shots to score 14 points for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hill made it to double figures with 12 points. And center
Rashunda Johnson, who has been struggling all season, had 15 points
and nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   UT forced Oklahoma into 14 second-half turnovers _ 22 for the
game _ and turned the Sooners' miscues into 31 points, 19 in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   OU got to within 66-65 with 3:28 to play, but the Longhorns
denied the Sooners the comeback, in part, by making nine of 11
free-throw attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Halliburton writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
