<HEADLINE>
FUNK REMAINS THE LEADER, BUT OTHERS FOLLOW CLOSELY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA QUINTA, Calif. _ Fred Funk left the course Saturday as the
leader of the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, but he did not leave very
happy. After building a three-stroke lead, Funk bogeyed two of his
final five holes. So instead of heading into Sunday's final round
with a cushion, Funk will have a one-stroke edge and a host of
competitors in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a three-under-par 69 at Bermuda Dunes Country Club,
Funk stood at 20 under par for the tournament (268), one stroke
ahead of Steve Pate, who shot a 69 Saturday at Tamarisk Country
Club, one of the tournament's four course locations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two players lifted themselves into a third-place tie
at 18 under par _ John Huston, who shot a 63 at Tamarisk, and Skip
Kendall, who shot a 64 at Indian Wells Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The field will play Sunday at the Arnold Palmer Private Course
at PGA West as one of the PGA Tour's rare 90-hole events concludes.
Four players will start the final round within two strokes of the
lead and the $540,000 first-place check. Funk was upset that he had
added to the suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from having a pretty good lead to having a shootout,''
said Funk, who has played well early this season with 5th- and
12th-place finishes so far. ``I've made a lot of mistakes this
week, but I'm still in the lead, which is pretty amazing. And I can
still win the tournament. That's the good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the final day for the amateurs and, as usual, they
spent more time laughing than playing. The gallery got its final
glimpse of Michael Jordan, who spent four days playing with Charles
Barkley, the former professional football player Roy Green and four
different golf pros. Jordan's team finished at 46 under par. An
amateur team that included the former Mets outfielder Vince Coleman
won with a score of 55 under par.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who will have surgery next week to repair a torn tendon
in his right index finger, signed autographs for fans waiting near
the clubhouse, but he did not stop for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, however, said it would be tough going back to his day
job _ trying to help the Houston Rockets win a National Basketball
Association title. ``I had a great time,'' said Barkley, who made
sure everyone in his foursome had a good time as well. ``I don't
know if I'd want to go back if I could do this every day. I've had
a great time. It's time for me to get serious, though. Mike wanted
me to play with him, and I'm glad I played with him. This is every
man's fantasy. But it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's golf game never improved during his four days of play,
however. Asked if he was glad that nobody in the gallery was struck
by one of his shots, Barkley said, ``The way I was hitting, it
wouldn't have hurt anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent players hurt their chances in the tournament
Saturday. John Daly, who started just two strokes off the lead,
shot a 73 at the Palmer Course and fell into a tie for eighth, six
strokes off the lead. David Duval, who has won 8 of his last 27
starts, shot a 70 at the Palmer Course, leaving him seven strokes
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the ball pretty well, but I just couldn't make any
putts,'' he said. ``It's a shame. I could've gotten a lot closer.''
Duval did not sound optimistic about his chance to win. ``Even a 62
might not do it,'' he said. ``But we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Huston, however, had a bogey-free round that included nine
birdies. When Huston starts making birdies, they often come in
bunches.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm just happy to come in with a good score and get back closer
to the lead,'' he said. ``Anything can happen tomorrow. It's the
kind of course where you can shoot really low, or where you can
have a bad day. So it should be an interesting day.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer missed the cut at 284, shooting a four-round total
of 305. Palmer was greeted with a huge ovation as he approached the
18th green. Palmer, who is 69, said he was not sure if he would
play the Hope next year, although tournament officials want him to
return. ``This one has been very special to me,'' Palmer said,
``and there's a certain feeling about it that keeps me coming
back.'' He added that he was inspired to keep playing by his fans.
``When I walk down and I don't hear a sound, and there's no one
asking for autographs, I won't be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
