<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-HISTORY-H     01-23 1946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-HISTORY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Falcons find late-blooming formula under Reeves
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Taylor Smith arrived at Falcons training camp this summer,
he knew this season would be different.
</P>
<P>
   He had been to every training camp since the first one in 1966,
but the summer of 1998 was his first both as Falcons president and
chairman of the board. It would be a tough year, the first since
his father Rankin Smith Sr. _ the only owner the Falcons had ever
known _ had passed away. Suddenly, this was his team, all the pain
to endure, any glory to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   And though he'd had inklings _ the Falcons had gone 6-2 over the
second half of last year _ he couldn't have known how different the
season would be.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are going to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Those long familiar with the Falcons franchise never thought
they'd see the day come. After all, this was a team that had
managed only seven winning seasons in 32 years. It was a team with
only one previous division title, earned after going 12-4 in 1980.
And as had become all too typical, that 1980 season came crashing
to a halt. The Falcons took a 24-10 lead into the fourth quarter of
a playoff game against Dallas. A capacity crowd of more than 60,000
watched as the Cowboys then scored 20 points for a 30-27 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody playing on this level is competitive,'' said former
linebacker Tommy Nobis, who played for Atlanta from 1966-76, only
twice experiencing winning seasons. ``Anytime you are competitive
and you get beat and beat often, it's not much fun. The credibility
and respect, the lack of, when losing, comes with the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had won only one playoff game since (a 27-20 victory
over New Orleans in 1991) before this season began.
</P>
<P>
   But what has made the Falcons stand out is the losing seasons.
The Falcons weren't just bad, they were horrible. They've had 12
seasons in which they've won four games or fewer. They've had eight
seasons begin with an 0-3 mark. They've had eight different head
coaches (not counting interim). And in a classic move that proved
he didn't learn from his mistakes, Smith rehired one coach more
than a decade after he'd been fired.
</P>
<P>
   Norb Hecker was Atlanta's first coach. In slightly more than two
seasons, he won only four games, lost 26 and tied one. Norm Van
Brocklin was brought in as the replacement in 1968 after the
Falcons started 0-3. The Falcons finished that season 2-12.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutchman led Atlanta to a 9-5 season in 1973, his fifth full
year at the helm. But when they started 2-6 the following season,
he, too, was fired. Marion Campbell took over and the Falcons would
lose 19 of 25 under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came in 1975 (as the No. 1 pick), they had zero
respectability and a really bad football team,'' quarterback Steve
Bartkowski (1975-85) told the Palm Beach Post last year. ``I think
my college team (California) could have taken them to the mat.''
</P>
<P>
   Things were looking up when Smith hired Leeman Bennett in 1977.
A 4-10 team became a .500 team that year. His second year, Atlanta
won a wild-card spot, going 9-7. Two years later came the first
divisional title, and Bennett still holds the distinction of being
the only Falcons coach until Dan Reeves to have a winning record.
But after losing a playoff game in Minnesota during the
strike-shortened 1982 season, Bennett was fired and Dan Henning was
hired to be coach No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons finished in last place in Henning's first three
seasons, going 22-41-1 overall. And when the Falcons lost to the
0-13 Colts at home near the end of 1986, the search began for coach
No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   After their first couple of choices fell through, Smith decided
to let history repeat itself and rehired Campbell. His previous
6-19 reign proved no fluke. This time, Campbell went 11-32 until
being ousted with four games remaining in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was immensely proud of bringing the Falcons to Atlanta and
keeping the team in Atlanta,'' Taylor Smith said of his father. ``I
think he was very disappointed that he didn't have more success
than he did while he was alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The quirky Jerry Glanville entered the picture in 1990, but even
Elvis didn't show up to collect his free tickets during Atlanta's
only winning season (10-6 wild-card team in 1991) out of four under
the former Oilers coach.
</P>
<P>
   June Jones tried his hand for three seasons. He took the Falcons
back to the wild-card game in '95 with a 9-7 mark. But after going
3-13 the next year, he too was sent packing.
</P>
<P>
   Under Glanville, the Falcons had fun _ off the field, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said we'd have a Breathalyzer at the door, and whoever
wasn't drunk couldn't come home,'' former Falcons linebacker Tim
Green told the Palm Beach Post. ``We thought he was kidding, but he
wasn't. It was the closest thing to living in the old West. It
sounds juvenile, but it was a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But fun took over and football got shoved way down on the
priority list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our fun and didn't concentrate that much on football,''
Green said. ``When you're in a hot city like Atlanta, (stuff)
happens. If we did some good things on the field, we could win, but
if things turned against us, that was it. The word on the Falcons
was they'll give you a good minute, but if you get them down,
that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was more of a disciplinarian and let the players know it.
When defensive end Chuck Smith spoke out about his desire for a
more defensive-minded coach (Jones was known for his run-and-shoot
offense), he found himself suspended for a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has been through so many negative things,'' said
Smith, now in his seventh season with the Falcons. ``I got
suspended for saying what I believed in. But we fought for what we
believed in, and along with some other veterans and coach Reeves,
we turned things around. I'm really glad we got a defensive-minded
coach in.''
</P>
<P>
   With Reeves, the Falcons got a coach they could respect. This
was a guy with eight Super Bowls of experience as a player and
coach. This was a guy who played for Tom Landry, who coached the
Denver Broncos to three Super Bowls and who turned the New York
Giants into a division winner. But most of all, this was a coach
who still remembered how it was to be a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call Dan the `Gotti' of the football team,'' said
cornerback Ray Buchanan, in his second year with the Falcons. ``He
keeps everything clean. He treats us as professionals as long as we
act professional. Dan doesn't care if you party, just don't be a
(jerk) about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a franchise riddled with bad decisions, and the
coaching was only one part, albeit a large one, of the poor
choices. Bad drafts, bad trades and missed opportunities also dot
the franchise's history, the most significant being the Brett Favre
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time league MVP was Atlanta's second-round pick in
1991. Glanville reportedly didn't like Favre's potential, and he
was traded to Green Bay in 1992 for a first-round pick. The Falcons
eventually took running back Tony Smith with that pick. He was with
the Falcons only three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Falcons traded three draft picks, including their
'94 and '95 first-round picks, to the Indianapolis Colts for
quarterback Jeff George, whom they had selected with their No. 1
pick four years earlier, then traded to Indianapolis. George had a
much-publicized sideline fight with Jones and was suspended, then
later released with no compensation.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to get better without gaining impact players in the
draft, and the Falcons had no first-round picks from 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons couldn't keep high-profile multi-sport athletes
Brian Jordan or Deion Sanders. The two baseball/football stars went
separate ways, Jordan turning to baseball after the Falcons
wouldn't meet his salary demands, Sanders turning down more money
in Atlanta to sign with a winning franchise, the 49ers. Jordan, a
longtime St. Louis Cardinal, is now back in Atlanta with the
Braves. Sanders, who played in the World Series with the Braves,
owns Super Bowl rings from his time in San Francisco and now
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Again, enter Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Why would the winningest active coach in the NFL want to come to
a franchise with such a pitiful history? The Smith family was
willing to relinquish control. Reeves came in not only as head
coach but as executive vice president of football operations as
well. What that fancy title means is he makes the football
decisions, from the draft to the contract negotiations to the play
calling.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing he did was execute the trade that brought the
franchise extra draft picks in 1997. He obtained cornerback Michael
Booker, running back Byron Hanspard, tight end O.J. Santiago and
linebacker Henri Crockett with those picks. All but Hanspard will
start in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But the big coup that year was the trade with Houston that
brought quarterback Chris Chandler to the Falcons. The Oilers got a
fourth-and sixth-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Starting safety Eugene Robinson (1998), starting cornerback Ray
Buchanan (1997), starting fullback Bob Christian (1997, now on
injured reserve), fullback Brian Kozlowski (1997, starting for
Christian), starting safety William White (1997) and starting
cornerback Ronnie Bradford (1997) were all free agents Reeves
managed to lure.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 39 players on the 53-man roster have come aboard since
Reeves took control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sum up (what's been wrong all these years),'' said
Nobis, who is now the Falcons' vice president of corporate
development. ``Each coach has been in a different situation, but
what is obvious is that we've never had a coach here with the
credentials of Dan. And he influences everything. He brought a way
of managing these players and a system that's proven to be a
winning system.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Reeves admits he never expected a Super Bowl run. After
all, he took over a team that went 3-13 two years ago. Despite a
6-2 streak at the end of last season, it was still a Falcons team
that began 1-7 and once again dashed fans' hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible when you think about it, coming from 1-7
halfway through our first year,'' Reeves said. ``All my life, every
football coach I ever played for preached the same things that we
try to, and when you have a football team that believes in those
things and executes them I couldn't be prouder.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor could the Smith family, once much-maligned in Atlanta.
Average in-house attendance last year was only 40,000, and
Falcon-haters became so prominent that in Rankin Smith's final
years, he couldn't go out in public without being heckled. When he
died in October of 1997, the Falcons' record was 1-6. That same
day, they lost to the Carolina Panthers to fall to 1-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling he's enjoying the success,'' Taylor Smith
said, ``looking down and kind of saying, `If you needed me to get
out of the way, then I guess it was great. I hope everybody is
having fun down there.'''
</P>
<P>
   They are for now. Continuing to do so is the bigger challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've got a lot of work to do here,'' Nobis said.
``With what's happened in our past, we've got to have some
consistency. There were fans who jumped on the bandwagon (in the
past), only to be disappointed. It's been a roller-coaster ride, a
yo-yo, up-and-down thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them will wait. They don't want to see just a year,
year and a half of winning. They want to see consistency. We know
nobody is going to go to the Super Bowl every year, but we need to
win more games than we lose. When we have that consistency for a
while, they'll come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
