</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-MASS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
POPE CALLS ON FAITHFUL TO ``BUILD A BETTER AMERICA''
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RICHARD VARA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ With the revered gold-framed image of the Virgin
of Guadalupe as a backdrop, Pope John Paul II won roaring applause
Saturday as he called for the end of violence, discrimination and
other social abuses in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come to banish once and for all from the
(American) continent every attack against life,'' the pope said.
``No more violence, terrorism and drug trafficking! No more torture
or other forms of abuse! There must be an end to the unnecessary
recourse to the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more exploitation of the weak, racial discrimination or
ghettoes of poverty,'' the pontiff exhorted. ``Never again!''
</P>
<P>
   The forceful words brought hearty applause from the estimated
10,000 invited worshipers _ including hundreds of Roman Catholic
bishops, priests and lay leaders from throughout Mexico and the
Americas _ at a Mass celebrated inside the Basilica of Our Lady of
Guadalupe here. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The pope's sermon underscored the goals of a final report of
the Synod of Bishops for America, which was held at the Vatican in
late 1997. Bishops at the assembly focused on the massive spiritual
and social problems facing the church in North and South America in
the new millennium. They made several recommendations to define the
church's role.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the bishops, John Paul traveled to Mexico City
to formally conclude the synod and accept its report at the
basilica Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff's sermon reflected the impassioned call for social
justice through spiritual renewal and evangelization in the final
30-page synod document.
</P>
<P>
   The pope called for men and women to become aware of their
spiritual responsibilities through the gospels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will inspire them to build a better America,'' the pope
said.
</P>
<P>
   Applause from the congregation repeatedly interrupted his
sermon.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at an evening visit with Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo and foreign ambassadors, John Paul renewed his criticism of
unfettered capitalism, corruption and ``excessive individualism''
on a global scale
</P>
<P>
   The pope warned that even though the modern economy holds great
promise for human progress, its emphasis on markets poses grave
risks to freedom and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human history cannot direct itself against humanity,'' John
Paul told the dignitaries. ``That would be the same as directing
itself against God.
</P>
<P>
   ``This continent can be the continent of hope if its human
communities and its leadership classes make a common ethical
foundation their own,'' the pope said. ``I hope that in the near
future, respect for life, for truth and for the dignity of every
human being prevails.''
</P>
<P>
   Before speaking to the diplomats, the pope met privately with
Zedillo for 40 minutes _ twice as long as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Problems such as corruption, poor government administration, a
lack of human rights and other ills have long plagued Latin
America. Countries in the region are struggling to develop
political, social and cultural strategies in the face of
crisis-plagued economies, persistent unemployment and burgeoning
populations.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Norbeto Rivera of Mexico, in his welcoming remarks to
the pope in the basilica, said the world is undergoing ``an absurd
time of hopelessness and injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``America _ the continent of hope _ finds itself among
corruption and violence, and we are anguished,'' Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope did not read the synod report, which was formally
released to the public, in the basilica. The document reflected
John Paul's view that America should be seen as one entity rather
than be divided into north and south.
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems addressed by the report was economic
globalization. ``If globalization is ruled merely by the laws of
the market applied to suit the powerful, the consequences cannot
but be negative,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the synod praised globalization for bringing
different peoples together and for efficient and increased
production.
</P>
<P>
   The synod stopped short of a call for lending nations to forgive
the debt of poorer, developing countries. But it criticized high
interest rates and blamed ``the irresponsibility of people in
government who, in incurring debt, have given too little thought to
the real possibility of repaying it.'' It recommended new studies
of foreign debt problems and criticized corrupt officials for
pocketing money intended for national development.
</P>
<P>
   The report urged greater involvement of morally conscious
Christian laity to eradicate corruption, an endemic problem in
Latin America. It called for church and government leaders to
cooperate in developing economic projects to lessen dependence on
drug crops as a source of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The report called drug trafficking ``one of the most urgent
challenges which many nations need to address.'' The narcotics
trade, it went on, ``is, in fact, a challenge which threatens many
features of the human progress achieved in modern times.''
</P>
<P>
   On the sensitive issue of the church's role in helping the poor,
the document reiterated the necessity for a spiritual commitment to
help the needy. The document warned, however, that it should not be
an exclusive focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In loving the poor, the Christian imitates the attitude of the
Lord, who during his earthly life devoted himself with special
compassion to all those in spiritual and material need.''
</P>
<P>
   It urged that all work by priests and lay leaders with the poor
be directed to a spiritual encounter with Christ. Many activist
priests and bishops, especially those with leanings toward
liberation theology, have encouraged social activism, if not
outright rebellion, to undo social and economic repression.
</P>
<P>
   The document rejected discrimination against women, a sensitive
issue in many male-dominated Latin American countries. It
encouraged women to take leadership roles in American society and
church life.
</P>
<P>
   The synod report will be the foundation for various American
churches to work together in new evangelization and outreach
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The intense emotional bond between the Mexican people and the
frail spiritual leader of the Catholic Church was evident on the
second day of the pope's five-day visit to Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of people lined the papal procession route
to the Basilica of Our Lady of Guadalupe, where the pontiff
celebrated the first publicly broadcast Mass of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viva el papa!'' or ``Long live the pope,'' thundered through
the massive semi-circular basilica when the 78-year old pontiff
entered. The basilica houses the image of the Virgin of Guadalupe,
which, the faithful say, mysteriously appeared on a cloak about 500
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is especially devoted to the Virgin of Guadalupe and
announced that the feast of the Virgin, Dec. 12, will be officially
celebrated in both North and South America.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass, the pope spent several minutes alone in private
prayer, standing at eye-level with the Virgin's image.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
END
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle staffer Dudley Althaus and free-lance
journalist Andrew Downie contributed to this report. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
