r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN     01-23 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WINS BY TKO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE _ Baron Davis threw the first punch, an uppercut from
his left kidney that ended wildly, finding nothing but air. So did
the next punch, an aimless right cross, and the next, a
limped-wristed left.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was his intent. Davis wasn't swinging at anyone.
He was making a statement.
</P>
<P>
   After a first half in which Louisville was the aggressor, after
a halftime in which UCLA coach Steve Lavin challenged his team's
desire and after his dazzling, anti-gravity reverse layup gave UCLA
a lead it would relinquish just once _ and very briefly _ Davis'
exultant punches foretold a knockout performance by UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the turning point in the game,'' Davis said. ``We
caught them on their heels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals never recovered. Stunned and staggered, they
watched UCLA take command with its most impressive half of the
season _ mixing patient offense and sound defense to defeat
Louisville 82-70 on Saturday afternoon in front of 19,987 at
Freedom Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big,'' Davis continued. ``If we can just carry out the
way we played today for the rest of the season, the sky's the limit
for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, at least, the NCAA Tournament. The victory came without
starting center Dan Gadzuric (sprained ankle) and improved UCLA's
record to 14-4. Now, it seems, only a collapse will prevent the
Bruins from accruing the 18 or 19 victories needed for an at-large
berth. The more wins they get in January, the greater their margin
for error in the final month _ when they make the rugged Bay Area
and Arizona road trips.
</P>
<P>
   But there were temporal effects, as the Bruins were quick to
note in their cramped cube of a locker room in Freedom Hall. The
second half _ in which UCLA outscored the Cardinals 51-32 and
outshot them 66.7 percent to 34.5 percent _ provided a paradigm for
the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   To survive next week at Washington, or in three weeks at
Stanford, the Bruins must recreate the poise and precision they
showed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, they were the more patient team, the more
relaxed team and the better conditioned team. (Ray Young, Jerome
Moiso and Earl Watson played every minute as Lavin, spotting their
rhythm and confidence, instantly whittled his rotation.) Their
gambling, lunging defense was replaced by thinking and footwork.
The wasted motion and scattered play of recent weeks was compressed
into taut execution _ no bad shots, no poor passes, no silly fouls.
</P>
<P>
   And after a 20-minute absence, their energy returned, courtesy
of the season's most productive halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that I don't mind the air balls or drop-kicking
the ball into the fifth row, seat six, as long as they play with
fight,'' Lavin said. ``If you're going to make mistakes, make
aggressive mistakes. If you're going to lose, go down swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Davis did after his dazzling layup with
18:30 remaining. It gave the Bruins a 39-38 lead _ their first
since midway through the first half _ and sparked a game-changing
11-2 surge.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, UCLA had a 53-44 lead and the reeling
Cardinals called timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they came out in the second half, they were a whole new
team,'' Louisville guard Cameron Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis would finish with 25 points, a career high, and six
assists. But unlike the Oregon win _ when he often was one man
against five _ he had solid support. Not every Bruin played well,
but no one played poorly. Even Watson's nine turnovers were
harmless, since most came in the opening minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Without Gadzuric, his frontcourt partner, Moiso started
passively and gained aggression as the second half unfurled. He
made 1 of 7 shots in the first half and 7 of 8 in the second,
finishing with 17 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Forward JaRon Rush, again struggling from the perimeter, had
three steals and nine rebounds. And Young, who started in
Gadzuric's place, played harrowing defense and rattled Murray into
many of his seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made this such a tremendous win is (without Gadzuric) we
had to have people help with the rebounding and the defense,''
Lavin said. ``That's a sign of a team starting to mature....
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we were quicker. We beat them to the
punch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
