<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-BAYLOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas A&AMP;M beats Baylor at buzzer
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ It was only fitting that the battle to escape the cellar in
the Big 12 would come down to a shot at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M guard Chris Clayton made a 22-foot jumper as time
expired to give the Aggies a 57-56 victory over Baylor on Saturday,
stunning the crowd of 3,431 at the Ferrell Center.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied at 54 when Baylor center Kish Lewis was
fouled by A&AMP;M's Joe White as Lewis attempted a baseline turnaround
shot. Lewis, who had 10 points and eight rebounds, went to the line
with 2.5 seconds remaining and made both free throws to put Baylor
up 56-54.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team had any timeouts left, so White took the ball on
the baseline and heaved a full-court pass. The Hail Mary throw
landed in the lane, where a group of players leaped for the ball,
but A&AMP;M's Jerald Brown managed to tip it outside to Clayton on the
left wing.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton let the ball fly and swished a 3-pointer as the buzzer
sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call that our victory play,'' Clayton said. ``Joe got the
ball down to Jerald, who is supposed to tip it to either side. We
do it in practice all the time. My man went inside to Joe's pass,
so I got a good look and it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor forward Jamie Kendrick, who led the Bears with 13 points,
thought his team deserved a better outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just real tough when you play your heart out and
something like that happens in the last second,'' Kendrick said.
``I saw it go in, and I couldn't believe it. It was like a
flashback to Valparaiso's victory in the NCAA Tournament last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Valparaiso guard Bryce Drew, now a rookie with the Rockets, made
a similar shot to defeat Mississippi in a NCAA Tournament game last
March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows about Valparaiso, but a lot of teams use that
play,'' Aggies coach Melvin Watkins said. ``Cincinnati used it to
beat Duke this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it on our last timeout, and the kids executed
it perfectly. But I know it takes some luck to make a play like
that. We do it in practice until we make it, and the percentages
are not good. Sometimes we have to run it five or six times.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory for the Aggies (8-8 overall, 1-5 Big 12) ends a
seven-game losing streak this season but a much longer drought in
conference road games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the first road victory for A&AMP;M in a league game
since March 4, 1995, when the Aggies defeated the Bears 87-78 in a
Southwest Conference game. A&AMP;M had lost 25 consecutive conference
road games until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gets the monkey off our backs,'' said A&AMP;M guard Clifton
Cook, who had 15 points and a career-high 11 rebounds for his sixth
double-double. ``Now we can go to practice with a positive attitude
instead of having our heads down. We have to keep this going.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (6-14, 0-7) just hopes it can get something going after
such a heart-breaking loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not easy,'' Baylor coach Harry Miller said. ``Our guys
were completely silent in the locker room. It's a very
disappointing and emotional loss for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he would have handled the last play differently had
Baylor been able to call a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had another timeout, we would had put someone on the
inbounds passer to make him throw it in the backcourt,'' Miller
said. ``But who knows. Someone might have hit a half-court shot had
we done that. It's one of those things that happens, but it's very
disappointing for our team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
