u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-TEXAS-HALLFAME     01-23 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-TEXAS-HALL </SLUG>
 FAME-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Local heroes' enshrinement will enhance gem in Waco
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ Four prominent Houston sports figures _ Roger Clemens, Larry
Dierker, Clyde Drexler and Hakeem Olajuwon _ will become official
state icons Wednesday when they are enshrined in the Texas Sports
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   They will join Judy Rankin and three posthumous inductees _
Sandra Meadows, Bill Foster and Rube Foster _ to give the exclusive
club an entry list many believe to be the best in the history of
the prestigious establishment.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few years ago when the opportunity to salute the
sports heroes of the state was a thing of the past. From 1987
through 1992, the public had about as much access to the Texas
Sports Hall of Fame as people crossing the Atlantic have to the
Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   After 35 years on display in Grand Prairie, the facility had
gone into exile. It was nothing more than a warehouse of boxes
filled with plaques and memorabilia of Texas legends.
</P>
<P>
   This hibernation of honor included some of the biggest names in
sports history _ baseball great Tris Speaker, Texas A&AMP;M running
back John David Crow, University of Texas and Oilers running back
Earl Campbell, four-time Indianapolis 500 winner A. J. Foyt, and
Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   And few people seemed to care. The Grand Prairie facility was a
bust and shut down in 1986, so something had to change if a museum
of sports accomplishments was going to be reborn in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent members of the Waco community, including
former Waco Mayor Bob Sheehy and Baylor president Herbert Reynolds,
created a plan in 1990 to have the facility moved to Waco. That
difficult task became a reality in April 1993 when the Texas Sports
Hall of Fame had its grand opening in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The patience and hard work of dozens of community leaders has
paid off, because the facility turned a profit in 1998 for the
first time. Executive director Steve Fallon, who took over the job
three years ago, said attendance was up 18 percent last year and
revenue increased 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, sports fans in Texas are starting to appreciate the
importance of the facility and its impressive members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times in the past when inductees didn't want
to go to the ceremony,'' Fallon said. ``They didn't know anything
about the Hall and didn't think it was something they needed to
show up for.
</P>
<P>
   ``When George Foreman was given a tribute room in 1994, he
didn't want to come up here. Once he got here and saw it and the
facility, he stood up at the banquet and apologized to everyone for
being so nonchalant about it.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of thing has happened several times in recent years
when inductees come to Waco for the first time and see a building
that has become one of the finest hall of fame facilities in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   One of the changes that brought increased attention and success
to the facility was the plan to bring together all the hall of fame
organizations in Texas. Charlie McCleary, founder of the Texas
Tennis Hall of Fame and Museum, was instrumental in combining all
the sports organizations into one location when the Hall moved to
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The TSHF, which was established by the Texas Sportswriters
Association in 1951, now houses the Texas High School Football Hall
of Fame, the Texas High School Basketball Hall of Fame, the Texas
Baseball Hall of Fame and the Texas Tennis Hall of Fame and Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Each organization has separate rules and procedures for
nominating people for induction, but all the members now are
showcased at the Waco facility.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Waco and Baylor University were instrumental in
getting the TSHF moved to Central Texas. Baylor agreed to a land
swap with the city so the building could be constructed just east
of Interstate 35 near the Brazos River and close to the Texas
Ranger Hall of Fame. The city issued certificates of obligation for
$1 million to begin the construction.
</P>
<P>
   The number of visitors to the 15,000-square-foot facility has
grown each year, with more than 50,000 patrons passing through the
TSHF in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the people in charge realized visitors are not enough to
allow the project to grow and prosper. For the TSHF to be
successful, new ideas would be needed to bring in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are a nonprofit entity like this, you have to come up
with creative ideas to generate funds,'' Fallon said. ``People are
encouraged to join our Good Sport Club, which is a booster
organization with special opportunities for the members. We also
have been successful in renting out the facility to various groups
for parties and receptions.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be quite a party Wednesday with so many well-known
sports names being inducted. Fallon said they are expecting their
biggest crowd ever for the induction banquet and ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest problem each year is trying to pick a date when
all the inductees can attend,'' Fallon said. ``The NBA lockout
messed things up this year because we had picked a day when the
Rockets were off, but it changed to Hakeem having to miss part of
the team's training camp. (Rockets coach) Rudy Tomjanovich really
helped us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich decided to call off the team's late workout
Wednesday so he and team vice president Carroll Dawson could attend
the induction ceremony for Olajuwon and Drexler.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon also had to pick a day when the University of Houston
didn't have a basketball game so Drexler, the UH coach, could
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clyde was a little hesitant about it,'' Fallon said. ``But
(former UH coach) Guy Lewis (a 1994 inductee) talked to him and is
coming up with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing was much easier to work out for Clemens and Dierker,
who don't head for spring training until next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out great for Larry because he will be on the Astros
Caravan tour,'' Fallon said. ``They will be in Temple the day
before the banquet, then he will come up here with (Astros owner)
Drayton McLane and several players.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio and Ken Caminiti will be two of the players who
will watch their manager inducted into the TSHF.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduling conflicts kept two new inductees _ Dallas Cowboys
defensive back Mel Renfro and jockey Jerry Bailey _ from being
enshrined Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Renfro has a commitment at the Super Bowl activities in Miami
and Bailey will ride Kentucky Derby prospect Answer Lively at
Gulfstream Park, but both will be inducted in June, along with
former Oilers head coach Bum Phillips, after the TSHF's annual golf
tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
