<HEADLINE>
FUNK STAYS IN FRONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA QUINTA -- Fred Funk was breezing along with a four-stroke
lead in Saturday's fourth round of the $3 million Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic when he went into, well, a funk.
</P>
<P>
   A sizeable advantage soon was reduced to one shot and set up
what promises to be a final-round scramble for the $540,000 first
prize today at PGA West's Arnold Palmer Course.
</P>
<P>
   Funk, a former University of Maryland golf coach, bogeyed two of
his final five holes and settled for a three-under 69 at Bermuda
Dunes Country Club to leave him at 20-under 268, one stroke ahead
of Steve Pate. At 18-under was John Huston, who had a nine-under 63
at Tamarisk Country Club, and Skip Kendall, who had a 64 at Indian
Wells. At 17-under was Bob Estes, after a 67 at Bermuda Dunes,
followed by Scott Verplank at 16-under and Gabriel Hjertstedt at
15-under.
</P>
<P>
   A group of five players at 14-under included John Daly, who
struggled to a one-over 73 at PGA West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done a lot of good things this week,'' Funk said, ``but
I've also made a lot of mistakes. I've gone from having a pretty
good lead to a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still win the tournament. That's the good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Funk also has a less-than-impressive track record at the Hope to
think about. This is his 10th appearance in the tournament, and he
has missed the cut five times. He tied for 43rd a year ago, and his
best-ever finish was a tie for 14th in 1994, when he won $19,250.
</P>
<P>
   But Funk does sound a little more confident this year,
especially after rounds of 65-68-66-69.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I got a little uptight in the past, he said, ``knowing
you have to shoot 5-, 6- or 7-under every day. But this year, I
came in here playing really good, and I'm just going to let it
happen tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said he would take a similar approach. He has been close
before -- he finished second in last year's Buick Invitational and
was 10th in the PGA Championship -- and hoped he learned a few
lessons from those near-misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get there, he said. ``Hopefully, one of
these times it will go my way.''
</P>
<P>
   It definitely went Huston's way Saturday. Huston, who set a
72-hole tour record for strokes under par when he went 28-under in
winning last year's Hawaiian Open, did not have a bogey. His
longest birdie putt was a 25-footer on the par-3, 199-yard fifth
hole, and twice he two-putted for birdies on par fives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good day,'' Huston said. ``I drove the ball really
well, and I hit a lot of greens, so I kept giving myself chances.
Then I made a lot of really good putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't too hard. I didn't feel like I had to take any
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Verplank, the tour's Comeback Player of the Year in 1998, has
started the '99 season strongly. He closed out 1998 by finished
third in Las Vegas and tied for fifth in the Tour Championship.
David Duval played his 11th consecutive round below par Saturday,
but his 70 at PGA West left him seven shots behind.
</P>
<P>
   The cut was at four-under 284, and a number of recognizable
figures didn't make it. They included Paul Azinger, Andrew Magee
(who had a 10-over 82 on Thursday), Mark Calcavecchia, Tom Kite,
Steve Jones, 1997 Hope champion John Cook and Fuzzy Zoeller.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer was last at 17-over 305, but he did close his 75
on Saturday did feature a birdie on his final hole, the par-5,
532-yard 18th hole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
