<HEADLINE>
JACOBSEN ENJOYS TIME WITH STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA QUINTA -- There was plenty of crowd noise, sometimes during
his backswing, but Peter Jacobsen still said he had a great time
playing with Charles Barkley and Michael Jordan in Saturday's
fourth round of the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great time,'' he said. ``People screamed for
autographs during my backswing a few times, but you have to expect
that, playing with guys like that. Michael plays well. I've played
a lot of golf with him. Roy (Green, another of his playing
partners) is a good player. Charles ... had a couple of good
holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen even resorted to strumming the guitar while Barkley
prepared to hit from the tee on the par-3, 130-yard 17th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just singing the Barkley blues,'' said Jacobsen, who
also has made a name for himself as a member of his musical group
``Jake Trout and the Flounders,'' which features several members of
the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan joked that Barkley needed the music to help with the
rhythm of his swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been dancing with his feet all day,'' he told ABC's Jimmy
Roberts. ``He might as well do it to some music.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's practice swing looks good, but hitting a ball in front
of him is another matter. He pauses on his downswing, which often
results in errant shots. One almost hit Jordan on the par-4,
439-yard seventh hole.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, asked to put Barkley's swing into words, took a long
pause before responding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's unnerving,'' Jacobsen said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's group finished a net 46-under par. The Houston Rockets
forward -- he signed his new contract on the 10th tee at Tamarisk
Country Club during Thursday's second round -- said he would like
to play more, but there's a little matter of professional
basketball getting in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could do this every day,'' Barkley said. ``But it's time for
me to get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is every man's fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Couples finished 72-75-72-71--290 and became the second
consecutive defending champion to miss the four-round cut. John
Cook, who won in 1997, was a casualty of last year's final round.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Kelly made the first double-eagle of the year when he
holed his second shot on the par-5, 483-yard 14th hole at Indian
Wells CC. The tour's last double-eagle was made by Woody Austin at
last year's Kemper Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
