A6021 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-2NDLD-WRI     01-23 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS LEWINSKY TO SUBMIT TO QUESTIONING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite with new reporting)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-FITZGERALD,
IMPEACH-BIBLE-BELT, IMPEACH-LINCOLN, IMPEACH-WITNESSES-REVIEW)  
(HLW) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's impeachment trial was thrown
into turmoil Saturday, after a federal judge ordered Monica
Lewinsky to submit to questioning from House Republican prosecutors
or the independent counsel's office, and Senate Republicans said
they would query the president in writing.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Lewinsky arrived here from Los Angeles, her lawyers were
working out the details of when and where she would meet with the
prosecutors. House aides said the meeting would likely happen on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's anxious and she wants to get this over with,'' said an
associate of Ms. Lewinsky. ``This has been a one-year nightmare,
and she wants to get on with her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the Senate wrapped up a second day of questions
and answers on the floor, Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, was
quick to seize upon a comment by a White House counsel, Gregory
Craig, who had said in answering a question about the possibility
of an interrogatory that the White House would ``get responses to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott told reporters: ``We do expect to send a letter or some
questions down to the White House with the president, I believe by
Monday. We'd like to see what the president has to say about some
of the inconsistencies in the testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   A presidential spokesman, James Kennedy, later clarified Craig's
remarks, saying that Clinton's lawyers, but not the president,
would answer any additional queries.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in particular expressed outrage at the day's events.
In a last-ditch effort to block Ms. Lewinsky's interview, Sen. Tom
Harkin, an Iowa Democrat, appealed to Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, who is presiding over the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Permitting the prosecutors to question Ms. Lewinsky at this
stage would violate the Senate's constitutional authority to try
impeachments, Harkin argued in a letter that he hand-delivered to
Rehnquist's clerk. But congressional lawyers said that Rehnquist
had no standing to overrule the order.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's uproar and extraordinary political theater came after
eight days of plodding civility, as the House prosecutors then the
White House lawyers presented their arguments, and then senators
posed written questions to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   While the imminent questioning of the president and Ms.
Lewinsky, the central figures in the yearlong scandal, promised
fresh drama, it was unsure what new information they might add to
volumes of depositions already delivered. But even the way answers
are provided could have an impact. When Clinton responded to
questions from the House, many House Republicans said they were
offended by the brusque and legalistic tone of the answers.
</P>
<P>
   Senators had a hard time keeping up with the fast-paced events.
``It's confusing and complicated,'' said Sen. Jack Reed, a Rhode
Island Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil Saturday was triggered by the decision from Chief
Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, moments before the Senate convened,
ordering Ms. Lewinsky to ``allow herself to be debriefed'' by House
prosecutors or, if she preferred, by Starr's lawyers. If she
refused, the judge wrote, she would forfeit her protections under
her immunity deal with the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling came in response to a request from Starr on
behalf of Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the lead prosecutor, after
Ms. Lewinsky rejected a request to meet with the House prosecutors
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky and Starr reached an agreement last July giving her
immunity from prosecution, provided that she answer questions
truthfully before grand juries ``and in any other executive,
military, judicial or congressional proceedings.'' In her one-page
decision, Judge Johnson of federal district court ruled that the
independent counsel could compel Ms. Lewinsky to answer questions
in a briefing with the House managers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement specifies that such briefings will be conducted by
Starr's office and before ``attorneys, law-enforcement agents and
representatives of any other institutions'' as his office requires.
The House managers represent the full House, and qualify as an
``other institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Starr's aides question Ms. Lewinsky, as is expected,
they will act largely as conduits for questions from the House
prosecutors, who will be able to attend the meetings, said House
aides and officials familiar with the talks.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky would face intense questioning either way. The
prosecutors believe that her answers could be pivotal as the Senate
decides whether to call question witnesses or to decide Clinton's
fate without them, the managers say.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers have never met her face to face, and they
think they may be able to glean new information from the former
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The managers have always put Ms. Lewinsky at the top of their
proposed witness list. And if the Senate agrees, Ms. Lewinsky could
be subpoenaed to provide a sworn deposition.
</P>
<P>
   But as early as Monday, the managers will have to persuade a
majority of senators to depose Ms. Lewinsky. So the prosecutors
want to interview her before then in order to give senators their
best assessment of how Ms. Lewinsky could help untangle of the
conflicting testimony.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Lewinsky's testimony has never been more important than it
is now,'' Paul McNulty, the chief spokesman for the House managers,
said in a statement. ``In the last four days, the White House has
challenged the reliability of her testimony in a number of key
instances relating to her conversations with the president'' and
Betty Currie, Clinton's personal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, Ms. Lewinsky testified three times _ twice
before a federal grand jury and once in a sworn deposition. An
associate of Ms. Lewinsky said she testified truthfully then, and
would give the same testimony to the House managers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Starr, Charles Bakaly, dismissed accusations
from Democrats that the independent counsel's office had secretly
gone to federal court on behalf of the House managers to force Ms.
Lewinsky's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly said the White House could also question Ms. Lewinsky,
but he said his office had not received such a request from the
president's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the White House would participate in the
questioning of Ms. Lewinsky, Kennedy said, ``There are no such
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We, unlike the House managers,'' Kennedy said, are respecting
the Senate and the procedures adopted by the Senate, and we have no
intention of violating those procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers had balked at allowing her to meet with
the House managers, arguing that it would cast her in ``a partisan
light.`` But they appeared ready to comply with Judge Johnson's
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the independent counsel to trail along with the House
managers struck us as wrong,'' Jacob Stein, a lawyer for Ms.
Lewinsky, said in a telephone interview Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor Saturday, Democrats assailed the fairness of
the House prosecutors' using Starr's authority to compel Ms.
Lewinsky's cooperation, while Republicans demanded to know how the
Senate could resolve important conflicting testimony without
hearing from witnesses like her.
</P>
<P>
   Honoring 19th-century impeachment rules, senators submitted
written questions to Rehnquist, who read them aloud.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, one of the 13 House prosecutors, explained
that the managers merely wanted a routine meeting with Ms. Lewinsky
before deciding whether to ask the Senate to depose her.
</P>
<P>
   But White House Counsel Charles Ruff ridiculed that claim. ``Can
you imagine what that little conversation is going to look like,
held in the independent counsel's office, with the people there who
have the capacity to put Ms. Lewinsky in jail?'' Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes spilled over to Senate Republicans and Democrats, at
the trial recesses Saturday. All but one of the 45 Senate Democrats
signed a letter to Hyde Saturday, urging the Illinois Republican to
drop his request to interview Ms. Lewinsky. Hyde responded in a
letter that the Senate rules and procedures did not require him to
gain the Senate's permission to talk to possible witnesses.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only Democratic senator not to sign the letter was Robert
Byrd of West Virginia, a respected guardian of Senate tradition,
who issued his own statement on the matter. ``This is clearly an
attempt by the House managers to pre-empt the coming vote by the
Senate on whether or not to depose witnesses,'' Byrd said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republicans said the House managers were merely
exercising the same rights to interview a potential witness, as the
White House surely has with witnesses friendly to its side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
