<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTONCOLLEGE-UCONN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC WOMEN HIT NEW HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston College women's basketball coach Cathy Inglese told her
players to expect a loud, frenzied crowd at Saturday's game, and
she told them to be ready for a fast, full-court pressing game by
the University of Connecticut, the No. 2 team in the country. Above
all, she told them that they didn't have to play over their heads,
that if they simply did ``what we do well, and with consistency, we
could win.''
</P>
<P>
   They proved her right.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles defeated UConn, 78-66, at Conte Forum, handing the
Huskies their third loss in two weeks. UConn is 16-3 overall, 9-1
in the Big East. BC improved to 15-3, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   The full-house crowd of 8,606 _ half of whom, judging from the
cheers when UConn scored, seemed to be from Connecticut _ was
excited by the stepped-up Big East rivalry. The teams have met 35
times since 1981, and before Saturday UConn had won 16 straight.
</P>
<P>
   No one was sure what to expect Saturday, with both teams
carrying key players on the disabled list. BC has been playing
without guard Cal Bouchard (anterior cruciate ligament), and UConn
has four players sitting out because of injuries. So each team had
three freshmen on the court at the start of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We each had to step up individually, just a little bit,'' said
BC junior Alissa Murphy, who stepped up more than just a little as
she poured in a game-high 32 points. Murphy was filling in for
Bouchard at point guard, with freshman Nicole Conway taking over
Murphy's spot at forward.
</P>
<P>
   UConn wasn't so lucky with its fill-ins. Freshman Tamika
Williams had team highs of 20 points and 11 rebounds, but after she
scored the game's first basket with three seconds gone, the Huskies
would never again take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   BC, which crowded under the basket to keep UConn from getting
second shots, limited the Huskies to just 28 first-half points
while racking up 46 of its own. That statistic is especially
amazing considering that in 11 of its 18 previous games, UConn had
scored 100 or more points.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed only fitting that as the buzzer sounded at the end of
the half, one of Murphy's two 3-pointers was falling through the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   UConn tried to regroup in the second half. The Huskies came out
after intyermission and started pressing BC, leading to an 11-2
run. UConn came within 9 points, at 66-57, and the visitors' fans
started making more noise.
</P>
<P>
   The more the Huskies pushed, though, the more the Eagles pushed
back. They forced UConn to commit 23 turnovers and 24 personal
fouls, and held the Huskies to two 3-pointers on 19 attempts. Coach
Geno Auriemma kept sending in new players, but no combination
worked for UConn. Freshman starter Kiersten Walters had no points
and no assists, while starting guard Svetlana Abrosimova was held
to 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did all the things that you need to do to win, and we
didn't do anything,'' Auriemma said. ``All the credit goes to them;
they played us about as good as you can play us. They didn't put us
on the free throw line much, which is a big key. We gave them some
confidence, and they took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   BC freshman Brianne Stepherson, who had 8 points and 5 assists,
credited her team with keeping the tempo up. ``We had our game face
on and were totally focued on 40 minutes of basketball, 40 minutes
of pure heart, because we know how big it would be if we beat
them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stepherson and Murphy played all 40 minutes of the game;
freshman Becky Gottstein played 38 and had 14 points. Conway had 11
and senior Whitney Steele scored 10.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese said that the triumph was another step forward for her
team, which last month scored a significant victory over Notre
Dame. ``Now, this one is a major springboard for us as far as
getting some respect back, and that people know we're a good
team,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite getting a flat tire on the way to shootaround this
morning, this day has worked out really well.''
</P>
<P>
   To say the least.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
