<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BCWOMEN-MURPHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY WAS RIGHT ON TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're a basketball player, there are games you dream about.
Saturday, Alissa Murphy had one of those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going out,'' declared Murphy, a Boston College junior
guard/forward from San Diego, tossing back her ponytail and beaming
a smile the size of her home state. ``I don't go out often, but I
am going to go out tonight!''
</P>
<P>
   Even her vanquished foes weren't disputing Murphy's right to
celebrate after she had led the Eagles to a gigantic 78-66 win over
the University of Connecticut, the No. 2 team in the country,
Saturday afternoon. ``She probably had the game of her life,'' said
UConn forward Tamika Williams. ``It felt like she scored about 40
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost. In her fourth game since shifting to the backcourt to
fill in for the injured Cal Bouchard, Murphy scored 32, a career
high (by 12) that included 8 straight midway through the second
half. She shot 11 for 18 from the floor, 8 for 9 from the free
throw line, and pulled down a team-leading nine rebounds in 40
glorious minutes of fearlessly driving the lane whenever she wasn't
popping 'em in from outside.
</P>
<P>
   It's called playing out of your mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``She plays like that in practice all the time,'' shrugged
Bouchard, her roommate, who is out with a torn anterior cruciate
ligament. ``We all knew she could do it, and to come out against
UConn was just a tribute to her confidence and her skills.''
</P>
<P>
   If beating the No. 2 team in the nation is exciting, beating the
No. 2 team in the country that just three seasons ago crushed your
team, 76-38, in your BC debut is nothing short of sublime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got humiliated in our first collegiate game,'' said
Bouchard, Murphy nodding in agreement next to her. ``And since then
they've dominated us. It was just sweet redemption.''
</P>
<P>
   For Murphy, it was redemption built on last summer's renewed
determination to come back to school in the best condition of her
life. ``I shot more jump shots than I ever shot in my life,'' she
recalled of her ``vacation'' spent practicing on her own, working
at basketball camps back in San Diego, and touring with a Big East
all-star team in Europe. ``I worked hard in the weight room. I
played almost every day, shot extra shots, just dedicated myself to
coming back in shape, coming back as a better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Redemption was also built on quiet consistency. Fifth on the
team in scoring (averaging 5.5 points per game) as a freshman, the
player whom coach Cathy Inglese calls her most underrated was third
as a sophomore (9.1) and this year led the team at 14.6 going into
Saturday's game. Her previous career high, 20 points, came in a
Jan. 5 win over Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday the 21-year-old economics major was anything but quiet.
Right from the pregame shootaround, when she couldn't miss, Murphy
knew it was going to be a good day. By the time she hit a 3-point
buzzer-beater to end the half, she was beginning to realize just
how good it would be, both for her and for her team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad job by me; I didn't realize the time,'' said Murphy,
recalling her buzzer-beater. ``I could hear Coach _ I don't know
how I heard her with that crowd _ but I heard her voice coming
through and as I looked up I saw and I just'' _ and here Murphy
gasps _ ``threw it up, one-handed runner, and then it was sealed.
It was definitely going to be a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she'd called her family back home with the good news,
Murphy laughed. ``I tried to but the phone was busy,'' she said.
``We don't have call waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   When that's the only thing that doesn't go right on a day you're
playing the No. 2 team in the country, you are indeed having a good
day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
