<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP TRAFFIC WINS AT SANTA ANITA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- The first time trainer Richard Mandella saw Stop
Traffic, the filly was on sale and nursing a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday he saw the 6-year-old mare again -- in the winner's
circle after she cruised to victory in the $200,000 Grade I Santa
Monica Handicap at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice way to start the year,'' Mandella said. ``Stop
Traffic just keeps carrying the banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop Traffic paid $9.80, $4.20 and $4.60. Belle's Flag, an
entry, finished second and paid $3.40 and $3.20. The other half of
the entry, Closed Entry, finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing fourth was Seeking the Pearl. The horse drew a swarm
of media from Japan documenting celebrity jockey Yutaka Take's trip
to the states for the race.
</P>
<P>
   Hideyuki Mori, who trained Seeking the Pearl, said the horse
handled her first dirt race well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will return to Japan and consider other races for her
overseas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stop Traffic's win came in spite of the fact she was blocked
behind other horses at the quarter pole. She broke through at
midstretch and made her move on Belle's Flag, who led at the top of
the stretch. The seven furlong race was run in a tepid 1:22.17, but
Mandella wasn't unhappy with the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see it was running long,'' he said. ``But (Jockey)
Corey (Black) had her in a real nice spot waiting to commit
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Stop Traffic ran in last year's Santa Monica, she
didn't do as well then, finishing in seventh, 14 1/2 lengths out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know what got into her that day, that's the only
bad day she ever had for me,'' Mandella said. ``She ran about 100
yards and just quit. I never figured it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandella bought the horse for $300,000 from Gerald Ford, a
Dallas, Texas banker. She was on the block as a 3-year-old at the
annual Keeneland Breeder's sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was laid up with a tibial stress fracture,'' Mandella
said. ``We checked her out. I bought her, brought her home and put
her in training and never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   For Black, the trip aboard Stop Traffic was his first Grade I
winner since taking the 1994 Hollywood Turf Cup aboard Frenchpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was on her game obviously,'' Black said. ``(Mandella) had
been singing her praises all week telling me she's been training
unbelievably well.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: On this day in 1974 Jockey Chris McCarron rode in his
first race. He finished last aboard Most Active at the Bowie
Racecourse. ... Alex Solis, who's recently had a hot hand remains
Santa Anita's leading jockey through Friday. So far Solis has had
120 mounts and ridden 26 of those to the winners circle. His horses
have been in the money 49 percent of the time. Bob Baffert leads
all trainers at the meet with nine wins. His horses have been in
the money 54 percent of the time. ...
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of trainers, Lisa Lewis saddled her first winner,
Capsized, in the sixth race Friday. ... In his quest for an elusive
6,000th win, Eddie Delahoussaye remained winless Saturday. He is
still six wins short of the goal achieved by just 13 other jockeys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
