<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL MINDS SEEK THE BIGGSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime around midnight the telephone rang and a groggy Linda
Biggs shuffled across the room to answer it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a psychic,'' a woman on the line whispered.
</P>
<P>
   `'A what?'' Linda asked, half asleep.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks now, the Biggs family has been getting calls from
strangers at all hours of the day and night.
</P>
<P>
   People they've never met want to talk to them about the
disappearance of 11-year-old Mikelle, the girl who vanished from
the street near her home in Mesa on Jan. 2, and hasn't been seen
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some things to tell you about your missing daughter's
case,'' the clairvoyant told Linda. `'I've been getting some very
strong feelings about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' Linda said, her voice rising. ``Are you getting the
feeling that you're talking to the wrong Biggs family?''
</P>
<P>
   Days later, as Linda retells the story, she's still not sure the
woman believed her. And the calls keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   Linda and her husband, Darrin, live in Mesa, only a couple of
miles from Mikelle's parents, Tracy and Michael ``Darien'' Biggs.
The missing girl's father is often referred to by his middle name.
Meantime, Darrin's name is in the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' Linda says, ``we've heard from our share of kooks.'' &QL; 
WELL-MEANING CALLERS
</P>
<P>
   Some callers are well-meaning. They ask if there's anything they
can do for the family. They want to pass along their own special
theory of the disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, really,'' Linda says, ``how can even a nice person
believe it's OK to intrude into the lives of people whose daughter
is missing? What are they thinking?''
</P>
<P>
   They're thinking they're part of the family. And why not?
</P>
<P>
   Since the day Mikelle Biggs went out for an ice cream cone and
didn't come back, her story, her parents, her face have appeared on
just about every television newscast and every newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   There are billboards. There are fliers posted everywhere. There
are benefit auctions. One family's loss becomes every family's
loss.
</P>
<P>
   People feel as if they know Mikelle and the Biggs family, as if
they're a part of it. What's a few late-night phone calls between
relatives?
</P>
<P>
   ``Mikelle's parents, when I've seen them on TV, seem really
grateful for all the support they're getting,'' Linda says. ``But
if we're getting the number of crank calls we're getting, I can
only imagine what is happening to them. I would only ask people one
thing: Stop.'' &QL; 
PEOPLE FEEL ENTITLED
</P>
<P>
   Curious people could call the police, of course. Well-wishers
could send cards. Or simply say a prayer. That's not good enough
for some. In Jerry Springerville, which is every town in America,
people feel entitled to some small brush with fame.
</P>
<P>
   Getting on TV is the best. Talking to someone's who's been on TV
is close enough. Mikelle's parents have been on TV.
</P>
<P>
   A woman called the wrong Biggs household one day and got Darrin
on the telephone. He explained to her that his children were fine
and she was speaking to a different family.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the same woman called again, and again Darrin
answered. This time, she asked to speak to his wife. Darrin rolled
his eyes and handed the phone to Linda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid you're husband's in denial,'' the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If getting hassled by people like this takes just a little bit
of the burden off the actual Biggs family, we're happy to do it,''
Linda says. ``I can't imagine how terrible this must be for that
mom and dad. All of us feel for them. We've all seen their story on
TV and the papers and everything. It would be really nice, though,
if people who want to contact them would stop, and think, and leave
them alone.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice, I tell Linda, but it won't happen, not here in
Springerville. She has the same strong feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The two of us, we're psychic about these things. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
