<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      01-23 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets take opening steps in transition
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
There was no triangle offense, but there was a legendary center in
the low post. There was no meditation-preaching Zen proponent, but
a straight-talking coach with work to do. No Michael Jordan, but a
group of rookies taking their first professional steps less than
two weeks before at least a few will have to play.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen's first day as the center of attention served to
remind how much had changed, and how much must be done to make it
all feel as natural as all those years running with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   He said he enjoyed the change of pace, even if he seemed taken
aback by all the fuss, having for so long had Jordan to assume the
heat of the spotlight. He also got his first taste of the
transition he and the Rockets had assumed with the addition of
seven new faces among the 14 healthy players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' Pippen said Saturday at Westside Tennis
Club. ``It's a change that's been coming for a long time. This
organization is different. Playing with a guy like Michael, who's
always been a superstar or a franchise, now to come somewhere to
see a team want you so much, is a little different. It's a good
position to be in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be fair to adjust to playing with such a dominant
center. Then I can feel my way and find my niche with this team.
This is a team that had a lot of success without Scottie Pippen. I
have to sort of feel my way in. I didn't come here to be
destructive.''
</P>
<P>
   But as comfortable as he might find himself with the sudden wave
of appreciation, the offense is different and his style demands he
play instinctively, to use the offensive system without feeling
constrained to adhere to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably have to think a lot more,'' Pippen said. ``I
can't say I can walk out here the first day in the system at ease.
It takes time to develop. I'm going to put in as much time as I can
to try to be at ease with this offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been used to running the triangle (offense) so it's a
little different having a dominant center inside and providing some
spacing. I'm having fun. Inside is the No. 1 option, they double
down, which may give you opportunities to spot up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't too difficult. It was a learning situation. There
was standing around for the most part, just trying to learn and
getting accustomed to what the coaching staff wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But the coaching staff does not know how long it will take for a
rebuilt team to feel at ease.
</P>
<P>
   Though coaches are experienced with calculating how hard they
can push without pushing too hard, no one has much experience with
preparing in less than two weeks (interrupted by two exhibition
games and a public scrimmage) to sprint through a 50-game NBA
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to stretch how much we can do,'' Rockets
coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``There is going to be a little
confusion on a lot of people's part. We have to get so much in in a
short amount of time. We're going to have to push that limit all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're a little bit behind here. We're adding so many
new players. I've never been big on excuses. We're going to go out
and do the best that we can. We're going to be all right. It's
going to be a gradual process. We have intelligent players. We're
going to get this thing worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   But such concerns did not drown out the obvious happiness with
returning to work. If the six-month lockout or the protracted
haggling to complete the collective-bargaining agreement did not
exhaust patience, the two days waiting for league approval, all
while the team waited at the practice facility to get to work, made
Saturday's start of an adjustment period welcome compared to the
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy,'' Tomjanovich sad. ``We had healthy bodies,
a lot of energy, a lot of positive feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know (how long it will take for players to be
comfortable with the changes.) This is so different. It's crucial,
but we're going to do it together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in some crazy situations before. That second
championship year (1994-95), that team didn't play together until
the first game of the playoffs. Somehow we got that chemistry
together.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first day taking on a similar process, Hakeem Olajuwon
said he had little concern about Pippen becoming comfortable with
the Rockets' style.
</P>
<P>
   And Pippen and the six other new Rockets _ centers John Coker
and Antoine Carr, forward Anthony ``Pig'' Miller and rookie guards
Michael Dickerson, Bryce Drew and Cuttino Mobley _ will not be
alone in the learning process.
</P>
<P>
   Even the veterans of the Rockets' system, Olajuwon said, must
adjust, with so many new parts added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie is so experienced. He's trying to find out what the
plays are so he knows how to execute,'' Olajuwon said. ``He's very
easy to work with, very positive, good leadership, good interaction
together, good chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to have confidence this is also his system.
The system is just to guide you. His game and his talents have to
show. He has to play his (style) to make his presence felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a whole different team. That's the attitude we have
to have. We have to learn how to play all the way from the
beginning. The same principle applies to me. I'm learning to play
from the beginning, even though the system is the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought in new faces, athletes, young, energetic, looking
forward to play. Looking around I see all this talent, you gain
enthusiasm. The coaches are excited. It's good chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   With such good feelings, Pippen accepted the praise and
expectations and seemed almost as relieved to get to work to earn
them. Friday's celebration made it clear he is expected to bring
renewed championship contention. Friday, Tomjanovich called him
basketball's ``most complete player.'' Saturday, Pippen seemed to
have no doubt that that's what Tomjanovich would get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm just looking to fit in,'' Pippen said. ``Once I
feel much more comfortable with the system I'm looking to do more.
I'll develop myself into what Rudy wants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
