<DOCNO> NYT19990123.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-23 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6045 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-1STLEA     01-23 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-1STLEAD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A BITTER FEUD OVER A JUDGE'S RULING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update and rewrite throughout; this story is now on NYT
Page 1)   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the trial of President Clinton moved toward a
critical set of votes next week, the Senate's spirit of fragile
bipartisanship frayed nearly to the breaking point Saturday and a
party-line vote looked almost certain to kill a Democratic motion
to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the changed tone and party confrontation should
not have been unexpected. Two weeks ago, when all 100 senators met
in the ceremonial Old Senate Chamber and hammered out a bipartisan
trial plan, they reached agreement by simply putting off the hard
issues that divided them: whether to allow witnesses and whether to
continue the trial all the way through to an up-or-down vote on the
two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Those are now the very questions that are to come before the
Senate for a vote as early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, senators were left breathless Saturday by the speed
with which cooperation deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was left so unsettled that Sen.Trent Lott, the
majority leader, simply deflected questions about a statement made
by his press spokesman earlier in the day, that he was going to
block debate by the Senate on the two most critical motions, one to
dismiss the trial and the other on whether to allow witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ought to now say we are going to do it one
way or the other, all the way,'' Lott said. ``We will clarify as we
will go along. We will do that Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately objected to the prospect of not even being
allowed to debate the issues. ``To say to senators, `We're going to
deny you the right to speak about the motion to dismiss,' is
mind-boggling,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the
minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters about the duration of the trial, Sen.
Russell Feingold, D-Wis., said, ``I notice a shift every half day
in terms of people thinking it will go on for months, or it's going
to be over in a few hours.'' Asked what he thought now, Feingold
said, ``I think it's going to go on for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has pulled back before from the brink of partisanship
and some of Saturday's Democratic complaints may well have been a
tactic, on the eve of critical votes, to scare Republicans, who
desperately do not want to appear as partisan as their colleagues
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   On both sides of the aisle, there were still Democrats and
Republicans who thought the Senate might yet cobble together a
majority next week against calling witnesses, or find some other
way to move directly to a vote on the articles of impeachment,
which would end the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to bring about an end that makes sense,'' said
Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt. And Sen. John Breaux, D-La., was trying
to explore whether the motion to dismiss the case, to be presented
by Sen. Robert Byrd, a West Virginia Democrat, could somehow pass
if it were to include tough language condemning Clinton for
inappropriate behavior in the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   But on this day at least the Senate seemed to be descending into
the same kind of bitterness as the House, spurred to some degree by
the House Republicans themselves, who had secretly approached the
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, who Saturday won a court order
instructing Monica Lewinsky to cooperate with the House
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the former intern was back in Washington to be
questioned somewhere in the capital on Sunday. Daschle called the
House prosecutors' maneuver the most ``clear demonstration of raw
partisanship that I have ever seen,'' and 44 Democratic senators
urged the House not to go ahead with the questioning. Daschle also
asked, through Chief Justice William Rehnquist, whether the
prosecutors would permit two senators, a Republican and a Democrat,
to attend the questioning. The House Republicans refused.
</P>
<P>
   Many Senate Republicans defended the House move, saying that
since the prosecutors will have to submit a witness list on Monday
and justify it to the Senate, they needed the chance to see whether
Ms. Lewinsky could add to their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely appropriate,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
But another senior Republican, Sen. John Warner of Virginia, agreed
with the Democrats that the House Republicans had broken the spirit
of the bipartisan agreement on how to handle witnesses.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans began the day with their own grievance. They saw
the surprise announcement on Friday that Byrd would be the one to
sponsor the motion to dismiss the case against Clinton as a sign
that the Democrats themselves were hardening into a party position.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd had been one of the Democrats who had early on held out the
possibility that he might vote to convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   So after a party caucus Saturday morning, senior Republicans
said they would oppose the motion, and they signaled that this
would be a party position. ``Frankly, it sets a constitutional
precedent that doesn't make any sense,'' said Sen. Don Nickles of
Oklahoma, the majority whip. ``Every single impeachment trial in
the history of the United States Senate has had a resolution by
voting up or down on the articles.''
</P>
<P>
   And by day's end, Lott seized on a White House offer that was
quickly retracted, or at least clarified, and announced that
Republicans would send the president himself a list of questions
they wanted him to answer for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hostilities, there are still some ways the Senate
could bring the trial to a speedy conclusion. If all 45 Democrats
hold a united front on the second vote pending before the Senate _
on whether to allow witnesses _ they need to pick up only six
Republicans to assemble a 51-vote majority. (In the case of a 50-50
tie, Rehnquist can cast the decisive vote if he chooses.)
</P>
<P>
   The House managers have not yet indicated how many witnesses
they will seek to call. The list they submit and how they defend it
could also influence how the Senate votes. ``If they can make a
case for witnesses, I'll vote for them,'' said Sen. Robert Bennett,
R-Utah, ``but it has to be a strong case.''
</P>
<P>
   If witnesses are approved, Lott is looking for a way to
stringently control the length and scope of the questioning so that
the trial could end next month. ``The leaders' intention is to have
this not go beyond mid-February,'' said John Czwartacki, Lott's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are envisioning perhaps a week of taking depositions
in private _ and the possibility that the witnesses would then not
be called before the Senate itself. But it is far from clear
whether senators would really be able to control the process if
they voted to allow depositions of witnesses behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   And David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, warned the Senate
on Friday that if witnesses are summoned for deposition, the White
House would want to call witnesses itself, cross-examine witnesses
and subpoena documents for discovery.
</P>
<P>
   It is not even clear if Senate Democrats would help Republicans
bring about a controlled deposition process, so angry were they at
the House managers. Some have been arguing privately that they
should simply let the Republicans hurt themselves politically and
be blamed by the public for a long trial.
</P>
<P>
   And the Democrats were already demonstrating today how that
would work. ``Mr. Starr is now directly participating in the
impeachment trial process,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli of New
Jersey, invoking the unpopular independent counsel. Torricelli said
the actions of Starr and of Rep. Henry Hyde, the chief House
prosecutor, ``undermine the Senate's exclusive authority and raise
serious constitutional questions about this proceeding.''
Torricelli sounded a lot like Democrats did in the House just a few
months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
