<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-FEUD-AZR &LR;      01-23 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-FEUD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEVES' PRESS CONFERENCE IGNITES SMOL DERING RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What better venue for this lasting hostility than Miami, the
city of riots, point of entry for Fidel's finest exiled thugs, a
tourist mecca where crime takes no holiday, but where the
championship of pro football takes a backseat, initially, to an old
family feud?
</P>
<P>
   Located, as it is, just south of the Reeves-Shanahan Line, Miami
isn't much farther than a well-flung moonshine jug from Atlanta,
home of the Reeves clan.
</P>
<P>
   The clan leaders, Dan Reeves and Mike Shanahan, once were like
kin, although there is no documentation that they ever went raccoon
hunting together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan was probably one of my closest friends at one time,''
Shanahan said. ``Any time you end the way we did, there's always a
little bit on the inside of you that rubs each of us the wrong
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves affirmed, ``I couldn't have been closer to someone than I
was to Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Reeves believes that Shanahan came to view the essence of
their relationship as ``You scratch my back, and I'll stab yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, Reeves held a public blood-letting Wednesday
in Atlanta, telling the world what he thought of his former
colleague. And it wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan, who now has the job that Reeves believes still should
be his, was highly indignant by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before they leave south Florida, it's a safe bet that each will
use a shotgun to help settle their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves got his forum after coaching the upstart Atlanta Falcons
to an upset over the Minnesota Vikings in the NFC title game. His
sparring partner emerged when the Shanahan-coached Denver Broncos
came back to eliminate the New York Jets in the AFC title game.
</P>
<P>
   In Super Bowl XXXIII, it's the Falcons vs. the Broncos at Pro
Player Stadium next Sunday. &QL; 
Sideline showdown &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it's Reeves vs. Shanahan. Grab a good Cuban cigar,
sit back during Hype Week and watch an entertaining feud play out.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was coach of the Broncos from 1981 through 1992. During
his run, they went to three Super Bowls with John Elway as
quarterback. They lost them all but an almost-certain Hall of Fame
quarterback emerged.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Reeves had rescued Elway from Baltimore. The Colts were
awful. Elway said he'd play professional baseball before he would
play for the Colts, who had drafted him in the first round. So
Reeves, considered one of the game's premier offensive coaches,
traded for Elway, viewed as the game's next great signal-caller. It
seemed a perfect match.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Reeves gave Shanahan, a one-time assistant coach
at Northern Arizona University, his first NFL job as his receivers
coach. In 1985, Reeves promoted Shanahan to offensive coordinator.
Two years later, Shanahan, quickly making his mark as a bright
young coach, was hired as head coach of the Los Angeles Raiders.
Fired during his second season, Shanahan was brought back to the
Broncos by Reeves in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the storyline follows divergent paths.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said in his shocking diatribe Wednesday that Shanahan
became a Judas, a disloyal back-stabber who wanted Reeves' job and
undermined him to get it. Reeves accused Shanahan of taking
confidential coaching critiques of Elway's performances back to the
star quarterback, drawing Elway into a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan denied it, adding that Elway never really liked Reeves,
his suddenly conservative offense or his autocratic style of
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say things in a coaches' meeting as far as critiquing play
that you would never say to the player,'' Reeves said. ``If John
ever got any bad feelings about something that I said, it had to be
something from a staff meeting. I knew they were really, really
good friends, and still are. Now, does that mean Mike did it?
You've got a lot of people on your staff. I have no proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, did Reeves open his mouth? Shanahan wondered
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to accuse someone of doing something, I'm at
least going to have some proof, something more than a strong
feeling,'' Shanahan said. ``In no way would I ever tell John Elway
or any other player something that was said in a meeting.'' &QL; 
Elway in the middle &QL; 
Reeves recalled hitting the roof in 1990 when Elway ripped him in a
Denver newspaper column.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem I had was if John Elway had a problem with
me and you're coaching his position, why did I not know that prior
to reading it in the paper?'' Reeves said. ``If you were a position
coach and you were that close to him, why didn't you say, `Sit down
and talk to him?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said Reeves knew exactly where his relationship stood
with Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``No ifs, ands, or buts about that,'' Shanahan said. ``It was a
tough relationship from the first year. Everyone in this town
(Denver) knows that. Everything went downhill after that column.
Dan called me into his office the day it came out, he threw the
newspaper at me and he yelled, `How did this story get in there?' I
said, `Dan, I didn't give this story. Why are you yelling at me? I
had nothing to do with it. Why not talk to John?'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I went down to the weight room, and I got John. Then we
went back and I told both of them, `John, I'm getting tired of
this. Why don't you tell Dan why you don't like him, and Dan, you
tell John why you don't like him.' So they both told why they
didn't like each other, and that was it. After that day, except to
talk about football, Dan and I never talked again.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Reeves fired Shanahan. He said Wednesday he did it
because Shanahan was ``insubordinate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he had my best interests in mind at the time,''
Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Baloney, Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had looked me in the eyes, man to man, and told me how
he felt, I could have respected that,'' Shanahan said. ``Instead,
Dan looked me in the eyes and said, `Mike, I want to call the
offense. You want to call the offense. So I've got to make a
change.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Reeves and Shanahan, and to a large degree Elway,
couldn't coexist because they all want control, they're all
stubborn, and they all believe they are masters of offense.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, even Reeves acknowledged that ``Mike knew how to get
the best out of John.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowlen fires Reeves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Broncos dropped to 8-8 and club owner Pat Bowlen,
prodded by Elway, fired Reeves. Afterward, Elway, who on Sunday
will become the first quarterback to start in five Super Bowls for
the same team, said the final three years under Reeves ``were like
being in hell'' and that ``I would not have been back here if Dan
Reeves had been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves expected to be replaced by Shanahan. Wade Phillips got
the assignment. He lasted two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan finally got the Denver head coaching job in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Shanahan and Elway did what Reeves and Elway hadn't
done. They won the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said he thought they had put their differences behind.
He, Elway and Reeves played a round of golf together last year
during the Masters in Augusta, Ga. When Reeves underwent quadruple
bypass heart surgery six weeks ago, Shanahan and Elway were among
the first to send well wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop Wednesday, Reeves flung moonshine jugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I'll ever get over, quote, the situation,''
Reeves said. ``There's still a lot of hurt that won't ever go away.
You never forget those things. I had a lot of great times with
those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting it off his chest before the teams got to Miami might
have been Reeves' way of gaining closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you're fired and you've been in a place for
12 years you can't say it doesn't hurt you,'' Reeves said. ``It
changed an awful lot of people's lives just like me making a
decision about Mike changed people's lives. It caused a lot of pain
for my wife and children, and it wasn't like they deserved it
because we weren't successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay in Denver for the rest of my career. I can't
tell you how many times Pat told me, `We'll finish our careers
together.' That's the way I personally saw it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
