A6063 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCLAUSC-LADN     01-23 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLAUSC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WOMEN ROUT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Against the backdrop of the UCLA women's
basketball team's 94-53 rout of USC on Saturday, the teams look at
themselves and answer questions that have become obvious at this
point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   For UCLA, the questions cause coach Kathy Olivier to dream for a
moment before bringing herself back to the present.
</P>
<P>
   She knows people wonder if this Bruins team (15-4, 7-0 Pac-10)
can become the school's first to go 18-0 in conference.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Philman, who scored seven points Saturday, emphatically
says she wants to be on the team that does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more experienced. We're more focused,'' she said. ``We
work on our weaknesses. The coaches prepare us. We're more
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivier smiles. This season has been something for Bruins fans
so far. The team ended Stanford's 63-game home win streak last
week. On Saturday, the Bruins won their eighth straight game in
front of 9,530 _ a Pauley Pavilion women's record crowd _ and
handed their rival its sixth-worst loss ever. It was UCLA's largest
margin of victory over the Women of Troy (6-10, 2-5) since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA shot 63 percent from the field and had five players score
in double figures, led by Maylana Martin's 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Martin continues to play well despite four weeks of recurring
headaches caused by a fluid leak in her spine. She said she will
meet with doctors again today.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier takes all this into account, then admits she tries to
stay focused. But she knows this team is capable of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take care of business off the court. They take care of
business on the court,'' Olivier said. ``They want to be good. They
want to go 18-0. That's their goal. As exciting as what we did
(Saturday) and against Stanford, we still have other things to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   For USC, Murphy's Law is in effect. The season just got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Senior center Adrain Williams hurt her ankle while blocking a
Janae Hubbard shot just 2 minutes, 40 seconds into the game. The
extent of her injury is unknown, but coach Chris Gobrecht hopes
it's just a sprain.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was the last of a highly touted recruiting class of six
that never panned out because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   USC now has eight players, including three freshmen who started.
</P>
<P>
   Gobrecht's eyes were a little red when she met with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make me fight back tears,'' she said. ``Nobody should have
to go through it to that extent. I've never seen a team be put
through what this team has been put through.''
</P>
<P>
   USC was overmatched from the start, committing 24 turnovers and
trailing 49-20 at the half. The Women of Troy shot 30 percent from
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Elmore, one of the freshman starters, led USC with 16
points, and sophomore Tashara Carter added 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would've been better this year,'' Gobrecht said. ``We
didn't know they'd all go down. I'm hopeful for some perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to get better. They know their time will come. L.A.
was SC's town for a lot of years, and the sun will rise again. None
of these kids doubt it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-99 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
