<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 31)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HOW THE MIND WORKS &LR;  By Steven Pinker. Norton, $17. A psychology
professor argues that the mind is not a blank slate at birth, but
comes with specialized modules shaped by natural selection for
communication, perception and everyday tasks. In 1997 the New York
Times reviewer Mark Ridley called this ``witty popular science that
you enjoy reading for the writing as well as for the science.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MIRROR &LR;  By Lynn Freed. Ballantine, $11.95. The ambitious
heroine of this stylized historical novel leaves England after
World War I for a new life in South Africa, where she is hired as a
housekeeper by a wealthy Jewish family. After an affair with the
elderly head of the household results in a baby daughter, she
struggles to maintain her independence and control her romantic
destiny against imposing odds. ``Like so many of the best books,
`The Mirror' makes us laugh while packing, finally, a punch in
which life's sadness prevails over its consolatory moments of
humor,'' Brooke Allen wrote in The New York Times Book Review in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ORDEAL OF INTEGRATION: PROGRESS AND RESENTMENT IN AMERICA'S
`RACIAL' CRISIS &LR;  By Orlando Patterson. Civitas/Counterpoint, $15.
Blacks have made remarkable gains over the last 40 years, an
African-American sociologist maintains, but extremists on both the
right and the left who deny those gains are impeding further
progress. In 1997 the Times reviewer James Q. Wilson called this
provocative analysis ``defiant, even angry, often right and
sometimes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOTES OF A NATIVE SON &LR;  By James Baldwin. Beacon, $13.
Originally published in 1955, this is a collection of essays on
such disparate subjects as protest novels, the movie ``Carmen
Jones'' and the death of the author's father. ``Few American
writers handle words more effectively in the essay form than James
Baldwin,'' Langston Hughes wrote in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUL ON ICE &LR;  By Eldridge Cleaver. Delta, $11.95. This is the
searing 1960s prison memoir of the former Black Panther, who died
last year at the age of 62. In it, he lashes out at what he calls a
sick country while recounting his own troubles with the law, which
began when he was 18 with a conviction for marijuana possession. In
1968 in the Times Book Review, Charlayne Hunter called this a
``highly readable and often witty'' book ``about the imprisonment
of men's souls by society.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PRITCHETT CENTURY &LR;  By V.S. Pritchett. Modern Library,
$14.95. Victor Sawdon Pritchett (1900-97) _ novelist, critic,
travel writer and all-round man of letters _ found plenty to write
about, from the Victorian class system to Salman Rushdie. The
result is ``a rich anthology'' by ``one of the most versatile and
consistently satisfying writers of the century,'' Alfred Kazin
wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACE OF A HERO &LR;  By Louis Falstein. Steerforth, $14. This 1950
autobiographical novel by an aerial gunner during World War II
revolves around the 10-man crew of a B-24 based in Italy, and the
flak and fear they encountered on harrowing bombing runs to Vienna,
Munich and the Po Valley, among other places. In his review Herbert
F. West called the story ``both exciting and important.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A WALK IN THE SUN &LR;  By Harry Brown, University of Nebraska, $12.
This is the grunt-level tale of a platoon forced to regroup and
carry out its mission after losing its leaders during the Allied
landings at Salerno, Italy. ```A Walk in the Sun' is one of the
most honest books to come out of this war,'' Harvey Breit wrote in
1944. ``It is a small novel possessing dramatic tension'' and
``poetic and realistic speech.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARE YOU SOMEBODY? THE ACCIDENTAL MEMOIR OF A DUBLIN WOMAN &LR;  By
Nuala O'Faolain. Owl/Holt, $11.95. This candid, dignified account
by a columnist for The Irish Times features the booze, religious
repression, guilt and other mainstays of the modern Irish
narrative, but steers clear of its sentimentality and affectations.
``O'Faolain brings a spiky, independent intelligence that
vanquishes cliche,'' Zoe Heller wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SNAKE &LR;  By Kate Jennings. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $12. This lean
novel, set in postwar Australia, is about a mismatched couple
living on a remote farm whose marriage is doomed from day one:
She's desperately unhappy and restless, while he's disappointed and
tormented by her shifting moods. ```Snake' is clearly the work of a
powerful imagination,'' Carol Shields wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUSHKIN HOUSE &LR;  By Andrei Bitov. Translated by Susan
Brownsberger. Dalkey Archive, $13.95. This complex Russian novel
recounts the life, loves and drunken death of its upper-class hero
during and after Stalin's reign. In 1988 the reviewer Frank Kermode
admired the book's ``fiery intelligence,'' adding that ``the author
this work most vividly recalls when at its eloquent and weird best
is Dostoyevsky.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WAITING FOR THE BARBARIANS &LR;  By Lewis H. Lapham. Verso, $15. The
editor of Harper's Magazine, in 25 cranky essays that are
nonpartisan in their vitriol, portrays an America where the art of
investing has overtaken the art of governing. Last year the
reviewer Johanna Berkman said ``these dour yet witty ruminations
spare no one and nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
